text: as you get through the pint , the head becomes a memory and there is almost no lace- the one drawback to an otherwise beautiful , amazingly hot ( like charlize therion hot ) beer . she smells a bit like coffee- not surprising for a beer based in dark beans .  for something that is this old to have this much carbonation . i am fucking impressed . a two finger off white head is standing proud over this dark red body . so good .  at the downtown chicago rock bottom , they named it rooftop pilsner for its rooftop dining area ( with a fine view of all the much taller yuppie condos surrounding it ) . they had to brew this in a hurry following the may windstorm that blew their rooftop taps open , draining all of their serving tanks ! pretty good for a style which we 've all had bad examples of . fizzy head leaves a golden yellow color underneath . no off-flaveors to speak of . nice citrsy hop aroma which i found to be a little stronger after a scoop of salsa . a decent session beer .

smell : the nose appeal is a bit mild but has a great pine scent with some orange lemon-like citrus . i was expecting something intense , given the name torpedo , but it 's incredibly balanced but flavorful . the dryness is n't overbearing and makes the mouth feel a bit relaxed but not shy to receive more .  a : exceptional , should be the example of perfect lacing ! it pours a golden hue topped with a frothy white head that leaves you feeling the beer wants you to drink it .  id love for this to have a heavier mouthfeel , but this is a darn good session beer for a cold night .

a : a pleasant straw to light amber color with a two finger foam . s : for me a beer should smell much as it tastes . this is not to say the smell is bad it is fine but does n't comvey to the drinker the full range of flavors that sre found in the beer .  a-dark as night with tan head around the edges s-sweet vanilla . very inviting and i can not wait to dive in .  m : the body is medium with a low carbonation and a tooth rotting sweetness . so unbearably sweet and sugary without any sort of balance .

on-tap at the abbey . a - nice burgundy body , decent head , though again , the bartender did n't want to cheat me , so poured less head than it otherwise would be . maybe my nose is having a bad day ... it 's not congested at all , but i 'm not getting much out of any beer i have today . t - really tasty , a toasted graham cracker with a lot of clove evident . d - strong beer , but you could toss back a couple .  a- one of the nicer looking ipa 's i 've seen . dark orange body with a solid finger 's worth of head , and very intense carbonation .  m-moderate carbonation , medium-bodied beer , with a noticeable hoppy dryness .

very little aroma - bit of bread , a smidgen of vanilla . little but nice , but i 'm going to take in foam if i sniff any harder .  it pours like ink into the glass- this is as black as it gets- as a moderate brown froth emerges and then sticks around a while .  mouthfeel is way too light for what i was expecting .

i thought this was a very nice amber ale . i knew it was n't going to be a brut , but this beer had lots of flavor . malty and chewy with a touch of caramel sweetness , but with enough hops to balance it out .  poured into a new belgium snifter a - transparent blood red , half finger head , off white almost tan/brown and some serious lacing s - sweet .  m - average carbonation .

aroma is floral hops . taste is sweet rich malts with a very strong earthy leather hop bitterness .  it is a beauty to look at - but enough with looking .  typical mouthfeel for a lager i guess , although i do n't know a lot about what this style should be like .

hints of toffee and pecans shrink behind a moderately roasted but otherwise unremarkable nose . everything is on display here ; light nuttiness is followed by a sometimes chocolaty , sometimes fruity body with no shortage of roasted quality . the finish is delightful , owing bitterness to both roasted malt and elegant hops ( cascade must be bittering because this is tettnang all the way ) .  now this is a beautiful looking beer . gorgeous -- and i have n't even tasted it yet .  light body and a bit watery , but the munich possesses a david-like flavor that surprises those who order it expecting something more saccharine .

s- really not picking up much here besides grain and maybe some malt , my buddy confirms this so i 'm not crazy here .  pours a brown/chestnut with 3+ fingers of rocky sand colored head . outstanding head retention & lacing s : bready , roasty , & nuttyness t : bready , roasty malt , & dryness up front .  very light and summer-appropriate . could drink several . definitely a solid brew .

the smell had a metallic smell to it mixed with a cocoa smell .  the color is really fantastic on this one , a deep reddish brown with a fantastic , yet thin , layer of head that does n't quit .  like most light lagers , the only character to the smell and flavor comes from the malt , hops and water . there is a clear attention to the quality of ingredients , and a successful attempt at balance and smoothness . the mountain-filtered water imparts nothing offensive on the palate .

s : not my favorite beer aroma , its decent though . the alcohol is very present in the nose , which i do n't get in the taste . the maltiness of the beer is very present in the smell which i like .  pours a deep gold with an enormous head that retains wonderfully . perfect look .  the body is a little thin for my likes .

taste is really , really solid but the aroma was rather bizarre with a strange `` coffee-gone-bad '' funk to it or something .  the appearance is one intangible , with a thick , clumpy froth leaving gorgeous lacing down the glass . brilliant orange .  this is a good straightforward ale . light golden yellow color , a little fizzy but nothing a little harder pour into the glass did n't take care of . lighter flavor but has a nice balance for whats there . nice little hop background that comes through the nose.it 's drinkable also .

i was mildly surprised to see a stout on draft in the netherlands , but the bar came highly recommended . nonetheless , a very tasty stout , with nice dry tones and not much residual sugar .  exceptional looking beer .  feels a bit watered-down in the mouth , but flavor is there and we 're not talking corona . a little fizzy .

smell was faintly fruity , but not particularly strong . taste is extremely hop laden with a significantly dry finish . this beer is robust enough to border on a porter or stout , but exceptionally hoppy and dry to be true to the ipa style .  appearance - a very appropriate pumpkiny-orange pour capped off by an incredibly full 3-finger , subtly orange tinted off-white head . cloudy appearance . very impressive .  mouthfeel : light and highly carbonated and a bit sour and tart overall : honestly this is my first experience with fantome and it is just awful .

musty aroma . slightly funky , coffee , raisins and oak . a light tart crispness is actually nice but reveals a light brett infection in combination with the nose . medium-full body with moderately-high carbonation . good .  11.2oz foamy pillowy head flows up the glass . clumpy head slowly slides down , leaving a rather decent trail behind .  m : thin and light with average carbonation .

aroma is lacking a little , sweet , slight alcohol and hoppy , not much there . full bodied , smooth and highly drinkable considering the abv . the hops and malt are well balanced , one does n't overpower the other and this will certainly please a hophead but would also work well as an introduction to the style .  great orange/tan color with a fantastically huge head that lasted forever , leaving stupendous lacing .  medium thin body .

i got very little aroma but then i think i 'm handicapped in this department .  notes from 9/15/10 a - beautiful pour into a duvel tulip . straw/orange slightly cloudy liquid with 3 fingers of head at least . head is off white and thick/pillowy , reminds me of the foam generated iin a root beer float .  [ postscript : 18 months later , and another 6-pack of this enjoyed , the mouthfeel was much less sticky , but way too carbonated .

the aroma is very modest ( dark malt ) .  the pour is beautiful . thick like motor oil and `` black as midnight on a moonless night . '' a dark head on the beer which eventually disappears into a ring around the edge of the glass and eventually becomes headless . nevertheless , this is one of the more beautiful beers i 've seen .  it has abrasive bitterness from the start on through the finish , increasing in intensity and lasting well on into the aftertaste with stinging astringency . yes , there 's some raisin , toffee , and booze on the taste as an undercurrent that shows through on the finish pretty well ... .but absolutely nothing approaches the hoppiness here .

s - not much aroma . hint of malt .  pours a gorgeous dark dark brown . almost black with a nice brown glow around the edges of the glass .  mouthfeel - medium..maybe a little on the more watery side , but still creamy-ish .

s - muted , with some cereal sweetness , breadiness , and subtle , earthy hop aroma . t - bready , with melanoidin and dried apple .  appearance : pours a very nice hazy rust color . it looks like rising bread dough .  slightly creamy body , though it falls flat at the front of the palate . it could use ( i ca n't believe i 'm saying this ) a bit more carbonation . or more body .

poured into my westy chalice , which is much easier to find than any of their actual ales ... a : opaque brown , except when held up to a bright light : this gives a warm , deep glowing amber color . s : sweet caramel . dark malts . not bad , just undistinguished .  the look is decidedly porter-like , with a magnificent head of darker froth that would make that style proud .  ( from notes ) i picked this beer up while living in dublin , i poured it from a .5l can into a pint glass ... a : a nice roasted dark brown nearly black color , with a tannish head , decent lacing ... s : the smell is pretty weak but i am getting some faint burnt malt and slight coffee ... t : the taste is about the same except more fully roasted flavor ... m : smooth and watery ... d : a decent beer from guinness , but once you have had their special export to belgium , you wonder why they make anything else .

slightly sweet and somewhat pleasant , but nothing earth-shattering .  a- pours a very cherry red color with a full three fingers of slight red-tinted , thick white head .  good carbonation and a softly crisp , dryish , smooth medium-light bodied mouthfeel . thin , watery , sweet pale malts , sort like if you dunked a slice of white sweet bread into a glass of water , light lemony flavor with an even lighter amount of hop spiciness , a very , very mild bitterness towards the end , and a dryish sweet malty finish .

a very creamy half finger beige head quickly recedes to a nice cap s : pretty subdued , pick up some nice toasted malts along with a bit of coffee and chocolate t : all of the different flavours picked up in the aroma are present in the taste , along with a slight burnt bitterness that blends everything together m : nice and creamy , easy on the carbonation but a tad thin d : a great session beer for the cooler months .  the pour is excellent . coffee black with a tan head which seems to slowly rise well after the pour .  well carbonated and only a mild body . expecting and would have liked something a little thicker .

almost pours like a stout . very noticeable burnt or smoky smell to it . t-taste was very good .  2010 vintage poured into a nonic . pours a deep , viscous black with a thick dark khaki head .  feels light , but not as light as a lager and lightly carbonated .

s : it smells sweet and hoppy , but it 's rather light on the scent . i thought that it would be too sweet because of the scent but it 's not , it 's very nice .  probably the most beautiful pour i 've seen . sizable chocolate colored head almost `` rolled '' up the pint glass and stuck around for a long while . black as night , a little deep coffee color at the edges .  that smokiness carries over abundantly into the taste . the lesser side of this is the feel ... bit to far on the light end of things . overall though , solid rauchbier , though probably my least favorite so far of the aecht schlenkerla rauch 's .

then the cleaner aroma of chocolate was more prominant . t- big flavors of roasted malt , coffee , dark cocoa , chocolate covered raisins .  excellent head retention and lacing . surly beers always look amazing !  mouthfeel : light bodied with moderate carbonation , slightly drying leaving that coffee dryness on the palate .

aroma was decent ... lightly fruity but hardly overpowering .  appearance : jet black , nearly opaque brew with dense head of foam .  mouthfeel : the weight and carbonation do well , nothing bad to say about it , nothing extraordinary .

$ 7.99 at whole foods for a 750ml . was expecting a really good stout with the packaging and brewery location . poured gently into a pint glass , i received less than an inch of beer and the rest head , and it did not settle . i have seen other reviewers speak of nothing ut head in the cisco beers , but then rate it ok . update after contact with brewer . brewer admits to carbonation and suggests letting the beer settle , offered to send me a fresh one which he believes will not be as heavily carbonated as the one i sampled .  black as black can be . medium brown head that laces with authority . highly , highly drinkable for the style , the overbearing chocolate/coffee flavors canceling out a lot of the bitterness and making it very smooth .  the carbonation felt on the high side to me .

s : very little smell coming out of this one .  first time trying this beer . a : this is one good looking beer . red with a cream colored head . leaves good lacing throughout .  really malty tasting , also was considerably less sweet then i had expected . smelled a bit like cocoa and malt . was really lite for a porter . not bad but not my favorite porter out there . it may have been better had i let it breathe , still not a bad porter though .

a-yellow amber in color with white head s-very sour and funky . this style gets me every time t-sour and funky yet very smooth and delicious .  pours a beautiful amber with a frothy foam head with nice lacing from a 12 ounce bottle .  but overall , mouthfeel was ok. after having a couple bottles of this in the past , felt this was a terrific sixtel to kick off the summer .

the smell is veryy subdued , even as it warms . spicy with caramel and vinous malt . the fact is this is a fantastic quad , exceptionally smooth and very drinkable .  had about a one-finger head with great retention .  mouthfeel is medium bodied with low to medium carbonation . smooth , easy to drink , but gets kind of muddy in the finish like some of the other nognes i 've had , which kind of makes my mouth feel dirty , but good winter beer nonetheless .

aromas are malt , sugar , slight hops and slight medicinal . nothing strong or offensive , and nothing too exciting . taste is very smooth .  really beautiful bright color and enticing appearance in the glass .  light bodied , without much of a mouthfeel , just a very slight slickness left on the tongue . other than the mouthfeel , this was a pretty decent example of the style .

the aroma , while a little faint does have a distinct hint of vanilla . damn good porter .  it pours an almost opaque black that 's capped by an extremely creamy chocolate-colored head . but the best part is the effect given by the carbonation as it 's reabsorbed into the liquid : it looks like an hourglass , the brown bubbles `` falling '' down into the black abyss at the bottom of the glass .  mouthfeel is average , not too thin , and i think appropriate for this beer .
this winter lager looks fantastic . something in the smell puts me off a little .  looks pretty ideal actually .  mouthfeel : a little thin , but not watery .

the smell is virtually indescribable . good , but faint .  pours pitch black with a strikingly dark , lush head that , for the style at least , hangs around for a long time .  mouthfeel was on the thin side , but a creamy finish evened it out to average at best .

smelled of malt and light hops with a slight citrus finish .  awesome rocky head with great lasting power ; the color is a deep red ruby . perhaps the best head i 've ever seen .  its has a light mouth feel for a stout .

despite its billing as a coffee-brewed stout , the smell of this brew is fairly unremarkable and is perhaps a bit yeasty . what this beer lacks in smell , however , it makes up for in taste .  poured from a bottle at a good temperature getting a mammoth , foamy , super frothy , fluffy , billowy , off white , long lasting head and loads of clingy lace .  m : pretty darn thick and syrupy .

aroma was light on the hops for a double ipa , more caramel malt aroma . a very nice job .  hazy amber body , with lots of tiny-bubbled co2 trails visible . huge , thick head easily rises an inch over the rim of the glass without spilling over .  the mouthfeel on a doppelbock is a tricky thing -- too thick and you wo n't be able to drink your half-liter bottle , let alone your full liter mass .

lot 's of sweet caramel in the nose . little to no hops in the aroma .  the best look i have ever seen out of an ipa . great bronze/copper color with a great white head .  mouthfeel is ok , but a bit to thin for what i expect from a stout .

smells doughy with a bit of teriyaki ? theres also a bit of citrus and pear but i still get a bit of teriyaki , but not in a bad way . much maltier than i expected in flavor with noticable alcohol . im thinking this would go well with a smoked gouda .  great look - booming 4f frothy cream-colored head , with tons of sticky lacing ; golden amber in color , 50 % opaque , and plenty of visible carbonation .  t & m : slightly alcoholic bite at first . very fizzy taste of citrus with a somewhat sour lemony wheat taste . d : very fizzy so will fill ( bloat ) you quickly . exemplary of the style .

all in all the nose is not that strong , and falls a little short . t : sweet malt flavor is prominent . o : i think this is a solid pumpkin brew , but the aroma falls way short .  pour : not completely black , but dark with garnet highlights under the thickest , frosting like head that i 've ever seen on a porter . lasts to the end with good lacing too .  m - thin on the mouth , ok carbonation .

s : this one 's yeasty with a hint of alcohol in there which masked other things for me . t : caramelized malts and plum seem to dominate as well as a smokey taste .  black in color with a head that looks like meringue .  i thought i did n't like saisons until i tried this one . kind of a mild coconutty taste , almost pina colada like ? i 'm going to revisit this one for sure whenever i get a chance .

aroma - fruity and citrusy , almost like soap or detergent . a mish-mash of hop aromas , resulting in an okay blend .  appearance : beautiful gold with wonderful tan foam . an exceptional look by any standards .  deep red-brown color with amazing billowy off-white head : thick and lasting with good lacing s : hoppy and malty balance with yeasty notes and spices t : orange and nutmeg maltiness with a hoppy bitter finish m : a little thin , but this is towards the end of its season by now .

this beer poured a reddish amber with a very thick foamy head but suprisingly littel aroma . thi beer put up a great appearance butt eh flavor and aroma somewhat left me feeling let down .  pours dark black with one of the best foamy heads out there and there is nothing like the cascading effect smell : slight smell of roasted malts taste : very smooth and creamy .  moderate to thin mouthfeel , carbonation is ok . my only problem with this is the mouthfeel was n't as creamy as i was expecting , but overall , a very nice stout .

light chocolate and smokey aroma with coffee notes .  looks great ! lots of tan head that crowns about two fingers , along with a dark copper colored body , which has no haze in the aroma and taste i get metallic hops , a good bill of roasty malts that equate to a slight coffee and toffee quality , and a hint of chocolate .  the taste ends with a really nice strong bitterness that lingers on the palate for quite awhile . the carbonation seems to be moderate perhaps a little more on the high scale but seems to be average for the style .

decent , somewhat watery lacing s - nothing too special in the aroma category , maybe a little malt , slight lime citrus t - sweet malt with an excellent wheat finish .  it is a beautiful looking beverage .  mouthfeel : medium bodied . low carbonation .

light caramel smell with a hint of grass .  a- the settles out to a nice two fingers of off white frothy head that holds wonderfully and leaves some spots of lace at first then an epic landslide of think foam grabs hold and slowly cascades down the glass .  maybe some floral hops and a quite malty after taste which i didnt mind at all . the whole mix is very plain .

s : lightly grainy malt aromas balanced well with some slightly herbal/spicy hops and a bit of light fruitiness . a bit bland , but not bad at all . t & m : clean grainy , lightly sweet malt flavor is quickly cut by a spicy hop flavor from the saaz hops .  this beer pours a brilliant cherry amber that picks up some gold towards the edges of my tulip with a semi-thick , sustained film of slightly tan head .  it tastes excellent as it has a nice coffee and roasted taste which compliment that big hops very well , this beer is very drinkable as it doesnt have that `` back of your throat dryness '' that some ipas tend to exhibit . you could drink this all night if you were an ipa fan .

an ipa brewed with mango , pineapple , and grapefruit purees added . s : bouquet is somewhat faint , and suggests all of the fruit that are held within . there is also a nice hit of hops mingling with all of the fruit .  liquid dark bread .  carbonation is a little too pronounced .

it 's opaque and thick in apperance , but actaully quite drinkable . the smell is coffee and charcoal ... the taste is slightly acidic when it first hits the mouth , but it quickly smooths out to a rich coffee flavor .  appearance- pours a deep amber/light raisin color , slightly hazy , with one of the most fabulous heads i 've ever seen . the sheer staying power is incredible . four-plus fingers of off-white foam that settles to the likeness of half-melted marshmallows .  flavor and mouthfeel both lighter than expected , especially for a stout . medium-high carbonation .
there was nothing saison about this beer .  looks quite beautiful .  overall : mouthfeel is about standard , nothing special .

s : bouquet is a tad faint , but suggests that this will be chocolatey porter . t : semi-sweet and super rich , founders porter boasts molasses , chocolate , and caramel .  a : poured a nice clear amber & selective yellow body with a creamy one fingered head , rises nicely . the lacing on this is outstanding . t : that lasting head gives this a strong creamy hoppy taste .  the body is quite a bit thinner now after a couple of years of age . the finish is a bit astringent and dry . the astringency almost has a pine/ spruce thing going on that contributes to drying out my mouth after each sip .

aroma must be hidden beneath the foam and remains quite mellow despite its rather distinct flavors .  pours a golden color with creamy off white head that it retains very well .  m : a little thinner than i am used to for imperial stouts , but it still has a heavy body . the mouthfeel is n't is a little sharp from high carbonation , would love a creamier texture here .

s - cocoa nibs , dark roast coffee . t - lighter in flavor than expected .  pours a slightly hazed copper colour with a massive , massive tan head that foams into a mountain above the rim of the glass and hangs around for a long long time and once dissolved leaves chunks of residue on the glass . awesome stuff .  the body is a bit thinner than i would like , but then again this is a porter , not a stout , so viscosity is not a foremost requirement .

s - the aroma is very burnt , but there is some fruitiness towards the back . little aroma of yeast .  a - awesome head ! ! ! pours into crazy shapes ... brew is cloudy orange/amber color . lots of great lacing .  moderate carbonation and a light , slightly watery mouthfeel .

this beer smells of bread and malt , also catch an alcohol presence .  pours a very nice looking beer .  there is a slight floral hop scent to go along with the malt aroma that you would expect from a beer this dark . this is a flavorful lager . it 's malty without being sweet and there is just enough hoppyness to leave a bite on the tongue .

sweet caramel smelling but with a tiny hint of metal .  thanks muenchenerkindl for such an excellent extra 12 oz bottle poured into a duvel tulip an awesome midnight black with a good two fingers of tan head that settles into a large curtain of lace that lasts to the end aromas of oatmeal , malts and grains , yes almost barleywineish with a light alcohol smell oatmeal , chocolate molasses and fruit with a lite hop end note wow i like the taste almost like some sort of hybrid oatmeal stout barleywine palate is medium to thick you need to sit back , relax and sip this one .  m : nothing wild here ... medium-bodied with moderate carbonation ; hoppy finish , yet sweet and not dry .

poured a deep copper/orange with a fair bit of fog and a fluffy , thick white head.the smell was average at best and not too much interesting poking out .  first off , i rarely care about the appearance of a beer , but this one looks perfect . it 's ink black color caught my eye as i was pouring it .  it is perhaps on the thin side and sweet side and is not too complex , but has good character that hold up well .

aroma is ok , a little lemon , little funk from the new hops i think . the taste follows but more amped up .  poured golden cream-colored with a substantial head that lasted the entire drink . like the other nitro-can ales , the beauty of the drink was in its appearance above all . it has a beautiful cascading effect . there was not much of an aroma .  thin body , decent carbonation .

very nice , mahogany colored beer . low aroma-some hints of spice and maybe vanilla . the major `` spruceness '' of previous years isnt here . a very drinkable beer this time round .  i do n't usually `` 5 '' appearance but thisone i thought was perfect . a nice rich , dark golden color . a frothy , pillow-like white head that stuck around and laced oh so well .  taste- almost the same as the smell with a malt/roasted taste up front with a strong coffee finish . overall i like this brew . one of the most significant coffee smelling and tasting brews i 've had . good stuff

enjoying this beer on halloween , 2011 . i do detect the smell of pumpkin , fall spice and a touch of vanilla , but it is not that intense . t/m : what the beer lacks in scent , it more than makes up for in flavor !  tan head - quite tall and persistent . perfect .  mouthfeel is thin and creamy smooth .

generic roast and sweet malts , pretty much .  this beer pours black as night with a creamy amber foam . nice carbonation .  it 's a little too thin for my taste , but like i said i could easily drink this all night and this is why .

smell is pretty much average with hints of sugary lemon and citrus fruits .  pours a beautiful red-pink with some fizzy head that lasts for about a second and recededs to a glass that looks more like wine than anything , carbonation rising on the sides of the glass looks great .  thin bodied but slightly creamy .

pours a dark mahogany , sort of like a lighter brown ale . no discernible aromas from the beer upon the initial pour . very refreshing and smooth for an american style barley wine . at 8.5 % , probably a beer i would only have one-i enjoyed this at the end of the meal after having two two hearted ales . a nice meal , a great finish !  pours with a big and frothy head that threates to leave the glass and envelope the room ... beautiful mocha color . less than average lacing , but the head stays around to the end in a diminidhed form . the goodies beneath are a unique and cloudy reddish-brown hue that is murky and inviting .  mouthfeel was medium with a faint taste of saaz hops on the tongue . pale lager ? ! ? i might have gone with pilsner , which is a lager , plus the label mentions both ale and lager , further confusing things . the finish was unpleasant with a harsh metallic taste lingering well after the swallow .

i really appreciated that this pilsner is not the basic clear straw yellow boredom beer . 4.5 s basic pilsner smell really of some barley . 4.0 d very drinkable with interesting taste , low abv . could not be improved , really . cellar rats continues to impress with this fine pilsener .  a : very dark pour with carbonation bubbles that fall down and end up creating a long lasting dark tan , wet sand , brown head .  nose ... oh , that great `` red '' smell ... hops and spice with some sweentess thrown in for good measure , west coast floral represented well , just a great pleasant hop aroma caresed by cinnamon.. delish.. mouth etc ... carbonation then the real bite of spice and hops , a little watery at times but the flavor is fantastic , refreshing and crisp as it gets toward the end of the glass.. very enjoyable verdict ?

the aroma is okay with some caramelised malt and slightly metallic hops playing on the nose . not a lot really going on here .  ultra thick white foamy head . insane lacing . never heard of this before but based on previous reviews i included this in my order.. way to go ba .  m : the body is medium with a moderate to high level of carbonation .

mild aroma . good fine head with lots of lace .  this black beer lets a little red through when held to the light . it has a creamy , frothy tan head that fades and leaves excellent lacing .  poured chilled in large pint glass a : black , no head , not many carbs , not much lacing s : malty , hoppy , sharp in the nose ; persistent t : sophisticated dark , charcoal , nearly burned in flavor ; very hoppy ; tastes heftier than the 7 % abv . very powerful , superb black ale .

pours nicely to create a beautiful colored head with good lacing with a slight malty smell out of the glass . nice ! very good subtle mouth feel makes this beer feel , oh so drinkable .  then , the top of the head begins to condense into a creamy , rich , dense material like melted chocolate ice cream . it all settles into something picturesque , with solid sheet lacing that looks like latte foam .  mouth feel is medium bodied , but i think it could use a bit more carbonation .

this was once a distinctive brown/nut brown ale , but since being bought out , this beer has fallen quite a few notches .  poured into a tulip glass a golden orange with a two finger foam white head . great lacing and retention .  to me , this beer is more like a porter than a stout . not very creamy . the tart cherry flavor is at first a bit exciting to the tongue , but it gets old quickly . i ca n't see having more than one of these at a time . the smell of the cherry is nice the whole way through .

smell : citrusy -- but not overwhelming . overall a subtle aroma .  a nice bright and golden color , white head is two fingers thick and very dense . plenty of carbonation bubbles scampering for the top of the liquid .  appearance : nut brown , creamy white head that forms a skim coat smell : smoky ( obviously ) , very much like smoked pork : greasy and slightly metallic ; some noble hops are evident but not prominant ; tinny and some very faint fruity esters taste : predominantly smoky , with the same sort of tinny metallic character as in the nose ; no bitterness , omly smoke mouthfeel : medium body , perhaps a little on the lighter side ; little apparent carbonation ; kind of flat and a little watery this si the marzen 's little brother .

the smell left something to be desired as no flavors really stood out to me except for some alcohol . the taste though was very pleasant with coffee and chocolate extremely present all through out my sip of beer . very refreshing beer for a stout and not at all overwhelming .  this beer pours a true opaque black with a nice amount of creamy tan head that leaves tons of lacing on the glass .  m : carbonation balance is nothing special .

s : wheaty with citris smells . primary a lemon smell for me .  i had this beer poured from a bottle into a pint glass ... a : the beer pours a nearly pitch black color with a nice mocha color head , about 2 fingers , and the lacing is superb ... s : the smell is weird , it has tons of burnt malt and also a hint of citrusy american style hops ... t : the taste is interesting .  i instantly fell in love with this blond , frothy , pilsner-style beer . i had it on tap at a pizzeria chain with a seriously respectable draught list ( brixx in chapel hill , nc ) . scrimshaw has the best possible hop character as far as i am concerned -- floral without being too aggressive or bitter . some belgian-style lacing on the glass . dangerously drinkable . i 've had it from a bottle since ( okay , a few bottles ) , and it is just as great . i plan on making this the beer of summer 2011 , as it is important to have a plan .

smells dusty . pleasantly tar-ish .  a - beautiful deep ruby-orange clear color , carbonation bubbles streaming upward . 2 finger foamy , slightly off white lasting head .  mf : a bit flat , could use a boost in the carbonation department .

nose was bitter , with nothing else jumping out at me at the time .  a- dark brown with mohogany highlights..huge billowy tan head .  this harp was brewed in canada by moosehead . this is a very satisfying beer ; especially when all the over-hopped , over-malted , extreme productions . become too much ... which is the true beauty of this harp . it is straight forwardly flavorful without making great demands on the palate . lively with a clean finish . this is the first harp i have sampled in a few years , and is easily the most tasty i have ever encountered .

s - overall , a restrained nose . light amounts of 2-row and some english noble hops .  because im crazy like that and the affligem chalice was dirty . this tripel pours a cloudy deep gold with dramatic streams of big bubbled carbonation . the head is creamy and pillowy and drapes the glass in foam .  in terms of style , the mouthfeel was flawless . however , since it is packaged as a winter brew i feel it falls short of the mark . imo , the carbonation is too coarse , or the body a bit too thin , for a `` winter warmer '' .

s-not much to speak of , a little malty . t-pretty darned good . rich malt followed by a nice soapy hop bitterness . very well balanced in the malt to hop ratio .  pours a black with ruby highlights with a thick and creamy off-white head that retains well and laces the glass . it 's fun watching the nitro bubbles cascade to the top .  tasted in at the brewery on a breezy december day in tustin . aroma minimal . just a little bready . pale gold in color , minimal head . some chill haze . light body with a noticeable grain sweetness . a very easy touch of floral hops . an excellent example of a drinkable light ale .

look : black with brown ring on the bottom with a 1 inch perfect head and great retention smell : there is a bit of smoke and ash on the nose but not much else taste : figs and chocolate upfront and just a bit of breadyness in the middle and some ash on the backend mouthfeel : full body and low carbonation a great butteryness and just a bit of a dry finish overall : pretty good little dry stout .  it poured a perfect deep copper with a two-finger tan head , and it let perfect thick , tight rings of lace .  m : a little bit too light for the style but it helps the drinkability .

smell : floral = good , but not the smell i expected in this dipa . immediately curious as to the hop strains used .  appearance : the color of the beer is black and opaque . the deep mocha colored head is thick , rich , lustrous , and long-lasting .  there 's a strong taste of spices that sets the tone of the drink and towards the end of the mouthfeel it turns slightly bitter although all in all the beer feels fairly balanced .

s : do n't get much smell at all . nutty maybe ? - best i can do . d : very drinkable . too drinkable for the alcohol .  appearance this was black and thick like engine oil with a giant head that showed great retention . the foam was like lumpy shaving cream and covered the inside of my glass as it went down . awesome !  m suitably moderate to big but nothing extreme like an ris .

aromas were light for a beer so dark , gas station coffee and toffee .  a - a big thick three finger head of densely packed tiny bubbles distributes a huge amount of creamy lace on the glass , and shows outstanding retention . the lace on the glass looks like icy frost on a window in the wintertime . this looks outstanding , and gets a rare five for appearance in my book .  the mouthfeel is a little light , but not overly so .

s -malt and earthy english hops . f - excellently balanced . sweet malt is upfront and there is a buttery diacetyl nuance .  a massive four fingers of incredibly dense rocky foam fills the top of the glass , leaving an obscene mesa upthrusting in the center . merengue like tendrils of lacing rest on the sides like a heavy layer of snow .  m : very normal carbonation .

too mild .  pours a beautiful copper into my black crowes pint glass . the head lasts for the entirety of the beer leaving a wispy lacing on the glass .  this is a fantastic dark beer . if you are use to the typical light american style of beer this one probably is n't for you . however if you like a dark brewed beer with a strong flavor and finish this is the beer for you . also at $ 20 a case it is a nice money saving change of pace for a guiness drinker .

the nose was strong , but gave nothing more than an average lager sense from the aroma .  the color combination between the beer and the head is terrific ... looks sexy as hell .  4.5 m a bit on the thin side .

does n't tantelize me with its aroma tatste was very nice though , big malts throughout with hints of caramel and cherries and a slight warmth from the alcohol .  appearance : opaque pitch black with a chocolately head . beautiful .  unremarkable mouthfeel , but the drinkability is pretty solid on this one .

serving notes : english pint glass , room temp aroma : balanced malt and hops .  poured up jet black with a bit of a rocky , caramel coloured foamy head that hung around for several minutes before subsiding to a layer of khaki coloured frost . very sticky lacing looks like cake batter stuck to the sides of my glass . beautiful ! !  the lack of flavor is the most important part , it 's more like a watery , sour drink with a bit of beer added . i guess that is malt , but it 's ... light . on the bright side , it 's refreshing at first and there is no really offensive `` off '' flavor 's , i 'm not picking up any metal and it 's rather clean .

caramel malts very apparent in the nose . and it does n't have the cloying potpourri spices that turn me off of most winter-warmer brews .  was jet black with a bit of ruby shinning through on the edges . had a creamy tan 2 '' cap that stuck to the glass the entire ride down .  the taste was strong sour vinegar with some cherry and alcohol flavors . this one upset my stomach and i think this 2005 vintage was past its prime . god only knows what it was like fresh . this beer was not good and i happen to like sour beers .

a -- clear dark brown with a nice thick tan head ... very nice . s -- most disappointing thing about this beer . a mild malty smell but not much else . t -- what it lacks in smell it makes up in taste . d -- a delightful beer , a session beer for sure .  appearance : gently hazed champagne body with a soft , stiff , enormous , airy , white head with great retention .  m : a little out of style ... pretty light bodied with good carbonation .

solventy alcohol and toffee are all i really pick up in the aroma . it 's odd that i ca n't pick up the coriander in the aroma , because it 's actually quite prominent in jacobites flavour .  poured from a 22oz bomber into a tulip glass . english in style resulting in a more aqueous body with a thick creamy head .  mouthfeel : full-bodied , low carbonation . there 's an odd chalkiness .

wow , what a nice little ale ! very plesant biscuity malt flavor with a nice bitter hop presence . pours a beautiful pale orange with a large and persistant head . drinkability is sky high due to creaminess and overall refreshing quality of this beer . this is my third sampling from rogue and i have been very impressed with all three so far , ca n't wait to try more .  poured a very unusual and quite beautiful shade of ruby or perhaps garnet , quite striking visually which i was not really expecting .  aggressive fizzy carbonation .

visually it has a cloudy , amber color and a very mild nose .  an electric yellow beer with a moderate haze , the lightning white head billows to charmin-like proportions and even the inside of the bottle has a rocky , well-puffed lacing .  tastes almost like graham crackers with spicy hops m - medium everything d - very drinkable , probably the best session beer

smell : muted malt with a surprising hop presence .  highly attractive red-amber color , clear with a dispersed flow of miniscule bubbles , the head one finger deep but stays at that depth for some time .  poured into a traditional english mug , typically reserved for a cream ale at my favorite pub in downtown minneapolis , lyon 's pub . after removing the orange slice that i did n't think to ask without , the taste is of wheaty malt and orange rind . this beer goes down quite easy . a great summer drink and heads and shoulders above blue moon . not being from the midwest , it is n't available to me or it would become my new summer session beer .

faintly smells of peppermint and pine .  the brew is bright light gold with a magnificent , thick creamy head that slowly dissipates to leave thin bubbles and a slight lacing around the glass .  the color was the only thing remotely impressive about the beer i thought , it was a fine dark reddish color with a medium body , there was almost no head ( maybe a half inch ) . this beer has a very weird taste , almost like bubble gum mixed with some fruit and spices . for me this is typical of magic hat , i only really enjoy the heart of darkness . the after taste was even funkier than the initial flavor , i doubt i 'd drink this again .

i was n't too impressed with the aroma . the taste is very clean and refined .  appearance : beautiful , golden , clear liquid with sparkling , bubbles that rise to a frothy head .  the feel is a little to light , almost watery .

a mild caramel and malty aroma .  a uber-carbonated beer , took the barternder a good ten minutes of pouring to get me a full glass . huge white head , fix fingers of head with an awesome swirl on top sticking up sevearl inches over the glass , reminds you of a ice cream cone swirl , so gorgeou . head falls in chunks , great lacing ... the aroma is light caramel on the nose with corn , light finish , i was expecting to get skunk where is it ?  m : medium but complex body with minimal carbonation .

smell was inhibited by the lack of head . faint/sweet . taste was complex and full . medicinal qualities were evident . overall the best porter i have tried .  eggenberg spezial dunkel pours a gorgeous , very dark clear red-brown with a dusky thin head ; no lacing .  this beer drinks very easily ; it is actually pretty light on the mouthfeel , a little creamy smooth , but mostly just light .

smell was the weak point , malty for sure , little hop in the smell . taste was way over expectations . very clean crisp flavor , hops were decently balanced with malt and everything gelled well .  on-tap at flying saucer served in a tulip glass an almost opaque not-quite black with a decent frothy light tan head that lasts and leaves great lacing on the glass .  very mild flavor and mouthfeel , but very lively and well carbonated .

the aroma is more subdued than i expected - sweet caramel malts , alcohol , and some grapefruity , piney hops .  presentation : it was poured from a 14.9oz/440ml nitro or widget can into an imperial ( nonic ) pint glass . appearance : it pours slowly and extremely foamy with an abundance of tiny tan bubbles . after a minute or so , the bubbles settle on top of the beer which is a lovely honey amber colored liquid . the head that forms is supper creamy , slightly oily and light tan in color . the lacing slides down the sides of the glass just above the head .  a bit light bodied with ample carbonation .

mild hoppy aroma .  a - one of the thickest heads i have ever seen , looks like lemon meringue pie ... also reminds me of a giant thunderhead with a tornado of carbonated bubbles going from the head to the bottom of the glass that will not quit . very cloudy yellow as the head begins to settle .  mouthfeel was fine . a little thin - i think that a big , thick mouthfeel would accentuate the pumpkin pie-like characteristic that i think they 're going for .

aroma is understated , but it 's all about the flavor .  pours a pitch black color with a thin brown head into my glass .  very easy to drink ! it has the feel of any other wheat beer , but the watermelon taste is so unique that it simply floored me . initially , i thought the color seemed very artificial which made me expect an artificial flavor . there is little up front beyond a generic wheat beer , but in the aftertaste lies a brilliant watermelon flavor ! it is easy to drink and not very filling . it is slightly more alcoholic than your run of the mill macrobrews making it possible to drink a great many of these at any given time . it 's a good beer to give to new beer drinkers . it 's an excellent example of how diverse craft beers can be !

08/02/08- purchased at the liquor store down the street from the motel we stayed at in akron , oh . presentation- 12oz bottle , forgot to look for freshness info . smell- smells not unlike most macros but not quite as corny and more of a malty caramel scent to replace the nasty corn syrup you usually smell .  this brew poured an opaque black colored body with a dark brown head that was mostly lasting .  body seems to lighten a little on the swallow , maybe just the ease of consumption but takes away on the mouthfeel score for me .

the aroma brings caramel malt with a rubbing alcohol overtone on citrus hop .  wow , this beer looks friggin great .  slightly watery with a dry finish , a la guinness . medium effervescence . nice warming alcohol bloom . relatively rich for a weak body .

after reading these reviews , i must have gotten a `` skunked '' one . this was the worst ipa ive ever tasted .  a dark caramel brown body under a 2 cm head which took several minutes to dissipate but it leaves nice lacing on the glass . a solid look for my favorite style of beer .  a bit thin in the mouthfeel but nothing off-putting .

s - clean aroma of malt and some mild spicy , woody notes with just a hint of herbal/citrus hops . t - fruity , herbal hop character up front , very round and smooth . overall i enjoyed this one , though i am sorry to say that the aroma is a weak point ; it is nice but , for some reason , far too weak .  cdkrenz , thanks for the trade ... poured into a pint glass this brew has the best red amber color that has a tint of ruby when held to the light . the head is a reddish cream color that settles to a thin cap with nice sticky lacing all on the glass .  it had a medium feel to it in my mouth with ok carbonation .

slight roasty malt aroma .  pours a nice hazy dark copper with a three finger white head that subsides to one finger .  m - medium-bodied , but a bit too hoppy on the finish to be as refreshing as it should be .

a little roasted or toasted grains in the aroma with a definite nuttiness .  poured from a 11.5oz bottle into a cigar city pint glass ... a - pours black with a two finger light brown head . head retention and lacing are excellent ... s - coffee and dark roasted malts dominate here ... t - dark roasted malts , chocolate , and coffee .  great finish , though a little thin .

smell was not overly pungent as i one would expect with a double ipa with 85ibuu ... huge hop taste right off the bat , secondary flavors of hops , followed by more hops not much if any malt to balance ; very long finish .  listening to the brabanonne as instructed on the label while enjoying this - although the hymn is only about a minute long , and this certainly takes quite a bit longer to finish ... seal brown , impenetrable liquid , with a hefty sandy brown cap which recedes to a thick mocha-like finger . superb retention , especially for the abv .  m : thin , fizzy and cutting .

its a beer both my beer snob friends and i enjoy yet is easily drunk by those who may be timid when it comes to new beers . stella is an exceptional lager as far as lagers go . it is crisp , refreshing and contains little of that lager signatre taste .  it was 3.35 euro for 0.5 l. slainte ! a : hazy straw , fluffy white head , lots of lace .  lighter bodied , thinner carbonation .

smells faintly of caramelized malts and honey with some bready yeasts- pretty light and simple . tastes similar to the nose , only more intense . highly drinkable , easy and refreshing .  cloudy dark amber color with a huge frothy head and excellent lacing .  finishes dry with light floral hoppiness m : light bodied and medium carbonated .

thin mouthfeel , delicate tingly carbonation , confused almost skunky nose , but a surprisingly true taste . typical over-ripe banana nose met cleanly with light aromatics .  honestly , if i had n't read the label i would have sworn i had poured a stout from the looks of this one . a full two inch head that rose above the rim of the glass and held it for quite a while .  m : yeah , i guess .

on-tap at flying saucer , raleigh nc ... attractive brown nectar with a thin almond head . aroma is rather weak : some pale malts , caramel , a bit of hops , and not much else .  pours an ominous black with dark brown head that is thick & creamy . simply amazing appearance .  mf : thin for a baltic porter , the big flavor makes up for this , medium carbonation d : this beer has a ton of things going on and i must say it is well executed .

not much going on in the aroma . a little malt not much else .  bottle poured into my fancy new samuel adams glass appearance : huge white fluffy head exceptional retention , crystal clear amber color .  m - light to medium body , medium carbonation . very slight harsh bitterness lingers on the back of the tongue .

smells mapley , a little too sweet . tastes mapley and nutty with a subtle , bitter finish -- really nice .  a massive white foamy head greets me like a beer commercial . great retention and a crazy amount of sticky lacing .  appearance - horseblanket smell - horseblanket taste - horseblanket mouthfeel - horseblanket just kidding about the appearance and mouthfeel ( kinda ) .

s- not a lot to speak of . weaker spices overall , maybe with a slight maltiness . overall smooth , with a slight hoppy ending d- lovely christmas beer .  a vigorous pour yields a fast-falling one finger head , large bubbled . it forms a nice glass ring . the body is a wonderful near-opaque black , with ruby highlights only when potently backlit .  a little grassy , little grainy and a bit watery . slight softness to feel from carbonation , otherwise not that soft and too thin .

s-light oaky notes with a bit of sweet malt .  pours a dark brown with a nice one inch of tan head after a gentle pour . retention was excellant with plenty of lacing .  m- not a bad mouthfeel i just felt it to be average . light on the tongue , a little too dry and yet somewhat of a lingering aftertaste .

pours a dark ruby/amber colo with a nice big one finger light yellow head an lots of light white lacing . nose is very light on this sadly .  gorgeous . almost looks like the ultimate kriek . just perfect .  it was a little over carbonated for my likes but still had a great feel to it in my mouth .

now quaffing : ephemere - apple presentation : 12oz . i always anticipate anything new i get to try from unibroue , which is absolutely a world class brewery . the nose is faint with an apple sweetness . this is a very balanced beer with a definite apple theme that is not overdone . overall this is a very unique beer that is extremely drinkable .  lace everywhere , and leaves big rings as i down the pint . head has great retention , too .  i poured this guinness into my tumbler at 45 degrees . the beer was very black and bore out a big tan head . the beer smells like a guinness as it should . the taste was big molasses but the brew had a bit of a dry finish . i like the beer and will buy again .

very mild roasted malt scent , not much is jumpking out at you .  on tap at the stuffed sandwich a : peach/golden hazy color . head is solid , 1/4 inch layer of whipped cream on top of the body s : lots of funk .  m - nice light carbonation and creaminess , but the body is a little light and watered down .

smells like a good belgian pale ale , but the aroma is a bit weak .  this beer is a beautiful , deep golden color . produces a moderate head that dissipates pretty quickly .  light in body , but crisp and sufficiently dextrinous in mouthfeel to help lend excellent drinkability . lightly carbonated . perhaps a bit thin , but otherwise outstanding .

aroma reminds me of hallertauer hops and it is blended with a dry toasty malt flavor and a weird ester i am not familiar with .  pours dark and thick like motor oil with a thick fluffy dark brown head .  very little carbonation , the beer feels light but also dense .

other lightly caramelized , toffee malts join to round it out . t - the smell gave great forewarning to the taste . here is where the smokiness begins to fight back , but again not overpowering . o - this beer was near its best by date and therefor leads me to believe it lost a little bit of its fresh smokiness and began to mellow out .  bottle : poured a murky brown color ale with a super huge foamy head with good retention .  m : very medium-light body and a slightly bitter but almost watery finish .

s : not particularly smelly . light notes of hops , caramel malt and faint mint . t : citrus hops dominate .  bottle , a : pours black with a frothy tan head , gobs of lace , great retention .  appearance : high carbonation , 1/4 inch head , cloudy , yellowish-green smell : wheat , and melon taste : very watermelon -- almost like a watermelon jolly rancher , bready wheat , with some small hops near the end mouthfeel : sweet , light/smooth body , high carbonation , slight bitter taste in the end .

i do n't get too much aroma but it 's certainly a pleasant coffee presence . the flavor is wonderful . there'the typical fruity sweetness you come to expect from an alt .  on tap at the gingerman in austin dark gorgeous amber to brown pour with a creamy nitro like lasting head .  carbonation is too high , but it tastes pretty clean and fresh .

it poured a very nice chestnut brown clear ale with a cream coloured head that lasted throughout the experience . the smell was fairly non-existant , but was more than made up for with the taste which was a very pleasent maltiness with a nice subdued sweetness . alcohol not in your face ; overall a very nice ale with good `` drinkability '' .  poured deep black as midnight with a huge creamy head the would not fade till the end .  m : very carbonated .

s-not much of a smell at all . i was afraid that i was going to be disapointed , but ... t-wow !  batch 8158 this is what a stout should look like . pitch black , thick bodied and a tan head with ample lacing .  thanks kplynch for the bottle . color is orange amber with a variety of floral hops hitting the aroma . it 's on the lighter side , but tasty . just not really living up to the imperial in ipa . i 'd call it a well balanced , smooth ipa with notes of citrus and floral hops ...

it poured a dark brown but did n't have strong smell to me . i 'm not sure if i was just in the mood for a stout , but this surely hit the spot .  this beer poured into my pint glass absolutely beautifully . it was a brilliant , clear , amber color and the head pillowed over he rim of my glass like a thundercloud .  mouthfeel : light for darker beer . nothing special . but as in mouthfeel , nothing here will blow your brains out .

s : weak smell , slightly sweet and malty a : perfect blend of very subtle bitterness with a perfect amount of woody sweetness . d : an excellent amber .  one of the best looking brews i know of . deep chestnut brown-to-black . lovely , long-lasting , frothy-creamy , cream-colored head . good with food , on a hot day as a thirst-quencher/heat beater ( really !  m - not bad , but a little thinner than i was hoping for .

no head , just a small ring around the top ... s : kind of nutty , some sweet candy smell , no smoke that i can tell ... t : sweet malt very quickly fading to a spicy smoked flavor .  a - this brew is a black as i 've ever seen any beer . it is the perfect black . this has the looks by which all other stouts should be measured . ~ this is a stellar example of what a stout should be .  m : very light carbonation but there is just a bit to give the beer some levity .

pours a very dark and to me pleasing color with a fairly good head that does'nt stay long.smell is kinda malty and very slightly spicey .  wow , the head on this beer is darker than most beers i 'm drinking these days . beautiful chocolate brown head and dark , almost syrupy-pouring beer . the body in this beer reminds me of double bastard , but the flavor is ( of course ) a more chocolatey , coffee taste .  m - nothing really too exciting here . the bottle i got was not really crisp , not really flat , not thick or thin , a little silky do to the alcohol , but nothing to write home about ... d - i just noticed that i 'm killing off a bottle of this stuff by myself ... thank god it 's a cool night , this will warm me right up .

pours out a dark orange , w/ a really thick light peach head , takes a bit to fill the mug . kinda gives off a herbal smell , a bit of pear in there too ( at least that 's what it smells like to me ) , though that does n't stay for long .  reviewed from notes taken 4-02-2010 served on nitro at the left hand tasting room a - black with red highlights and a thick , dense off-white head that lasts the whole glass .  speaking purely from personal preferance , this beer looks about as close to perfect as any i 've had . spice and hops stand out in the nose . nice balance of malt , hops , and spices . a little thin-bodied -- this beer 's only flaw .

s : very faint hop aroma . a little weak for this style . t : good layered hop flavor throughout the drink .  a creamy , marshmallowy , eggshell white head foams up about 1 cm and rests effortlessly on the surface . very nice appearance !  the body is light and the carbonation is very high .

almost non-existent aroma . flavor is bitter . sorta reminds me of a pacific nw pale ale meeting a stout .  a : slightly hazy orange light copper color with pillowing white head . great head retention especially considering the abv .  mouthfeel is slightly thin , with lower carbonation , not bad .

s- citrus , roasted malt and some hint of caramel . t - hoppy , citrus fruits , malt .  a- this is midnight black with really dark reddish brown head that consumes 1/2 the glass .  body is a little thin for an oatmeal stout , but it still has the smoothness . carbonation feels a little too heavy for this style i think .

a : beautiful light amber with just enough carbonation . s : not a whole lot , which is bit disappointing . beautifully sweet malt backbone . d : a damn good lager .  amazingly translucent .  felt a little weak in the mouth , not much texture .

aroma is minimal and somewhat generic .  pours with a huge , frothy , slightly off-white head . long lasting and leaves a beautiful lacing down the glass .  medium to thin in the body . i thought the carbonation seemed a bit to high and lessened my enjoyment of this brew .

s : it almost has a little hint of a skunk scent though i think it is something else . yeasty , sweet , fruity . not amazing though .  bought a few extra as well . excellent pour , a thick foamy white head that lasts ages and leaves thick lacing on the mug . nice deep golden color .  this beer contains the same yeasty , yummy taste as other delirium beers . as a series , their three beers do n't go out of their way to be different from the others . in my opinion , tastes just like tremens with more color ( it looks like carbonated jack daniels ) and more seasonal flavor ( smells of strong caramel and tastes much more tart and spicy than other deliriums ) . had this a month or so ago in a 750ml bottle from a local pub , and it was labelled `` noel '' . to me , it tasted slightly different , or maybe because that night it was my first beer .

not much of an aroma , but what i could smell hinted lightly of a wine rather than a beer . it is a light bodied beer with a definite warmth about it .  great retention and excellent lacing .  and a bit thin d-easy and enjoyable , drinks almost like a session ale .

s : not much of a nose , but some good roast notes . t : great mix of roasted malt bitterness and sugary sweetness here .  a - this beer looks great . very light pale color , pours nice white head , great lacing too .  mouthfeel is a little thin , but the taste more than makes up for it .

hoppy with a touch of citrus , this beer has some kick and an exceptionally smooth finish . if i had to pick something to quibble about , it would be the smell . but the finished product is very impressive ; i would n't change a thing .  a : pours a very deep brown , nearly black , completely opaque . a strong 2+ finger head forms pretty tight and holds nicely .  the mouthfeel is clean and crisp , with less body than i 'd hoped for .

it sounded like the head was full of a certain snappy , crackly and poppy cereal . smell : surprisingly little smell for a beer of this style .  i loved the way this beer looked in my glass , beautiful amber/red color , nice head , and lacework was plentiful.not really like a scottish ale except in color , but then the labelling on the bottle acknowledges this .  m : for a stout the mouthfeel is awfully simple , though the sweet notes add some much needed depth .

overall presentation was spot on s : grains , feeble stale coffee , touch of chocolate sweets m : mostly barely and light malts . creamy and super slick d : yes , very drinkable and inviting  stone old guardian ( early 2008 ) is a crystal clear , sparkling , viscous , red-orange-brown ale with a frothy light beige head with oily bubbles . the head has an eggy consistency and leaves great lacing .  it does leave with bit of a skunky after-taste but its a small aspect of this otherwise delicious beer , m-medium carbonation with a slight watery finish d-the taste seems to lose its quality but it does n't seem to take too much of a dive . its a very thick beer so it does seem to go down slowly .

smell is on the light side , but acceptable and it 's hard to pinpoint and specific aromas . goes down really smooth . taste is typical dark lager which is pretty darn good and slight sensation or bittterness .  appearance- beautiful two finger head .  i felt this beer was too carbonated and hence it was too slick and creamy in my mouth .

it is a nice , rusty amber color with a hint of spice in the smell . it tastes great-almost like a brown ale with a nutty after taste .  pretty great looking beer overall .  well balanced m : a little coppery and bitter .

honey , caramel and dark roast coffee taste . not alot in the nose , slight hint of coffee .  carbonation looks extremely well done , and the streams are impressive . good appearance .  the body seems a bit watery , but matches well with the rest of the beer and makes this highly drinkable .

pours golden with a little haze , 1.5 finger of head , leaves beautiful lacing . smell , a little hops , kinda watery some yeast , ca n't make out anything specific taste : piney hops with some bite , pretty much just hops , finishes with alcohol notes that remind me of rum , warms a little body is medium , carbonation is pretty high , very crisp . leaves a little oily finish .  pours a really beautiful , off white head . sticks around the entire time , leaves a substantial bit of lacing on the sides of the glass . color is golden amber , looks fairly well carbonated .  mouthfeel is very syrupy and cloying with a potent kick of alcohol .

smell is of yeasty esters with a grainy background . there is a hint of a vinous character in the smell , a characteristic of the yeast i think . taste is smooth but rich and complex dry roasted maltiness with an earthy character and a hint of bittersweet .  appearance : pours a crystal clear pale gold with a fluffy white head on top . the head settles to a full cap with tons of spider web lacing covering the entire glass .  mouthfeel : does n't feel bad , just tastes bad . decent body and texture .

aroma is pure fresh hops and lemon . very faint sweaty sock smell unfortunately .  in the pint it is as black as night with a substantial foamy tan head .  m - my only complaint about this beer , wish it would thicken up a bit . approriate carbonation .

s- a fair whiff of rasberry , very subtle but nothing special . t- a hearty punch of cereal flavors starts out and ends with a nice sweet rasberry burst that lingers pleasently .  two-finger brown head on top settles quickly into a dense , creamy cap that has ridiculous retention . this one looks simply amazing .  mouthfeel was pretty average drinkability was pretty good i could see myself having another one .

this was followed by a slightly disappointing nose , a mixture of both hops and malts , typical of a scottish ale , and a hint of burnt caramel , but nothing to write home about . a very drinkable beer , it tasted quiet old fashioned , like a pint of 70~ / 80~ before it became very commercialised .  appearance : deep brown with a large head with good retention .  very thin body and i could easily put away six of these . i feel it is a little thin overall and that would be something i would like to see changed .

bready and somewhat sweet aroma along with some mild citrus hops . very nice and certainly refreshing .  pours a jet black , very opaque , big frothy khaki head , excellent lacing .  m : smooth , full-bodied , but the lack of carbonation makes it a bit watery , the booze can stand out at times . d : this is certainly a tasty beer , but it is very expensive , and at the end of the day i prefer regular old viscosity more , especially with it 's nicer carbonation , body , and the fact that it is considerably cheaper .

the aroma is a bit weak , with notes of raisin and other dark fruit plus mild alcohol .  pours a very black with a beautiful 2 finger milk chocolate colored head that leaves sticky mapping on the glass as you drain it .  m -- maybe i should n't have drank this after sipping on a j.w . its not quite what i would call `` watery , '' but it could use a little more body . carbonation levels are fine .

s : bready malt with a hint of alcohol . d : very drinkable , heafty for sure , but also drinkable .  the lacing was exceptional ... a very impressive pour .  definitely lacking in mouthfeel - expected something fuller and creamier .

if you are not a fan of fruit beers i suggest you try this one . the smell does have a strong apricot smell . but you get a feeling that its a fake extract and not apricot puree or some thing close to natural . there is a malt scent that is quite assertive as well .  this fine brew has a big fluffy dense head and lacing that sticks to the glass .  the feel is a little too thin .

terrific lacing s - not much hint as to the flavors within . some piney hops , little else t - sour candy flavor , a slight burnt , with a bit of a crisp finish . enjoyable ale with a bit more than just hops going on .  pours pitch black with a 2-finger ever-lasting head that leaves beautiful rings of lacing on the glass .  medium body , but maybe a bit thin , moderate carbonation .

underwhelming . t- similar to the smell of course .  a-pours a dark as night black with a coffee coloured two fingered head . lacing is incredible . the cap lasts the whole way down as well .  sampled this beer at founders own tap room . the beer was way too sweet . the malts from the stout style could not overcome the maple and and sweetness from the high gravity . that rarely happens , i almost never orphan a beer . founders has many beers that are excellent , this was not one of them .

i did n't get a lot on the nose here , just a little metallic note that messed with the subtle roasted malt .  creamy off-white head with rising bubbles . fluffy head - lacing is moderate - all lasting several minutes .  mouthfeel : very light/somewhat watery with a high degree of carbonation .

aroma - malty , some smokiness and coffee aromas . some yeast influence , but brief . not bad , just not inspiring . great .  pretty much a textbook appearance .  the only place i would knock it down is in the mouthfeel .

not much aroma that i can pick up , a touch of sweet maltiness though .  appearance : great looking dark lager with gorgeous dark hue , nice lacing , and medium carbonation .  the mouthfeel is medium and slightly watery with some sharp carbonation .

good taste and average smell but nothing real distinctive .  a : pours a hazy bright yellow , looking like a hay field . provides a nice 2 finger foam head with superb retention . there is a thick layer of lacing as well .  lacks a good bite . it 's dry and nibbles , but i want a good bite in my iipa . not that this is bad , just a bit short . easy drinking , though .

aroma is a slight improvement , with some great berry and cream characters backed by a heavy perfume of booze .  a : nearly faultless . rich mahogany color , incredibly puffy 1 '' head that lasts forever , nice lacing .  m - somewhat thin to medium bodied but with just the right hoppy aftertaste to leave my mouth tingling for another drink .

when i pored it into the pint glass it was a little on the pale side for my taste and the smell was a tiny bit weak .  poured a jet-black color , the color of motor oil mixed with molasses and appeared to have the same consistency . small , creamy head definitely laced the glass throughout .  mouthfeel is a bit dry , but that does n't really take away from it 's drinkability .

very mild nose . just very faint hints of malt with some whiffs of alcohol and spice . mild touches of biscuit , big hits of caramel , very subtle touches of molasses , light fruit touches , alcohol and even some faint touches of honey .  despite a slow pour , a prodigious , rocky tan head of 3-4 '' was produced in my glass . a great looking brew !  m : well , that 's where i 'm a bit disappointed . medium body , with mid carbonation .

good tasting beer that is easier to drink than many with similar appearance and style . recommended with beef ( i first drank this along with a porterhouse steak ) . at 6.9 % , you start to get that aftertaste typical of higher abv beers , but it is n't as strong or undesirable as it can be in say , at 10 % beer .  a : it 's a dark amber or bronze color that is brilliantly clear . the head is a foamy eggshell white that stands about a finger and a half . a whole lot of lacing !  first sip reveals a mild smooth body and fine rolling carbonation . the body gets a little watery on the finish , but it is a mild and the brew goes down very easy and would be an excellent session beer .

not much on the aroma side , but the taste is classic bock ; all malt without any real hops influence , but not sweet .  pours dark black colour with a nice medium tan head . great head retention and lacing of the glass . awesome stuff .  aside from the dry end this is an easy to drink beer with an average mouth .

overall , the smell is nice , but rather faint . the aroma leaves a little to be desired , but overall it 's got just a touch of everything - maltiness , hoppiness , spices , dryness , sweetness and carbonation .  has little carbonation and a small whitish head that dissipates into a milk mustache ... a beautiful auburn color that diffracts the light .  m - i tried not to destroy by palate by keeping this beer in my mouth for an extended time , so i really ca n't comment on this .

smell is not all there , i expected a little bit more . taste is excellent ... a light beer with a complex taste that is somewhat supprising .  at first glance i fell in love with the rich amber color .  i saw this on the top of a shelf in the back of a local beer store and it was not priced but i decided to buy it and give it a try seeing who i never hear of it , i think i bought it for a quarter . i was very suprised when i poured it out , it was a nice pale ale and it was full of hops aroma and flavor . when i drank it i just sat back and sipped it tring to enjoy every drop . well done .

aroma - has a bready malty base with hints of spice and yeast . kind of short-lived , the scents are light but steady , even in a belgian glass . mouthfeel - sturdy feel , moderate carbonation , well done for the style .  appearance : wow ... best head ever .  good flavors , with excellent roasted grains and a huge creaminess ; very little detectable hops , which was fine ; perhaps just a bit too much on the creamy , sugary side . a little rough , going down , but not too bad ; it just would n't be an all-the-time beer because of this .

s-not so good . not much there ... . balanced carbo .  appearance - rich dark amber brown with a cream head . beautiful label on bottle .  complex . looks like an ale , drinks like an ale , finishes like an apricot wheat . the first time i had this was in burlington vt with a plate of mussels . i could n't get over the intrigue of this brew . i totally forgot about the mussels until my second glass .

something along the lines of ginger ale or dish soap and an unidentifiable frutiness . fresh water and overall clean . not quite as roasty as the nose suggests , but roasty nonetheless . the nose is a little weird and does n't quite reflect the taste , but no big deal .  decent retention , a good amount of lacing . excellent clarity and a brown/reddish color .  m : smooth but it has a ton of carbonation which i 'm not a huge fan of .

smell in the glass does n't amount to much when chilled , only a faint roasty malt . when swirling the dregs in the bottle , there was a plummy smell , like a baltic porter . this is a perfect session stout if you are so inclined .  11.2oz bottle a- pours a dark brown color with a huge light tan head that sticks around forever and leaves a lot of retention along the glass . this is a really pretty pouring beer .  m : the body is medium and the carbonation is low to medium i suppose .

the aromas seem a bit subdued .  a - probably the best color i have ever seen in a beer . a deep ruby red with hints of pink and orange . truly reminded me of a sunset on the horizon .  my sister always goes on vaction to mexico and says this is her favorite beer . i collect 40oz bottles have about 150 in my collection , so when i saw this in a mexican resturant i was happy to say the least . i got my chance to drink this beer and add a new bottle to my collection . beer was smooth and pretty good for being on 4 % alch , was suprised that it was dark in color . taste was like other mexican beers , but i liked this more , due to it being `` rare '' only problem is the price i paid $ 15.00 for this 40oz bottle .

smell : smells strongly of roasted barley with hints of chocolate .  outstanding frothy finger of head atop a beautiful , nearly opaque mahogany body .  m/d - a little thin , though probably appropriate for a session beer .

very low aroma of light malt and hop . flavor is rich , thick sweet malt with hints of fig and raisin , also some cocoa and caramel .  the head holds awesome retention and lacing on the glass is crazy . really a near perfect looking beer .  mouthfeel was slightly on the thin side , not quite watery , but close .

nose was rather on the mild side , exhibiting some hints of clove and chocolate . too understated , though . overall : 4 appearance : 5 | smell : 3 | taste : 4 | mouthfeel : 4 | drinkability : 4 840  the beer is an incredibly dark ruby color .  m : medium body that could use more carbonation .

good flavor coming from the black and chocolate malt . nothing overwhelming on aroma . a fine mild flavor finish .  a - opened the sucker and out came massive foam . poured slowly into duvel , tons of head . lots of sticky lace . brown , fairly clear dark tea color .  overall , a bit thin .

perhaps my fondness for this old friend clouds my judgement and raises the ranking but i do love to get nostalgic and revisit this stout . as usual , there was not much smell associated with the initial pour . i know there are better stouts out there and i am told what we get in the states is a pale comparison to what you would find in ireland but this will always remain a favorite .  367th review on ba bottle to tulip 750 ml cap & cork 086/477044 app- sunshine yellow with a gigantic three finger bell filling head . very good looking saison .  palate was medium to light bodied , lively carbonated , watery onto a dry finish , some slight metallic feel .

nose is burnt malt with some coffee .  pours a shade or two off midnight black , could n't see any light penetrate this at any point . dense body , and an even denser and creamier mocha head . heavy retention and lace . gorgeous stout , even left me with a stout mustache .  m : medium body is dry and chalky , with a bit too much fizz .

aroma is very faint , but i 'm in a typical college bar so i would be surprised if i could smell anything beyond the stale beer , ashtray and urinal cake . anyhoo , what i could detect was some sweet malt , faint fruity esters , and some flowery noble hops .  -very black body with a tall , fluffy brown head with a nitro look to it . good lacing as well -at first it is mostly bourbon ... as it warms , chocolate comes through as well as some roast , vanilla and some warmth -milk chocolate throughout the taste .  taste is creamy , though the mouthfeel is a tad on the thin side but no so much it hurts the experience .

smell : light and sweet . maybe a slight hint of golding hops , but just a hint . taste : sweet and chocolatey .  appearance was exceptional ruby-red to light brown with a frothy head smell was somewhat bland more so than i had expected for a beer of this quality and reputation , and the drinkability was limited by its hefty alcohol percentage otherwise , an all-around outstanding brew that certainly warrants recognition enjoyed this one recommended  it starts out thin with the wheat malt taking center stage then gets spicier as it goes . it finishes with a lot of banana and touch of yeast that lingers a fair amount for a lighter beer . the rest : a solid , tasty wit ; it checks all of the boxes of the style , and does it pretty well .
