hazy . s : little bit of caramel & pine . for some reason i 'm not getting much here . t : heavy on the pine , then some wood & grapefruit flavors . this beer is really damn bitter . another good west coast ipa ... does n't really distinguish itself from the rest , but worth the $ 11 a six pack .  gorgeous pour ! deep , dark orangehoneysuckle gold with a giant white head .  i found the mouth feel a little thin , not as think and syrupy , as i would expect , but it 's a minor complaint .

the aroma is not very strong at all , typical of canadian lagers . smells pleasant enough though , not offensive .  a lovely muddy chocolately copper colour with a toffee fudgy coloured 4 finger head , that poured on like ice cream once the yeast sediment was mixed and poured on top , it couldnt look better to be . lots of lovely brussel lacing , solid head lasting throughout the beer .  taste is malty sweet goodness with a light hop finish . this is a nice session beer very drinkable . it has the malty sweetness i have been craving lately mmm .
the smell is malty and brown sugar like . not really sure .  pours a very dark brown with a frothy head that lasts forever .  m : higher carbonation than expected , medium-full bodied .

it looks good enough , and has decent aroma but has terribly unbalanced flavour .  perfectly pictured stout pour -- jet black , no light peering through , dark tan everlasting head with perfect lacing -- from this season 's ( 2005-2006 ) version .  this is a bit over carbed to be true to style i think but still very drinkable .

excellent drinkability .  pours a hazy bright golden yellow with thick , billowy bleach-white head that stands up like meringue .  body though is a bit thin and watery which is a little disappointing .

the smell was thin and hard to pick up , what i could pick up was very fruity with an even thinner malt aspect hidden in the rear of the nose . it should be noted that as the beer warmed the smell got stronger and easier to pick up on .  500ml bottle served in a shaker glass.enjoyed on oct11.melon yellow in color.haze appearance.white close & dense crown.good retention leaving lasting lacing collars.citrics & hints of melon to the nose , some banana hues.sour upfront then a pleasant sweet malty flavor comes , subtle spicy hues too.slightly astringent notes.medium body.medium carbonation.rough but gentle finish.refreshing.well balanced flavors .  m : thick , creamy , almost sticky . a bit too heavy for me .

d - the aroma was n't all there for me , but otherwise , a very tasty , drinkable stout .  the appearance is on par with massive amounts of bright white head , with an orangish golden body , which of course is quite hazy .  m - bubbly and medium on the tongue .

the neglected little brother of negro modelo , modelo especial , is an exceptional crisp clean summer beer .  black , looks fantastic .  some balancing earthy hops mix with the spiciness of the rye to finish this with a satisfying dry ending . the mouthfeel is medium bodied , with a slightly astringent creaminess . there is just enough of a light sharpness to the carbonation to keep this crisp in the mouth .

s : quite a malty smell . caramel ? t : very sweet , but in a good way .  this poured a perfect beautiful black leaving a nice thick tan head that lingered for a while .  quite thin and watery at first , yet it seems to improve in time .

not a strong aroma to it , smell of an indistinct caramelized fruit . a pitch black beer befitting the stout description .  pours an opaque dark-chocolate brown with a thick , creamy fine-bubbled pale tan head .  this is miles better than early versions when moo brew was just getting off the ground . nose is very expressive and lifted with intense oranges and tropical fruit . the flavours are much more serious and show genuine pale ale chracter ; firm , bitter hops , some piney notes , but surprsingly the fruit offered on the nose is a bit hard to find . doesnt harm the beer though . well worth its percentile rating .

the aroma is rather mild , it has some spiciness to it , but is fairly unimpressive . nice complex taste -- some spiciness , but also tastes of sweet malt , bitter hops , and fruit .  pours a beautifully clear golden orange with a solid 2 finger head that melts slowly and remains sticky .  appearance : very cloudy , much more so than an average wheat beer . smell : smells faintly of hops and strongly of yeast and fermentation . it tasted a lot like a bad experiment of mine where i mixed some peach cider with some yuengling because i was sick of drinking yuengling . the only difference was that instead of having a peach flavor , the flavor was more like mixing apple juice and a wheat beer . very difficult to drink since i resented every swig .

bit of a macro beer smell to it.. uh oh .  a fantastic extra from a fantastic trader rhong187 a really dark burnt chocolate with a dark mocha head that caps a two fingered head that does n't look like it is going to be going anywhere anytime soon . as the beer gets drank and warms down , head stays and turns a deep ruby red alot of carbonation coming from the bottle and gives this beer a real live look .  this one strikes me as kind of flat . needs a tad more carbonation and i think it would be leaps better than it is . nice creamy smooth mouthfeel though .

some tart aromas and some bitter herbal notes . not much here . great clean flavors here .  pours as black as the night with a mocha colored head that is thick and has excellent staying power .  m : a little weak for my tastes , but it probably degraded a bit over the past year , still quite oily and resiny , medium-bodied .

aroma is very lager-ish .  the bottle was filled to the brim and looks like it might have leaked a little while shipping , so i decided to crack this one open the day after i got it . being so thick and having the bottle so full made it tricky not to spill when pouring . there was about 3 fingers worth of a deep brown head that clung to the sides of the glass the whole way down .  thin feel , but not too thin .

smell : a bit of hops , but not much of a nose .  poured in my struise glass this beer looks absolutely fantastic . what a big head with a very nice red/brown fluid .  m- thin to medium body- highly attenuated- with a coarse carbonation which delivers a slightly bloating feeling . could stand to have some softer carbonation .

the smell was muted in comparison just some banana , a slight whiff of lemon and faint husky grain . sweet start with banana , cotton candy that was cut nicely by wheat and grain flavour .  it stays forever and looks beautiful like a solid entity .  surprisingly light in the mouth , and very drinkable , but as i have been rereading some of my reviews lately , i think everything is drinkable , it seems that i would almost always take another .

nose : usual belgain nose , thick . the nose is close together , for me , that means the different scents are hard to pick between . i get cofee , tofee , spice .  poured into a tulip glass . this is just a seriously killer looking beer for an ipa .  '' the nutmeg overpowers the beer and completely destroys any other tastes that might have been present . if there were hops in the beer they were negligible and added most likely as an afterthought . leave this one on the shelf this christmas and go find out what uncle al spiked the eggnog with .

s- very flowery/powdery , little bit of dryness , hoppy , interesting mix of a kolsch and a lager . t- earthy , less flowery than the nose , not sure exactly how to word it , but it tastes very fresh , delicate hop bitterness hits the back of the mouth , lemon rind , delicate overall but definately drinkable for the fall , it 's a nice change of pace from oktoberfest beers .  a - deep brown black with 4cm thick cream head that last to end of the glass .  m- near dead flat . it seems to be a bit on the thin side as well . d- despite the feel this beer still drinks deadly smooth .

had a pint of this at the flying saucer in raleigh , nc , served from the tap . s- not much in the nose , a little floral hop , but not much . i 'd just had a dogfish head 90min ipa , so there was a very noticable difference in the big aroma of the 90 to this one . t-surprisingly good considering the lack of nose i was getting .  a - seriously a great looking beer ... what i would think a great looking ipa would and should look like .  tastes great , but the mouthfeel is a lot thinner than i 'd like for the style .

a very good offering from cascades lakes brewery in north deschutes county oregon . everything about it is true to pilsner form : refreshing , crisp , noble hops taste , and color . it was a bit short on flavor ( compared to victory prima - but what is n't ? good price on 22 oz . of the cascade lakes brews i 've tried this is the first that i was impressed with and truly enjoyed  looks great , tastes great .  mouthfeel - very average .

good smell , not strong , lemons , malt .  out of a bottle this beer was a chestnut brown color with a huge three finger head . the khaki foam died back slowly , displayed good retention and excellent lacing .  slick and little bit flat , the mouthfeel is a disappointment considering the other solid qualities of this beer .

the smell was surprising . very deep with , i dare to say , a meatiness to it . my kids called it a stink .  attractive red-amber with a thick , off-white head . beautiful lacing -- lovely and meticulously detailed . a in presentation , for sure !  mouthfeel is flimsy and light , but the carbonation is mellow , so that 's not too bad .

as for scents , i can find much more than diacetyl and bare notices of amber malt . not loud or jumping with bold aspects , but on-point for the style and well-rounded .  on tap ( in a 32oz masskrug ) at the brewery , it has a beautiful orange glow and the perfect cloudiness .  medium body with low carbonation . a bit more carbonation would be good too .

smelled really sweet . brown sugar , caramel , raisins , and a fairly stong alcohol aroma too .  a : 2 finger head rises up of dark chalky color and thick , the beer itself is pitch black and looks semi thick .  no offense ... er..ahem ... gentlemen , however your review of this all time worst pisswater excuse for even a macro beer is to say the least , culpable , at best , dubious , but in truth , how can you live with yourself ? t-non-existent m-ok , not too harsh , but goes flat quickly . good carb up front .

served from a 12oz bottle a-nice amber red color with great clearity and head/retention s-cereal grains , slight hoppyness , honey and toast . t-yeah buddy . tons of crystal malt ranging from caramel to light raisin , nice deep hop bitterness . m-great full body viscous brew d-not hard to finish one  the head is an amazing display , a full inch thick of off-white foam that does n't shrink at all hardly . the beer is quite black although some light peers about the extreme edges .  this is way to watered down for me . mouthfeel and drinkability : finishes somewhat dry . this brew also has a super light body with higher levels of carbonation-okay , these are appropriate for the style .

s- mild toasty grains and some plum banana grapefruit .  a total stunner in the glass : the color is black black and more black , seriously giving any huge bad-ass stout a run for its money in terms of color . the head is an ultra-creamy thing , looking like the froth on top of a root beer float or something .  the mouthfeel is a bit astringent and finishes extremely dry .

appearance : beautiful crystal clear pale golden beer that pours a very thick & sticky white foam head . smell : soft grain , metallic and floral hop aromas .  one of the coolest looking labels that i 've ever seen . it is blacker than charcoal and forms a great mocha colored head .  m - even , with a slight bitter aftertaste .

s : the aroma is too light with only tart apples , spicy yeast , pears , alcohol , and herbal hops coming through . t : yeast and light phenolic notes are most apparent at first , but the spicy hops , apple , and vinous qualities really come out with some time and air . even though a chalice is pictured on the bottle label , the next one i try will be from a snifter to try to capture more aroma .  poured a very crisp transparent gold with 3 fingers of bright white creamy head . got some really good lacing . this is a beautiful beer . the bubbles are exploding up to the top of the glass like a mini a-bomb got dropped in my glass .  mouthfeel : medium bodied and a bit undercarbonated imho .

s- not giving much away at first take , maybe a hint of bread coming from the yeast . smells of fruit develop later , maybe banana or apple . t- sensual fruit flavors , again maybe banana but predominantly spicier like apples , pears , maybe cranberries .  very nice looking beer .  the hops are n't super astringent and they finish well . mouthfeel : medium-bodied .

s- light toasted grain and malt sweetness , some floral/sweet fruity hops . really fruity stuff here , though . m- lacking hops , malt is very nice though and makes this an enjoyable beer nonetheless .  looks vicious and dark with an inch of coca head that lingers for a while !  m- smooth , medium-high carbonation , clean , with a hint of dryness in the finish . d- of course . it 's cheap , available everywhere , and quite good .

pretty weak nose .  cockeyed cooper pours a deep maroon/mahogany blend . the head is the color of light coffee , and a somewhat aggressive pour yields 4+ fingers worth . retention is off the charts , and when the foam cap finally does creep down it leaves a near solid wall of lacing left behind .  the appearance and mouthfeel were n't too great but i could n't get over the great taste .

the aroma is one big sour mish-mosh of belgian yeast . sweet syrupy flavor that has a tart and sour finish . i ca n't detect any sake .  pure black in color and laces the glass very well . wonderful looking beer .  m : thin to medium viscosity , resinous and sticky on the palate but lacking the heft of the other qualities , with moderate carbonation . the bitterness demands a little too much attention here , constraining its smoothness .

smell is a standard stout aroma , rather bland , the weakest point of this beer , taste is much more like a hoppy porter than any brown ale i 've ever had , but this is a very good thing , toasty malts with a very pronounced bitter hop presence .  appearance is outstanding - there 's really quite nothing like this - a dark black ( really very dark ruby red ) stout with a 2-3 finger creamy stout head that has nitro bubbles cascading throughout the glass . a perfectly poured guinness has no comparison so far as appearance goes .  smell : wheat , alcohol , wierd hops , tangy smell , maybe some wine alcohol smell in there too taste : hints of grass , toasted wheat , nice and smooth , mellow , nice malt aftertaste and a bit tangy mouthfeel : a little tart , this one is pretty highly carbonated .

great head retention & lacing s : a little caramel t : sweet bready malt , caramel & earthy hops up front .  it poured a cloudy burnt orange color that was beautiful to look at . it was like looking through a stained glass window . there was also a nice light tan head but i was too busy looking at the brew .  mouthfeel is pretty thin as well .

had this on tap a few times today at septemberfest in dublin ... a : nice golden color with a small head ... s : not much aroma aside from some grassy smelling hops ... t : nice full taste , the bitterness is there but the hop flavor is not very pronounced ... m : crisp , very nice .  poured from 12oz brown bottle into a clear pint glass a : beautiful hazy yellow-copper with a towering , rocky two-to-three finger head and sheets of lace s : hallertauer hops smell great -- tangy and spicy .  low carbonation .

very low aroma i 'm suprised . almost a metallic , coppery smell .  great retention and great lacing .  i 'm just back from a trip to the bahamas and the place i stayed at offered heineken , kalik and miller lite . i 've had both heineken and miller lite so i thought i 'd try the local brew , kalik . boy was i impressed . i drank quite a bit of this brew while sitting by the pool and each one tasted as good as the last . i sure got a good buzz but even better , no headache ! if you ever get to the bahamas be sure to try kalik .

holding this beer up to the light it looks amazing , it does n't have as much smell as some beers , but i might just have a stuffy nose !  appearance - pours a golden honey with a thick , pillowy head . the half inch head eventually recedes , leaving beautiful bands of lacing around the glass . the carbonation is moderate to high and gives the beer a lively lift .  taste was bland . not much to write about . normally , i 've been very happy with everything i 've had from them up until now . hopefully this was an experimental beer that taught from it 's mistakes .

smell : a little lacking in all honesty . did n't get that much from this one . nice grapefruit notes with some oddball tobacco notes on the finish .  an incredible foamy light brown head rested on top for a reasonable amount of time .  mouthfeel is thin and crisp .

it left no laing as it dropped , but lacing was later seen on the sidewall as i tipped it for a swill . s- this fizz in this beer penetrates your nose leaving me with reminders of new years ... champagne and sparkling cider . faintly smells like beer . t- very unique with only hints of what i expected from a triple ( i had to double check the bottle , and yup , its a triple ) . i has flavors very reminiscent of a wit beer . no spice , no banana .  deep amber color . formed a thick , dense light tan head which collapsed down and retained well .  m : disappointing . suffers from lack of body .

first thing i get is faint herbal hops in the nose . lightly metallic . rich , far more rich that the nose suggested .  a : this beer looks heavy . it pours slowly , and looks very viscous .  its got a light alcohol content and indeed a long haul session beer . this is a very tasty beer considering how light it really is . this pared real well with a cheddar burger .

s : dark malt , slightly tar-like .  just a beautiful sight to pour , very rich and thick , dark thin cream head . smelss and tastes of the following -- coffee , vanilla , chocolate , molasses .  the body is a little light for me which just adds to how drinkable it is .

the hops are a bit dull but the fruit aromas make up for it a little bit , still a letdown tho .  this beer has a sexy apperance , but is lacking in mouthfeel and taste . it has a wonderful head and is a very nice dark ruby , but something was missing when i tasted it .  mouthfeel is medium bodied , slightly syrupy , and carbonation is low which produces a somewhat still feel .

aroma is surprisingly subdued . little bit of herbal aroma , slight bit of alcohol .  truly majestic appearance - a very ruddy dark brown , almost bordering on black , with a smooth , creamy nitro head that left sheets of lace .  mouthfeel : good carbonation , otherwise nothing special .

i think this beer was a good one . i happen to think this is one of my try again beers . and am very impressed with the packaging of the beer . this is definately a beer to buy for your satanic friends .  a : extremely hazy orangish-yellow with a fluffy white head . it really is an attractive looking beer .  after my first taste i really was able to feel how refreshing this beer truly is , and i enjoyed ever sip . not your normal fall seasonal , due to the lack of heavy sweet notes , but none the less one of the better seasonal beer i have had .

a - pours up a slightly hazy gold , with a dense white head s - faint smell of malt with hop accents .  a : mohogany red brown with a fluffy tan head that lingered for a few minutes . very pretty in the snifter looking glass .  carbonation is a little bit higher than i prefer .

the smell was good , but nothing exceptional . tasted better than your average beer - a good bit of bittering hops , but so smooth as to be almost unnoticeable .  a- excellent black color with a large lingering head- tinted grey- and some lacing .  smells like apples , tastes like hops . very tasty . the fragrance certainly did not match the taste , which is a good thing . the apple/apricot scent is strong but would be overpowering to the tongue , the muted apple notes balanced well . i would definitely order this again .

pretty light amber color that was fairly clear ( also surprising ) that turns more of light straw when held to the light . there was a really nice white head from the pour that lasted for quite a while and left some white specks down the glass . citrusy , piney and some sourness also . t : very , very drinkable for a dipa . crazy how drinkable and smooth this is . not quite at the top of my list my really good .  pours a very nice burgandy with a tan head that is thick and rocky . in certain lights this brew appears to be brown , but i like it better as a burgandy .  brewed in celebration of the liar 's club 7th anniversary . aromas are amber malts and simple hops ... very clean and fresh . only a little grapefruit peel in the taste . very little about the sweet malts in this brew ... only enough to cover and blend with the hops to keep them from being obnoxious . good for several pints ... too bad they ran dry .

sweet malt dominates the nose ( think digestive crackers ) .  a huge cottony off white head with some pretty fantastic lacing leaving a magnificent cling down the glass . quite a sight ! when swirled the foam becomes a frothy cap on top of the beer .  mouthfeel needs a bit of work . medium body , carbonation is low . needs more carbonation .

crystal clear pale ( maybe a little too much on the pale side ) nutty amber body that pours with a great 3 finger off-white foamy head . s-lots of hop aroma almost overshadows the solid caramel malt backbone .  it is as black as anything i 've ever seen and pours with two fat fingers of rootbeer float-colored head .  the roast flavors give way to a hop bitterness in the finish with virtually no malt backbone in between . hints of licorice and coffee give this nice complexity for a lager . m- a little fuller than your typical schwarzbier . d- it drinks like a big beer , much more so than it 's 4.9 % abv would lend you to expect . overall : this is a very flavorful schwarzbier . my personal criticisms are that i would like it to have a little more malt in the middle while toning down the roast malts just a little . still , not a bad beer by any means .

the standard yeasty belgian aroma is missing .  i do n't like ambers , but this one is interesting . the looks are one of the best i have ever seen . lovely light amber colour .  the body is a bit lean and draws somewhat thin in the finish .

nose is musty belgian yeast . very small amount of bitter hops detectable . the nose is much more belgian than ipa .  pretty damn good looking beer .  mouthfeel is a little thin ( but then again , what do you want from a wheat beer ) with tangy carbonation .

yuk ... ..sorry but there it is , not a fan of this style , not a fan of this brew ... once said i have never met a beer i did n't like ... now i have , i am depressed ... .oh well , somebody pass me a aschi super dry ... please !  sample from bottle ; bottled on 1/22/09 a- poured carefully from bottle to yield a huge foamy , well-retained , cream colored head . as i refilled the glass throughout the sampling , the head became less foamy and a lot more rocky ( proteinaceous ) . the body was a hazy copper color , with lots of active carbonation visible from the sides and top of the glass .  mouthfeel is surprisingly light for the style . very little carbonation makes this one almost too easy to go down .

it looked great as it poured and settled . the taste is similar to belhaven 's scottish ale but much more creamy . this beer is oh so smooth and one i can see myself returning to .  poured from the bottle into a stemmed tulip . a - nice orange amber body with a white fluffy head on top . lots of sticky lacing on the glass .  a little thin in the body for my taste , and a bit low in carbonation .

i agree with the akbelgianbeast , extremely overrated . it starts off with hints of epoxy , maybe some asphalt , the middle and finish have the taste and texture of some low-end cheap hairspray , and that nasty array of not so nice flavors lingers for far too long , this brew is definitely the shame of the deschutes line-up .  really quite impressive . the liquid is cloudy with a yellow-gold color .  carbonation scrubs the tongue with perky bubbles ( almost too much , but not quite ) and has a medium-light body .

the mild malt and spice nose should be stronger .  poured from the bomber into a duvel tulip glass the beer was jet black in color and topped with three fingers of sticky head that retains very well .  the initial taste is medium in body , and the malt flavors are similar to those in the aroma , with enough hop bitterness to balance it . all sweetness disappears approaching the finish , and you 're left with a mild trinity of tartness , hop spice , and roasty character , combining to leave an overt dryness on the palate . so it has a warm place in my heart , and i feel validated to say that i can honestly still enjoy it for the same reasons i used to , even after having learned a great deal more about beer since that time .

tons and tons of carbonation bubbles . taste of malts and somewhat like nuts and raisins . a solid beer that could become a part of the standard rotation .  poured from a 12 oz bottle into a pint glass . crystal clear pale gold color with a 1 '' firm , fluffy white head .  the mouthfeel is a little weak .

smell : i detected some berries and citrus , good hops , some grain , and a light malt .  pours a good dark black with a caramel head . good head , receeds quickly but leaves good lacing .  the only disappointing part is the mouthfeel , which was more thin than i would have liked .

s : malty , mildly grassy hops . not very powerful .  was a beautiful rich and golden color ; looked like a killer ipa .  this is a good bridge beer for those who often find themselves at a party that are n't as fond of typical domestics . perhaps an unrealistic setting for beer in general , but i like them cold ! pleasant aroma and flavor for what it is . it 's a very drinkable , hot summer 's day , beer . it 's not a bad tangent from the original bud light .

clear s - aroma was quite mild but clean . d - very good , but rating held down by the unimpressive aroma .  reviewed 6/14/2009 ( bottle ) : pours a dark dark reddish brownish color body . big foamy tan colored head .  it 's very easy to drink , crips , and light , but it 's a bit thin in character & feel .

a deep caramel with a hint of amber . the initial smell did n't impress me much , and lowered my expectations for the taste . very tasty . all in all , a pretty darn good beer .  impressive head is like a cloud . beautiful looking beer .  hellooo hops ! this is a nice beer that hits you with hops right off the bat . nice hops with a touch of malt , and a lingering hop influenced aftertaste . i ca n't help but pick the slightest metallic twinge in the flavor and aftertaste , not sure where that could be coming from . not a bad strong ale at all , definitely worth revisiting but probably not distinguishable enough to stand in the upper echelon of style .

very one dimensional with the raspberries . very strange and not that appealing . '' t- intense sourness as the beer hits the palate . overall , really liked the sourness in this one ... almost on par with many cantillons i have had . very happy to have had this opportunity .  pours dark , very dark , brown color with light , light , brown frothy 2 finger head .  as a williamsburg native , and dark beer fan , i was severly disappointed with this porter . it could have been that the six pack was skunky , i guess . nonetheless , a big disappointment . if one could imagine a porter that is too sweet , this would fit into that category . baltika is also a sweeter porter , but only has a hint . this beer is blatantly sweet .

i guess i was expecting something like a lemon version of buffalo bills orange cream ale , which i though was a relatively good balance between the beer and fruit flavors . saranac would have been better off calling this a shandy or something other than `` brew '' . anyway for what it 's worth : a - golden yellow , average top..looks like beer s - get some lemon , but still could be beer t & m - really no beer here , not even a decent lemon flavor , overly sweet , cloying . finish is syrupy and well ... just bad d - drainpour this concept works well with ice tea , not so much with lager ...  wow , what a fantastic looking beer . pours a deep yellowish golden color and is very cloudy like most unfiltered wheat beer . the head on this beer is just absolutely ridiculous .  the mouthfeel was much lighter than expected with a slight buttery feel .

the smell is light malt , light hops , and something .  when poured into a glass the upward cascade of bubbles is a wonder to behold . the contrast of the black color of the beer and the ivory foam head scores highly with me .  the mouthfeel is average , medium-bodied , watery ( even slightly oily ) in texture , with soft carbonation .

not something the style is known for , but even less here , as the roast characteristics do n't really come through . just faint crackery malt and a trace of earthy spice . t -- much better than the nose . the malt on this is fantastic . pretty tannic , especially at the beginning , which makes it taste like tea with orange rind it .  pours fairly clear light amber color with a nice 3 finger white head with awesome retention and some nice glass lacing .  it finishes very clean with a hint of carbonation lingering on the palate .

it does n't give me much smell , but there is at least a hint of sweet fruit .  orange/amber color , with a thick creamy eggshell white head ( we 're talking this could be used as a pillow ) , that leaves amazing amounts of lacing down the glass .  a very nice balance of flavors m : average mouth feel .

s= the smell is not quite as intense as i would prefer , but it makes for a nice search that reveals smokiness and carmel . t= the is a great red . the spicy , hop and bold , malt balance is warmly welcome .  a - black with dark brown highlights . dark khaki , thick , creamy head 3 fingers high on the first pour .  grapefruit rinds , m : maybe a little more structure would be good- everything but the pine tends to fade on the finish .

it is pretty pale , but much more vibrant than a macro adjunct lager . s : grainy and sweet . other than that i am not picking much up , but the beer is pretty chilled.a t : hop bitterness is most certainly throughout the entire sip , and at its strongest on the back of palate and aftertaste .  pours a perfect amber with a huge full light tan headskie that just wo n't quit .  m : medium-bodied , but i feel like there 's something missing .

s : smells of bread . a little yeasty with an almost nut undertone . no hops present . t : it is sweet up front with a mild malt flavor . well done d : quite drinkable .  purchased a single can from martignetti's appearance = great thick , milky creamy head that goes down to about 1/4 '' and stays . deep , clear amber . very beautiful . it looks beautiful and i can see why some might like the taste .  look : black as night with a 1/2 inch head and good retention smell : the nose carries some nice licorice and dark fruits taste : plums and figs that a tad sweet present themselves right away the back end has a nice roasted malt character and a hint of chocolate mouthfeel : is a bit thin and over carbonated for the style overall : the beer is ok right now but i think that this one will do well with some age .

s : a faint smell of sweet malt , coffee and hot liquor .  deep brown brew with a large , beautiful tan head that sticks everywhere , leaving sticky lace all down the glass . this is a beautiful beer .  mouthfeel is a touch light for my liking , but i 've come to expect that .

s : citric and a little cindery t : this is a different taste ; there is fruitiness and some spiciness .  pours a very clear and golden color with lots of nice champagne like bubbles and a small white head with some mild lacing . this looks amazing in it 's glass , nice big 3 finger head with a clear yellow straw color with a really cool stream of bubbles up from the etched d on the bottom . really nice big thick lacing unlike any other beer .  body was a smidgen thin , but it held the 8 % back quite well , i knew it was more that 5 % , but thats what i perceived from this great brew .

not much in terms of aroma , and i do n't think it 's just my choice of glassware . maybe some biscuity malt and hop leaf ? tastes delicious , though . i think part of why i like it better now is that i 've come to appreciate tasteful use of diacetyl -- the buttery sweetness is complemented by light hop spiciness and even lighter citrus notes . finishes somewhat dry but could be crisper for the style and my tastes .  appearance : this is probably the most gorgeous pale beer i 've seen up to this point . retention is ridiculous , and lacing is incredible . superb .  a little less than medium bodied , with lowish carbonation .

smell is ok- nothing exceptional- strong roasted wood smell coupled with some chocolate and molasses .  it pours a nice orangy amber color with a nice creamy off white head . most notable was the lacing . it ringed around the glass , identifying each sip , almost like a tree ring marking its age . very impressive !  had this side by side with weihenstephaner 's dunkel . i think the comparison made this beer seem pretty awful . the beer is a ruddy , red , muddy river looking beer with a sizable , reddish head . super sweet and caramelly . it reminded me of michelob amber bock but stronger and richer . it seemed like there was caramel and toffee syrup added . taste is like the nose , syrupy sweet like artificial caramel . i did not like this beer . i think i would be able to drink it easier if it werent side by side with the quintessential dunkel but still i dont think i would like it very much more .

aromas are lightly sweet and roasty but nothing jumps out at me here .  a- pours a hazy gold with a huge 3 finger head that dissipates very slow , leaving an impressive cap . great looking beer .  crisp malts , light fruits and near indiscernible hops all float to the nose . a bit dry going down with some malts , a surprising hoppiness , and a good , somewhat delayed fruit hit at the end . light-bodied and highly drinkable , but still tasty , which is what i look for in a good summer sessioner .

s : the aromas are not bold ( though this one has sat a year ) but what is there is rather nice . nice sweet brown sugar with notes of cinnamon and nutmeg . a light fruit juice aroma that i ca n't quite put my finger on . t : wow , this is one wonderful brew .  golden , it has a big white head slowly shrinking to a smaller but lasting , puffy , somewhat rocky head , and leaving a lot of nice , frothy lace .  the only real complaint i have with this beer is that it is just too thin ... i do n't buy that this is an ris ... if this was just an american stout , the thinner body would be suitable , but it 's just not on an imperial stout .

rich , medium amber color topped by a large , bubbly off-white head with lots of staying power and a good amount of thick lace left on the glass . smell was mild ... malt with a bit of hop spiciness . an excellent choice when everything else on the menu is a fizzy , yellow macro brew !  jet black coloring and pours with a think caramel-colored head . kept a solid layer of foam on top as i drank the entire glass .  very much like the herbs for a fish of sorts . m/o : not the crispest carbonation that i was expecting but the beer has a great complex flavor with some great sweetness and bitter hop flavor .

smell - strong of piney hops and nothing else . closer to room temperature a bit of a malty scent is apparent , but it is subdued by the hops . it is easy to finish , and i would n't mind another .  served in a pint glass this beer pours a motor oil black . it may be categorized here as a smoked beer , but this has the rich sexy dark brown foam and black body of an amazing stout .  there 's a slight bready quality to the mid mouth impact , but the flavor is balanced and lessens evenly as its swallowed . i do n't look for a lot of bite or chewy mouthfeel in vienna lagers , so i 'm pretty happy with firebrick .

smells vinegary , sour , and acidic .  the name refers to a new zealand rugby team ( `` the all black 's '' ) , because nz hops were used , and because the beer truly is pretty much all black under a thick and creamy one finger tan head that ai n't going nowhere , leaving thick sheets of lace everywhere . a truly beautiful sight !  mouth is over-carbonated indefinitely .
the smell was predominantly chocolate with a mild hint of coffee .  a : great orange/amber color with cascading nitrogen foaming and staying on top throughout the beer .  medium to light body .

a - pours up cloudy pale yellow , almost white with a thick white head that dissipates slowly s - smells mostly of yeast , some citrus in the background and a hint of spice t - starts off with sharp carbonation tingle , replaced with slight sweetness at the edge of the tongue , and finishes with a hint of spice .  intense carbonation from the looks of it , nice fluffy and cloudlike head , great retention and lacing so far .  mouthfeel is thin , but typical for brown ales ( i always expect a fuller beer based on the smell ) .

this is a good looking pale ale that has just the slightest orange/reddish hue . the aroma is pretty light of grains , hops and just a touch metallic .  pours a deep brown with two fingers of bubbly mocha head and spider web lacing .  the mouthfeel is a little thin for the style but its still a fairly minor flaw .

looks a bit intimdating , or maybe i just read into the marketing to much ... s : hop smell is dominant , with stong caramel notes . not as intimidating on the nose . t : this is where its at .  for all intents and purposes it pours like duvel . a fantastically clear golden body , with a billowing soft white head .  too carbonated , average m/f .

the aroma however is rather more subdued than i imagined it would be mainlly biscuity malts..rather odd as i did not chill this at all.oh well . nice palate to this one , quite silky and thick . overall another intresting and good beer from a smaller oregon brewery .  poured to a pale golden color , with foamy white head that lasted the entire bottle , with high carbonation and excellent lacing .  mouthfeel is tough .

smells of slight hoppyness . it 's for sure not as aromatic as some other ipa 's . in fact i ca n't smell much at all in this beer . taste is great . i could session this ipa for sure because it goes down smooth and is n't heavy or it does n't wreck the palate . it could be a little sweeter imo but it 's still great . mouthfeel is great . overall it 's a great ipa .  granted it looks cool , but it 's a bit tough . a - clear orange with a big rocky head and amazing lace .  the mouthfeel is also unexpectedly thin - for a beer this dark i was anticipating something more viscous .

s : not much aroma to speak of . quite a remarkable stout .  the beer pours a blackish red color its very attractive and pours a thick head that disaperas in a couple of minutes but leaves lacing till the end of your beer .  m : a bit light and quite fizzy for the style .

s- a slightly sweet , bready smell . there 's some herbalness to it ( obviously lavender ) t- very pleasant . the lavender is there , but by no means overwhelming .  pours a very dark , almost black amber with some reddish tones to it . a very sticky map covers the glass as you drink .  it goes down smooth and is nice and wet on the tongue but is just a tad thin .

not a bad looking winter beer . s- some rye , caramely malt , kind of oaty . mild is a good word for it . t- the smell does not really set you up for how this tastes . very appealing . but this is a really nice winter beer .  8.4 oz bottle poured into a tulip . pours an absolutely beautiful blood red , crisp and clear , with a thick , dense , foamy bright pink head .  mouth feel : reasonably full , not unpleasant , a little carbonation at the opening .

s : shy on the nose . the scents are clean , though , and inviting .  slow pour ( with the proper swirling with 2 ounces left ) , into a 23 ounce h-w glass yields a huge off-white meringue-like head that lasts and clings to the glass like spackling . simply a gorgeous beer , a delight to look at . called a `` heller ( i.e. , bright , or light-colored ) weizenbock , '' this brew is truly that : on the lightest end of the weizenbock color scale .  m - well , this is honestly a step down from the better macros . it has a decent body , but the hops detract a bit from refreshment the beer provides .

smell : fruity and bready . slight hint of the malty depth of the taste , but too faint and indistinct . some roasted character to the flavor emerges with warmth , further balancing the great fruit and malt notes . rather hoppy for a doppelbock , but everything is superbly balanced , and bold enough to justify the high abv ( which is detectable only through the deep malty flavors ; not much alcohol burn here ) . juicy , like a good dipa ( which works great with the peachy hop flavor ) . overall : tastes more like a riff on a doppelbock than an actual doppelbock , but the flavors work great together and all the classic elements are present . very good .  a : pours a massive head that laces nicely . clear brown color , very bubbly . sounded like pouring champagne .  mouthfeel is average , thin and just a bit too carbonated for my taste .

very caramelly and a little bit cloying . big floral , citrusy hops . firm hop bitterness is just a little lower than i 'd expect from a west coast brewed ipa , but very smooth nonetheless .  two finger tan head that is very creamy and has excellent retention and beautiful lacing .  a slightly over-caramelized ( read : burnt ) sweetness resurfaces on the finish , somewhat diminishing the overall enjoyability of the brew . the beers ' only weakness , a touch thin and yet over-carbonated at the same time . still , this is a winner from a rather uneven stable of beers from new holland . my only concern is how this came to be listed as a red ale ; it 's fucking brown ! ? !

smell - a strong sweet smell with only a little malt scent to it . smells a little young to me . very tasty i take back what i said about it being young , smells young yes but the flavor is just right for the style . drinkability - not a session beer but if you can get past the smell its pretty good . nice show for the style .  this beer poured wonderfully , gave great head , and had the most beautiful dark appearance .  it was a light to moderate mouthfeel . good balance of carbonation .

s : some chocolate and coffee notes.. not getting a huge scent off this one ... t : sweet chocolate . d : i could do a six pack of this.. a pretty decent imperial stout , for a pretty fair price .  a-extremely dark brown in color , almost black , completely opaque with a huge and thick dark coffee colored head that lingers for well over a minute and leaves a nice lacing on the glass .  fairly dry with ample carbonation and a lighter body . a bit coarse in texture .

very drinkable and well-crafted beer for its high alcohol content , but not at the `` elite '' quality of some other belgian triples . slightly sweet , yeasty-alcoholic smell . taste was full with a good amount of sweetness and malt , finishes with a pleasant alcohol taste - nice , long finish .  pours a beautiful good .  light body , wish it were bigger and more creamy .

smell is like a malty dopplebock , nothing really sticks out . great great taste .  a - nice and black , medium brown foamy head that does n't fade much and lastes throughout the session . the head also laces the glass evenly . i 'm impressed .  mouthfeel - the only downside imo is that it has a dry finish and leaves the pallet thirsty .

s- smells of toasted malts , has a sort of sweet gingerish cinnamon smell nothing to powerful . t- it has a fairly sweet taste that goes along with the ginger smell i ca n't taste much cinnamon .  almost black in color with and off-white head . it looked creamy and delicious .  ( m ) medium bodied and a medium mouthfeel .

the aroma is very malty , not quite enough hops to really stand out .  this brew poured a medium head of fine to medium sized brown bubbles and a opaque black body . an average stout in my book which is not marked by the strong coffee flavor of most stouts .  m - thin , lo-carbonation , smooth and easy on the palette .

taste : super sweet , super syrupy and very cloying . for a minute there , i thought i just swallowed robitussin cough syrup . hold on ... robitussin tastes better than this . overall : i am not familiar with wheatwine as a style and that may have something to do with the taste i am perceiving .  the beer is a super dark red or amber . it looks delicious on appearance .  feels like champagne .
smells of burnt malts almost like toast , with some slight chocolate undertones .  nice lacing . looks very thick .  mouthfeel was unremarkable , which is as much as can be expected of any pilsener .

s : some bitter yet pleasant hops but that 's about it . boring .  displays awesome retention , forms a mesa in the middle of the glass and shows off an impressive formation of 3d lace . an awesome appearance and nice aroma save this one from finding the 'c ' range .  the carbonaton is a bit high and detracts a bit from the quality of this beer , but overall an excellent , potent stout that is sweet without being too sweet .

not much for smell here . a bit sour and malty . the flavor is awesome with big hops and a subtly paired malt .  on tap night of a million zillion speedways o'brien 's pub san diego , ca dark as night black with brown edges , thin head but the body of this beer is just spectacular . it 's thick and oily and leaves the glass absolutely covered in sticky lace . unfortunately , the appearance is one of the few fine things about this beer . while there is still a bit of the coffee and roast combination left from the untreated version of speedway , the dry hopping has given this beer an incredibly woody character .  m- medium body , slightly carbonated , has a bit of creaminess to it .

s - smell is clean , but almost completely void of any flavors .  this is a barrel-aged version of florence with brett . notes from my phone : beautiful hazy orange gold with thick creamy bone-white head . this is perhaps the most beautiful beer that i 've ever seen !  the nitro can has both its positive and negative effects on this very english strong ale , the look of the beer with it creamy head and cascading pour is the closest you can get at home to an `` authentic '' pub pour unless you have a beer engine and sparkler in your bar . nonetheless , the aroma is english hops ( most likely east kent goldings ) on top of a mild caramel malt sweetness . the taste is lacking the true depth a real ale should have , but it is well-balanced and mild . for those expecting the assertiveness of an american pale ale this beer will be a dissapointment , but for those searching for a closer approximation to a british session beer served in a suffolk pub , this is a nice try .

s - clean biscuit and toffee . slight damp earth smell . not a ton of character overall . t - everything an english ale should be .  clear orange amber with a huge thick white , firm , pillowy head .  m - overcarbonated , light bodied for the style , but really good .

smell is nothing spectacular , but smells clean and like a good stout .  a personal favorite in terms of appearance . black , usually does n't let light through . nice , thick , somewhat tan head sitting on top and leaving remnants on the glass throughout the drink .  lighter in body than i anticipated .

500ml bottle pours a nice 2 finger head , dark colored foam , dark black beer smells roasty and a little metallic ( hard water maybe ) .  head is an incredibly massive head of dark brown foam , easily five-fingers , and far more extensive than the three fingers of body . looks heavy , rich and black .  mouth feel is a little thin at first with too much carbonation for an english style brown .

this beer pours an orange color with a very citrus filled aroma and a medium head .  poured from a can into an imperial pint glass a-like it or not this beer looks damn sexy in its own glass .  mouthfeel is thin and a little overcarbonated .

dark mahogany brown in the glass , not quite black ; on the light side for the world 's strongest stout . swirling reveals thick , syrupy legs not unlike a spirit or liqueur . it smells intensely of alcohol , peat , oak , faint roast - a hell of a lot like scotch . it 's simple and unimpressive .  ebony the color on the pour , the head unboastful in size , light chocolate in color , the texture frothy , and as it evanesces , the lace left behind a fine covering upon the glass .  m : sticky and fairly thick , dry , slightly dry , prickly carbonation , hint of warm alcohol , just a little too syrupy for my taste .

s : plenty of spiciness from the wheat and yeast , but not much else . underwhelming . t : far , far better than the smell : big wheat sharpness , plenty of yeasty spice , and some nice fruit flavors as well ( apricot and lemon ) ; some cinnamon on the finish , and just a bit of booze on the aftertaste.. quite complex and thoroughly enjoyable .  pours black with a big , thick , firm and pillowy off-white/tan head . nice looking .  m - uberchewy , sweet . med-light carbonation .

smell is average , mostly roasted malts . a very good tasting beer ... tastes like a stout , but not nearly as heavy .  beer poured a clear golden orange with a generous 2 finger white head that is leaving a perfect lacing behind .  m/d : sweet and full-bodied , just the right carbonation for the style .

some fruity esters with a light maltyness in the aroma . subtle hops as well . the hop flavor is way to strong , and the hop combo is terrible . really not a fan at all .  beutifull beer with a huge white cap of dense white foam.clear or cloudy depending on the pour amber body .  a little grittiness in the texture . m - a little weird and overcarbonated for a porter . it would be better off less carbonated and as creamy as it appears .

n- floral and slightly pungent hops with a hint of toasty malt . t- nice toasted malt flavor accented by a soft bitterness and a refreshing fruity/piny hoppiness . m- medium-light body , moderate carbonation , sticky finish from the hop oils . d- this is a quality pale ale .  a - it looked big . poured out black as black , with a huge 3 finger brown head , that settled down and layered the top of my glass .  other than the slightly thin body , this is a superior porter .

s. pine hops and a bit of malt . not an overpowering nose by any means .  the can poured out a thick tar black brew with a one finger high deep reddish brown head . the head dissipated moderately into a thick lace that covered the top of the beer .  the mouthfeel is a decent medium , a little too much carbonation results in a thinner feel than i would like .

it has a light aroma of roasted malt and molasses .  a - a beautiful bright red color with a very fizzy , nice sized white head sitting atop .  cloying . full-bodied , slick and thick . an odd astrigency lingers .

s : quite light actually , hoppy predominately , grassy . t : taste has a nice biscuit character upfront , followed by very fresh tasting hops , quite bitter for this style , but quite complex - a mix of lemon , earth , pine , and grass , very tasty , one of the best tasting bitters ever for me .  surprisingly horse-mane black coloring for such a smaller abv beer . giant liquid-cookie head that bubbles up , comes back to earth and really lingers .  m : pretty thin and not too lively .

aroma is not overpowering . in fact i have to a deep breath to recognize its characteristics . i think it 's hard to decipher the aromas because it 's so well balanced . there are faint chocolate and coffee bean notes , but they 're minor and this is by no means a desert porter . i taste hops , light malts , and oats . heck , i 'm on my 2nd already . the overall sensation this beer gives off reminds me of ss 's oatmeal stout - you can definitely tell the two beers are siblings .  this is really a gorgeous looking beer .  mainly a flattish mouthfeel .

s - surprisingly little aroma , some spice notes and citrus sweetness , but it 's not very potent . t - very complex for an amber , i was pleasantly caught off guard by all the flavors .  '' a- dark mahogany/black and opaque . ~3 fingers of creamy , cascading tan head . loads of sticky lacing . beautiful .  m : it doesnt give the mouth a longlasting tingle that some ipa 's give but gives a tasty coat on your mouth that lasts and gives the chocolate taste as well .

bottle into my orval glass ... pours a medium copper with a big carbonated light tan head , good retention and lacing ... the aroma is super light only a little yeast ... .the taste is surprisingly super nice , very flavorful .  a - beautiful deep brown-black , opaque and crude-like , and capped with a perfect pillowy head ala duvel except sandalwood-hued ; serious lacing ensues .  wow ! really liked this beer . i did n't think i would . looked like it could have been any pils when i poured it . smelled like a nice lady 's perfume ... with hops ! : ) nice hops balance with some maltiness too . i am not a pilsner fan but i think i am now . way to go victory !
raspberries ? t - very light aftertaste , delicate chocolate .  this looks beautiful in my tulip glass .  a touch too much carbonation for my liking .

s- i was n't able to get that strong of a smell from this beer . it taste like roasted spices . d- it was a good beer as far as pumpkin beers go .  poured from a 750ml bottle the ber showed a very dark red , opaque in the middle but translucent blood red on the edges . white head that had excellent retention and left a beautiful lacing on the glass .  after several sips i finished the taster and got a bottle of water to cleanse the palate . the body was average for a wit , but the hops made this sloppy mess nearly undrinkable .

aroma : light caramel malt , low hop aroma . very nice head retention . wish they could get some more hop aroma into this beer .  appearance : gorgeous frosted lemon body with a luciously frothy 2 finger white crown . seriously sexy !  feel is a bit thin , probably because the alcohol presence is a bit pronounced .

not too strong of a scent . taste : creamy malt flavor with a ton of bitterness and hop flavor .  a thick pour into my tulip glass yielded an opaque black body with a beautiful mocha head that seemed to last through the entire beer . gorgeous .  m - nice carbonation , but it could be much bigger bodied .

smell -- bready and yeasty , with plenty of malt sweetness , a bit of melon , and some grassy hops .  appearance- beer pours a dark brown with a pretty big frothy head about three fingers high . this has to be at least the best looking black & tan .  sweet tasting ... m : a little on the acidic and sour side to me .

smell - very faint bitter malts with some chocolate tones . taste - malty and chocolaty , but the cocoa type .  perfect appearence . deep ruby color with a full , long lasting head of a light tan .  body is a bit thin , with the malt slipping quickly away under the bittering hops that dominate the finish .

s- notes of citrus with a hop smell present that is not overpowering , overall not a strong scented beer in general .  22oz bottle poured into a mexican tulip - fridge temp - 2008 appearance : pours a semi cloudy golden orange with a towering 5 '' yellowish head . it shows great retention .  mf - medium body , very creamy , light carb .

to acidic or stale , it faded as i drank it down , but the initial smell was not pleasing . t - after the smell factor i was worried about the taste , but was pleased with the distinct hop bitterness . not real powerful , but a nice , crisp ipa .  flash forward to tonight : i really want a beer and no one to drink with - let 's crack the mean manalishi and see what happens ... looks absolutely amazing - everything you 'd want out of a strong midwest iipa : nice dark amber , almost red color . excellent rolling foam off-white head . leaves intermittent thick and sticky lace .  found it medium bodied for the style considering the rich taste .

malty and sweet but rather mild . a hint of dry yeastiness and just a bit of light fruit , mostly uneventful but still appetizing . not too terribly flavorful but pleasant . certainly a nice session beer . very nice overall , decently balanced and a good accompaniment to food .  this beer looks like a stout should near black with about 1.5 of very dense tan head -- miniscule bubbles courtesy of the nitro tap , which left excellent retension all the way down the pint glass , like the strata of a sandstone canyon .  m= body is medium/average but probably a little too thin . i was hoping for a little thicker in the body as well as taste department .

smell - i know i 'll smell lovely lovely pacman yeast before i even open the bottle .  a lovely brew .  makes it look like a blue moon ... i dont know just dont see the drinkability and mouthfeel to be good at all ... it was one and done for me ... .

the aroma is very light , small amounts of hops but that 's pretty much it .  pours a surprisingly clear amber , with a fluffy , sticky , voluminous , lace-leaving head of slightly off-white .  mouthfeel is very cloying with a firm body and medium carbonation .

s - very light . some malt and hops . t - strong hops , sweet caramel , good alcohol burn in the finish .  the beer arrives an extremely dark black with a creamy mocha head that 's there for the duration .  the feel is alright but it does n't matter at this point .

appearance-pours a clean beer the color of apple juice with a thin white head . smell-not getting much . a bit of acidity and a whiff of barrel . drinkability- an absolute pleasure to sip .  a fantastic looking beer .  should you drink this warm or cold ? when it 's cold the flavors are : dark chocolate , coffee , heavily roasted to burnt malt , and bitter hops . when it 's warm the flavors are more like : sweet chocolate , maybe some sort of fruit , coffee , heavily roasted malt , and not so bitter hops . i perfer the sweeter chocolate , not burnt malt , and less bitter hops flavor when it 's warm .
smell is malt , light smoke , hint of citrus & spice .  really an exceptional looking beer .  a bit of a thin mouthfeel , for a porter .

s - mild aromas of chocolate , clove and anise . t - nice mild chocolate and medium to long roasted malt flavors . ~ this is a the kind of stout i would go out and drink through an evening .  poured into a pioneer stein ( # 42 , 2009 edition ) , formed a 2 1/2 '' frothy tan head over the slightly cloudy caramel hued brew . head falls slowly with an audible sizzle of bubbles bursting , with tons of lasting lace .  the carbonation is medium strong ; the few medium sized bubbles are fresh . the liquid is semi-smooth . a lager with lots of off flavours .

s : grainy , yeasty , and decent . sweetish .  a- nearly opaque due to darker color , but good clarity on the edges head : big creamy head with a tan color to it . intense lacing .  the mouthfeel is light also and thin .

on first pour into a standard schooner glass very little head formed and unlike some reviewers i got little aroma except a very faint toffee .  a - the pitch black pour is topped by a dense tan head . fantastic retention and sticky lace rings cover the inside of the snifter .  little bit of fizziness and a lingering cottonmouth aftertaste i could have done without .

a light brown nitrogenated head about 1/4 inch deep persists for the duration of my imbibing . the smell is the only ordinary thing about this beer , for it is minimal and hints of chocolate . the taste is complex , with a strong chocolate presence , competing with brandy , vanilla and malt . it is very drinkable and is one of the very best beers anywhere .  this beer pours an amber color , with a slight red tint . it has a thick light tan head that fades very slowly , leaving many thick laces .  m : medium mouthfeel , slightly thinner than what i was expecting , especially once the carbonation is gone .

appearance-amber color with an off white head with an amazing amount of lacing smell- a very weak malt smell taste- an amazing carmel malt taste . very sweet with a hint of bitter .  poured from 12oz to a tulip glass pours an amazing melon shade , the cherry is very apparent in shade , like taking a a lager and adding a dash of cherry red to it - ending up in a beautiful color indeed .  mouthfeel is a little bit lacking as the beer is a little bit thin , although it is still okay .

likewise ale drinkers may order a smithwick 's with a guinness head . s - i rate every beers smell as average due to the fact that i can not smell t - smooth and refreshing . i am not a guinness draught fan but i am a smithwicks fan . o - p e r f e c t in every way possible  a - beautiful dark amber with tons of head - good 2 inches . retention is pretty good over the course , lacing sudsy but thick and a little web like .  m : a tad overcarbonated , a bit watery , medium-light body . a bit astringent .

smell : mild and pleasant . light malt aroma .  appearance : very dark , think black oil look too it . seemed to pour thick and left about a 2 finger dark tan head to it .  a little bit of sweetness also from the yeast taste : there is a very interesting dark fruit flavor profile going on here with raisin definately standing out as the main flavor mouthfeel : medium body with really high amounts of carbonation typical of lost abbey beers overall : i really dont care for lost abbey and their high levels of carbonation in their beers .

aroma is very light here , just a fruity hop note is all .  appearance- beautiful beer ! gold , leaning almost into a cognac tone , the monstrous three to four finger crown billows and slowly begins to pop away . incredible , massive lacing .  m - good mouthfeel . a bit low on the carbonation .

smell is the most disappointing aspect here . not bad per se , just underwhelming . a bit of funk , but not a ton .  bottle marked best before 22mar11 , served in a tulip glass pours a beautiful black with ruby highlights where light touches it with a light brown moderately dense head that fades to a persistent outer ring with patches of thin foam in near the center .  just ok . this is a very sweet beer . it 's a good beer to drink when you are plowed . drink it very cold . when it warms up , it tastes like butt .

nice amount of hop haze with excellent lacing . s- i get big bitter resinous notes backed up by a small amount of sweet grapefruit/tropical scents . not the greatest ipa i 've smelled , but not bad .  pours beautifully !  i 'm so sorry , but i do n't see what everyone else does in this beer . the malt flavor is too aggressive and tastes over-toasted . in this case , both flavors are too aggressive . still , in all departments i find it profoundly below average , except maybe appearance and mouthfeel , which are standard ( gold with a tinge of brown and not too oily , respectively ) . this is just one of those beers i ca n't get into .

s : not strong . some dark chocolate and coffee notes . no hops at all . t : mostly dark roast malt with a hint of coffee .  purchased single 22oz bottle from martignetti's appearance = beautiful looking dark ruby amber .  aroma of allspice , nutmeg , figs , apples , leathery yeast , and pepper . flavor of dark fruits including plums and cassis . slightly sour . palate lacks expected richness . good but not great like the previews ( appearance and aroma ) lead you to believe .

the smell was very modest but there was a hint of malt .  call me weird , but i thought this was a beautiful beer in appearance . a very cloudy apricot color , half a finger of fluffy head and very sticky lacing .  mouthfeel : a slight cloy in the finish makes this a less-than-refreshing ipa . drinkability : this is a nice , simple beer with a delectable hop profile and light body .
aroma is sweet , semi-floral , and malt .  very nice looking brew .  m : on the thin side , and carbonation is on the low side .

the aroma yields pleasantly sweet caramel notes and some bitter apple/fruits .  d- looks amazing and sure gets you effed up , but i was disappointed with the kaiser after being enlightened by the maharaja .  mouthfeel is a letdown - it may just be this bottle but the carbonation is too weak . only have one of these 750ml bottles as it 's imported and a special occasion but i 'd be keen to have another one , if only to compare the carbonation .

smell is a bit strong of oak wood and a mild amount of spice . not a whole lot else on the nose . very little oak comes to play , and what is there really amps up the flavor of the pumpkin .  appearance- beautiful solid black with a minimal white head .  the body seems a bit lighter than i would have expected .

smells of caramel and sweet , sugary hop candy . no vicious bite to the smell like i expected . the aroma is not that strong . exceptional . this bomber will finish off my night .  draught @ obriens san diego the beer in its comforting pint glass appears black as midnight , the head a soft chocolate crown , the lace a concealing curtain to drape the glass .  a nice toasted nut element , good smokey , roasted flavors , but the body is thin and watery to me .

ca n't smell much but that might just be me . overall a really nice beer .  poured into a tulip glass the beer was a beautiful clear orange blonde color with noticeable effervescence . nice off white head that dissipated quickly with no lacing .  this 'beer ' is weak . this 'beer ' is flavourless . no wait , i can taste some corn syrup , and what 's that ... pickle juice ? honestly , i think i taste hints of pickle juice !

the aroma is more malty with some pine notes .  g : i & g tulip a : dark reddish brown with some light escaping near the bottom of the glass . one inch of creamy lightly tanned head with good retention and leaves thick lacing .  mouthfeel is very light , a little watery , with a somewhat crisp feel to it .

it does n't smell overly strong , hoppy , or oaky . kind of smells like a watered down ipa , not what i expected . it 's a smooth hoppy that actually does n't have any oak taste present , which surprised me .  looks really awesome !  mouthfeel is a touch watery .

smell : mild caramel is all that is picked up .  best before 3/2009 a : pours a hazy bright golden with a massive foamy head as every good hefe should have . super-long sustain and massive lacing .  mouth : very light for the style , heavy on carbonation .

s : very faint whiff of roasted coffee , caremel , t : mix of roasty malt , some prune , some tartness .  it eroded oddly and left big soapy dollops and sticky sheets of lacing - impressive . the body was an orangy gold color and it had a light haze .  it feels a bit thin and overly carbonated for a strong english ale .

fine , but not bold enough . the nose gave me some worries that it would n't quite deliver the punch , but the flavors definitely came through in the end .  jet black , with complete absorbance . lofty , dense , steadfast light bister head leaves sticky , coating lace .  mouthfeel is a bit thin .

the aroma was comprised of sweet malt , bitter hop , and subtle citrus .  it looks absolutely beautiful in the glass , with a ruby brown color that really catches the light nicely .  it seems to say , above , that it 's cask ... it was certainly carbonated when we tried it - just not highly carbed . a bit light in the mouthfeel like all of the brutopia beers we tried .

s : light chocolate-mocha notes with a touch of grainy roasted oats and grassy hop undertones . t : soft and sweet flavors of dark chocolate with a fairly bitter punch of grassy hops .  cascading midnight black with a creamy dark brown head ... awesome .  only criticism : powerful aggressive carbonation , would it ease if i left it a while - just too fresh ?

a ruby red colour , with a nice smell to it too .  this beer poured black into my glass , not simply dark brown , but a light impervious black with a creamy coffee colored mousse of a head that floated above the abyss darkness below out of pure fear .  mouthfeel is surprisingly thin , with some grapeskin-like astringency on the finish .

a clear amber beer with an off-white compact foam that leaves nothing on the glass . a rather faint smell of oatmeal biscuits and a hint of oranges .  a- beautiful . very foggy , nearly opaque bright straw yellow body . pours with a big , foamy , 2 finger + white head . cloudiness is mostly uniform but has some dynamic qualities to it .  m - two words : over-carbonated . it 's just too crisp for my liking for an imperial stout .

vague malt smell , not picking up much else .  a : enormous , light beige head . o : i love the label . gorgeous looking beer .  m : medium-bodied in the style , not the smoothest imperial stout for me .

the aroma is dulled a bit . i do n't know how old the bottle is but it does n't quite strike a chord with me . decent flavour .  appearance : as poured the beer is a cloudy antique gold color with a 1 `` fluffy white head that recedes slowly . there are rings and legs of lacing clinging to the sides of the glass and sipping creates sheets and legs and small patches of lacing , some of which cling to the side and some of which slide back down to the liquid .  m : medium bodied , but the carbonation is lacking .

not really breathtaking , but worth a whiff . t - delicious !  perfect lacing . i mean perfect lacing .  on tap the the brewery . all american hops . pungant and resiny . big hop flavor with rye spicyness . caramel , and good bitterness . quite dry and refreshing . my first founders beer every . pretty happy so far .

the smell though has always bugged me a little , the sour yeastiness makes me think of the old half-full cream container you end up finding in the back of your fridge . all in all , the more stouts i try the farther this creeps down my list of favorites , but still good stuff , and a great `` old standby '' in nyc where it 's always on tap , even if you 're stuck in a sh*thole .  this maerzen came out to be with a decent two finger thick , light tan head . the body is a picturesque dark golden amber color , and very well filtered .  m : the body is on the slicker , thinner side of medium , with sharp yet low carbonation .
nothing much in the aroma , somewhat earthy i guess .  excellent retention and lace .  in the mouth , it 's a touch thin and gritty .

i was underwhelmed on first try of this brew . i find that a heavy , yeasty aroma masks most the fruit and malt notes .  an amazing looking beer .  the mouthfeel is atypical for a saison . it 's a little heavier and not as carbonated as is typical of the style .

retention of head and lacing ability were good . aroma of herbal hops and slight caramel malts . this aspect , combined with a nice flavor , rendered the beer very drinkable .  great looking beer , with chocolate mouse colored head .  not sure what 's going on with this one . smells and tastes like a bucket of water with household cleaner thats been laying around for a couple of days . try for yourself , but i guarantee you wont want to try it again . also , ive read about people paying upwards of $ 9 for a 22 oz . bottle . i paid $ 6.49 . pay no more ...

tried this beer for the first time out of a bottle , into a frosted mug . the smell was average at best . really had no distinction from other beers of the same color .  highs : appearance , complexity lows : complexity ok , i must admit i was a bit overwhelmed going into my first fabled trappistes offering . bottle , pours caramel brown with a two-finger brown-tan head that fades at a moderate pace leaving a medium to heavy amount of lacing that lasts until the bottom of the glass .  m_moutheel was actually ok except that it felt like sugar was coating teeth . other than that it was thick and full bodied .

aroma obviously consists of chocolate , but mixed well with coffee . not as strong as i expected it to be since it is showcasing chocolate so much . a surprisingly under-the-top flavor-wise , but extremely enjoyable . so many times i have tasted chocolate or cherry-chocolate beers that taste fake & powdered .  deep amber in color .  the mouthfeel is nothing exceptional but it is also not bad . it is a bit fizzy but this does n't offset the flavors .

smell - smells a bit like an ipa . my first thoughts were that it was very watered down .  a : opaque black , showing dark brown at the edges , with over one finger of diminishing beige foam head . heavy lacing remains on the glass .  that being said , it feels a bit too thin . qutie unfortunate .

sweet light malt aroma with some subtle spice and light floral hops . clean , crisp and extremely smooth creamy body .  wonderful big white head , nice and fluffy , lingered leaving lots of lacing . nice amber body , lots of small carbonation bubbles come to the surface .  mouthfeel : thin to reference the entire continuum of beers , but average for a pilsner .

smell - the scent is simple consisting mainly of malt but there is a hint of hops as well .  this beer is a great looking o'fest beer .  on the palate , this one is fairly light bodied with flavors of tart cherries , prunes , raisins and lightly roasted malt .

smell : the scent is relatively clean . there 's minor sweetness from the malts but the beer 's scent is n't very powerful or exciting . taste and mouthfeel : as far as macro lager goes this is pretty damn tasty .  a : pours a brilliant , hazy gold . one of the creamiest 2-finger eggshell heads i 've ever seen , with excellent retention .  mouth feel : frouthy and a bit slimly , carbonation is good .

nothing special about the smell -- maybe i 'm getting sick ? nah , just not a strong nose on this one . tastes really nice . very light on the spices .  found one 6 pack left at the local beer store ... a : perfect look . pitch black with no light shining through at all . super thick 2 inch white head that slowly fades .  m : mouthfeel is average . nothing special , medium to low carbonation and bone dry .

aroma is not strong , but is spicy and hoppy and inviting . flavor exceeds the wan aroma , being hoppy but not bitter , with nutty and malty undertones and spicy and horehound hints .  pours super dark black with thick tan head . this is stellar !  m - heavy , almost cough-syrup consistency with light carbonation .

the small was like burnt oak . a little hint of a plastic-like smell . aahh , a nice flavor a little burnt oak taste , a little coffee taste , a bit of a chocolate flavor , a nice blend of tastes with a solid hop background . a fine example of a porter .  pours a super clear fiery reddish orange . a creamy eggshell colored head sits on top and provides some awesome sticky lacing .  mouthfeel is a little thicker than i thought it would be , and it 's drinkable if it 's cold enough to mask its most interesting characteristic : this beer tastes like bananas .

s : sweet malt , real light hops . t : great noble hop flavour , grass , hay , soft bready malt .  poofy head unceasing and belgian in quality , this is a gorgeous looking light-colored ale . give this to someone drinking bmc just to watch their face pucker up .  this beer seriously surprised me . it pours a pretty nonexistent head . look like a deep mahogany in bottle and glass . taste is subtle but gets better after finish . it is a good brown ale . not mind-blowing but rather enjoyable to say the least . better than i expected .

s : floral , earthy hops are here . has a very fresh and clean feeling too it , even tho the hops are overloaded .  a foamy white head with very good retention . plenty of raising carbonation in the pilsner glass . beautiful .  mouthfeel is quite a bit thinner than i would have licked it to be , but the carbonation level is nice .

a nice fluffy one finger red brown head coats the top of my beer and leaves a lattice lacing on the glass . s- aroma is weak but i get hints of brown sugar and sweet malts . some caramel and/or toffee rounds it out . t- a nice caramel and toffee type of taste .  exceptional retention .  my first `` f '' rating here on ba .

s : nothing special . unroasted coffee beans , malts , some chocolate , and perhaps some barley .  a-deep brown with some reddishness . big tan head on this one . quite the lovely looking beer .  medium and a little grainy with prickly carbonation .

quite lively without being out of control . weaker aroma with some corn syrup notes and a low , biting spicy acidity . flavors are abundant in this pils .  poured into a snifter with laser etched bottom appearance - the classic obsidian shade of a imperial stout . topped with a creamy , mocha shaded , full finger , head of foam : this is the beer 's lingerie , working some awesome visuals and coaxing me to proceed .  nice taste , extremely easy to drink and light bodied . the only problem is that it is a little gassy and over carbonated . very nice .

s : clean and crisp . bread with just a touch of hops . t : slightly tart and malty .  a : pours a dark , nearly impenetrable black body with a perfect finger 's worth of light tan head . it 's exquisite , in the way that all nitro-tap dark beers are : watching the suds coalesce into a dark body as they cascade up the beer is nothing short of eye-pleasing .  mouthfeel was deceptively thin because of the high carbonation , but was n't that bad if given a chance .

sierra nevada esb pale brown with a fluffy slight off-white head . slight herbaceous hops and pale malt balance . extremely refined bitter , clean and crisp overall with a wonderful malt balance . carbonated and defined upfront with a sticky pine hoppiness , feint grass , caramel and pale malt along with a clean aftertaste . just a very well made esb , easy to drink , and tasty . recommended .  $ 13.99 / 4 pack dan 's liquor plover , wisconsin appearance - a hazy pale orange to dark yellow in color . the bright white head tops the brew at up to 3 inches and is solid . as the head slowly tapers it leaves a great lacing along the inside of the glass .  for such a lively beer , it falls a bit flat in the mouth - not terrible , i just expected a bit more .

2005 vintage , purchased 10/30/09 . this beer was completely flat and was very murky , looked like prune juice . i guess you could call it port-like , but it was so oxidized it was undrinkable . i guess that 's what i get for buying a vintage ale for $ 4.39 .  this is how lagers should look . a beautiful golden color with a steady head that stays well .  the flavor and mouthfeel is where i miss the original bender or some of the bigger coffee stout beers . the most disappointing part of the beer is the finish which has a nutty , dry bender like flavor , but is overall rather thin and has a watery character .
