smells buttery , biscuity , and toast . flavor has much more to offer than the aroma .  it is really a nice looking beverage .  this is an epl through and through . do n't be persuaded by the pilsener title . i had it after a holsen which is a real grain bomb . neither beer is that great but this one seemed inferior . and compared to holsten permium that is n't saying much . i you like stella artois or heineken or something like that in a can then go or it , but it is n't too good .

the spoetzl boys have done it again ! this beer smeels good ; not that overpowerering wet barley smell you get with some strong beers , but a light kinda fruity smell , almost like an apple cider .  i recently tried rogue 's chocolate stout and was really impressed , however this one blew that out of the water . the main reason for this was probably the nitro charger in the can which gave the beer a `` icecream-ish '' mouthfeel , and also lended to quite a show while waiting for the head to form in the glass ( which remained the entire time and was very creamy ) .  m - high carbonation , but a little watery .

the beer pours thick and caramel colored with a white head , and a strange aroma . you can tell the increased sugar content by the sweetness on the front end of this creamy beer . either as an introduction to craft beers or an evening session beverage , this offering is a very good example of quality craft brewing .  pours a full three finger head . great retention and lacing .  an overall fantastic drink a- poured a rusty orange/brown color . kept a nice white head the whole drink s- like nothing you 've ever smelled before as far as im concerned . had a pleasant wheat aroma t- detected not only a creamy wheat flavor , but also a hint of blueberry m- thick d- i highly suggest it . not usually a fan of beer of this nature ( wheats ) , but would try another make of this

s minimal , sweet smell , malty .  a- an amazing pour.. deep ruby red highlights in a dark brown beer . a salmon-colored head that laces nicely .  mouthfeel - kinda effervescent . nothing exceptional .

served on-tap in a clear pint glass a : beautiful amber-orange hue with thick , sticky off-white head and plenty of lace s : disappointing aroma overall -- muted and weak , especially with the hops grown on location , i thought the aroma would be heavy . floral cascade hops aroma is definitely there , but it is medium in intensity . maybe it is a function of the overly cold serving temperature , but i thought more hops and pale malts aroma would be there . t : the taste surpasses the aroma by a long way .  i finally decided to buy one ... a : perfect look for a barleywine . deep copper with a thick white head that never completely fades .  mouthfeel is a bit sticky and the flavors stick around for a bit after swallowing .

presentation : 12 oz . smell : i 'm surprised that i do n't get a bit more here , but what i do get is a hint of fruity sweetness , a preview of the hops that are sure to follow in the first drink and just a bit of caramel . taste : wow ... my nose did n't fail me , there is the hop bitterness right up front , but it is complemented later on by the malt character that follows . like a good imperial ipa , these go down easy and hide the higher abv . verdict : a great beer , but a bit young and brash .  hinninger kaiser pils looks beautiful , and almost unmatched when poured into a regular stein . there are vast amounts of bright white and soft pillowy head , and the body is gold and crystal clear .  the mouthfeel is low carbonated almost syrupy , not what i expected .

this is my first year to try the anchor christmas ale and i really enjoy it . s- this is the only department that i 'm finding lacking about this beer . the aroma just is n't strong enough to match wits w/ the taste . so in all- its delicious . m- hearty and lingering , but not lingering strongly enough to be annoying . d- i love it .  it pours a beautiful dark bloody red with a short-lasting pinkish head .  tightly packed carbonation which makes the body feel more medium , feels just a bit too foamy for my tastes .

s : sourdough bread , yeast , dry alcohol esters akin to a chardonnay , a little bit of nail polish . i was underwhelmed by the nose and the mouthfeel was nothing to write home about .  dark horse special reserve black bier poured an impenetrable black in color topped by a dense , tan head . an impressive amount of belgian lace remained on my glass .  thin in the mouth , which leads to great drinkability . would make a good session beer .

smell is dusty coco and irish cream , lactose ?  ..poured from a can into my tulip glass ... . appearance : wow , liquid tar pours out of the can and into the glass . this stuff looks like it could stain the glass its in .  kombucha is usually very vinegary , but this was more in line with a reserved lambic . carbonated to the tongue , but low head retention . m+d- it is a touch watery .

s. i get some citrus and floral hops and rye t. first thing i taste is floral hops followed by some sweet malts and finishing off with some citrus , primarily orange and grapefruit .  a - it 's damn hot and muggy here right now , and the bright golden body and thick , fluffy white head 'atop this beer looks really damn good .  it smells and tastes like a cheap beer . it is not worth the money that a premium beer can ask . i ca n't think of anything good to say about this beer other than i 'm hoping it will be gone soon . i 've tried pawning the beer off on people and they did n't want to drink it either .

smell is faint , even right after pouring . nothing really leaps out at me - not bad , but nothing really good either . towards the end of the glass as the beer has warmed up some of the hops is a little more present , but again , it is faint .  the pour is outstanding with brilliant white cranium and a golden rich looking and clear body . lots of carbonation is stimulating the head retention that lasts throughout the 1 liter serving .  i think that it is a bit overcarbonated and that the body is a bit thin , but the smell and taste are absolutely wonderful , and i could drink this all night .

light sweetness with a bit of nutty , buttery hops .  st-ambroise oatmeal stout from mcauslan brewing pours dark in my glass with a 1 finger light brown head .  good , predictable macro carbonation , not too fizzy , and a softly crisp , dry , thin , light bodied mouthfeel , average , to be expected , nothing to really complain about here , again , predictable , you know what you getting before you pop open the can .

aroma is pretty mild . light hops and a mild bready malt that gives it an almost dusty quality .  poured into a tulip pours a beautiful clear deep amber with two fingers of thick , creamy head ( almost like foam on a root beer float ) .  m - syrapy with a decent carbonation .

s - malty with a sharp cocoa aroma . t - roasted malt of chocolate and coffee with a definite hop presence .  a : a beauty ! hazy copper with a creamy head with tons of retention and lace .  it feels just a bit watery .

good head retention , very clear , and light aroma . first sip and you can taste the light maltiness of this brown ale .  pours a very clear but very dark scarlet , clear enough to se through but dark enough to soak up a lot of the light . buttery tan head froths up out of control and sits there as if it were a solid object . it leaves frothy , thick lacing behind , and absolutely refuses to diminish to less than a full finger throughout the glass .  in fact the beer this most reminded me of was the dixie blackened voodoo i reviewed which had the look and taste along stout lines but a much lighter body .

it 's got an off white head but it fade pretty quick . smells very dry , really roasted with coffee and some chocolate notes on it . the dryness is similar to a belgian but not much more is present that would scream belgian ale .  appearance ; thick and creamy beige head , perfect retention throughout the drink . beautiful chunky lacing , dark , brownish amber body .  taste : thin malt levels , corn , honey , green grapes , grass , and no bitterness . mouthfeel : lightly crisp to start , dry and smooth at the finish . light in body , thin in flavor . clean aftertaste .

i detect fruits , alcohol , and some roasted sugar ; very faint and rather subtle , perhaps a bit too subtle hence the lower score . the taste is both typical and different for this style . hints of fruit and alcohol are present , but at the same time this beer is highly carbonated with a fair amount of hops creating a creamy texture that feels unique from any other tripel i 've ever had .  pours a a clear gold with a constant upward stream of fine white bubbles and an extremely long lasting , frumpy , pure white head . the overall effect is of a beautiful looking beer that is interesting to taste but that i wish would stand still for a moment so that my palate could peg it down .  lighter with some fizzy carbonation and a dry finish .

this beer starts out very mellow with a very small bouquet , but wow what a surprise on the tongue , i was really impressed with this ale .  22oz bottle ( best by july 2010 ) poured into a dogfish head signature glass . a - pours a mostly clear bright orange with a beautiful whipped creamy one finger cap of foam with excellent retention . when the beer level falls ( the head never really goes away and stays with the beer throughout the glass ) , it leaves behind lots of sticky spiderwebs of lacing on the glass .  m - carbonation is more muted than i thought .

my first hunch was that the spars artesian waters may have enhanced the big fluffy mouthfeel , the terse rocky crown , and regal lace adorning this pale ale . cascade hops are alleged to provide aroma , but my pint delivered no smell at all , perhaps due to the ongoing hops shortage .  i doubt a hefeweizen can be more appealing : pours a hazy golden orange with a massive off-white head that retains impressively ... the paradigm of a hefe .  the moutfeel is medium , thicker than a lager , but about average for this style .

s - fruits , malt , mild not pungent smell .  a - a very great looking beer . a black body on the bar , very dark brown if held up to some light , with red shining through on the edges . awesome fine bubble , off-white , two finger head that left intricate sheets and lace on the side .  m : mouthfeel is thin and light . thin in an offputting way .

s : malti aroma with some floral scents ? some fruitiness seems to be there as well . d : budvar is light enough to be had alot .  this brew poured a medium head of fine to large brown bubbles and an opaque black body . it has a very mild malt aroma to weak for a good stout and a strong coffee flavor . i did not taste the typical chocolate or roasted notes that are typical of most good stouts , only coffee .  hahahahahaha bourbon my as- . this beer tastes like the worst cake frosting i 've ever had . body 's not bad either if you can get by the taste .

smell : light , slight dry bitterness lingers in the scent . drinkability : very drinkable , while the bitterness is the intended emphasis , the dry hop taste helps it achieve that bitter end , unique and palatable .  pours with a very healthy light tan head ... .some molasses , burnt caramel aroma ... dark ruby red ... quite smoky on the first sip , which develops some delicious flavours ! ... alcohol is very well masked ... leaves some great lacing ... some will find it abit thin but i find it very drinkable and way to easy to drink , this sixer will be gone very quick !  on the tongue , everything that was on the nose is amplified , bigger , bolder , stronger , more . the body was a bit different than typical , a touch more syrupy and thicker . still nice but not what i 'm really looking for in a wit .

the nose is suprisingly light for a big stout with hints of chocolate and dark malt . a pretty solid russian imperial with its only real weak spot in the nose .  the body was clear and bright . the rich golden/apricot color glowed . the 1 '' + of frothy , creamy , off-white head lingered- leaving splotchy lace .  they float the lemon in the beer , so you do n't have a chance to yank it out before it imparts flavor . great example of the heffeweizen style , with banana and clove aroma and flavors . a light beer that can be quaffed in copious amounts .

smell is of tame mild hops and crystal malts .  the pour is a beautiful two fingers of brown head . pitch black in color with excellent lacing . this is what a porter should look like !  smell has ton of spice upfront , with belgian yeast and banana . lots of pepper in the taste , which is great because i love pepper . nice bready malts with the belgian yeast flavour . a bit overcarbonated for my preference . this was n't hard at all to get through the bomber by myself .

probably canada 's finest macro lager ! the taste is sweet , grainy , and slightly hopped . now that moosehead invested in a us headquarters in colorado , they have no more excuse for not bringing it to the usa . it would kick the shit out of all the other canadian imported brands hands down . ( and i am admittedly a molson guy myself )  excellent retention and a smashing amount of heavy lacing . this is just a beautiful beer .  this brings us to mouthfeel and i 'm once again taken back to the question of carbonation . in the mouth there is a degree of weight and intensity , however this is beset on both sides by an intense carbonation that strongly effects the overall weight of the beer . the carbonation issue is really just a thing of personal taste but it needs to be put out there , but , overall ; this is a fantastic beer .

smells of toasted malts , quaker oatmeal , and just a touch of cabbage .  15.5 ibus og 1.016 12 oz bottle with a best by date of 02/20/2011 poured into a saison dupont glass on 12/16/2010 . appearance 5/5 brilliantly clear , deep ruby brown with a light pink colored fluffy and persistent head that left excellent lacing .  spices are clearly evident in the flavor ... some cloves and cardamom both come through with a lot of caramel malts , and an unfamiliar flavor , that i am , in my mind , linking with the yeast used . the beer is pretty light for such a dark color . i expected more carbonation , and i was a little bit disappointed at the smoothness .

being fairly new to the style , i expected much more fruitiness up front , but got the earthy , roasty bitterness of the darker malts at first , and not until later , when the beer warmed , did the flavors begin to blend and the sweetness begin to come out . the nose was muted . the thing that stood out most was an aroma like grain that had started to turn into a bit of wet fungus .  a - a thick , frothy and solid head with great stamina . the body is a deep yet translucent orange .  watery feel for a stout but with just enough body to get you through .

s= smells sort of liek a typical beer . quite nice with the corriander actually . o= while the smell was a bit of a miss the taste is wonderful .  i may be a little biased , but i love to just admire and look at beers this black and opaque .  m - light bodied , thin with a bit of a sticky feel .

the aroma was of faint malts with a hint of fruit notes .  poured this one into a 33cl guinness glass . produces mounds of sticky and rocky tan cranium , and has a black opaque body with reddish hues visible on the edge of the glass .  beautiful mouthfeel : needs more carbonation .

smell i did like so much . taste i did love though , i think this is the first beer i 've had where i genuinely dislike the smell but love the taste . wonderfully complex , fruity ( apples inparticular ) , malty , sweet , a kiss of alochol , it was great . overall a very good beer .  in fact , it 's probably the darkest beer i 've seen in recent memory . a real black hole of a stout . oh , and despite not being allowed in as a scoring factor , the bottle is one of the coolest looking i 've ever seen .  enjoyable to be sure , but it seems like maybe , just maybe , it could have a slightly higher carbonation level .

light lacing ... the aroma is really light , i can barely pull anything out , a little sweet coffee but that 's about it ... the taste is pretty and a surprise . very flavorful , a baltic should be sweet but this is pretty roasty and light smoke which actually is really nice .  definitely the best looking of the three with a nice yellow/orangey color , cloudy with tasty yeasties .  source/serving : draft smell : coriander , orange flavors , belgian yeastiness , and some brown sugar . overall fairly deep , dark flavors . taste : quite sweet up front with pronounced coriander . the middle does n't really go anywhere , just sustained - or even more - coriander . perhaps there is a ephemeral note of some ripe fruits and alcohol . disappointing . finish is oddly bitter , noticeable alcohol and has a slightly off spiciness .

s - sweet , bready malt , dried fruits - golden raisins , apricots . some metallic aroma apparent .  a - cloudy reddish brown body with a pale tan head that lasts forever at a height of two plus inches .  m - the feel is sharp initially with a chalky and sublime salty finish on the palate .

nose is rather light , with some spices ... nutmeg , allspice taste is a creaminess that is unique .  finger and a half of white lacing ? insane lacing ? the lacing was some of the finest i have ever seen .  m : carbonation comes on unexpectedly crisp , but it drinks smoothly .

smell is weaker than expected , but fuity , with notes of wine ( for obvious reasons ) . great summer ale . very fruity , and definitely on the sweeter side . perfect carbonation , makes this a very drinkable beer .  a very nice looking beer .  the mouthfeel is a bit lighter than expected but doesnt detract , and drinkability is excellent for the abv .

smell : smell is mostly of malt , hard to detect any hops or really any other scent . really not an aromatic beer .  the beer was hazy dark copper color , thick rich looking off-white head , lots of wet lacing on the glass .  this colored water pours with a pale golden body topped by a thin head with no laciong at all . the aroma is barely detectable with some malty notes . the flavor is almost non existent , however some malty sweetness is evident . no wonder everyone puts a lime in these , it 's to add some flavor .

s : the smell is much weaker than the taste . in fact because of this the taste surprised me a bit . t : a bitter-hoppy start , then a nutty/sweet-caramel finish .  the beer looks great , dark brown very bubbly brew with a tan creamy chunky head that sits nicely through out the expierence . nice lacing - very impressive looking beer .  taste : this is a fairly thin-bodied brew , and the carbonation seems a little much . it has a nice malty taste in the middle , but it 's dominated by strong , orange-tasting hops . this is certainly a hoppy beer , but the hops are n't that intense or asskicking .

s : nose is somewhat muted - sweet caramel malts with minor smoked notes . t : taste is nice .  a : the beer pours a dark brown/red hue . a big , pillowy head sits on top and leaves some nice lacing on the glass as it recedes . it is a beautiful beer .  mouthfeel : extremely light feel considering the alcohol and massive aroma .

poured into a 16oz widmer glass , i wanted some of the aromas to come out on this one . a - dark , deep brown fading up to a pitch black . s - weak point of the brew i must say . i can only pick up some smoke , a metallic sting , and some sour mash . t - much more flavorful than the aroma leads one to believe . massive roasted caramel malt profile , toasted chicory , and some mild bitterness .  the color is as promised - not just copper , but the most refined , polished expression of crystalline copper purity you 've ever seen in an ale . the head is feathery and shows graceful retention and lace .  the mouth is actually a little heavy and chalky for what should be , and mostly is , refreshing .

750ml , corked and caged ... cork reads 2002 vintage . the smell is something i do n't really like . it smells a bit citrusy and spicy but has an acrid foul twang in it as well .  appearance is great . perfect clear ( no yeast in the pour at first ) peach color with a totally luscious looking cream colored head that wo n't go away and leaves plenty of lacing .  feels a bit thin , low-medium body and medium carbonation .

bone white head ontop of a watered-down coffee pour . aroma of coffee , toasted , buttery bread and grilled cheese . ( i know , fuckin weird , but i ca n't deny it . ) light cocoa powder , nutella smeared toast , and ovaltine powder .  fantastic presentation . very light and frothy head over orange-yellow .  m - medium bodied and somewhat oily , but the carbonation is a little too lively and prickly for the style , which in turn really thins out the body .

low smell , lots of lurking semi-roasted malt and some booze . some fruit , too .  the beer poured a dark cordovan with a gorgeous tan head .  overall : very light bodied for the style , but very drinkable .

the hop presence was there , but not particularly noticable . overall this is a quality english brown ale , but may be disappointing if you 're expecting a true warmer .  black color . very thick full cascading type head .  the mouthfeel is kind of bland .

the aroma was average . earthy grains sweet malt . i think the taste is what stands out .  pours a light gold with brilliant clarity and a firm frothy white head .  looking at it you 'd expect a stout , smelling it you 'd expect it to be sweet - it 's neither - and it feels thinner than expected as well !

not a strong smell of light nutty malts . ah yes ... a taste i thought i forgot ; a fantastic malt and hops balance .  lots of lacing . beautiful , simply beautiful .  i gave the mouthfeel a lower score due to the extremely bitter after-taste and the thin-ness of the body .

smell- the smell was very mute in this pouring ... maybe just this in specific , all i could detect were mild vanilla notes .  this beer is just beautiful when poured into a glass . two finger light brown head that is very creamy .  some bitter to this as well there is still some hops to it a little syrupy but there is some carbonation to it so it is bearable .

not a very strong smell emminating , but heavy on the malts and chocolates with some sense of coffee . definately a roasty scent .  impenetrable black with an ovaltene head .  mouthfeel is thin and becomes slightly tannic at the finish .

sporadic sloches of soapy lacing left behind . citrus hop aroma with hints of pine and citrus fuit balanced out by some sweet caramel malt . very hoppy for the style with a bitter piney hop blast up front which is balanced by a nice caramel malt backbone . i 'm also picking up slight hints of rye .  pitch brown/black with a giant , never-ending mocha head . plenty of lace left behind . one beautiful beer . certainly the chocolate and coffee element are there , earth and oak make a solid appearance .  poured into my maudite snifter and produces a caramel color with a finger and a half of off-white foam . light carbonation . banana , pear and floral aromas . a rather tart , spicy taste with some alcohol taste present . while this is highly drinkable , the experience is more enjoyable as it warms .

salty briny nose , most likely through the power of suggestion .  the frothy head is immense , this had the appearance of a fine hefeweizen but looked great for a saison too .  f & t : crisp , firm moderate body , more rounded feeling than a lot of macro lagers .
nice looking stout . smell is typical stout smell , nothing spectacular .  black as the night , exquisite head .  mouthfeel is thin with just moderate carbonation .

s : not the strongest smell , but their is a faint hoppy smell . t/m : basic pale ale taste but with a crazy ipa kick . d : great . best pale ale from a can i 've ever had .  poured a dark , golden amber into my affligem gold-rimmed goblet . looks beautiful .  it 's slightly watery , but refreshing and finishes a little dry mouthfeel is pretty average .

light wheat and banana aroma . balanced wheat and lager with notes of banana , citrus , and occasionally clove .  nice clear amber with very light tan head . great head retention with thick and creamy lacing .  the mouthfeel is light to moderate .

it has a dark amber , hazy appearance with a somewhat lackluster smell . the flavor is a blend of chocoloate with floral overtones , a little bit of hops , and barley .  this beer is very nice looking . poured into a lindemans glass , this beer is very red and is topped with a short pink head that leaves sheets of lacing on the glass .  almost feels a bit thin and watery . the mouthfeel throws me a little because it 's a bit thin , but on the whole , it 's a tasty and quite drinkable bruin .

not much smell ( unless you live on arsenal , it 's really hard to smell an ab beer . ) very good taste .  a - super clear deep golden color with a thick head and excellent retention s - grainy malt aroma , slight noble hop scents as it warms t - super clean , crisp malt up front with a crisp moderate hop bitterness on the finish that helps to dry it out ; clean lager character : no esters or phenols from the yeast m - medium-light body with moderately high carbonation d - i do n't know if this totally fits the oktoberfest/mrzen category , as it is marketed as a fest-bier , which does not always follow the generally accepted definition of the style , but this beer is highly drinkable and could be enjoyed in just about any kind of weather with a wide variety of foods .  m - medium to light body .

with this beer , the hops just kind of say `` hello '' and then the malt takes over things . s : i do n't get much from the smell at all , just a bit of bready malts . t : the hop presence is sufficient , but no where near dominate . thankfully the malt character is excellent , featuring sweet biscuit , caramel , and a bit of black tea like bitterness . o : this is a fine ipa that i would drink any time , even though it 's not exactly my favorite example of the style .  very attractive hazy dark straw color with a big frothy head and gobs of lacing . this beer looks perfect .  not a big wit guy , but it is summer in san diego and i just got done playing some b ball and was thirsty . i always see it at places and not big on most japanese breweries . very refreshing and complex at the same time . over all i am glad i tried it and i am actually going to buy a pack down the street right now .

it has a roasted , grassy and metallic aroma , which may have a note of chocolate .  beer looks absolutely beautiful !  mouthfeel i liked the fullness of the body here , but the carbonation was quite annoying . otherwise , this felt good .

source/serving : bottle smell : raisins and chocolate , but quite mild actually . taste : quite bitter up front followed by a massive wave of malts . notes : a multidimensional beer that has so much going for it .  12oz pour $ 5.00 goose island clybourn goose 's ipa was served in a straight tulip style glass . poured a dark golden hinting at copper with a bright white one finger head .  m : the mouthfeel is average .

smell : i could n't really smell much . taste : definitely bitter , but in a good way .  pours a hazy pale golden yellow with sky-high , frothy white head with great retention and generous lacing . beautiful beer !  m : very light , slightly watery , lower carbonation .

not much smell there , which is a huge letdown compared to everything else about this beer . faint slightly smoky smell with hints of chocolate . no real pepper smell , but you can actually feel a slight burn in your nose . t - chocolate , roasted malt , slight smoky flavor , and chipotle pepper in the background .  appearance- pours a large , fluffy 2 finger head that very slowly recedes into some nice clinging lace and a fluffy cap . the color is a nice red/brown and i am pretty impressed to see just a slight amount of bottle sediment .  ok , born and raised in st.louis.. i may be a bit biased . but last summer , i had my heart stole by this beer . i didnt want it to happen.. it just sorta did . its bright a little rich , and nice bitter finish . citrus and maybe honey , i think in these hot humid summers , it cant get any better than a nice summer kolsh at about 35 degrees . ahhhh

not much of a hops taste more malty aroma which comes thru on the tsate . a very drinkable beer that i would recommend ... ... ... ... ... cheers  huge frothy dark tanned foam whips itself into a firm stacking and keeps a steadily thick amount consistantly present on top . one very nice looking strong ale !  body is thinner than expected on the palate , and the uppity carbonation level does n't help .

easy light drink , bit much on water , particularly with lower alcohol . a bit of bite -molasses and hoppy . liked : only mildly roasty , only bit of the coffee , and hint of chocolates and nutty . very good stout .  hold it up to the light to see something really incredible . an amazing looking beer .  m : it was thin with moderate carbonation .

smell : it 's disappointing to say the least because i do n't get that much hops . very faint citrusy and piney notes . it 's still a very good beer . very good , but maybe a bit over-hyped in my opinion .  coloration is a nice ruddy brown with a healthy 1 '' khaki head which is simply beautiful in appearance . huge and uneven and thick .  i understand it may the fruit flavor comes from apricots . as expected the taste did n't improve the experience . i gave the rest of the six pack away and got similar reviews from all who tried it .

a pleasant wintery smell , although slightly weak .  3 fingers of gorgeous creamy of white head . excellent retention w/ a little less lacing down the glass .  appearance : like beer smell : beery taste : like pils in germany mouthfeel : beer-like drinkability : i did n't see jane stop until they stopped bringing it i 'd say its an excellent example of the style .

as far as i 'm concerned beamish is just what a dark beer is supposed to look like . heavily roasted barley gives it at rich , complex , almost meaty flavor . it does n't reach the level of complexity of some of the best dark belgian beers , but i do n't think it 's supposed to . it 's mild enough that it wo n't conflict with any food pairing , and simultaneously robust enough to stand up to anything . i ca n't give it above average for smell because it does n't really have one , but that hardly detracts from the overall experience .  the pour begins with an ever-expanding head that forms quickly and sorta takes over . very mousse-like and very sturdy in formaiton and retention . the color is the standard copper-golden and with typical dry-hopped haze . an outstanding look .  this is not a beer for holding onto and chatting this is a beer for downing quick . when it heats up , the taste gets worse . there are alot better australian beers than this .

i love a good stout - and this is a good stout . i am bias to dark beers , but this one is all around very enjoyable . notes of anything dark - chocolate , coffee , but again , nothing that stands out or over anything else , and working together in harmony . it finished really smooth , very very slight bitter , and sweet almost , and entirely satisfying .  beautiful amber colour , huge and fluffy head lasts `` forever '' .  poured on tap . big thanks to sean for this ! pours a deep cloudy golden color with almost no head at all . smell is nice and sweet with a great maple aroma . taste is nice and sweet , maply but sweet enough to even it all out , easy drinking and super excellent , very awesome !

bought at/price : binny 's / $ 4.99 dennis : one of the first bear republic brews i think we 've tried , this definitely sets a good tone for the brewery . the smell of this stout when opened is perhaps a little sweeter than expected ( molasses perhaps ) but the taste is a bit more mellow . nicely hopped , there 's just a twinge of bitterness on the swallow ( probably where that 8.1 % alcohol is hiding ) but over all everything is nicely balanced to make a pretty darn good stout . jen : i am very impressed with this stout . this stout is a bargain and is definitely necessary for a stout lovers fridge .  this beer pours with a lot more darker golden colored body , than its pilsner sister .  slightly thin body but just a great flavor .

s : malt . that was about it . a small nutty scent , and alcohol was there but otherwise , malt . very nice .  appearance- beer pulls a hazy golden with a spiderweb pattern across the top .  the feel was slick , medium-bodied and mildy carbonated , the best aspect of this otherwise horrid brew .

very little smell . taste : great mouthfilling taste ! upfront caramel malt with a hint of sweetness .  dark orange . lofty , creamy bubbles clung together above the liquid , showing very good density .  it had a light mouthfeel and slightly carbonated .

nothing overwhelming in aroma . slightly hoppy . outstanding .  huge tan head with really tight bubbles . head lingers for the entire glass leaving lacing behind . brilliantly clear .  feel is light and refreshing , but very active , carb is felt and a bit distracting , it 's not a sleeper .

smell was mainly malt with subtle hops . not the greatest aroma . taste was much better .  bottle courtesy of jjpm74 : poured a clear dark black color ale with a big foamy head with perfect retention and perfect lacing .  roasted aroma with hints of dark ( bittersweet ) chocolate and coffee . could be fuller bodied , a little less on the tounge then expected . different flavors hint you on the first sip , roasted malt , coffee , dark chocolate , hop citrusness . finishes dry with some hop bitterness and a nice aftertaste . another quality brew from the boys and rogue !

the bottled version leaves much to be desired vs. on draught . extremely refreshing and drinkable , pleasant sweet malt w/ barely discernable hops for structure .  pours a bright and clear dark amber color . head is a nice half an inch , and retaining well . looks great .  i thought the mouthfeel may have been a tad dry and thin for all that malt , but that just adds to the drinkability , which is very good for the strength of this beer .

i was impressed with the rich amber colour , but the smell was very plain . could n't really get a whiff of anything off this beer . the mouthfeel is gorgeous , very creamy and goes down an absolute treat . overall very nice , i 'd drink it again . its there in the smell as well , however faint .  appearance : thick white/tan chunky head with excellent retention and nice lacing . a better looking red ale you 'll be hard pressed to find .  mouthfeel/drinkability- mouthfeel was at best average for the style .

the smell was of malt with a slite hint of hops . overall this one was excellent .  a : poured a nice deep yellow with a two finger head that left beautiful lacing down the side as it subsided .  m - medium carbonation with a rather watery texture .

concentric rings of lacing all the way down & pretty good head head retention s : some chocolate & roasted malt , not a bunch t : nice subtle chocolate notes up front .  imperial is the perfect name for this outstanding beer appearance : black . has a dark brown/light black one-finger head which lasts a good minute or two and leaves nice foamy lacing on the glass .  smooth but lifeless .

it has a bitter/citrusy smell to it . it kind of has a bitter taste like a pilsner at first .  reviewed 10/24/2007 ( bottle ) : pours a reddish brown , lighter brown edges . tan head , good sized and lasting . good lacing .  medium-bodied rather than thick .
nose is sweet and hoppy , but with a slightly unpleasant piney note . not sure what it is , but it smells a bit off .  a great looking pale ale .  the mouthfeel seems a tad too watery as well .

the nose was balanced nicely , but it was not that forward .  from a 500 ml brown bottle . massive head development on the pour , a solid foamy mocha coloured entity with amazing retentio that settles very slowly . the body is deep pitch opaque black , faint almond nimbus when held to light .  mouthfeel : it was a very light beer .

s : initially , i get a wet dog smell but that fades quickly into a nice nutty coffee flavor . very nicely done , minus the wet dog smell in the nose .  very dark brown with a reddish head , great retention and lacing .  taste is clean and very hoppy in a sweet and earthy way . not as much citrus/pine note in taste , lots of hearty hops and almost fruit like malt backgrounds . very easy drinking double . highly enjoyable but not something completely unexpectant from the style .

smell - malty and some hops , with an interesting citrus tone .  a - darkish brown with impressive lacing and a mountain of cool cloudy head .  the taste is really well balanced but the beer feels a little thin and watery which is surprising given it 's alcohol content .

s - sweet and a somewhat floral citrus .  pours a pitch black with a nice creamy head .  pours black but with some deep red highlights with a slight off-white head that is gone in a flash leaving nothing behind , milk chocolate is very prevelant in the aroma with a little smokiness and a roasted coffee hint.nice deeply roasted flavor with big doses of cocoa and smoke , alot of flavor melding going on but seemed a little light in the mouthfeel department otheriwise a top notch brew.a easy drinker with alot of flavor needs a little tweaking to be great in my opinion .

smells of dry dirty yeast , sweet corn and plumb skins .  this one pours a nice opaque black in the glass with nice a tan/brown head that has good retention . a perfect picture of a stout .  m - very light and crisp .

s - toasty malt with a citrus hop notes . t - good toasty malt taste .  exceptional appearance ... very dark brown with a pillowy head that clings in a beautiful lace .  m- carbonation is high , and initial mouthfeel is good , but somewhat thin .

again , the smell was `` off '' but all was forgotten when tasting .  it 's a rather nifty looking glass , too . it certainly appeared appetizing . looks beautiful poured into a fancy glass !  a bit too thin , and a tad over-carbonated . the body was n't quite there , but still a winner .

appearance : amber color with a 1/2 '' off-white head ; looks really good smell : little bit of hops ; some kind of weird smell ( maybe some caramel malt ?  pours pitch black and completely opaque without even the slightest bit of lighter hues when held to a light source and a frothy dark chocolate neige/brown head that slowly fades into a lasting ring . large chunks of soapy lacing are left behind .  the mouthfeel is crisp and refreshing , although almost too light and dry .

smell is sour canned fruit and syrupy peaches .  by blackberry so this will be short . beautiful pitch black with dark tan head . lots of hops in this dark intense beer .  medium bodied slick mouthfeel , slightly cloying .

seems like a lot of the winter warmers i have been drinking lately have been a little heavy on the hops . this one has a large malt body with just enough hops to keep rom becoming sweet .  appearance : beautiful yellow sunset over the western skies - 5 smell : minty pine with a touch of aspen covered hills - 5 taste : tastes of juniper molasses tea , if youve had it you know what i mean - 5 mouthfeel : have to be honest on this one - 2 drinkablitiy : if youre listening to willie and youve had a few ... 5  lightly bodied with a lean , but passably dextrinous mouthfeel .

a very quiet `` pop '' of the cork ... pour was carbonated and good ... whew . light yellow/gold ... decent bright , white head . good lacing ... nothing spectacular . aroma is a touch dissapointing ... was expecting a bit more spice and smells ... a tiny bit of spice and a little wheat ... taste is very good ... bitterly balanced ... slightly citrussy and quite malty .  very possibly the most gorgeous glass of beer i 've ever seen . this beer pours a dark crimson rose with a massive pink head that leaves just little lines of pink lacing down the sides of the glass . it really is a pretty beer . top notch i 'd say .  m : light to mid bodied , little watery at first bit smooths out as it warms up .

s : very malt-forward ( almost like a red ale ) , a bit of sticky sweetness , caramel , earth , florals , dried hay . barely any hops detected ( ? even though the smell leaves a bit to be desired , overall i 'm really impressed .  a - poured out a deep copper hue with a tan , bubbly/soapy , 4-finger head that left sticky rings of lace .  mouthfeel is the only real weakness for this beer .

smell is not too strong . chocolate and coffee with some sweetness to it creamy sweet bitter roasted coffee .  it pours a luscious opaque sable brown with a thick , fairly persistent , fluffy , fine-bubbled pale tan head that leaves a good bit of lacing .  so , i guess it 's got an average mouthfeel .

s - a very spicy aroma with a little bit of citrus hops coming through .  from the bottle , poured dark brown to black , with a nice foamy tan head , with good lacing .  mouthfell was ok , but it is a stout , it better have a decent feel to it .

smell - caramel pasty with a extremely slight hint of hops .  pours a dark brown with some reddish hue.foamy head , vanilla colored milk shake looking lace that lasts the duration of the drink .  the looks are not deceiving , in that this beer goes down very easy . the finish is semi-clean with a hint of flavor left on the tongue . p.s . i like this beer better on tap than from the bottle !

low aroma . some sweet malt . smooth body-has that soft `` creaminess '' you find in a great pils . very drinkable . damn good beer .  lacing is superb but head retention is merely `` well above average . '' color is an opaque blackness that turns a reddish brown only when held up to the brightest lights at the thinnest portion of your glass .  almost a medicine-y mouthfeel .

smells a bit like wet golden retriever and flowers .  a - dark , dark brown allowing a mere hint of light through at the base of the pint . the head is substantial at two plus inches and maintains some very nice lacing .  m- a solid amount of carbonation coupled with a lighter body makes this drink overall a little too light for my personal tastes .

smell : fruity/floral hops with a noticeable bitterness . i 'm not a fan of smelling the bitterness beforehand .  beautiful chestnut colour , very good head .  it had a medium body but was kind of rough along the palate as it went down .

not much aroma initially.nice 2 finger foamy head . feels like at porter wiuth the exception of nice spiciness to it .  pours almost black , with just a hint of ruby when backlit . but the head ... the head is just perfect .  veeeery smooth taste , could drink a few of these . not sure how true to the style this one is , almost like a stout lite . i like it quite a bit though , hides a 6.3 % well . malts are dominant in the flavor , but balanced excellently ... i dig it , dawg . would buy again , but not a super deal at $ 4.88 a bomber

nose - didnt get a good smell because of the atmosphere - fried bar food ruins beer aroma .  one of the prettiest beers i have ever seen : a deep ruby red color with lots of carbonation , a creamy , foamy , rocky head , light brown head and some nice sticky lace . the head diminished , but settled down to a fine creamy layer that lasted throughout .  mouthfeel is ok. not too thick or too thin , but carbonation could be a little weaker .

not an incredibly pronounced smell , maybe a bit of spiciness from the rye , but not a whole lot to detect in the smell department . i really love the taste , nice and spicy from the rye , a good bit of roastedness on the end .  perfect looking for a stout .  this beer pours a hazy orange/amber has a 1/2 finger head with very little retention and spotty lacing . the aroma is a strong citrus at first but as the beer warms there is a earthy bread odor . the taste is a spicy citrus with bitter grapefruit in the finish . this beer is smooth and very drinkable , i plan on having this one again .

it pours rather unimpressive , and the smell is pretty much non-existant .  modest to light pour called up a massive five finger head with excellent retention and beautiful copious lace .  m- a very fine carbonation .

very slight smell of malt and a light hop aroma . the taste is spicy and slightly peppery with a very pleasant hop bitterness at the finish .  this beer pours a cloudy pale orange color . this beer looks a lot like a really good hefe , and i like that .  m : this is crisp and refreshing early but the carbonation goes quickly and turns watery .

aroma is vague and sweetish pale malt , floral hops . taste is crisp fruity bitterness , light malt with notes of honey in the finish .  beer pours a beautiful dark copper color with a nice thick white head .  it is medium-light bodied ; bubbly , with a dry , slightly gritty finish , almost like it was dry hopped . this is a pretty solid dubbel .

s-reminds me of a coffee flavored candy of my childhood -- a little too sweet smelling for my taste in a beer t-1st is sweet coffee- finishes with a nice bitterness , good carbonation if drunk with large head -- less so later -- but even after head is gone good for a stout d- would only want one of these per session between richness , coffee flavor and abv .  beautiful garnet red pour with excellent lacing and two finger lingering head .  mouthfeel : feels slightly carbonated and thicker than water on the tongue .

s-mild smell of roasted barley with little else that i can detect .  the appearance is f*cking gorgeous . this is what a stout should look like . pitch black and pours like motor oil . a nice three finger chocolate marshmallow head upon a somewhat forceful pour .  it was lite bodied , almost watery .

to encapsulate my sample : this beer 's drinkability number is off the charts for its style , since this is a malty beer with smoke accents instead of tasting like you 're face down in a fire , or snuffing some lucky strikes out on your palate . the smoke in this rauchbier is a tinge on top of a strong malty base , instead of an overstrong , overbearing nature . the aroma seemed a bit unidirectional considering .  be it tap , bottle , or can , the pour is beautiful . i love to watch it settle . head is creamy and feels good on my whiskers .  the beer did suffer a bit on the palette from the high hopping rates , as this did not glide down in a soft manner , and presented a bit of an edgy mouthfeel .

the fruity aroma was apparent , but not overly sweet smelling . appearance - 4.5/5.0 - beautiful rich brown color , light head , but color is awesome smell - 3.0/5.0 - fruity but not overly so , little malt , ok , but nothing special taste - 4.0/5.0 - rich malt flavor , sticks around a bit , licoricsh , little chocolate , full flavor takes a bit to kick in feel - 4.5/5.0 - smooth and velvety , some aftertaste but enjoyable drinkability - 4.0/5.0 - not regularly otherwise i 'd be an alcoholic , would definitely have again though  a : wonderful sunny body cloudy with some specks of yeast , great white head with good staying power and amazing lacing .  the mouthfeel was kinda thin and fizzy , but did n't really detract from the wonderful flavors .

aromas are toasty but subdued and simplistic . flavors are sweet up front before big toasty and earthy notes dominate the middle .  crystal clear honey body with a generous 1 finger medium density just-off-white head that retains beautifully and leaves loads of lace .  i 'm sorry guys but another swing and a miss . beer aggressively foamed out the bottle immediately on opening , after sitting in the refigerator for two days , so no mistakes on my part there . the sourness overwhelms any good qualities which are there , lying underneath but truly irrelevent . cigar city is a great brewery with great potential but lets get it together guys . do not put these beers on the shelf when they are clearly sub-par . cheers everybody- it 's only beer . i expect great things from this brewery but let 's please enact some quality control .

a - orangeish tan with almost two inches of head s - mild smell , not offensive but not appetizing either t - a bit sour and very bitter m - sharp on the tongue , you can tell there 's a lot of alcohol in this beer .  pours a jet black stout like color . leaves a very nice creamy , slow sliding lacing around the glass . a great looking beer !  flavor is nice and smooth with the sweet nutty flavor followed by a cocoa sweetness . watery mouthfeeling makes this one a smooth brown ale .

sadly , i did n't take any notes so i have to rely on my feeble memory ! after having one of my favorite local beers , millstream schild brau ( amber ale ) , i decided i wanted something with some hoppy kick to it and saw the snpa on tap . i have no idea why people would drink something like bud ( which laughably touts its high quality hops in their commercials ) when stuff like this is available nationally . this will definitely be my `` go to '' beer when i want something hoppy , though usually i like something a little mellower in this area .  poured a beautiful color , phenomenally shiny , that shifted slowly from gold edges to deep but lustrous amber in the middle . had a thin and simple soft head , sat very well , with thick and slow lace that leaft a stain of sloppy but wide horizontal strings and splotches . a good looking glass of beer , no doubt . smelled of soft pumpkin , moderate toffee malts , with notes of sweet cinnamon and hearty nutmeg poking up , as well as small hints of cinnamon .  m : fairly light , slick body with a low amount of spiky carbonation . mediocre .
smell is some bready malt and a bit of spice . very drinkable .  this is a nice looking beer .  the mouthfeel is not a complex one and is rather unbalanced and nondescript .

a few light , citruisy fruity notes cap a roasty , distinctly coffeelike scent . smooth , slight roastiness and coffee are layered with a gently fruity flavor i have n't experienced in many porters ; nothing offensive here , very easy to drink .  pours a very dark brown with a red tint when held up to the light , medium size creamy light tan head , excellent lacing .  the mouth feel is a little thin , unlike some higher-end ales , but the drinkability is very good .

the smells were of cherries and corn malts .  appearance : pours a dark cola brown , almost black , with a 2 finger creamy light tan head consisting of very fine carbonation bubbles . excellent head retention and perfect lacing . i do n't see how it could look any better .  lager quality with a lighter cleaner body and feel . my one `` complaint '' is the bite of the carbonation that holds a particularly sharp feel .

the creamy king , even better than guinness app - dark black , little carb with a big white uniformed beautifull head . smell - bittery and hop-ish taste - the bitter taste of irish stouts , very well done , but much better from tap mouthfeel - exceptional is perfect . it 's creamy and amazingly smooth . drink - have em one after another , very drinkable .  a great dark lager that reminds me of yuengling porter when it was made at the old brewery . the color is dark and when poured into a glass creates a nice white/gray head .  pours a deep red with an inch or so of head and reduces quickly down to a nice lacing.. no much of a hoppy nose more of a malty raspberry preserves.. mouth feel quite light with a tinge of pucker.. i would have to say there is a very clean bittering hop flavor masked in the fruitiness .

has a nice thick , white , foamy head that leaves good lacing on the glass s - smell is n't overpowering , and there does n't seem to be a lot going on , but there are hints of hops with a little bit of pine scent involved t - a great tasting beer with hops dominating the flavor , just like the nose . not very similar to the other holiday brews i had this season , but definitely a great one .  a - pours a brilliant clear amber with an off-white moundy head that takes it 's time going down . provides beautiful sheets of lacing .  the taste is of roasted malts , toffee , and to some degree , molasses . the smell is good and the taste is incredible ... but letting this porter get warm isnt such a good idea since it significantly reduces its drinkability . i will definitely pick up another case of this becauce it is probably the best porter i 've ever had . if you like this then definitely give brooklyn black chocolate stout a shot because thats damn good too .

lots of malt on the nose . getting a hint of something sweet and flowery , like fresh cut hay . something else too , that reminds me of `` dessert '' .  a nice orange color with the most impressive head i 've ever seen : absolutely solid .  mouthfeel : body is a bit thin , but it is a brown ale .

a light scent - similar to blue moon .  the pour epuals a even 50/50 split , half head , half body . body is black which is very dark for a brown ale . head is a thick light mocha brown that stays a long while .  more of the same in the finish , kept triggering my gag reflex medium bodied , slick with moderate carbonation , skewed way to sweet , needs some alcohol burn to mitigate this horrible drinkability .

smell is pretty clean , not offensive , but nothing really describable , rather bland smelling actually .  pours an inky black , with a 2 finger ecru frothy head that slowly reduces , looking like foam on a specialty coffee .  the mouth feel is a bit light for such a porter .

bought a 22 oz bomber from papago brewing back in november for $ 4.95 . smell is average , a bit grainy , nothing much noted . mouthfeel is very full and lively . rogue has produced the best lager i have ever sampled !  a- a deep , dark inky black liquid with barely any light coming through at the edges . the brown head is thin but very creamy and leaves some nice lacing .  it had a medium to light body .

smells of cinnamon , ginger , something nasty i ca n't put my finger on .  a : nearly clear off-white yellow with puffy fine bubbles head that kept it all the way , great lacing s : mild nose with spicy yeast , some soft floral aspects too t : traditional saison with earthy/floral qualities probably from elderflowers , noticeable hop bite in finish , hops were more than normal for a saison but not offensive m : decent mouthfeel with all the qualities of a saison ( yeasty , spritzy ) but with stronger hop finish  carbonation is medium to medium-heavy , and mouthfeel is slightly viscous , landing just north of water .

pouring into a glass , it pours a nice black color , and if you like black this is for you , smell well it smell like beer , taste like nice dark larger that you want to drink again .  pours a deep , opaque black-brown with a fairly thick and fine-bubbled light tan head , quite appealing .  mouthfeel is a little thick a little syrupy .

the smell is faint and hard to get a good idea on , a little vinegar , an earthy , woody smell , some sweetness . i always associate new belgium with fat tire and forget that they have some pretty great brews out there and this one is one of them . i think the 2010 vintage is pretty good also and i might come back later and review it next time i crack open a bottle , two 22oz flanders bombers in one night is too much sour though .  a-really looks the part . deep dark brown bordering on black with a creamy , frothy tan head .  f - medium body but carbonation is very weak .

it had some fruity-ester smell , but not as much as some .  this brew appears a clear copper color with constantly rising bubbles of carbonation and 2 fingers worth of frothy off-white head . quality retention with this cap and lacing appears all along the glassware with bubbly patches .  mouthfeel : surprisingly thin , but not too watery .

not so great smelling with a hint of something off there .  i was quite impressed with the consistency and dark color pouring out almost in clumps .  m - the mouth feel is lush and oily but a tad too soft by the end .
smell was sweet with slight coffee hints .  super dark in color , allowing no light to pass through .  ( m ) - a very high carbonation level .

smells of malt , grapefruit , and nutmeg , ok but not impressive .  the nitro can widget leads to a beautiful cascading effect , pefectly dark beer , with the fluffy white head . looks fake it looks so good .  sharp and light bodied .
not a whole lot of smells goin on here . t : smooth cream ale with a crisp clean finish .  keeps a huge frothy lasting beige head . gorgeous beer .  light body and mouthfeel .

smell- earthy and spicey noble hops . quite hard to get much on the nose out of this beer .  pours an exceptional rich , golden orange color with a big , dense , cloud-like , cream-colored head .  mouthfeel : pretty light in the body department .

i love kolsch . s & # 8211 ; clean sweet german malt , and light esters . t & # 8211 ; this brew has the distinct german taste , presented in a big , rich , full manner and avoiding the sweatiness .  this is probably the most intense , thick , beautiful looking nitro pour i 've ever had the pleasure of gazing at . dark blackness with effervescence of the gods fueling a truly never-ending frosting-like cap . the curtains of lacing are epic .  wow ! what a pleasant surprise ! i tried this beer on-tap at a new restaurant near my apartment called `` kushi . '' i was in the mood for a light , white ale - and this beer definitely delivered . it was crisp and refreshing . taste was tart and light , a little sour , but well balanced . i 'd have this beer again , and again , and again..

a slight skunky smell at first , but it quickly disappeared . afterwards smells of pear , vanilla and medicinal herbs .  it pours with a massive head that has real staying power ! a lot of different flavours going on in this brew ... overall , a good buy but maybe it needs more ... funk perhaps , i do n't know but it needs something ... but i did enjoy it !  m - high carbonation , chalky , tannic , medium balance , some sweetness and high bitterness for a stout . i would love to see this oak aged as it would help to refine the bitterness and carbonation that hurts it .

gorgeous pale ale . muted bready aromas -- cracker and crystal malts , and a touch of caramel , though not overly aromatic and certainly the least hoppy alpine beer i 've smelled to date . clean , simple flavors : bread , a touch of caramel , some citrus hops , though overall very simple and classic . a highly drinkable pale ale , though it disappoints , only because of alpine 's otherwise world-class lineup .  probably the best head i 've ever seen . when i was done drinking it i spun the head around the glass and it filled up the whole glass .  no real cascade , but a full , rich tan head with plenty of texture over a nearly black and opaque body . heavy lacing clings to the glass . delicious aroma of black bread . espresso and chocolate flavors . labels soak off easily and make an excellent decoration for plain garage walls .

malty aroma has hoppy and fruity hints , and is not strong but still has appeal .  looks great . moderately clear , dark amber color and reddish hue .  mouthfeel -- medium-light in body with prickly carbonation . slightly gentler carbonation would have been preferable , but a twirl or two dozen remedies the issue .

s : somewhat lacking , though i smelled roasted malts , coffee . t : taste is quite good , delicious milk chocolate combines with a light coffee and mocha note to create a great flavour .  golden orange body with a super fluffy white cap that make it hard to fill the glass .  medium-full bodied with smooth , lower carbonation .

aroma is a blend of herbs , spice , and medicinal antiseptic .  huge carbonation leaves a mountanous head reminiscent of belgians .  weakest aspect of this beer is the body , which is a bit on the thin side , with light carbonation .

black as the ace of spades s : it smells like a pale ale . some mildly sweet malty aromas but the hops stand out , smells a bit of grass and may be some citrus .  so , the appearance is flawless . anyone who gives it less than a 5 , is delusional . absolutley gorgeous , with three fingers of tan head and exceptional lacing .  the amount of flavor packed into something this thin and `` refined '' is unusual and noteworthy . it feels a little creamy on the swirl , but i do n't really like where it stimulates the tongue . however , the mouthfeel leaves something to be desired , so how many will you want to down consecutively ?

it has a nice cereal character that i really like , but the overall impression is just a nice drinkable beer . the beer has a slight tutti-frutti to the nose , but that does n't translate to the taste , where the raw grains take over .  this poured the most amazing red with un-ending pinkish head .  rich caramely malts , maple syrup and toffee with a hint of bitterness to balance , but definitely very sweet . finishes with ripe fruits . mild carbonation . notes : very pleasant and surprisingly delicious to pair with just about any food .

smell : a little grassy hop , a little citrus hop . there 's some doughy malt in there too . the aroma is a little on the weak side . i usually like my dipas to be potent in the nose and this lets me down . its not intensely bold as some dipas but its still pretty good . feel : not intensely bitter , fairly crisp and refreshing , the alcohol is hidden very well . drinks like an american pale ale with 5 % alcohol by volume , not a 9 % dipa . its not exceptional but its very solid .  beer is bright yellow and completely clear with a big white head of tiny and small bubbles , nice carbonation , steady moderate to low , and some lacing on the glass . looks great .  mouthfeel is rather full but not heavy , and it is certainly not full-bodied but moderate .

smell : this is where it missed for me . glad i did n't judge this brew soley on the basis of smell . taste : here we go ... .sweetness , dried fruits , vanilla , espresso . all the cool things you would expect from an imperial stout .  very nice looking .  mouthfeel is average , not much to say one way or the other , except , i guess it was smooth .

for a beer with such a nice balance of robust flavors , the john john ale does n't smell like much .  the beer poured brownish black with ruby highlights and a huge tan/brown head that lasted for days .  the only thing i do not like about this beer is that it is a little lacking in body - seems a bit thin .

a bit of haze with a average level of carbonation . s : not much on the nose , i pick up some faint fruity floral tones . d : quite drinkable , i really enjoyed it .  a deep rustic orange in color with a gigantic , sticky and awkwardly shaped head of foam .  mouthfeel : i 've never been a big fan of the body of almost all american porters as they just seem thin , a tad watery , and big on carbonation , and this one does n't break that trend .

a frothy billowing slightly off white head erupts from this brew . what little aroma is present is well balanced between yeast , malt , and hops . no single fragrance takes over . barely any fragrance is detectable .  this thing is black . blacker than the blackest metal ! it reeks of hops ... reek being a great thing ... it almost smells of an imperial stout ... the bottle calls it a black ipa ... this site calls it an american strong ale ... what the hell is this thing for real ?  mouthfeel is kind of thin , and a little watery .

i was hoping the color would be darker but it looks more like a ipa , light yellow like a apwa . taste is spicey with a faint taste of hops , it is not really bitter . the 7.2 is masked very nice i and i could drink 2-3 easy . i read reviews before driking and i exspected this beer to suck but i was suprised at how well they melded the two styles .  poured into a stemless tulip glass with two inches of ivory head that dissipated within a minute or two . leaves heavy lacing along the glass with striations that create some beautiful patterns on the top of this tawny-ruby body . tight bubbles remain on the top as the drink progresses making for an all out beautiful ale .  crisp and dry with soft to moderate carbonation . kind of metallic . the flavor was pretty good , but the mouthfeel was lacking .

smell : not extremely aromatic , but a subtle smell of pine scented hops . taste : light hops , crisp faint apple and floral up front that transforms to grapefruit in the back . it really tastes like a hoppy pale ale , but packs a decent 6.4 % that you would n't guess- nor would you peg it for a ipa . as an everyday beer i rate it as an a- , but i can see how some people are turned off on its mildness for an ipa .  pours a very , very dark color , almost pitch black with a nice tight head that clings to the glass perfectly .  mouthfeel is a bit lean , and watered down .

s- lime , some sort of ... hmm , it smells like ginger ale a bit .  has a huge , foamy tan cap that recedes into thick clumps on top of the brew , and leaves substantial lacing with register marks down the glass .  m : light smooth and refreshing , im serious . its a run of the mill average beer in the mix with huge macro beers that ussually will run marketing circles around it .

it has a slight alcohol ting and smokey coffee/mocha scent . this beer has a nice full body with full viscous mouthfeel and an almost molasses and toffee beginning , moving to a coffee and chocolate taste , then finishing strong with a warming smokey aftertaste . there is a nice blend of maltiness and bitterness . it is very smooth and has the nice imperial stout taste nicely balanced with maltiness and bitterness .  a_pours a beautiful clear copper/bronze hue with a two finger cloudlike off white head . retention is very strong as is the lacing . one of the better looking beers regardless of style i have seen in a while .  very suprised . i am a fan of lighter beers and this one provided a very unique grapefruit aftertast . i have yet to have any other beer that i can even compare to this one . it 's appearance and mouthfeel are typical of a lighter wheat or white beer .

s- decent wheat notes with some watermelon , maybe a little bitterness from the hops or fruit itself , nothing unreasonable .  more thanks to weefishheads for this one ... this beer was quite beautiful sitting in my glass . its body was a lovely sunset gradient of yellow to orange , slight haze clouding it .  a beer haiku for you : '' norwegian beer ? yes ! a great ipa option , seek out and find one ! '' my first norwegian [ that 's what she said ] . nice citrus overtones , not too 'hoppish ' , and very drinkable . a rare find , but well worth the money to have another option .

fairly good on the nose with roasted dark malts , faint touches of hopps .  beautiful color s-more malts than hops .  if this beer has anything going for it , it 's a decent body which lends itself to an okay drinkability rating .

do note this is made the `` jolly pumpkin '' way , and is a sour ale version of a stout . if you want a sweet , creamy stout , pass on this one . smell hints that it might not be your typical stout , with a hint of the sour notes to come . drinks like a sour beer , but with a creamy mouthfeel and dark roasted malt flavor that you would get in a really good , solid stout . i liked this beer very much , but have to shrug a bit if asked if this beer falls completely within the style . still , very fun to drink , and will have more next time i can find it .  enormous two finger , very frothy , beige head . heavy , layered lacing .  m : medium body and carbonation . it is a little sticky . some sharpness on my tongue as i swallow .

s - some faint toasted malts , but there really is n't much here , middle of the road , ca n't give either side an inch . t - sweet , malty body , with some dark fruits and smoke characteristics .  dark chocolate with a reddish tint , the head is big and mocha colored and leaves some wonderful lacing .  surprising amount of carbination gets you with the first sip , it foams up in your mouth . but the body is alot less than i was expecting ... not think , just mostly carbination on top of a thin to medium body.. ? the flavors linger on your tongue , mainly at the back sides .

very light sweet malt and floral hops hops are a bit light but nice little flavors . fairly full , carbonation has a bit of bite not bad , i was thinking it would be a bit more but its pretty easy to drink and the low abv is pretty nice .  pours a wonderfully deep mahogany with a two finger tan head that leaves impeccable sheets of lacing to the very end .  unfortunately this seems a bit thin but very tastey though . well for a sawbuck per growler it is real nice .

smell is nice , but a little off somewhere .  a - thick , light brown head that stays forever . opaque black except for a tint of dark ruby on the edges .  m : fairly light bodied and the only part that 's halfway decent .

smell is clean and crisp , bit of sweetness . no alcohol in the nose .  drank on-tap at plan b burger bar , glastonbury , ct served in a pint glass the crystal clear , amber colored liquid was topped by a tight , sticky , two-finger , sea foam cap . a thick spiderweb of clingy lacing stuck all down the sides of the glass .  mf : pretty thin , good carbonation .

it may not be for everyone , but i sure did find it enjoyable and i go on `` no fruit in beer '' kicks once in a while .  pours a beautiful black with a slowly forming rich and creamy head .  mouthfeel : on the light side of medium with a crisp finish . it is a touch too thin imho . with the malt being so delicous , i want a bit more body to compliment it .

rye crystal and malted oats gives it the colour and aroma , challenger and goldings give it the bitterness .  a slow pour reveals deep shades of copper , mahogany and gold capped by a thick , billowy head of white foam that just wo n't quit .  m- on the lighter side with lots of carbonation .

smell : sweet malt with a hint of floral hops .  this is just about perfect appearance . the deep dark red , 3 finger off white cream head , lacing , lots of bubbles , just well done .  mouthfeel is dry and light bodied , but it 's sorely lacking spritz .

i would have to agree with wiseguy142 and that this beer has great malt qualities , is very clean , drinkable , and deserves more attention . it pours with an inch head and smells of roasted malt .  appearance : the beer poured a nice 3 finger chocolate colored head . also , beer is pitch black with no clarity and no signs of carbonation . the head of beer has not come down yet and will have to say the retention is fantastic and lacing on the glass .  mouthfeel is flat feeling and a little thin .

smell is pretty average to be honest . not a lot of hop character , just a mild malt flavor and some typical lager sourness .  deep ruby red/brown color .  mouthfeel is ok , very watery , lacking hop oil and that `` slickness '' that many other ipa 's have .

on tap at jackie os a-dark brown to black with tan head around the edges s-very hard to get anything off of this t-very sweet . very sweet and smooth  a : 1 and quarter creamy , fluffy white head with fantastic , thick lacing clinging to the sides of the glass . brew itself was a cloudy goldenrod color .  somewhat thin and watery mouthfeel .

s- the smell is average . citrusy , piney hop fragrance that 's present but does n't go much beyond that .  extremely solid ipa here . nice dark amber color with a huge head .  this was probably just average on the mouthfeel , imo - whether you consider this a wild ale or bsda .

s : toasted malt , hint of chocolate . t : strong biscuity flavour , lots of rich english malt and minerality .  ..on the open , thick cream like tan foam started oozing out of the bottle . the head is quite good , but the lacing is exceptional ! .  the taste is even worse , at first it taste like a regular lager and then an overwhelming amount of chilli flavor hits with a spiciness in the back of your throat after you swallow . i really do not like this beer at all but they do do a good job of making it very jalapeo-y . if you 're into novelty items and spicy food then this the beer for you .

smell : caramel and banana bread . i believe that 's expected in this style .  in my opinion , this is one of the best looking beers in the glass that i 've ever seen . great balance of color , bubbles and head . absolutely clear - no chunkies from belgium .  m : 3 day old ginger ale type carbonation ... o : not a great beer .

smell is slightly muted with only a hint of malt detectable .  golden colored topped with a thick foamy off-white head and lots of lacing on the glass .  the mouthfeel is light bodied , but a little thicker than i would expect from a beer with such little taste and aroma .

the aroma is a of light herbal yeasts , with pleasant fruit notes . there is a definite musty , skunky undertone .  looks delicious . very good looking beer .  the ringwood yeast just tore this up and gave it a slab of butter on top ... m : crisp , but just tastes pretty bad ... d : a pretty bad beer , the ringwood yeast dominates this brew so much that i had to drain pour the rest , too bad .

smell : not as fragrant as i thought it would be . plenty of dark sugar and fruit with a fair amount of holiday spice ( nutmeg , cinnamon , allspice ) in nose with also just a hint of citrusy hops . the fragrance was rather muted in my opinion . taste : starts nice and malty with caramel and dark brown sugar sweetness that is followed by a good dose of spices .  pours a gorgeous straw yellow with a monumentally large and thick head ... very rocky with generous lacing ... active carbonation .  starts creamy , but finishes surprisingly thin , which is more noticeable as the beer warms .

s - slight whiff of coffee , roasted malts , and a touch of chocolate t - surprised at how tasty this is given the fact the smell was ok , it has great sweetness mixed with roasted malts , great hoppiness in the middle , very well balanced .  a : pours a delicious ruby-chestnut body with a light rose-colored head that rises to 1.5 '' . the head recedes into a thick collar and some filming on the brew , with washes of lacing that track each swig and slide slowly down the glass . magnificent .  super easy to drink ... just a little thin on the mouthfeel .

not much to smell . this had a very easy drinkablity to it , and at that abv , you could make this an all day session beer ... which i would . i thought it had a slight honey/citrusy flavor , nothing overwhelming . dry finish . good stuff , i would say slightly tastier and more pleasing on tap . pat  great head retention with nice lacing .  elements of pine , citrus , resinous elements too -- slightly oily but in a very pleasant manner . the biggest flaw i can find with this beer is that it wastes too much of the carbonation in the beginning when it is first poured . it is slightly flat in the mouthfeel although i have tasted some other ipas recently that were far worse in this department .

the nose leaves a bit to be desired . either way it is n't as fragrant as i would like . quite excellent and a much better than the nose would leave you to believe .  this beer looks great , with a huge rocky and cream like head floating on a clear and golden orange sea of a well carbonated potation .  the beer 's mouthfeel is smooth , if a bit watery ; this may be the same problem as the vanishing head .

s : a hoppy aroma is seconded by the malt backbone . t : spice from the hops and a smooth cream from the malt .  black with 2+ cm of brown head , some lacing s - espresso , alcohol , some chocolate , roasted barley t - roasted barley , coffee , and then some hops . it 's somewhat subdued for an ris , but it 's still a great , cheap beer .  m- medium body , slightly watery d- very drinkable . watery , but enjoyable .

i really love the packaging on this one , very unique . poured a crystal clear , straw/light orange color . i did n't get alot off the nose on this pour . light hops and malts , but nothing too distinguishible .  so i purchased a bottle , and i did like it better ... a : amber-copper , creamy off-white head , great retention and lace . perfect .  light and effervescent , with a hint of caramel malty sweetness . i bought a six pack of this , and after drinking the first beer , immediately grabbed another six . definitely the best 5.99 beer in the store . do n't pick this up if you 're looking for a complex thought-provoking brew . but if you want a session beer that 's a good alternative to macro-swill and are n't into over-hopped domestics like sam adams and goose island , this is a great seasonal . similar to a leinenkugel brew . a friend said that this was what you 'd get if newcastle brewed an amber . drink straight from the bottle - not really enough nuance to bother with a glass .

a good plain strong beer smell .  poured from bottle into tulip a- beautuful thick off white head . stout like . head lasts and leaves perfect rings of lace . body is pretty dark .  a smoked lager from fort collins brewery . 1.0 liter bottle for $ 8.29 . i was somewhat skeptical about this beer especially because i thought there two other beers edgar and doktor were an abomination , but i opted for it and was it ever worth it ! a slight smokinness stimulates the nose as well as some alcohol , caramel and citrus hops . the palate was dominated with notes of butterschotch , smoked malts , cedar , citrus notes , light fruits and the flavor was very lingering on the palate . i did polish off a 1.0 so obviously this brew was pretty damn drinkable !

did n't really start smelling until about halfway through the glass . like pliny .  pours pitch black . nice creamy head .  i remember when this beer hit the streets - people loved that cute little orange slice they served it with . it really introduced the variety of beer to many of my friends . my girlfriend once had me call coors over the july 4th holiday because she did n't like the looks of the white sediment on the bottom of the bottle . coors gave us the thumbs up to drink . appearance is quite hearty . for me this is a beer to compare other witbiers to . not the best , nor the worst . the irony here is i drank this beer given to me by my friend `` porter ''

the nose is delicate with subtle notes of dark chocolate . the nitrogen dispense leaves it creamy and smooth in the mouth .  a-pours an orange/copper with a head that is four fingers thick . the head is extremely dense and it dissipates slowly leaving a thick lacing on the sides of the mug . there was lacing down the entire glass .  medium bodied with a medium level of carbonation .

pale malt and light floral aromas . crisp pale malt with light caramel and floral hops all in subtle balance with a light grassy bittersweet finish . at first i was not entirely impressed as it seemed to be just another amber style beer . however , the subtle qualities of this beer are so nicely in balance it creates one heckuva drinkable beer .  sierra nevada 30th pours a inky , impenetrable black with a deep brown head .  m : slightly acrid which is a bit off putting . it really is not as creamy as i would have liked but there is a good amount of body .
