s - ca n't smell anything unfortunately t - wow , lots going on .  lacing is tremendous . the head on this beer is magnificent , probably from the pour , but holds well regardless . beer is dark , dark brown with a light brown head .  m : medium-light body with medium carbonation , this beer is a bit on the heavy side for the style .

s- some coffee notes from the glass and a strong alcohol smell . t- alcohol is not as present as the smell would suggest . coffee and chocolate are predominate with alcohol in the backround .  it 's almost kind of amazing how dark this beer pours .  magic hat wacko 12oz into tasting glass this beer is wacko . expected a fruity aroma , but instead got some beefiness . not much in the way of taste either , maybe some citrus from the hops . this beer did not do well in my new england beer tasting .

love it . the aroma and taste are ( naturally ) severely muted here compared to the regular drafts i had previously . but for it 's style , i 'm happy to find only the slightest sweetness ( in either of the servings i 've had so far ) , whereas i 've come accustomed to tasting a more sour , sugary sweet character taken from the lactose . they 've crafted a fine ale indeed .  perfect appearance : clear , golden orange , light amber , with a pillowy , tight off-white head that leaves messy , crooked lines of lace all the way down the glass .  m- kinda thin , but full of great flavors that wrap around your tongue .

really a very nice beer . surprisngly it did n't have a strong smell , it seemed to be keeping it all in the beer , it tasted of toffee , surprisingly smooth given it 's about 9 % alcohol .  beautiful color too .  m - smooth and medium/light body . a slightly dry aftertaste .

the ideal looking pilsner . corn and adjuncts dominate the aroma , but they do n't carry quite the same unpleasantness that macro lagers have . the stenching smell of corn syrup becomes overly sweet . this is a damn fine pilsner .  a -- pours a beautiful amber/copper color with a huge 4 finger head in my dogfish head signature glass . i know the glass contributed to the appearance here , but this is one of the best looking beers i have poured .  mouthfeel is strange .

smell : not alot just some musk and honey . it 's got a spritz to the carbonation with a sweetness and earthy blend with citrus thats really very pleasing . alcohol is well masked and this stuff will rock your world ! they are very drinkable !  tried this one in a tripel karmeliet glass , which really did it justice , gleaming burnt-orange body , clear with a huge head of off-white foam that left an opaque lace on the glass . it was litereally impossible to see through the lace .  i 'm almost halfway through the pint and still impressed with the carbonation . i 'm also surprised at the body ; it seems a bit thin and makes the beer rather perilously drinkable at nearly 7 percent alcohol . this long , bitter and dry finish is perhaps the most enjoyable quality of this beer , that and i suppose it 's dangerous drinkability .

once in the glass from the tap , a beautiful color fils your mind , a perfect not quite brown , honey amber tone with hints of gold . not quite an average ale , but not quite a lager , reminds me of red oak for those of you who have had that pleasure .  poured into a tulip glass . overall , an exceptional looking beer .  m - moderate beer body , strong carbonation bite .

georgeous copper colored beer with a massive , lasting lightly tanned colored head . subtle aromas of caramel , biscuit , herbal and just a touch of grass .  here we go ... this stout arrived at my table just as i remembered . very dark brown ( almost black ) , fine bubbles just churning away in the liquid . the whole inner surface is completely coated with creamy foam ... not resembling lace at all . this may not be the best tasting stout , but is sure is the best looking .  the mouthfeel was a lacking but i just may start picking these up as a session beer .

s : roasted grains ... not much more . t : this is the best way to have your guinness . d : guinness on tap is always a good , safe choice and always beats out the bmc competition .  bottle , with santa claus on the label , a : pours a dark , turbid brown , with a huge , voluminous white head , almost like a duvel in size , which leaves generous lacing .  smell : piney hops and malts are slightly toasty , tickles the nose readily easily . taste : hop sensation is immediate , blending with the mild toasty-earthy malt taste , progressing to a light , tangy-hop bitterness in the finish , surprisingly balanced . drinkability : darker than a typical ipa , the character of the malts successfully complements the well-hopped taste , very drinkable .

i found blue moon belgium white to be a very delightful beer with an interesting aftertaste and has a creamy texture . worth a try !  a : oqaque black with a two-finger caramel sticky head that stays with a solid lacing . t : thick milk chocolate melted ice cream , the roast lingering through the end with the hops that are somewhat resinous ( pine needle or rosemary ) and slightly citric .  got this in the secret santa 2008 - from dmeadows , thanks again ! a bit of a funky musty aroma mixed with the spicy nutmeg , quaff is a boatload of allspice , nutmeg , fig , plum and an underlying hint of alcohol booze - even after 2 years in the cellar . and the elderberries add quite a different take on the solid offering . sweet initial start , boozy and hoppy finish . a true winter sipper , tasty and enjoyable with the football game .

malt dominates the aroma . slightly roasty , slightly toasty . very mild aroma . a very nice drinking porter .  pours completely black with a good sized dark tan/brownish head .  the aroma has a touch of stale coffee that then moves to a better defined roasted malt in lager form . the dark malts are great , minus ther adjunt must to it . i ca n't really explain why , but this is one of my , `` right after a hard day of work while you wait for dinner to cook beer . '' easy on the palate and tastes good from the bottle and the glass .

s : not really much smell to this one . you can catch a hint of the the nut flavor but you have to really take a deep smell . browns do not really have a strong smell to them though ... t : great taste . the nuttiness is just right to compliment the caramel and spices .  liked it last year ; let 's see how this stacks up pours caramel with 2.5 fingers of rocky off-white colored head . stellar head retention & lacing s : subdued hop nose up front .  m - this one goes down extremely smooth , but it is a tad watery .

the smell is weak at first , offering glimpses of belgian yeast , and dark fruits the flavor is intense , malts and ops vie for attention . garden vegetables , pumpkin , squash and cabbage show through .  a - pitch black with some dark red around the sides . a good one finger light brown head forms and recedes at a normal pace .  it 's a bit thin in the mouth .

hard to detect any particular aroma , other than the hops , but just a very fine tasting beer , with a long , smooth , slightly dry finish .  l : clear straw yellow , white dense , creamy head with great retention and amazing lacing .  if you 've ever drank the milk after eating a bowl of fruity pebbles ... spot on i guess maybe add a little carbonation .

the faint aroma revealed a hint of malt with a touch of caramel . truly interesting . mouthfeel is very smooth and creamy .  wonderful looking beer .  m : where it falls the shortest with a light-for-style body and overcarbonated .

smell is weak compared to the taste . carbonation is subtle but fits the style .  it pours a dense ink black with an amazing looking dual tone caramel/tan head .  this brew can feel a little thin , although it 's so tasty that it hardly bothered me .

aroma is very mild with slight grainy notes and a hint of hops .  from a nitro filled pint size can ... pours honey golden yellow with typical nitro-style can head . the head is very dense , creamy and leaves belgian lacing all the way down to the end .  served on tap in the black angus restaurant at the stoudt 's brewery . body is a dark copper color . thick head with excellent lace . the scent is a bit fruity and has elements of apples and hops . a nice balance of sweet malts and bitter hops make up the flavor . alcohol peeks through , which is surprising as this is a relitively low abv ale .

smell of chocolate wafer , cocoa , a bit earthy - as in soil .  pours a beautiful hazed gold , reminiscent of belgian witbiers and not exactly the german hefeweizen .  m : sticky , slight aftertaste .

dark brown sugar aroma with a roasty maltiness . most of the nose is the roast aroma , but honestly could be a bit more aromatic . at first , i get the sense of black licorice at first , but it quickly turns to a brown sugar flavor with some roasty burnt chocolate .  appearance : dark brown with a very rocky , long lasting head . the lacing is incredible .  m - little watery , but lots of carbonation .

the initial smell of cascade or citrus hops where strong . the hop smell quickly disappeared and the smell was a little like a light beer .  anyway ... pours a wondferul dark gold , amber with a thick thick creamy lacing head . beautiful .  taste-taste 's like water . mouthfeel-very light , crisp .

the nose was a mixture of sweet malts , molasses and toffee . also acceptable .  pours a hazy goldish orange with a super firm , thick and pillowy head that last forever . this is a nice looking drink .  tastes like ... well , the bottle says , `` english style amber ale '' ( _not_ american amber , eh ? rich and sweet and malty , mild hop flavors . maybe a bit of a blend of an esb and an english brown , you know ? very pleasant . easy to drink . very easy to drink ( ahem ) . hmm .

try getting them to drink a belgium ; ) do n't get me wrong i like incredibly hoppy beer , but you know i 've forgotten how nice a well balanced ipa can be . smell was perhaps a little lacking . but a very pleasing beer .  a : espresso color , almost black with a tight creamy head .  very simple , but i simply like it . lots of carbonation .

but when i poured the ale , i detected a biscuit like maltiness as well as some fresh fruit odor .  this is the gold standard of color and not to mention head and foam for ths style of beer . what an awesome beige and yellow head and thick film of foam along with the fantastic bubbling .  this is one of my favorite beers . had it at a fall rennaisaunce festival locally . hate that it 's seasonal . it was light , and very refreshing on a hot autumn day in the south , and yet warm and comforting on the cool ones .

s : some grainyness & fruittyness t : huge breadyness & honey malt , plus some herbal hops up front . finishes cakey with loads of hop snap ( herbal & floral ) & a hint of boozeyness mf : chewy with low carbonation & perfect balance drinks great for the abv .  i poured a 12 ounce capped bottle into a tulip . a : it poured a dark thick black with a dark rich chocolate head that was massive , sticky and lingering . as the head slowly fell it left a bold lacing around the glass .  m - not as much carbonation as i expected after how it poured .

a moderate aroma of hoppiness and citrus , a little more than a lot of pales i 've had but not huge either . this does n't have a big taste , just a good smooth one .  pours a dark dark dark brown ( pretty much black ) with a crazy thick inch of dark brown foam/head which leaves a boat ton of sticky brown lacing .  mouthfeel is a bit thin , but the carbonation is pleasant .

has a distinctly malty smell to it . dark amber in color . full flavored , but at the same time lighter than other ales in the category . although lighter and thinner than the scotch ale i was expecting , this ale has turned out to be something i really enjoy .  the look could n't have appetized me more - black with a big creamed-coffee head . the head was extra creamy with super retention .  taste : sweet and funky but so refreshing . mouthfeel : lingering taste .

s : aroma is not forefront to this brew , but it smells like good fermented barley should .  pours an oily looking pitch black , with a good sized dark brown head . a beauty .  the mouthfeel is just a pinch thinner than i would have liked .

took a sniff and really did n't smell anything .  pretty much black , with nice darkish beige head , fluffy and dense with stunning lace . retains amazingly well . pretty damn close to looking perfect .  mouthfeel and carbonation are both slightly low .

i was in a bar , so my already weak nose ca n't give a review of this .  it pours to a dark golden amber color with a few continuous jetstreams of bubbles rising to the top to support the delicate off-white head .  it was very astringent .

nose : has a sour smell to it . a little white sugar sweetness comes though . for an 8 % , this is very good .  pours a very good looking dark amber color with a large creamy slightly off white head which leaves plenty of lacing clinging to the glass .  m- good carbonation . a little watery for an imperial stout .

essentially it comes off as a baby mcewans scotch ale , but it has its own personality . midway is the classic hard and cruchy ale water . it finishes ( waaay back in the throat ) with a hop-like pop , but i think it is the roasted malt doing the dirty work on this one .  bottle purchased at julio 's liquors , westboro , ma poured a somewhat hazy , light straw with a huge , five-finger bubbly head . the resulting chunks of froth eventually faded to a dollop of foam in the middle of the glass , which lasted for most of the drink . tons of bubbly , sticking lacing throughout .  m - moderate to thin body - the backbone appears to be driven by its hefty carbonation .

s : the smell is underwhelming , with muted grapefruit citrus hops and slight sulfur . t : begins with spicy , and lesser floral , hop aromatic flavors that energize the palate but fade quickly .  a : pretty head turns into lucious lacing . pearly , continuous carbonation is unusually beautiful .  medium mouthfeel and no carbonation .

scent is a bit floral , a bit bitter and ever so slightly nutty .  10/14/2011 bottling a : perfect pour into an imperial pint . midway between straw and copper , nice bubbling . good head retention .  medium bodied , but has too much carbonation for my liking .

overall somewhat muted .  at least four fingers of towering , foamy , white head , and great lacing- one side of my glass looks like it has a head of its own .  i usually really enjoy drinking founder 's brews . it is missing much of the character that founder 's usually has from its selection of hops and malts . i could n't finish this , as it reminded me of raspberry pucker . somewhere someone probably really likes this brew , but it was way too sweet for me . sorry founder 's , but this seems like you tried too hard and failed . i 'll still have other founder 's brews because of there fairly good track record with me .

it has a small spice smell with a bit of sweet malts in there not impressed with smell , other than that the taste is quite refreshing the mouthfeel was a little lighter that i had hoped but overall a good winter ale .  a- wow , what a great looking pour . nice one finger pink/cream head s- the smell really through me off on this .  mouthfeel is thick and flat , with a slight prickle that could come from carbonation or just from the alcohol .

a good looking glass of stout . s - smells roasty and a little sweet . not the most aromatic beer . t - chocolatey and roasty .  absolutely stunning pour .  the mouthfeel is light-to-medium-bodied with a mild amount of carbonation . my only complaint is that i expected a heavier mouthfeel .

the smell was a bit dissapointing as there was almost no smell .  a : say what you want but you have got to hand it to stone for making every one of their beers look damn amazing . this one is a gorgeous auburn brown color and semi opaque . a dare i say perfect rocky head forms which is a light tan color and clings to the glass about as well as it holds together .  average body for a stout not too viscous but the carbonation is a little low , makes you work to get the flavors out from the alcohol background .

a little bit murky , ( s ) malty sweetness with a slight hop aroma .  a beautiful looking beer .  a dark , dark brown beer shows reddish highlights . it 's mostly clear and sports a big , 3-finger head : pale beige , caf-au-lait , dense , thick . roasted chocolate nuttiness in the nose . dark cocoa up front turns thinnish through the top . some nice chocolate malt goes tangy for the roasty , nutty , bitter chocolate , toffee finish . it 's just a nice , tasty , roasty , chocolatey brown .

not nearly as dark head as others hvae mentioned , mostly dark cream , but huge ... if poured right , it 's almost cask conditioned ! [ btw the bottle was really sticky , either they had a broken bottle somewhere down the line ... and since i took the bottle from the box i ripped open from the [ [ obscure `` vendor '' ] scottish guy , it was not from this batch ] aroma : mostly malt , little hoppy very sweet . first sip man i 'm bummed , not was i was anticipating !  a : 1/2 '' cream coloured head that left a nice lacing over amber liquid with excellent clarity .  mouthfeel suffers from lack of carbonation , but flavors are all right up my alley .

aroma : hard to detect anything , other than some slight toasted grain . flavor/body : excellent blend of nutty malt and dry , lemongrass bitterness . an uncomplex , but oh-so-tasty brew , perfect for a session beer .  the appearance of this beer is superb . it poured out a clear and bright ruby , almost cherry color . it gave a big lacy head in the glass and had a nice carbonation .  mouthfeel - refreshing but a little sour-ish on the tongue .

the aroma is very faint , but is slightly sweet . in my opinion it is the pinnacle example of an esb . balance plays a huge part here and because its not over the top , its highly drinkable unlike some of the bigger american versions of the style .  the apperance is exceptional , gold honey in color , the usual amber color . the head was a gorgeous cream color that lasted the whole way through .  mouthfeel : medium bodied , but seems a bit flat .

aroma is negligible , no matter how many times i check .  lace just about as extensive and impressive .  this , i hate to say , really is n't very good . the spice is entirely too powerful , it 's cloyingly sweet ... everything is out of whack and the concept of balance seems to have been lost on harpoon 's brewmaster on this one . very glad i had the sense to grab a single instead of springing for a sixer . a real shame , as i quite like several other beers brewed by harpoon .

the only part that falls short is the nose . it 's not too strong at all , although it 's a nice blend of leafy and citrus hops and a bit of malt behind it .  hazy apple cider coulourd liquid tumbles from the bottle and stirs up a huge white head which immediately threatens to spill over the lip of the glass . as the head slowly recedes it leaves huge chunks of lace that defy gravity , while a huge circular island takes up residence and refuses to die .  m : this is where this beer turns a bit down for me . to me this tastes a bit undercarbonated , making the mouthfeel a bit watery for me .

not much of a scent , though , very little to detect beyond some roasted grains .  1 pint can poured into a pint glass a : gorgeous rouge with striking amber and orange tones . really great lace like a timeline down the glass .  m : a little thin and prickly , but not bad .

nothing real distinctive in the smell .  a : a vibrant goldlen ale with a strong haze . towering snow white head ... frothy and creamy . looks like scoops of whipped cream .  m- feels `` sticky '' to my mouth .

nose was slightly sweet , tending more towards malty , unusual for the style .  deep red amber color with a big cream colored head that got all rocky and left tons of lacing , great retention .  this beer is exceptionally thin in the mouth however .

s - mostly sweet hops . it 's not a very overpowering smell .  poured a rich 3 finger head , blacker than the blackest black times infinity .  aromas of grapefruit , malt , herbs , melon , chocolate and espresso . taste was an all-out battle royale between the toast malt and the grapefruit hops . tart and tangy , this full-bodied brew was not for the faint-of-taste . no fruity sweetness here , just a hint of molasses and brown sugar way in the background . a paean to malt and hops .

i just busted my first bomber of this brew , and i do n't know if this bottle is past its freshness date or not , but this might be the worst beer i 've ever tasted . incredibly sour , with no redeeming flavor quality at all .  nice tan head with amazing retention .  mouthfeel is pretty fairly light with decent carbination .

s : at first it smelt like a macro brew ( your choice ) with a hint of skunk `` odd '' . really an amazing change after it warms up a little bit . feels good for an english pale ale .  22oz bottle into a duvel tulip pours a deep almost opaque black with a nice frothy khaki head that lasts and leaves nice lacing on the glass .  i would have expected a little more body in this beer . a little skinny for my tastes .
malty smell , but other clean .  reviewed 8/20/2007 ( bottle ) : pours a huge foamy head , good lacing .  m : not particularly laudable .

aroma is not much . smells almost like a barley wine . smells like big foot but not as strong and not enough dry hop aroma . tastes pretty good .  real nice looking beer .  the mouthfeel is like nothing i 've tasted before ... kinda an awkward feel . '' not necessarily bad , but just very different and weird feeling .

yummy . this beer is just about the only good beer on tap at my school 's little bar . the taste is light and sweet , with just a pinch of english hops thrown in at the fore . it is quite possibly the sweetest euro-lager i 've had , which is n't a bad thing , just different . nice and simple , no complaints .  it has a frothy clingy tan head that goes to a collar and displays a ton of lacing .  the mouthfeel is a little more carbonated than i like in a brown & not as thick .

smell - the traditional soapy scent found with most wheat brews is present in this russian as well .  a : impressive creamy head 2 or 3 fingers deep . brilliant , clear copper coloring .  mouthfeel is on the light side , but there is too much carbonation in this .

this beer consists of 5 different malts and contains ginger . there were 5 batches and each contained a different amount of ginger . it did n't have much of a smell . since my sense of smell is not accute , i had my wife confirm this . not much going on . it reminded me very much of a belgian brew .  the appearance was stunning : a rich dark red color , almost syrupy , and a large but quickly fading head . it looked incredible in a large wine glass .  light-medium carbonation and medium bodied . piney hops and paint thinner nose . flavor starts with sweet malt but quickly goes to hop and finishes with a paint thinner aftertaste . overpriced at $ 1.50 for a 12oz bottle from manchester wine and liquors manchester , ct .

s - not overly aromatic , faint citrus with a little caramel malt and some alcohol is there , but does n't smack you in the face . m - a lighter mouthfeel than expected and very smooth for the style . o - a well-balanced , highly drinkable ipa that does not overwhelm with flavor complexity , but is still quite enjoyable .  not sure how i felt about this one ... poured a beautiful black into a simple glass mug .  feels thin for such a high abv barrel aged beer but it is easy to drink and the alcohol heat is mild considering .

s : light smells of roasted malts , some treacle , but light .  draught @ papago the beer pours a deep brown to black color with a purposeful and creamy chocolate brown head , the lace thick and concealing .  a little watery at the end .

it has a very light scent that is sweet . you can really smell the alcohol in this beer .  pours very dark with some beautiful ruby highlights when held up against the light . exceptional to look at .  m - thin to medium body , but not watery . the carbonation is at a moderate level . the mouthfeel overall is at the appropriate levels , but nothing jumps out as distinct or mind blowing .

straw yellow body , a tad murky . not much to be had on the nose , a light lemon and ginger with some bretanomyces-esque barnyard funk . sweet and straw like malts with subtle lemon and ginger notes , nice dry hop , more bretanomyces hints and some other bread like yeastie goodness . comparable to an orval , but not quite the complexity .  2004 bottle appearance- amazing head on this beer . the beer was a dark ruby color .  served in a bottle i picked this up during the christmas season just to try one of the many seasonal types of beer that were available . the smell reminded me more of a vinegar- esque flavor and once i took a sip my mouth was taken on a journey that i never want to recreate again . now do n't get me wrong , this is n't that bad of a beer , the flavor just was not something that i myself could truly enjoy . for those looking for an interesting take on a beer i would suggest this particular brew but i just did not like the feel of the pickle taste in my mouth after awhile .

smell is a bit distant but bring more of the belgian sweet & yeast than hops . i 'll warrant i was skeptical popping open an eight month old belgian ipa , but this is far & away the most complex belgian ipa i 've tasted to date .  pours a solid black color with a brown head that forms very good and needs no help .  light bodied and hardly any carbonation to speak of .

i wish this was n't 5 dollars a bottle where i live , i would gladly switch hit between this and noble pils all the time . clear and red . the rice flavor was present and reminded me of saki .  a beautiful looking beer .  mouth feel actually makes me think of watery , unlike several other fff beers i 've had .

i drank this out of a 12oz stein glass ... pour is a darker than amber/lighter than copper hue with an off cream colored head that settles ... .nose is unremarkable ... slightly perfumed with a touch of floral hop aroma but nothing of particular note .  pours black as night with nice ruby highlights around the endges when held to the light , has a nice thick tan head .  thin even for this style , i 'd like to see just a little more intensity in the backbone . mouthfeel : as you 'd imagine as you watch it pour , this is very much light-bodied . good carbonation and a clean finish .

nose is very mild , but what there is present is light breadiness with a touch of grass . 3.9 look : 4.5 | smell : 3 | taste : 4 | feel : 4 | drink : 4 1246  good lacing & excellent head retention s : corny & toffee notes t : breadyness , spicyness & boozeyness upfront .  m : moderate body , mild carbonation .

no where near the aroma i expected-while floral and hoppy its somewhat subdued .  pours out a hazy pink red with a mountain of white-pink head .  carbonation was ok , but with the heavier than expected mouthfeel , i think the hops were lost on the palate more than others textures .

the smell is pretty simple , grainy malts and not too much else .  served in a nonic , the 75 min ipa appears with 2 fingers worth of silky , creamy white head . displays a solid amount of retaining power that lasts with a full finger 's worth until the last sip . the lacing on the glassware appears as a webbing just about everywhere it was in contact . the brew itself is a hazed golden orange color .  the only place that is lacking is the body is a little watery .

the aroma is dominated by the hops , with not too much else there .  the beer after its departure from the 12-ounce brown bottle resides in the glass an onyx color with a modest creamy chocolate colored head , the lace a thick coating to cover the glass .  m : medium body with hardly any carbonation d : drinks good all the way thru that makes it seem like winter in the summer .

smells of molasses and a sort of sweet oak .  beautiful lava lamp look when the yeast diffuses down through the hazy straw body and fluffy white head .  not very full in the mouth , a bit thin in my opinion .

i really like the medium color and clarity of the pour and the head is quite fine , especially in the nitrocan . scottish ales are a favorite style of mine and this is a good representation , if perhaps , brewed to sophisticated and polished compared to a mcewens .  voluminous and tan . excellent lacing . very dark ; essentially opaque rich malt aromas and floral , evergreen pacific hops . molasses it 's a somewhat lively brew , though the effervescence that inflated the head does n't translate fully to each sip ( early on they do , but it seems to go flat quickly ) .  moving back it develops a bigger bready malt profile and the spice really picks up , finishing the hops take over leaving a big earthy peppery bitter hit . m-after the very exciting show with the cork and having the bottle almost overflow i was really surprised at how low the carb was . slightly slick , i would like it to finish a little drier . d-very nice , i would even venture to say that its better than dupont . i was really interested by how well they work in the high abv , i did detect a little heat but it only helped to bring out the spice and citrus flavors .

on tap @ lost abbey / port brewing 's 3rd anniversary party . smell : not much of a smell . smells pretty smooth with a slight hint of floral hops and yeast . feels very good .  this brew poured a transparent dark brown body with a medium light brown head that left an excellent lacing .  pours a nice orange/ruby color with a thin head . it has a nice bitter `` bite '' to it but it 's not overwhelming . some citrus fruit with a hint of some darker fruit , maybe plum ? weird , i know . i could n't defiantly drink a few of these over the course of a night .

but i was at grapevine and the olde ale had just arrived that day . but the aroma is , surprisingly , not bad .  appearance : pours a very dark brown with a light brown/tan head . beautiful as it settles , the movement underneath the half-finger head is trippy as hell , like brown cascading clouds , of course due to the nitro-can . decent lacing left as i drink .  mouthfeel is oe 's strongpoint .
this was a very good ipa , but the aroma was n't overly impressive .  appearance - super pale straw body .  the body has a little chalky hard-water feel to it -- like mineraly .

smells like ... well ... . i ca n't really get a good whiff of this stuff for some reason . mackeson 's is probably 3 times as thick as guinness , murphy 's or beamish .  bottle : poured a deep burgundy color ale with a super huge off-white foamy head with perfect retention .  mildly thin body , but not alarmingly so .

im not sure if was a contaminated batch or just poor handling but it was all foam and tasted terrible . the smell is faintly of sweet malt with a little freshness of hops . the color is a great dark amber and is suprisingly clear if poored right .  beautiful pour on this ... nice brown amber body with minimal bubbles popping from the floor of the glass , but the head is rich and creamy . beautiful look to it .  mouthfeel is a hint to the watery side , would have liked it a little chewier .

complexity builds and alcohol taste diminishes after initial sip , leaving a roasty taste with a chocolate kick very good beer . i like it alot more than the world wide stout and find it much more drinkable .  a - beautiful burnt orange with copper tones . off-white , foamy head that took several minutes to simmer down to a small ring . ample carbonation that held throughout the long life of the beer .  mouthfeel was alright but nothing to write home about .

smell : malt sweetness is mild but pleasant . taste : nice malt profile with caramel , bits of chocolate , and a soft bitterness .  pours a super clear magnifying fiery orange/red . a modest off white to tan head is bubbly from the the profile and creamy up top .  on draft at brewery , 11/19/07 . light golden-yellow with reasonable carbonation . aroma is of artifical strawberry flavoring , like a breakfast cereal or strawberry soda . flavor is likewise dominated by artificial fruit flavor , although there are oxidized , corny off-notes as well . i suspect this is just their blonde ale with strawberry flavored syrup added . aftertaste is mainly lingering , unpleasing mild astringency and some nasty bitterness . blecch . will never drink again .

the aroma is a light toasty cracker with some light grassy , noble hops . fairly subdued but what you can detect is very nice .  appearance : pours a lovely clear ruby color with a huge 3 '' head that slowly falls to a thick surface covering .  light to medium carbonation , with a creamy mouthfeel on the tongue and in the mouth which leans towards crisp and almost watery in the overall feel to it .

aroma is surprisingly tame for the style - vague hops run a spectrum of smells , none being particularly strong : warm fruits , piney , spicy , and aspirin . enjoyable , but not a favorite aroma and flavor profile of mine .  getting started , this gorgeous son of a bitch is one handsome hefe . foggy gold with a cloudy , billowy and sticky head that just bellows 'drink me !  m : somewhat thin , especially for the style i hoped for something richer .

brandon 's version pours well , with a clear , macro-lager yellowness to its hue . the aroma is mild , even for the style , with notes of grain husks , cereal , and dried grasses . mineral water & a light sourness in the background . kudos to highland ( and you might want to consider offering this dude brandon a job !  poured into a snifter at cellar tempature a- dark black with a carmel brown head that lingered for most of th tasting . nice legs on the glass .  m - medium to light bodied . it 's just thinner than i expected .

smell : malty nose with a bit of spice . i swear this smells like meatballs with marinara .  it 's alive and frothy ! wonderful head , beautiful jet black color .  m - the feel is lively and refreshing for something so big , could still stand a bit more oatmeal feel .

smell is a bit sweet , a hint of bavarian-style sweetness , banana and cloves , but just enough bitterness to balance it . a very distinct smell . taste is deceptive .  very nice looking beer .  mouthfeel is medium bodied , with high carbonation . not sure if this is a weird bottle but the carbonation is much too high for the style , better once it had some time to dissipate .

light floral .  looks awesome . aroma-yum , some serious belgian funk going on here .  this is one of those beers that drinks more like a wine than a beer . aged in wine barrels and carrying the flavors over into the finished product with a unique character added to the tartness of this beer . all the rr products are made to the highest of standards by one of craft beers true master brewers ! i recommend trying all their brews if you can get your hands on them..

beer tasted while sitting at my campsite , poured into clear , hard plastic glass . the aroma i found to be weak , maybe the bottle was too cold ? the taste is way better than the aroma , a good solid malty doppelbock ( kinda redundant , i know !  the appearance was exceptional . it is a caramel brown color with a very good looking thick head .  m : smooth . nothing too impressive here .

guinness is the original starter for any stout fan for sure , was the very 1st stout i have ever tasted and is what got me started for being a stout fan . smells has a bit of coffee icecream smell too it with bit of a alcohol kick .  pours the darkest brown head ive seen , which thins away quickly .  '' - phish my girlfriend picked this up despite the owner of the beer store saying it 's one of the worst beers he ever had .

unique , malty licorice like , very belgiany smell for some reason .  half dark brown liquid half egg cream like foam . staying power is somewhat exceptional .  s. rich brown sugar , molasses and smoke t. quite complex with molasses , roasted malt , smoke , brown sugar , cinnamon and clove in the front with a touch of hops in the back m. surprisingly clean , with lingering malt behind medium carbonation d. very drinkable for anyone who likes malt i first tried this beer at a local liquor store 's beer tasting . this is a great example of a fall seasonal for the relaxed craft drinker .

the smell is like a brown ale should be , malty and sweet .  pours black into my over sized wine glass . crazy thick creamy brown 3 finger head after a gentle pour .  mouthfeel : it 's ok but it could use more carbonation with the associated bite .

weak pine and citrus aroma . not much going on here for a fresh hop beer . pretty nice , except the aroma seemed to be lacking .  12 oz bottle poured into a pilsner glass . my weizen glass was dirty . ) a : opaque orange-yellow with honey highlights and a tall creamy white head . hills and valleys of lacing cling to the sides of the glass .  mouthfeel is light , a little on the thin side , with a mouthcoating bitterness . good level of carbonation .
- very fresh , brown-sugary light water ... hidden subtle bready grain.. light grassy hop notes .  pours beautiful ruby with bubbly tan head and good lacing .  mouthfeel seems a little watery .

on tap at st. james infirmary pale golden body , great head retention smell was bready and what not . definitely not a beer i 'm smelling every time i sip , but an appropriate smell nonetheless . taste and feel are excellent . it 's light but flavorful . i am taking a half point from my overall score because my burbs from this one tasted terrible !  pours copper with a creamy whipped off white head . think lace left down my glass .  short , dry finish which makes this eminently drinkable . light bodied and perhaps a little under-carbonated .

the nose is really , really quite faint . first beer of the session and i really had a lot of trouble picking out anything from the nose .  bottled nov. 2007 , batch 3 this looks fantastic . very thick , black , with a dark tan fingers of head .  sharp carbonation in the mouth feel . not a very friendly mouth feel but it is very drinkable .

the aroma is decent . it boasts primarily of pale malts and lager yeast with a mild hop scent .  dark brown with red hues , tan colored head with very good retention and lacing .  wow , i enjoyed the flavor of this beer , the hops are more present in the aroma than the taste , maybe showing up in the extremely dry mouthfeel though . not exactly full bodied , a little light compared to the dark lords we were drinking prior to this , but still it matches the flavors in an appealing way .

s : a clean aroma of orange peel and wheat . the smell is n't super strong .  black as nite . amazing layers of stacked , brown foam .  maybe this is a touch thinner than i like , but it definitely works on a hot day like today .

this is one of the most balanced beers available . the bitterness of the hops is just enough to counter the sweetness of the caramel malt . it is not quite as drinkable as a typical lager , but is about average for an amber ale .  what a beauty . the colour is a beautiful transparent copper with a thick creamy looking one inch off-white head .  the mouthfeel is thin with a watery texture , and lively carbonation .

aroma is muted and not really impressive .  wonderful looking brew .  light carbonation and light-medium bodied . starts almost sweet but hops dominate , boring , finish is dry and slightly bitter . brewed aug 12 , 2005 . $ 1.79 for a 330ml bottle from lina 's beverages painesville , oh .

aroma is mild . i get a faint , nondescript maltiness , and mild hops . decent , but does n't tell me much . that 's a good thing , really , because the ingredients meld into an excellent , fairly potent , warm , complex , sip-by-the-fire ipa .  a- the color of red wine but less translucent with a beautiful sparkling pink head that surprisingly leaves some lace s- smell is sweet and tart berries but also has a mask of farm scent .  an astoundingly good dark beer for the price : 10 bucks for a 12-pack at wegmans in state college , pa . it brings some of the unique flavors found in yuengling porter to a slightly lighter beer , but make no mistake ; the stuff is not weak . it might not be the most delicious beer on the planet , but the combination of good flavor and low price are unbeatable for me as a beer-enthusiast college student ( not a drunkard ! ) everyone else has described the taste well enough . my review is mainly economic .

this pale poured a deep gold color with a good finger size head . unfortunately , i could n't pin down a definite aroma . it was sweet , but that 's all i could determine . perhaps my nose had an off night . the perfect timing of taste continues as the beer has a solid hoppy finish . it leaves you wanting another taste , while retaining a the hoppiness a pale lover would enjoy .  this decadence is a dark mysterious brown with a few fingers of light chestnut head that is finely composed , with high retention and great lacing . i worked on this glass slowly , and quite a long while later there is still sticky lace on the side of my glass and swirls of bubbles on top the beer .  a good pale and pretty cheap . $ 4.99 a six and 5 buck pitcher specials are easily had . full flavored and nicely hopped w/goldings .

the smell was faint hops , almost no smell at all .  a midnight black , picture perfect stout , with head to spare that never goes away ... the beer is gone , can i lick the foam out or is that just trashy ?  creamy head and taste . drier than i expected yet not too hoppy ; which makes me happy ! the color is the dark murky chocolate you expect from a good stout , but lacks the `` fall effect '' one sees in guinness for example . overall a nice drinkable and easy on the palate brew !

s- slightly sweet . sort of buttery . cisco made sure their flagship ( this is their flaghship , right ? ) is one to talk about !  pours a beautiful dark rich red with a nice 2 inch plus head but unfortunately the beer does n't live up to it 's appearance .  it 's rare that i ca n't even stomach a beer long enough to get a few sips down . this beer gave me one of those rare moments . the smell was a sour , and the taste was dirty and skunky . i did n't want to waste the pack , so i made a couple of michelada cocktails . they were actully quite tasty.. nothing like worcestershire and tabasco to make something taste better !

the nose is malt sweet , with some hop floral tones .  appearance : the head is massive , dark brown , sticky and lasting . looks like meringue .  the mouth feel is very dense and viscous that is entirely too syrupy . a little too thick to be enjoyed , but if you can separate the mouth feel from the flavor , youre in for a treat .

nose is weak , no doubt there .  fantastic lacing & head retention smell : slight fruittyness taste : nice hoppy bittterness & caramel up front .  kinda liked this one , the guy at the beer store said the bottle was sitting there for awhile but it held up great.real hazy-orange color with a good head , smelled fresh and citriusy , body was a little thin to me for the style.refreshing taste with some citrius-yeast note very easy to drink.i also think this would be a good warm weather ale .

cereal grains dominate the aroma with a touch of butter . overall , an extremely solid malt liquor , much better than others in the style .  pours a thick black with an equally impressive brown head .  m : light to moderate body ; moderate carbonation ( a little much for the style ) ; hints of chalk & acidity .

s- caramel and malt . there was not a strong alcohol smell . nothing extraordinary . nothing too strong here .  i totally loved the color and the difference in it from the dark orange at the tinner bottom part of the glass , to the brown at the thicker top . it poured with two finger creamy colored and textured head with average retention which left good lace on its way off ... s - dominating yeast and banana aroma , with some sweetness in the back of it .  i 'm 90 % sure this is the same beer as their `` gretchen 's gold '' , which is really what i 'll be reviewing . the bottled version leaves much to be desired vs. on draught . i 've not tasted such a difference between tap and bottle in any other beer . extremely refreshing and drinkable , pleasant sweet malt w/ barely discernable hops for structure . scant head . overall a great beer in its style , with no real flaws . if you can get it on tap , it 's well worth it .

smells of roasted malt and chocolate .  a- a hazy , luminescent orange with a massive off white head that leaves massive lacing .  consequently , the body was found to be light , yet the beer was flavorful , with a nice , almost malty , finish . the mouthfeel was similar to what one would find in most of the american large brew beers .

noted a fairly strong husky grain aroma with some subtle floral , yet spicy hop lingering not far behind in the background .  lots of foam from the nitro can ; in fact , i was left with a glass completely full of creamy , dense off-white foam .. no liquid ! this settled after a few minutes to a fine looking clear amber liquid with about 2 fingers of exceptionally creamy looking head . this remaining head had excellent durability , with nearly a finger high amount still left when all the liquid had been drained .  the finish is fairly dry and woody , but the body is a little flaccid without much supporting carbonation .

s - fruits , my nose is a little stopped up right now from brown nosing . t - fruits , melon , maybe banana , kiwi , sweet malts , subtle caramel mf a- low carbonation , smooth , flavors are soooo well blended due to good aging .  pour is beautiful - black with a thick creamy tan head that just hovers on top , leaving thick lacing all the way to the bottom of the pint .  mouthfeel is unfortunately overly carbonated , it leaves it very bloating .

overall an attractive beer , but very little head retention s- right off the bat i get some caramel and roasted malts , ca n't really smell vanilla right away . overall , nothing too special but also inviting .  i got a growler of this fresh from the brewery and i 'll be a sinner if i say that this was not one of the finest beers i have ever had . thick pillow head that retained wonderfully .  it basically boils down to personal preference . a crisp mild bitterness lingers in the back of the tongue , accenting the overall characteristic of the beer . while thin on the head , it does have a nice nose of lemon and yeast . that musky , spicy smell that makes my mouth water .

releasing southampton 's altbier from captivity put its exquisite reddish copper hue on display . as the head began to dissipate , a nutty , slightly sweet aroma presented itself . traces of grain and yeast also pulled through , leaving behind any significant hop aromas . though perhaps appropriate for the style , the aroma seemed too subtle to appreciate . mellowed from extended conditioning and with a balanced , though slightly sweet flavor profile , this altbier makes for an exceptional session beer .  a rather pretty presentation .  the texture is smooth and a little oily . the favor is a nice mix of sweet orange peel , coriander and wheat malts . the finish is wheaty and a little dry . blue moon is very refreshing and drinkable . [ orange slice was not used for review ]

a bit of a gusher at first sip s_slightly bready . a bit mild t_huge banana bread flavours up front . d_not sure if this fits into the category but like a lot in the brooklyn brewmasters reserve it is a tasty crossover of styles . this is almost more of a dunkelweizen mixed with a dubbel to me and perhaps too sweet to drink too many of .  the dubbel poured into my goblet with a dense head of natural carbonation provided by the bottle conditioning . the thick tan foam lingers minutes after the pour .  it has a sharp astringency i can only assume is the fruitiness . the finish is chemical and most unpleasant . the finish was crisp , for what it 's worth . i like saranac 's pale ale , their adirondack lager is ok , and even their winter wassail is drinkable and interesting , but i had to sacrifice all of my remaining saranac belgian white beers to the drain gods .

the smell is faint and fruity . there are some pine notes and sour citrus aromas . the taste is good .  a- black with a real nice thick 2 finger tan head .  somewhat thinner bodied than some of my favorite pas .

aroma is nominal , fresh and slightly coffee/alcohol . a very enjoyable imperial stout , not the most complex i 've ever had , but really nice . strong though .  sampled on 3-16-07 best before 6-09 pours a nice and clear golden color with an unbelievably massive head that just sits on the top and then settles on the sides of the glass .  the mouthfeel is ok - just slightly under carbonated .

s - nutmeg , brown sugar , and molasses . has that new belgium earthiness about it that i 'm not a big fan of . the nose does n't do this beer justice .  a very impressive pour . pours dark brown with glints of mahogany edges ; brown carbonation cascades upward from the mid-body to the top where it settles in thick , craggy tan head .  of course . a little high in the effervescence .

s : not much there . metallic and chemical that detracts a bit . t : again , sweet malt with more chocolate than in the nose . i really like the taste of this .  a - dark dark brown body with a thick frothy medium tan colored head standing inches tall and fading at a snail 's pace . it is a fine looking hebrew .  m : sticky , almost syrupy and resinous to the extreme . kinda unpleasant but not terrible . o : not a bad double ipa , mouthfeel is really detracting though i think .

i have a cold so the smell was way less than expected but probably mostly due to the cold . taste is very good . overall a great beer .  true black body is topped by a thick chocolate milk foam head .  the mouthfeel is ... well ... ok ... a little bit of an after taste and the alcohol is apparent ... the beer is absolutely worth a try ...

i 'm a big fan of smoked porter and while i liked this , it was n't my favorite . smell was lacking . just not as strong a `` smoke '' smell as some others ( see alaskan smoked porter !  dark sunny golden with a delicate meringous head , mountainous and very rocky . superb looks . trust me , for a 6.8 % beer , this one is packed with flavors .  m- a thin body- highly attenuated with a nice spritzy non-bloating carbonation .
aroma was mild grains .  this is a beautiful looking beer .  m- a little thin and watery for a stout but goes down smooth .

wonderful lacing and good head retention . smell is of dark roasted malts with a light vanilla presence , not as much vanilla as i had hoped .  appearance : dark brown with a very brown head that abundantly fills the pint glass . it 's also long lasting , this beer looks like a champ .  presented much carbonation when poured.a thick beige head with spotty traces of sticky lace.a strong malt and coffee aroma.very nutty , molasses , and chocolate smell also.the color looks to be a very dark red to almost black.the smell and appearance are above average for most sam adams beers.the mouthfeel is a bit weak and watery.no carbonation bite to it.a very dry finish with a touch of a hop bitterness that stays in your throat.a drinkable stout and goes down smooth but is average .

an extra note : someone purchased this for me , and in the time that it took him to complete the rest of his grocery shopping , all of the great lakes products sold out except for the porter .  heavy cascading action as i watch being drawn off the tap . the head is thick and creamy .  mouthfeel is thinner than expected , with a slightly higher-than-expected carbonation . rather drinkable , but i 've had better oatmeal stouts .

s - not much scent , only a little burtness , aroma smelled by 3 people to make sure it was n't me . t - great , bitter bitter roasted malts , with a chocolate finish .  a : deep gold color . very good clarity . fades to the classic belgian lacing .  mouthfeel is medium-light .

s- this is not the best part of any cask beer , i am not sure why but you do n't get an aroma with cask ale . t- this is a solid pale ale , definitely a session ale and this beer is much better because it is served at the proper temperature , chilled , not ice cold .  one of my favorite sam adams offerings ... deliciously red with a huge foamy head making this an extremely attractive brew ... malt dominant aroma.. strong caramel notes and maybe even some toffee.. extremely smooth and sweet malts dominate the palate .  m : sharp at first , fizzy , but lights up as you hold it . still , a bit strong and that cuts down on how much you can have . d : i had 10oz with no problems , but a second might have gotten bothersome due to the fizz .

not much going for it in the smell area . slight malts , tiny willamette scent . eh . the taste is interesting .  good retention and great lace .  mouthfeel - a bit of a strange after taste but very crisp .

nose is lighted roasted/carmelized maltines and brown sugar . no hops noted , but a little of the alcohol strength is .  pours total black with a very thick big head and lace that coats the glass like shaving cream .  m : the only real cavet of the brew is the feel . but it 's generally a bit thin .

smells nondescript , but that does n't mean much .  you can smell it from a table away , and it looks awesome .  the feel is really light and crisp , almost how i wish many lagers and pilsners could feel .

the taste and aroma are not disappointing but not exceptional . we can expect more from such a beautiful beer . it 's very drinkable , although .  pours ruby with a large persistent head leaving loads of lacing . beautiful .  m - mouthfeel was alright ... carbonation was high and body was light .

s- not much stands out here . very subtle sweetess , mostly a presence of hops similar but more subtle than their pale ale . t- the first word that came to mind was aggressive . the most notable taste is in the bitterness , almost like licking a battery but in a subtle enough way to be pleasant . m- thinner than expected .  black with ruby highlights to a light source , a nice creamy tan head , and nice lacing .  medium carbonation and thin mouthfeel makes this brew very drinkable .

subtle spices .  poured into a duvel tulip ( fitting i think ) a fairly clear golden color with a big fully white head that slowly recedes leaving lace along the way .  full bodied with low carbonation that made it feel a bit flat and dull , mild astringency and a bit of warmth . the texture was pretty good even with the low carbonation .

a : almost clear amber , like watered down apple juice s : distinct raspberry and pomegranate smell that is appealing , it also has almost a diet soda scent .  a- a hard pour yields a massive four fingers of fluffy rocky tan head that hold for a good bit slowly before settling to leave a thing sudys cap but not without leaving a tons of chunky sea foam lace all over the glass .  m - interesting flavors dance around but actual feel is pretty standard light ale d - fun , interesting , pairs well with peppery steak or cheese , not too strong .

smell : light smelling with malt being the dominate odor .  a -pours a clear gold golden color with a two finger , off white head that has outstanding retention . there is significant lacing that clings to the side . perfect .  m : pretty low carbonation , which is definitely not a problem for the style . the body 's a little thinner than i 'd prefer , though . a nice , smooth mouthfeel to the beer .

s : does have a maple oat nose , with a bit of piney hops , not pungent at all .  appearance this winter time special is dark , reddish-brown in color with a nice head that showed great retention and laced the hell out of my pint glass . i mean to tell you , even as i drank this down the head stayed and filmed the glass . this one was just gorgeous .  m : a little too light in body , i know this is a brown ale , but i feel it was lacking something .

very nice eye candy . the smell was hard to define . first off , it was not strong at all . but then i picked up malts on top , as it should be , followed by coarse chocolate , nuttiness , fruit ( apples ?  appearance - looks great , black as night with a nice caramel tan head that hangs on the whole time .  it drinks a little like carbonated white wine . the finish is somewhat dry . an interesting and refreshing brew .

smell is a bit bland , but this beer makes up for it with flavor and drinkability .  so many coulours from red to yellow passing through orange , amazing head with different size of bubbles , last for long , there is some waste . nice aroma , candy and spice taste is nice , for being a 11 % beer you can drink some without any effort nice `` american '' bspa , also i love the bottle  had my fifth sn pale ale tonight thought id have another for reviewing purposes and same as always it goes down very smooth very clean light hops aroma with a piney finish taste . even though i love this beer i do think its an extremely drinkable all around beer just a bit hyped maybe ?

a very interesting beer that sat really warm in my stomach -- the `` winter warmer '' is definitely the best way to describe it . appearance : dark coppery red ; a nice 2 finger head that was thick and pillowy -- the carbonation was clearly visible and looked like it was going to last throughout the drink . smell : could n't get much out of it at all -- there was a very slight hoppiness to it as it warmed , but nothing overly discernable . taste : bitter , cinammon is very pronounced and that added to the slight sting on the tongue from the bitter . the spiciness was very interesting and the physical effect of it on the stomach makes it more worthwhile -- definitely a seasonal drink though .  pours golden amber with a rich white creamy head that slowly settles and stays . frothy lacing covers the glass .  mouthfeel : others have pointed out that nuova mattina falls short delivering a creamy mouthfeel . it is highly carbonated and too harsh .

above average head retention & lacing ... s : biscuitty malt , a bit of lemon , does n't really assert itself t : lemons , grapefruit , pine & biscuitty malt up front , the malts take a back seat quickly .  looks really promising , menacing deep brown to black colour .  mouthfeel : a little high on the carbonation and not as thick as i 'd prefer with a stout .

just the right amount of hop character . a perfect example of a dry american stout . try it with a polish sausage with sauer kraut , or maybe another sierra nevada stout .  a : dark mahogany , bubbles with every drink restores a wonderful white head s : sweet coffee t : dry , nutty , cocoa , and of course lots of coffee , very balanced and smooth m : medium in body d : tasty and smooth , reasonable alcohol , very enjoyable spot on for the style with a nice coffee twist .  not exactly a esb by definition but a good beer by my standards . a dark beer in color , with a fruity hint on the nose , of apple and a strawberry sort of smell . the taste is smooth fruity and a bit hoppy all at once . my only complaint was a bit of a bitter after taste , but hey it is a esb

smell : spicy and subtle . generally light .  big three fingers of off-white head , fading to a thick cap with great retention and maybe slightly patchy lacing . looks more like a nice stout than a bsda or black ipa .  m - the feel is cold and mildly coarse .

the smell is like maraschino cherries .  the brew pours to a deep red color with a nice inch high head that will not break down ! the brew has left nice heavy off white lacing on the sides of the glass .  this beer is very balanced m : little bit of body but still water and plenty of carbination but it complements this beer extremely well d : give me a twelve pack of these and i would be glad to finish them any time .

i have been searching for a 'true ' american hefe , and i believe i have found it . smell just a tad weak , but the flavor more than makes up for it . very nice clove and ripe banana in the backround , and incredible drinkability .  amazing retention and wonderful sticky lace abounds . this is a very exciting beer to look at .  really seems watery . carbonation is nice .

smell is faint to my nose . fist sip : blew me away with the flood of hops . in fact , it 's quite good .  this guy poured a deep amber/red , with an awesome amount of creamy foamy head that retained very well and left tons on the sides of the glass .  mouthfeel is a bit thin , carbonation high .

very brief malt sweetness then a big burst of bitterness . not bad , but probably would n't purchase it again unless i intended to age it for a year or so to see if it mellows .  fierce ubiquitous beeding which really carries a nose of almost sweet banana . dense super concentrated almost batter like foam head which finishes all whippy almost like the top of tin tin 's head . underneath the beer has a deeply golden fog .  the mouthfeel was really lacking for me in this otherwise uni ( brou ) que brew .

s - not a lot of smell to this one , mostly some bready malt , hints of spice t - taste is fruity and bready with a touch of spice . good blend of everything here .  roofing felt black ( running out of descriptors ) with the standard widget cascade and whipped cream head .  mouthfeel is okay , but needs to be either thicker or creamier to work with the taste -- as is , it 's just a tad watery .

s : oddly neutral ( perhaps because it 's on draught ? ) with some buttery tones and firm malts deep underneath .  a - poured into my duvel tulip a really nice deep and dark ruby with a big , creamy two finger light tan head that fades ridiculously slowly and leaves amssive side lacing . for a barleywine , at this abv , the amount of lacing and head retention is crazy .  mouthfeel : medium-bodied and slightly syrupy . minimal carbonation .

while not offensive , the smell is timid sweet and slightly fruity like a peach cotton candy ... not at all what you might expect .  a light brown to dark mahogany ale that pours with a voluminous , rocky off-white head .  split with the wife at the eccentric cafe in kalamazoo , michigan . looks like a wheat beer with absolutely no odor coming off the brew . very , very wheaty , to the point of being a bit of a turn off . more cherry & less wheat would have been a better combo , methinks . this got actively unpleasant as it warmed - the aftertaste was a killer .

the smell is simple : floral , citrus and grains .  i had this beer poured from a bottle into a pint glass ... a : the beer pours a nice light brown color with some orange and yellow hues shining through . the head is about 2 finger and very fluffy , the lacing is top notch ... s : the smell is nothing above average .  mouthfeel great carbonation . perhaps a little thin , but not a detraction . a bit sticky on the aftertaste .

s : most dipas i 've had attack my nose . kind of underwhelming .  deep amber/copper hue with a beautiful stream of bubbles hurrying to the surface .  medium-light body with moderately-high carbonation . good but a bit astringent and tannic .

not much of a smell really . i mean , there 's the normal smells you get in a porter , but it 's not the big notes of chocolate and coffee like you usually get . drinkabiliy seems normal ... for this style at least .  another kick ass brew from stone . black liquid , white head .  nice scent , very bitter with some nice citrus and floral american hops , but with little of the nice sweet , clean red ale scent i expected to go with it . nice hoppy , pale-ale-type flavor , nice american hops , with enough malt to keep it near to balanced ; much hoppier than a regular red ale , but that was what they were going for . goes down fine , if a little rough from the slight unbalanced aspect . pretty darn hoppy for such a low abv red ale .

s- faint aromas of malt and wood . you get some wood and whiskey right on the nose , along with the earthy hops and bready malts of the base beer .  a - dark , near black mahogany in color . thick , foamy dark brown head with incredbile retention and lacing . just a beautiful beer all around .  palate : medium body and higher end carbonation .
s - subdued citrus hop aroma , probably due to the age of the beer .  pretty gorgeous .  overall feel is good enough , but was a bit thin .

s : teriyaki sauce all the way , i feel like i 'm at matsu circa 1989 .  it has a nice dense tan colored head that is just sitting right on top of the beer . great lacing down the sides of the tulip glass .  m- a little on the thin side and a little under carbonated . overall i thought this was a good octoberfest beer , spot on for its style , besides its mouthfeel .

aroma was weak . but i just had an alpha king ( regular tap , not cask ) earlier and it smelled great . mysterious .  the color of this beer is a beautiful , rich , reddish , amber .  the mouthfeel is less than exciting . fairly thick , though not as thick as it could be , and hardly any carbonation to speak of .

what makes this beer stand out , both positively and negatively , is the chocolate taste . the highly malty taste complements the very potent chocolate taste . in brief , this tastes like a milkshake . if you want a light cocoa taste in your beer , this is not for you .  amazing fluffy tan head with excellent retention and lacing .  mouthfeel is medium bodied with some carbonation on the tongue .

if this beer has a weak point , its the aroma . i did n't get a lot off of the nose . i did smell the grain along with tiny hints of lemon and hop . overall it was sweet and slightly buttery . great taste , hardly filling , absolutely one of the best lagers i 've had .  appearance- darker golden pour , huge ass chunky pock marked head . beautiful lace streaks and chunks all over .  mouthfeel is highly carbonated and drying , as it should be .

smell was typical of the style . so typical that i ca n't even really remember what the aroma was like . nothing stood out here .  nitro tap at the palmdale location look : almost black and totally opaque with a brown ring on the bottom of the glass with a 1/2 inch tan head and exceptional retention and some spotty lacing smell : coffee notes upfront with hints of chocolate but the nose is fairly muted taste : roasted malts with hints of ash coffee and chocolate .  body is a little thin and the carbonation is a little high for the sweetness of the beer .

smell : mild - alcohol is detectable , but through the smell alone this is not an overpowering element . pleasant , peaty finish , somewhere between a cheap porter and a complex english dark ale .  creamy , long-lasting 1 '' beige head over the slightly orangey dark amber brew , which laced with heavy foam throughout .  mouthfeel is decent and light , but not as noteworthy as the aroma and taste .

i understand that some others might not like it , but i feel coors has a rich , creamy flavor and is a perfect compliment to food ( hence , `` banquet beer '' ) . i love the way coors goes down , and is incredibly drinkable . i like craft beer as well , but this is the king of macrobrews in my opinion .  pours an opaque mahogany with a 3-finger , frothy cafe au lait head . this is a fairly drinkable porter that 's beautiful to look at , but it 's more bitter than i like for the style .  the taste is nice , the coffee does n't seem overbearing or anything , but i 'd prefer more a thicker body and maybe more sweetness . very tasty but more body would be nice for a fit with the flavor .

the aroma ... . light sweetness ... light malt . not much on the aroma ... the taste ... quite good .  pours ruby red amber with a large fluffy off-white head that retains well and laces the glass .  m : a bit thin , but still decent .

s - pretty calm . some dark malt , little chocolate .  the beer poured into the chalice crystal clear ruby red with a white frothy head which rose and retreated slowly to lace the chalice from top to bottom .  m - very light for a stout .

the aroma is rather faint , but has notes of nutmeg and ginger with a touch of sweet malt mixed in .  holy shit , what a beer . great head with amazing retention .  mf is a bit lacking , thin , though creamy .

the smell is a little sweet with a mild but present nobles hop aroma . a little bit fruity and mildly floral with a little grassy scent .  visible carbonation , this is one fizzy looking beer ! pours with a thick creamy and towering white foamy head . heavy and sparkling lacing . wow , perfect example of the style !  bready malts and a faint aftertaste of alcohol is also present beer is way over carbonated . only thing that got to me was the over carbonated .
the smell of this one is a faint malty sweet aroma .  jet black with big mocha head .  mouthfeel : highly carbonated for the style .

smell is n't remarkable and nothing really sticks out . there 's better stouts but this is n't bad .  a- cork shot off like champagne , pouring pitch black with an ever-growing tan head that retained well and left excellent retention .  smells of sweet malt , grains , hops , toasted bread and honey . very weak nose overall . tastes of roasted malt , grains , lemon , citrus hops , caramel , bread and yeast ... a toasty flavor that is not typical for an ipa and more like a lager than an ipa . it 's a bad ipa , not hoppy or like an ipa at all ... a drain pour , as it was tough to finish this beer . bordered on terrible .

no freshness date . subtle earthy and sweet aroma with hints of roasted malt .  poured in my struise glass the beer looked very nice , big broken white head , a copper to amber cloured fluid with nice carbonation .  m - i 'm finding myself rather indifferent towards the mouthfeel .

s : smells pretty grassy with a touch of malt supporting the hops . t : tastes pretty grassy with some hints of pine and spicy hops .  nitro tap served at crossroads coffee and icecream on southside richmond , va. a : black with three finger superfine nitro head s : booze !  mouthfeel : carbonation is average . body is unfortunately a little thin , contrary to what your taste buds are telling you .
subtle aroma , but followed with an eye-openingly brilliant taste .  i love the appearance .  smooth and sweet , this is pretty nice . carbonation is a bit low , even for my liking .

smell : light floral malty aromas with a soapy character .  the carbonation in this beer is incredible , it looks like the beer is alive .  the disappointing : wow , what a highly carbonated brew , almost champaign in the fizziness .

an impressive cask stout . slightly subdued aroma , with light coffee and smoke .  the cask-conditioned punjabi poured a cloudy , copper-orange with a thick , creamy , white head that had excellent retention ( lasted the whole way ) and some lacing .  sort of thin . the hops seem a little tired , though .

s - aroma is subdued with hints of spice , alcohol , and bready yeast t - here 's the trick it is truly beer + pumpkin not liquid spice cabinet like many breweries end up making .  a - pours dark brown/black , but with medium body that is n't so thick that it appears syrupy . 1-finger creamy beige head with medium to large bubbles , good retention and good lace .  had on tap at the brewery . pours nice golden color , clear and crisp . true to style in every way except maybe not as malty . but this makes it nice and crisp . brewer does a good job on the lagers . light grassy hop aroma blends nice with the earthy malt flavors . recommended .

smell is rather mild , some hops detected . nothing mild about the taste , bold hops and citrus , very ipa like , spicy , lots of flavor here .  pours a nice cloudy , straw color with a great head .  im sure this loses ratings for its thin palate , but taste wise this is spot on . more roasted coffee flavors and a touch of smokiness . an imminently sippable brew . nicely done .

s : smells malty with a hint of fruity sweetness and a little bit of that adjunct bitterness . not exactly the greatest . t/m : the taste is great , though : heavy amounts of belgian dark fruits and a bitter finish , better than the aroma lets on . its very good and a lot fuller flavored than youd think .  appearance : an almost crystal clear dark yellow/ light gold beer with nice fluffy white head that has some staying power and great lacing .  the mouthfeel is probably a little bit too carbonated and thick for how this beer tastes - the delicate floral aspects make me long for something a little more mellowed out .

it smells faintly of grapefruit hops , and not much else , even as it warms .  dark black body , dark milk chocolate head . extremely dark and perhaps the darkest of the yeti beers .  m : medium mouthfeel , with medium carbonation . leaves the mouth semi-dry .

aroma is not this beer 's strong point . zero cherry , some minimal clove and wheat . a slight sense that this could be a hot alcoholic mess .  this beer was very attractive with its thick head and red color . it felt as smooth as it looked , which was delightful .  m : very light . a bit over carbonated but not overwhelming .

nose - chocolate malts with a clean , hoppy aroma . very distinct . taste - roasted malts with deep sweet cola taste .  a beautiful looking beer . there is a milky-white cloudiness to this beer that is oddly appealing .  the feel was unremarkable .

the smell is very faint . sweet , malty , nutty , in taste and smell .  superior lacing & head retention s : bready with hints of brown sugar t : bready & fruitty ( dates ) with a little too much boozeyness up front .  the mouthfeel is a bit thin .

it 's not urine pale like most macros . this is such a pale yellow it makes me think , `` now , this is a real session beer . '' i 'm not getting much in the aroma but i think that 's more b/c of the bar and less to do with the beer . this is good . nice beer to sit back and session for awhile while playing pool or skeet ball .  great retention .  very nice hoppy taste , crisp and clean with a nice malt balance and a great bitter aftertaste . goes down fine , perhaps a bit rough from overcarbonation , but a very well down ipa .

smell -- pilsner malt , lemon , a bit of pine bough , and sticky rice . not bad , but a bit ho-hum .  wow , good looking beer . pours with my favorite waterfall type head ... ( forms from the bottom ) 2 fingers of creamy tan head form and clearly let you know they are going to stay a while . lacing is everywhere .  t & m - lighter body and rather refreshing in it 's character ; if anything , feels a little too light ... almost a hair watery . clove character is lighter , but present with a hint of bubblegum .

nose is burnt caramel and oxidized malts . meh , it 's ok. oh , taste is pretty nice . somewhere in between an english and an american bw , has some flavors from both styles here .  it poured a surprisingly beautiful cloudy red , i would describe it like a strawberry color . good carbonation and a nice pink tinted white 1/2 inch head .  mouthfeel was far more watery than i expected .

there 's a bit of diacetyl in the nose , along with some grainy aromas and subdued earthy hops . the flavor follows the aroma , but without the diacetyl .  coal black body with a rich , milk chocolate brown head that stacks up like abandoned cars in a snowstorm . the head clings to the side of the glass as i drink , and it leaves fluffy chunky rings .  pretty good carbonation with a little creaminess to it as well .

this is a great stout . there is coffee , malt , brown sugar , chocolate . its just not the overpowering nose present i was expecting . the taste is good , not great with much of the smell being tasted in direct proportioned amounts . the beer looked great when i poured it but my first hint that this was n't going to live up to the hype was in the nose . still thouroughly enjoyable .  on tap at the brew pub a : pours a hazy yellowish , with a brown twinge color . provides a thick white foam head with excellent retention .  mouthfeel is avera- man , this beer is actually giving me a headache .

slight scents of yeast . nice smooth feeling .  a- beautiful looking beer in my opinion , light yellow color , hazy with a foamy , long lasting head .  m - my only complaint with this beer is that it is a little thin . i may be just really enjoying everything else about this beer which makes we want to forgive it for being thin .

this hefe is right up there with franziskaner imo , if i had a choise between the two i would be happy with either . the only drawback is the aroma , while not bad it had a faint skinky smell to it . but that 's not enough for you not to drink it , because it has a nice feel and very good citrus tatse to it .  poured into an imperial pint glass , formed a 1 1/2 '' tan head over the slightly cloudy reddish chestnut brew . head holds on with a miser 's grip , leaving incredibly thick layers of sticky froth .  a light to medium body , with prickly , active carbonation . the carbonation was just a tad bit higher then i would have liked , but was still enjoyable .

smell : not much to speak of . there 's the slightest hint of biscuity malt , and it smells slightly dusty - if that makes sense at all . taste/mouthfeel : this is an incredibly refreshing beer . the flavor is very bright and well-balanced . drinkability .  huge sheets of lacing and good retention .  very good beer but does lack with a thin somwhat over carbonated mouthfeel for a stout .

no head or lacing ( 2 ) s : hmm , this is ... interesting ? smells of burnt toast , prunes and a bourbony vanilla ( 3 ) t : oh dear , that 's abrasive .  excellent retention and sheets of lace that coat the insides of the glass .  mouthfeel was average -- no bad bite , but not much body either .

nose is a bit subdued . musty hops - orange rind , oak , floral notes .  this beer has a beautiful pour ; two fingers of head that slowly deflate , leaving thick lacing on the glass .  m : less smooth than the iv ; it has a rubbery booze component that i do n't care for . otherwise fine .

not much aroma . taste is different for a winter warmer and a nice change of pace .  the pour is pitch-black in color ; head is immoderate in size , light chocolate in color , and the lace thick clinging sheets that last till the bottom of the glass .  really interesting for a christmas seasonal . a good amount of spice and hops as it poured into a nice dark orange , with a little bit of lacing and head . i did n't really feel the `` festive ale '' as much as some of the other beers i 've had around this time , but it did have some good spices and taste .

errrr ... not sure what 's going on with the aroma here . is it my sniffer or does this smell like wet dog ? there is a very faint ginger smell getting through , like that of a lesser ginger ale soda . it reminds of a car-crash between the kind of hops/malt balance found in good barley wines and the fragrant spiciness of a pumpkin ale . there 's a medicinal quality to this too , but not in the negative way i would usually use that term to describe beer . fruit-like , candy-like , allkindsa-like , this is one intriguing concoction . a pleasure to sip and ponder , as each sip offers something a little different than the one before .  nice looking color .  somewhat substantial body , nothing too heavy . if any hit , a little too much carbonation but that is stretching it .
