aroma is balance malt and hop and very tight . the flavor shines on this one , especially for a lager .  the beer poured black with an incredibly creamy light brown head .  mf : there could be a bit more of a body to back up the full flavor of this beer .

poured from the bottle into a wide mouth pint a-pours dark black nice big head with very good retention and nice sticky lace s-nose is pretty subtle rosted malt , with small alcohol and chocolate notes .  this stout is so black that light can not penetrate it 's depths , seriously , i tried to shine a green laser pointer thru it .  it kind of explodes in the mouth and the carbonation is a bit on the sharp side .

could n't seem to get a whole lot outta the smell ... a bit sweet i suppose . tasted light caramels , hints of raisins and malts .  a : the beer looks like perfectly clear dark caramel , topped with a foamy tan head which provides generous lacing , and sticks around for a while after the pour .  m - mouthfeel is a bit on the thin side for my liking .

s - surprisingly subdued but there are definite hints of dark fruits , especially figs . it smells tasty , but not like something extraordinary .  poured from my home tap with a deep dark chestnut brown color and a luxuriously creamy beige head .  body was a bit thin/watery with average carbonation .

overall really light on the nose .  incredible appearance , smell , and taste in this one .  aroma is assertively malty and a little bready . well-balanced on the palate , hops are subtle ( that figures - the use of east kent goldings is revealed from the label ) . malty and a littly nutty , with a clean finish after the malt notes dissipate . a good session beer ( again , as suggested from the label ) , and a very close cousin to a true british mild ale .

there 's not much to say about the nose on this beer ; there 's a bit orange blossom fruitiness . overall , this is a very enjoyable ipa .  spezial weisse looks about as good as any hefeweizen con look .  mf- lower carbonation than i was expecting right out of the gate . mouthfeel was the only slight flaw .

the aroma is not overpowering but definitely has hints of the coffee implied by the name ... very espresso-y . that 's not really a word i guess huh ? the taste is great , very smooth ... .the coffee does n't come to the fore immediately which is pretty cool . the hop notes are pleasant and not sharp ... they accentuate the coffee bitterness which is the way it should be for this style .  bottle ( 2011 ) a beautiful rich copper color and a thick and stubborn off-white head . leaves gobs of lacing down the glass .  the only odd thing i noticed was sort of low carbonation , odd because there was a lot of foam on pouring . but it was n't really stale feeling , it just could have had more mouth presence .

curious back story drew me in . split a bottle during an afternoon 's round robin . looked like a perky rose wine or a pink champagne with 7-up advertisement effervescence . initial taste was unanimously honey which mellowed w/each sip . the sake influence almost slipped in unnoticed , but was worth the wait , like an old friend arriving at a party full of strangers .  easily the most impressive appearance of any single ipa ive had . perfectly clear deep amber in color . an average pour yields a 1 1/2 head that hangs around for a minute leaving lace on nearly every area it touched .  tiny bits of lemon or orange come in from the hops , but there is not a huge fruitiness . finishes dry too . this is an interesting beer .

s - citrus hops aroma .  2005 edition . looks really great ; dark amber pour with a big soft pillowy head that gradually dissipates leaving insane amounts of foam .  it is a bit thin and has a low abv , but this makes the beer a great summer refresher , when you do n't want a heavy beer .

s - i 'm not picking up a lot here , malt , some fruit and caramel .  it pours a dark brown , almost black , color with a beautiful chocolate milk colored head .  m : medium-little body , ok carbonation .

s : sweet malt and faint hops , citrus , earthy . m : light to medium body with nice , lively carbonation . t : sweet barley malt followed by mild , grassy saaz hops .  the head was huge , three fingers of cream-colored foam that displayed great retention as a rocky cap . it laced well too so i had to admit it was great looking , period .  about half-way down the glass , the mouthfeel seem smoother and slicker as well .

hats off to my beer brother james for giving me this bottle as part of a birthday present package . the subtelty of the finish is the best part ... no bitter beer face  pours a beautiful red/brown with a creamy tan head .  bit of texture on the feel but still pretty thin .

smell : very weak smell .  a - poured jet black with a gorgeous , chocolately one-finger head into a snifter .  `` bottled in 2009 '' pours a nice red in color , a hue i have n't seen in beer before , with no head , though it is carbonated . there are also weird vegetable flavors that are not that pleasant . noticeable alcohol flavors and dryness . the more i drink of this the worse it tastes , actually . this beer just does n't do it for me , and it hurts me to give a bad review to a beer from such a great brewery . this is the least distinguished ( a polite way to say `` worst '' ) dogfish head beer .

s - subtle coffee and cocolate aromas witha slight accent of anise .  pours like 3000 mile used motor oil black body hosts an almost three finger rocky chocolate brown head that has nice retention . leaves scattered lace .  mouthfeel is a bit on the thin side .

shiner has a very nice dark , malt color with a hint of aroma . it has a very mild taste , not to overwhelming , and yet not to strong .  a - brilliant muted yellow color .  palate is a little cloying from the fruity sugars , but ends dry . finishes with a parching pinesness and slick fruit punch .

hmmm , ipa from a can . s : not too much nose actually , the beer has a sweet bready body . almost like a dipa , but much lighter ... the hops are light but pine herbal grass and floral notes are hiding in there somewhere . t : different flavor , but i really enjoy it -- its rather different . like i said above , the malts taste like a dipa , but more watered down . it is really quite nice . d : i 'll have another ... right now please !  wow there is more to this version of the yeti than i thought , cayenne ... hmmm.poured a jet black with a fluffy mocha colored head that left a creamy mass after leaving multiple sheets of lace as it settled very slowly.aromas of vaniila/oak and bitter chocolate and some roastiness.flavors start out with hefty roast and bitter chocolate with cayenne hitting in the finish wich is very noticeable by me , not sure how others have felt about the cayenne presence.not sure if that cayenne presence is welcomed by me , its a bit annoying.i like the complexity and the uniquness but not my thing so much , although its not bad just for the record .  the mouthfeel is a little on the thin side , but drinkability is excellent .

smell is toffee , a little biscuity maltness soghtly spicy and a hint of yeast , probably due to the bottle conditioning . some fruits as well , but i cant put a finger on what fruits ... the taste here is sooo much more than the weak smell . taste is dominated by a fruity fudgy maltiness , imagine a not-too-sweet piece of fudge , but instead of being fudge-brown , it 's violet , and has faint but oh so noticeable hints of blueberry , raspberry and apples cooked in sugar syrup .  poured a gorgeous 2 '' violet pink head .  finishes pretty dry , perhaps a little too carbonated for the style .

cherries and sourness dominate the aroma . a little dirt .  poured from an 11.2 oz bottle into a stemless wine glass . a ) pours brown , and resembles apple cider in color/consistency .  medium bodied but a bit thinner than expected with a prominent roasted coffee presence that lingers over the dark malts and subtle barrel character into a dry finish .

s : spicy and herbal with a little bit of fruit ( strawberry ? t : interesting beer ... better than the smell and lack of protein might lead on .  black as night , with a head the color of chocolate milk . it 's a full pint , so it fits the glass perfectly .  cask at the cricketeers arm . served by a big dude named red . it is indeed chock full of coffee , toffee and roasty notes . very dry finish and as i can readily attest highly drinkable . great stuff .

massively drinkable and very enjoyable . could be misplaced as an english bitter and close the best of its kind in australia .  the body is deep black and holds a huge ; two fingers thick , mocha head that is so thick and lasting it almost looks like it is brooding .  to me smelled like wheat/grain , nuts . t : taste just like you would expect , after smelling . d : pretty good beer , surpassed my expectations . could drink this one all night and be satisfied !

while mentioned repeatedly as a saison , it has a much maltier character then your typical farmhouse ale . in the same vein at first look it appears to be a brown ale with a thin white head .  a : tar black with tan , creamy head .  mouthfeel is pretty thin , nice a smooth carbonation , but just feels weak .

smell : unexceptional taste : like really , really delicious candy . i found this a delightful accompaniment to an ethiopian meal and a wonderful surprise to boot .  a- pours a cherry color with a thick off white head and sparce lacing .  it 's pretty light bodied with a low level of carbonation .

i do n't get much from the nose , but then again , i 'm pretty hit or miss with smells given my unusually small nostrils ( seriously ) . a case study in hops . way to go smuttynose !  color is a beautiful deep copper , almost red .  the aroma is hoppy and earthy with some fruity notes , reminds me a bit of orval in this sense . the flavor has a nice character of fruity hopes and a mild malt sweetness , but the beer is dominantly dry . there is a very mild tartness here but generally the beer is dominated by a blend between some spicy yeast notes and pleasant hop bitterness .

smell - the most noticable aroma is a crisp and bitter hop presence . the malt character is moderate , and definitely in the background . overall this is an average pale ale , in my opinion .  pours a pitch oily black , with a nice two finger dark brown head that 's super fine and creamy , it really lays on the lacing .  if only the texture was less paper thin and more like cardboard .

s : kind of weak with faint coffee grounds odor with sweet raisins and vanilla . t : pleasant and grabbing coffee presence immediate with a ton of chocolaty sweetness to boot .  a-pours a beautiful hazy orange color with lots of a thick white head . the head has some solid retention , takes some time to go down , and leaves lots of lacing on the glass .  the taste is thick and interesting . its just a tad lacking , leaving this beer to taste like eating hershey 's special dark chocolate powder . this beer coats the tongue well , but the taste is over-powering . i 'm really impressed with the idea here and think this is a good beer .

not much of an aroma , but what i 'm getting is a coffee type scent .  dark amber hue with red highlights . nice one and a half finger , frothy , off white head .  m : a little thinner than i expected but still coats the palate , probably why it 's a porter .

from a 22 ounce bomber - $ 3.99 . s. holy cow - lots going on here . belgian yeast , citrus and pine hops , wild flowers , graphite and candied malt . killer nose . t. plenty of hop goodness without being overly bitter . d. this is one fine beer . the nose alone is worth the price of admission .  pours blacker than a saharan night during an eclipse . head is a thick , dense , and tan .  mouthfeel is excellent . it 's creamy and almost chewy .

s : honey , malts , wheat great nose on this . t : banana and cloves dominate the flavor .  the looks are perfect for this one folks .  creamy and chewy . pretty yeasty for an apa , although this is leaning towards english ipa i believe .
aroma is very nice and hoppy .  enormous foamy white head . mildly hazy and golden . leaves large patches of lacing for the duration of the sample .  mouthfeel is very rich , smooth carbonation .

it has a wonderfully complex aroma which consists of plums , oranges and a hint of toasted marshmallows . very drinkable .  bottle : poured a bright golden color ale with a large foamy head with excellent retention and some very nice lacing .  mouthfeel 5/5 medium bodied , appropriately crisp , and clean finishing , the mouthfeel of this beer is spot on .

theres a wonderful aroma of sweet grapefruit . overall , this is an excellent and extremely enjoyable pale ale , with its low hop bitterness and strong citrus hop aroma . i love it . i highly recommend this beer .  pours a midnight black that you can not see through . thick brown head falls to a very minimal one .  a- very murky , tan head , and faint hints of a red hue on the outer-most parts of the glass s- muted nose , that such of chocolate pop tarts t- marshmellow , chocolate , cocoa , raisen , over ripe cherry and a nice little chunk of bitter bight m- creamy and gorgeous . this beer is awesome .

a- pale hazy golden with a finger sized head and an active carbonation s- yeast , banana , clove , and bubblegum . exactly what youd expect in a wheat but on the strong side t- lemony with everything that i could smell . very nice m- highly carbonated and light feeling d- i wish i picked up more of this . very drinkable and a great take on the style . recommended  pours a slightly cloudy reddish brown with a gorgeous light tan head with amazing , photographic-quality lacing along the sides of my cab glass .  the mouthfeel on this beer is superb . very creamy with subdued carbonation and a medium body .

decadent as well , somewhat like chocolate covered cherry cordials . absolutely fantastic in the nose ! syrupy and mellow with buttery brown bread and nice fruit : apple , berry , citrus , and fig . sweet and woody and not terribly pronounced provided the outstanding nose . mild hops and vanilla with a ghost-like smoke note . very complex and earthy but rather understated . very nice however . a unique and enjoyable rendition of the style .  thanks to mer who imported this from italy ( hey i was hoping there would be italian on the bottle , but oh well ) ... appearance : i sampled this in a chalice ( not a chimay chalice however ) , which effects the color a bit ... the beer was slightly cloudy and blood red , bordering on brown . head was about an inch thick on top , white and megenguey ( alright , do n't know how else to describe it , but it stayed above the top of the glass without spilling over like a merengue pie ) .  mouthfeel is surprisingly smooth and creamy for such a sweet beverage . very nice .

nice , but not excessive , lacing all the way down the glass . smell : light yeasty aroma , with a belgian spiciness and sweetness . very smooth nose , without being overly mild or harsh . the look and the smell are amazing , but the taste is only just above average .  a- perfect pitch of black hue , a fantastic color of mocha head . lacing is beautiful .  the body is medium with one of the finest , creamiest , super fuzzifyingly , silky-slippery-zippery carbonations i have ever encountered .

fantastic . i could just smell it all night .  a : pitch black beer with a charcoal greyish-brown foamy 3-finger head leaving plenty of lacing all the way down .  good with food , good standing alone , and a wonderful , creamy mouthfeel when on tap .

the nose is huge . heavenly hops aromas of pine , citrus and resin and backed up by a malt backbone that miraculously isnt completely shut out by the monster hops . fabulous . the taste follows suit with more of the same balance between the two heavyweights . however it almost met up to my expectations , i think mostly because of its fantastic aroma and great balance . im not sure if id consider this one of the best dipas in the world , but it certainly was an enjoyable experience that brought a smile to my face .  750ml corked and caged bottle poured into a wine goblet - 2007 bottling - fridge temp appearance : pours a cloudy golden orange beer with a towering 3 '' off-white head . great retention with lots of soapy lace .  very well rounded .

smell : the most varied mix of spices as i have ever smelled ... you got mint , ground pepper , basil , thyme , lavander , cloves , it 's like he emptied his spice rack in there ! unbelievable stuff . taste : pretty complex , quite heavy on the spices .  thin , low on flavor , but undeniably sessionable irish dry ___ a : matte black body with dingy ruby highlights topped with a very persistent one finger extremely creamy buff head . the well-known reverse cascade effect is beautiful to behold .  awesome mouth feel . thick and creamy with the perfect amount of carbonation for the style .

the nose is brilliant .  12 oz can poured into a brandy snifter a - rich , dense , hot chocolate looking head on top that will not quit . very dark , red brown color that just looks thick . stellar start .  taste is very smooth with a great mouthfeel .

smell is very strong and pleasing . i get big raisin notes with oatmeal , allspice , nutmeg , and cinnamon . pretty incredible actually !  bottle , from whole foods in tustin , ca , a : pours a dark maroon red , with a thick rich cap of white foam , great head retention , extensive thick lacing .  the texture was excellent , not too thick or thin .

on the back side of the aroma profile is some floral hop bitterness to help balance this out ... it has a very inviting smell overall that i hope leads to a likewise flavor . i love the aroma as i 'm drinking this beer !  pours a beautiful dark red color , huge off white foamy head to it .  for a supposed potent*ipa* i expected a huge blast , but it is light refreshing yet surprising t. sweeter ipa , nothing too extreme , dry finish on the tongue with an exceptional mouth feel .

s : very aromatic . aromas of raspberries , caramel , apple , plum , apple and cherry pie , cheesecake , and sour candy . t : same as aroma . does n't taste like beer at all , tastes like liquid raspberry cobbler . exquisite in every category .  pours a mostly clear medium amber with plenty of thick , cream-colored head . great head retention and lacing .  great mouth feel it 's carbonated perfectly making this a great beer .

pretty typical looking ipa . tons of tangy citrus tangerine and ripe grapefruit with a touch of dankness . this is pretty much my standard for west coast ipa aromas - very few brews smell better , and if they do they deserve a perfect score . d - solid example of the west coast ipa style - i just wish it tasted as awesome as it smelled . the feel also makes it a little less drinkable , as the burning carbonation becomes a little unpleasant .  huge 5 inch head at first with excellent retention . about 10 minutes later i am served a gorgeous , glowing medium yellow/orange beer with a 2 '' frothy , layered head . after several minutes it settles with a pile of froth in the middle like cartoon dog poop , seriously , and tons of lacing with actual gobs .  this beer is full bodied and velvety smooth . it is a little high in alcohol , but the smooth mouthfeel and nice flavor would go a long way .

fragant , great nose . t : caramel malt , molasses , red wine with a hint of soy sauce .  it was a clear dark honey color with lots of carb streams and great lacing . it had a massive white head that took forever to whittle down to a constant 1/4 '' foam .  very well balanced , nice full mouthfeel seals the deal .

sweet hop nose . full juicy/piney ... very piney hop flavor and fairly well rounded . spicy , somewhat medicinal yeast .  dark as night with a creamy mashmallow like off white head .  mouthfeel is perfect , medium bodied with a champagne silkiness that is delectable when swirled .

superb . t : more dark fruits , along with a huge earthy bitter aftertaste .  a very large billowy head follows the pour . holding this up to the light , you get a unique pale yellow with all kinds of bubble action . the frothiness is very white and has excellent retention .  body is rich , creamy , smooth , and damn near perfect . another excellent offering from d'achouffe .

a : pours a very dark amber , can barely see through it , thick white head , copious lacing around glass s : loads of aromatic hops in the piney variety , some citrus , little to no malt presence ( dominated by these delicious smelling hops ) . this has an excellent smell ! t : taste pretty much matches nose , a walloping of piney hops with a little more depth than what i could smell . has a nice spicieness to it .  a- pours a deep brownish hue with a creamy , 2 finger , light brown head that sticks around for a long time .  mouthfeel is creamy and smooth , and the taste is complex with more dark fruit and caramel with almost port-like flavours .

among the best smelling brews ive experienced . t : flavor not as exquisite as the nose but still tight . i enjoy the bitterness of this imp stout matched with the deeply roasted malt . not the best tasting ris but the best aromas in my opinion .  2009 vintage pours a dark beautiful amber color with a perfect amount of head and some patchy lacing .  perfect body with great carbonation .

nose is wonderful with a mingling of smokey malt and spicey hops .  as black as a raven 's wing , this beer is really impressive . the feel on the tongue is smooth like a dark chocolate bar , the alcohol was n't really noticeable . this beer goes down easy and is one easy to drink more then one glass of .  mouthfeel is nearly perfect , with a refreshingly light and crisp body .

the smell is fresh pumpkin pie with the fixings ... cinnamon , big nutmeg , very spicy and nice . light pumpkin with good nutmeg flavours round out this very delicious and thoroughly enjoyable ale .  poured into champagne flute . a - pours a light blood colored red with strawberry shortcake looking two finger foam head . a thing of beauty !  very creamy and full bodied , perfect carbonation to keep it moving .

honey and heather ! reminds me of really good scotch . i tried to find the skunk but it is n't there , this smells like summer . good but not great . better than average mouth feel . smell is the strong point .  superb appearance !  nice mouthfeel of solid carbonation .

incredible nose a huge bouquet of fresh hops backed by a nice bready malt profile . another great beer from three floyds .  pours opaque black with a 1 inch creamy tan head that lasts for a lifetime after the cascading brown bubbles stop and settle ; great looking stout that sets the standard for stout looks with great lacing that leaves thick rings . guinness is always impressive to look at when it poured properly from a tap .  mouthfeel is perfect for a porter , chewable but not too much , this is a meal in a bottle .

aroma is this beer 's best feature . sweet caramel coffee with a hit of hardwood smoke blends with an alcoholic spiciness . dank forest woods come out in the end . good brewery , good stout .  snifter and was greeted by a massive 3 finger head that left a nice web of lacing down the glass .  there is the perfect amount of carbonation for the style .

the aroma was the high point for me : very sweet malts , sugary candy , caramel , and mocha coffee . can smell it from a good distance away . small , light brown head that sticks gorgeously to the side of the glass . i highly advise trying this one .  tried this on a whim ... made with raisins and beet sugars , i was hoping for an interesting experiment , but ended up finding one of my favorite recent discoveries , and the best so far by the amazing brewers at dogfish head . the color alone is an experience . i would paint my apartment with that rich , warm , brown-red color .  fairly soft but noticeable carbonation , thick creamy mouthfeel just like chocolate milk .

the aroma is perfect , of a light sweetness mixed with toffee , malts , syrup and nutty flavors .  label is black and white with a woman 's head on the left side overlooking a countryside . bottle opens with a loud pop and some beer fog . a - pours a beautiful deep orange with a large head that eventually turns into nice lacing towards the end of each glass . this would look great for a fresh saison .  feels wonderful on the palate . excellent carbonation as well .

smalls are strong dried fig and currant along with crusty bread .  a : pours a clear straw yellow , nice 3 finger bone white head settles to a small cap , lacing everywhere and sticks to the glass like almost no other beer i have drank , save for duvel .  mouthfeel is silky and full with a dry finish that reminds me of a light red wine .
it 's interesting , strong citrus aromas from start to finish .  beautiful rich , brown pour with a tawny white head .  perfect carbonation .

a familiar smell i 've come to love from quads . complex . complex as hell . pretty good alcohol presence . outstanding beer none the less .  uncaged and uncorked , this poured with a nice sexy yellow-orange and a poofy , survivable foamy head .  thick and silky with a medium body . velvety smoothness characteristic of only a handful of the best belgians . clean finish keeps me wanting to drink more .

i pour this chilled sample into my pint glass and the hop aroma hits me immediately . but back to the appearance first . the aroma is dominated by hops , floral scents first then i pick up hiints of pine and some sour citrus notes too . i get a quick hint of sweetness coming through and then the hops take over .  this looks great . perfect amber color with a steady one inch head that stayed the whole time .  a : jet black , no head s : traditional russian imperial stout , dense , licorice , oxidation , great t : dense , true russian imperial stout , cloying , deep burnt caramel taste , great beer , tastes like it has been aged for several years d : very good m : excellent

s- there is a rich perfumed caramel malt flows even during the pour with a cream note and a dark malt hint adds depth to this rich aroma . t- the dry toasted malt has a faint caramel note with a soft bitter hint in the finish with a slight sweetness . d- this amazing aroma is wonderful but the taste just does n't follow through with the same richness and depth .  crystal brown `` loverly '' color . quite effervescent - copious amounts of sea-foam looking suds .  t/m : mouthfeel is perfect to me .

strong belgian scents , hops . this one really wafts . taste is sharp carbonation , almost foamy . nice beer , but for the price it 's not worth it .  the beautiful cascading effect that is experienced after pouring is a treat for anyone near the lucky drinker of this beer . i put a flashlight behind a glass of this in the dark and could see a very faint red/brown light .  medium body with a wonderful rich texture that is soothing in the mouth . just enough carbonation to keep things lively .

awesome aroma . pine and citrus , candied orange , grapefruit , resiny , fresh hops . for such a great aroma the taste is very dull . d - very strange combination . everything great about the aroma just disappears .  the beer poured into a chalice clear medium orange/amber with a tall and white frothy and spirited head that fell slowly and then lasted to lace the glass .  love the body on this one . on lighter side of moderate , but the oiliness from the hops makes it somewhat slick and the softest carbonation fills it our gloriously .

one of the best smelling beers i 've ever had . huge , gushing pineapple notes lead the charge , followed by some pine notes . some pale malt notes in the background .  it was a dark and stormy beer ... brew was dark and had a rocky light brown head attachec . left an amazing lace on the glass documenting every sip .  mouth is silky smooth with a full body a great carbonation , did n't go flat like alot of darker brews have .

brett funk t : very tannic . overall a very very good beer .  a : pours a bright glowing golden with a huge frothy bright white head that slowly faded into a thick rocky film that left patches of sticky lacing down the glass .  m : completely smooth and wonderful . d : very easy to drink .

wonderful rich coffee nose . cocoa , campfire and sweet cream/milk chocolate . outstanding .  pours with lots of frothy head a-top a deep reddish mahogany , crystal-clear body . great retention on the light tan head .  m - almost syrupy . i love the mouth feel .

an impressive looking porter . very appetizing appearance . robust and earthy with some smoke , dark bitter chocolate , and baking cocoa . deep caramelization and very roasty throughout with hints of blackstrap molasses and a moderate char . big , bold and very roasty . again robust and smoky with lots of char and heavily roasted , chocolate malts . a bit creamier and sweeter than the nose implies . raw cream and semisweet chocolate are present . black coffee and some mild leafy hops . not as boisterous as the nose lead me to believe it may be but also more balanced than expected .  good thick , 1/2 inch head with great retention and great lacing .  absolutely wonderful . drinkability : pretty decent for the high alcohol levels .

all kinds of yeasty scents going on , funky and horsey mixes with fruit . very nice . the flavor has the same components as the aroma , but i notice them in the opposite order . i think the flavor was a little bit of a letdown after how amazing and funky the aroma was , but i still liked my first fantome beer quite a bit . i know that this brewery is known for their spices , but i would prefer a little less of a spiced taste so that fantastic yeast profile could shine .  440ml- & gt ; young 's pint a ~ one of the finest looking uk beers i have ever seen .  a great , thick mouthfeel makes this beer very satisfying and drinkable .

this stuff smells incredible , the fresh coffee and sweet dark fruit work so well together . finishes with a lasting coffee flavor , very nice . mouthfeel is medium bodied and oily , but thin and fairly flat .  pours out a black as a moonless midnite black clour with blood red tints . a dark tan frothy head inch high head recedes to half an inch but stops there and leaves ample lacing . looks about perfect as a stout can appear .  this beer is incredibly silky smooth and boasts a clean , light carbonation . big on the bitters , but great taste and mouthfeel .

the smell is extremely inviting , lots of sweet milk chocolate .  a : deep copper color with compact , dense and full head , tiny bubbles , clear s : medium deep roasted , burnt malt nose with etoh presence , some oxidation t : nice beer , some hints of oak aging , good deep roasted/burnt malt with yeasty qualities , reminded me of an amped dubbel , slight amount of sourness in finish ( barrel aging or infection ?  split this among a few friends last night in celebration of the hockeytown boys winning lord stanley 's cup.poured a jet black with a thinner creamy dark tan colored head , aromas obviously had deep dark roast coffee tones mixed with dark fruit and a hint of bitter chocolate.mas what a silky smooth mouthfeel this is what make a very good beer a great beer no faults to its mouthfeel whatsoever.flavors are rich but not overly so , smooth dark coffee and dark chocolate like a mocha espresso with a hint of spiced rum in the finish.a fantastic brew to end a fantastic night .

aroma : huge fruits , detectable from a few feet away . huge , prominent hop notes - pine needles , grapefruit , some orange zest - and lightly roasted to mildly toasted malts - caramel , toffee , and even some chocolate - round things off . only the faintest hint lf alcohol as things warm . a very complex nose . taste : lots of dark malts - the typical roasted coffee/chocolate combo , the same roasted caramel note that was in the nose - and piney juniper berry notes . drinkability : felt this one after a while , and it is up there , but overall it 's a very complex , drinkable brew with a lot of really great flavors and aromas - highly recommended .  pours an absolutely gorgeous deep chestnut brown colour , with a huge and frothy head of pale creamy white foam .  absolutely fantastic mouthfeel , creamy and oily without being cloying .

smells wonderful , a sweet raspberry smell , mixed with the yeasty mustiness of a hefeweizen . nothing over powering , all the good smells of beer without any sourness .  a - big thick black brew with a perfectly creamy , thick , and tight head that lasts for the duration of the beer . solid tan sheets of beautiful lace .  mouthfeel is wonderful . creamy with smooth carbonation .

the smell is awesome . very complex without being overwhelming .  pours a sizable , 4-5cm head of medium sized bubbles , light tan in color . beer is dark red-amber in color , transparent , and with lots of carbonation . lacing is a sheet of bubbles that fades to a thick string over time .  mouthfeel is wonderful . dry as chocolate coyotes thirsty mouth in the chocolate atacama .

this beer has a remarkable scent . it smells like starbucks coffee .  dark black in color with garnet highlights . huge , cascading head of super-thick foam that does n't back down for several long minutes .  mouth is silky smooth .

the aroma is delightful ... huge scents of figs , raisins , cherries , citrus with a slight alcohol twinge if you linger the nose . slightly bitter and dry in the finish and so wonderfully kind on the pallet ... could think of no better way to finish off an evening .  poured black with a nice tan head that didnt last long .  has good slight citrus notes with a full hop oil and hoppy feel and body , a good finish mouthfeel- very very smooth , it has an extremely soft and smooth body that really helps it going down , the mouthfeel is a real strong point of this beer drinkability- a very good beer that i would definitely want to try few more times and see how it matches up with some other ipa s certainly worth another look .

s - the aroma of oranges , lightly roasted malt and belgian years make for a very inviting scent . t - the smell is telltale of what the beer will taste like .  dense opague black with a lovely one inch creamy mocha head . easily rivals any rogue stout in appearance .  the other reviews cover pretty much everything , but i have to add that this is possibly the creamiest beer to ever touch my lips . it was so wonderfully smooth i damn near shat my pants .

aroma is a very fragrant load of citrus hops .  poured out of a cork and cage bottle . really dark brown .  before i can say anything about the taste , the mouthfeel is perfect . thick and smooth , with light carbonation that just seems so right .

smell was exceptional - vanilla , wood , almonds , caramel ... very , very nice and remniscent of a cognac or similar nice sipping liquor ( w/o any strong alcohol smell ) .  pours jet black with a small tan head . one of the nicest looking heads i 've seen .  decadent creamy texture , very smooth despite the high carbonation .

aroma : amazing fruity head on pineapple and malt . totally out of style , but totally yummy . taste : complex and heavy pale malts , slightly sweet tropical fruit .  it pours a nice head and the color is pitch black . what i was suprized with was how easy this was to drink considering that this was a stout with a very high alcohol level .  m - this is what really sets this beer apart for me . incredibly creamy and thick mouth feel .

( s ) it smells great . a ton of light and citric fruits .  this is one beautiful looking beer . looks like crystal clear stained glass that has been liquified and topped with a creamy head .  mouthfeel : chewy , full bodied . low carbonation , which suited the beer nicely .
its nice , floral , bitter , sappy . nice .  black with a thick head built by a classic stout reverse cascade a tasty looking tan head .  the carbonation is medium and perfect . mouthfeel is great .
s : wonderful , joyous sultry oak scents .  a : a dark brown color with and of white head that sits two fingers high .  mouthfeel - smooth and graceful . this beer has great texture and flow .

this beer is one of the more complex beers i have ever smelled ! it takes awhile to discern specific aromas . mildly tart and funky . nice . o - very enjoyable beer . i had had this beer many years ago and did n't remember it being so amazing .  half a pour leaves a towering 4 finger pillow in my snifter . the beer is jet black , and lacing is excellent when the head finally dies down .  smooth and full mouthfeel .

smell : that great balsamic vinegar aroma was present , but with an extra spicy cinnamon in a quelquechose kind of way , with a touch of musk and just enough alcohol to make me think i was smelling an old bottle of perfume i found in some dusty attic .  absolutely awesome looking hefe .  absolutely perfect . drinkability is very high as well . even , balanced flavors with that great mouthfeel make for a nice combination .

aroma of honey and lavender . very complex and almost reminiscent of a west coast barley wine . aroma is dominated by pineapple with hints of peach , vanilla , and a little raspberry . definitely the fruitiest non-citrus aroma i 've ever smelled from an ipa . taste is just mild sweetness , then a huge clean bitterness , with a feeling of a bitter tea finish .  reviewed 7/12/2007 ( 550ml bottle ) : pours a dark park brown/black colored body , with a tannish colored head , huge and lasting .  4.0 m great syrupy sweet bigness , absolutely love the feel .

towards the end a thin slithering dark brown foam stretched around the glass until it quickly shredded its bubbly skin . s : strong bourbon , chocolate oak , and almond nut aromas . raisins steeped in ethanol . t : one of the most malt complex and spicy-sweet tasting imperial stouts i have tried . licorice and molasses with a stinging hops like finish . rum and raspberries .  this one pours a dark brown , coke-like , with a 3/4 '' head , leaving big lacing all the way .  mouth is very nice , damn perfect .

s - smells fantastic - sweet malt , dark fruit ( raisin , plum ) , spice ( perhaps cinnamon ? somewhat disappointing following the aroma . nonetheless , it is enjoyable and worth a try .  pours a & gt ; 2cm head of cream-colored foam made up of fairly small bubbles . this gives the head a very dense , pillowy appeal to it . head descends gradually , but never fading completely ( remains a 0.5cm cap on the body ) leaving enormous amounts of lacing .  the mouthfeel is superb : sticky and chewy but also very creamy , with fluffy carbonation .

smell is just exceptional . a sweet juicy hop aroma fills the air above the glass .  a : minimal 3cm head off the pour with moderate legs and lasting lacing .  very smooth , almost velvety mouthfeel . excellent brew , but the 8.4 oz bottle is entirely too small .

smells wonderfully of grapefruit , hemp and pine notes with some herbal and alcohol notes .  pours a really thick head , nothing frothy but thick and luscious . a golden amber red body , thick with nice color .  i love it .

smell is fantastic , a touch of booze mixed in with sweet , sweet roasted chocolate . good beer . right now the components are there for a top-notch brew , but they 're oddly disjointed & vying for attention rather than complementing one another .  this is one beautiful looking beer . it is a slow pour , due to the vast amounts of light tan head that is created .  great smooth mouthfeel..creamy .

s - as i mentioned this beer is pretty funky . great hay and corn husk aroma along with the traditional funky dusty horse blanket . nice grassy hops finish this beer off . t & m - wow what an amazingly delicious brew .  appearance is an inviting cloudy golden yellow with an outstanding pillow head and great lacing .  m : eminently smooth with a light but firm body and some fine , velvety carbonation . perfect for the style .

s - nice aroma , deep and complex . smells of darkly roasted malts with espresso coffee , chocolate and molasses .  what a gorgeous beer ! dark coppery brown . white , light , fluffy head with clingy bubbles .  the mouthfeel is astounding . with all the charged up carbonation , i was expecting a soda like fizzy mouthfeel , but i am pleased at the silky smooth , well rounded and succulent body of this ale .

very unique aroma for an amber . extremely sessionable and unique ale but the nose leads you to believe it may be more complex than it ends up being .  it pours an inky black color impenetrable to light with a very thick creamy and slightly frothy head that retains like crazy and billows against the glass . lots of lacing evident to boot . the head is a nice chocolate brown color .  the body of this beer was exceptional , thick , clean , and enjoyable .

beautiful nose t - great complex flavor comprising smoked meats , dark fruits and apples and various barrels .  pours a swirly dark brown , turning into pitch black with a huge two finger head .  an exquisite mouthfeel for a baltic porter .

smells fantastic ! can detect slight caramel and alcohol in the background . delicious . tastes a little hot right now though , slightly decreasing its drinkability .  head retained the entire time , and left behind a massive amount of brown lacing , to the point that i wondered if i could ever get the glass clean again . awesome looking beer , to say the least .  nice , full , creamy mouthfeel , as good as it gets .

very pleasant smelling beer . very fruity with citrus and maybe a pear or apricot smell to it as well .  poured a hazy orange amber colour with a thick head that had very good retention . this was a beautiful beer with tons of visual character .  mouthfeel : super thick , creamy , sticky with medium-low carbonation overall : great smell , but the pure , burning ethanol is too much present for me in the taste .

the flavor is like the aroma with a tad bit too much bitterness but still very good . the palate is smooth but not as thick as i had wanted it to be .  first off , this brew is a picture perfect pour for a german pilsner . ultra clear and golden body , with a brilliant white head . retention lasts for a few minutes and diminishes into clumpy lacing .  this is definitely the best oatmeal i 've had . the mouthfeel is so luscious it 's insane . sweet and slighty bitter roasted malts mix with coffee , chocoloate , oats , smoke ; all in a sublime smoothness . you have to try to find the alcohol , but it 's there , warming the palate ever so slightly . on tap this was the smoothest beer i think i 've ever had .

absolutely fantastic ! taste : very mild in the taste , but with a strong , strong oatmeal component - stronger than many oatmeal stouts . every other `` stout '' aspect is pretty subdued : there 's milk chocolate chips , some simple sweetness , a regular malty note , and a little bit of coffee , but the coffee definitely is n't too prominent .  a : the beer pours a rich dark color with a huge foamy caramel/parchment colored head .  mouthfeel : extremely smooth and crisp .

very complex . t : sh & # 333 ; ch & # 363 ; tinge up front . d : unique combination of elements feels like a mash-up between a farmhouse ale and a strong ale . will try again .  golden in hue w/ a slight haze , topped by a formidabily thick , creamy , rocky persistant head that leaves lace . it 's reminescent of a belgian strong golden in appearance .  mouthfeel is just superb . satisfying .

great aroma ; have n't smelled many others like it . d : pretty good for drinkability , but not terribly high abv .  a : poured a deep dark brown with a thick creamy head , but that was the highlight of this beer .  m = heavy , heavy body , luscious creamy feel , great mouthcoating . one of the best mouthfeels i 've ever experienced in a beer .

strong roasted pecan smell with coffee tones . overall malty and enjoyable . mouthfeel : pretty heavy for a porter but very drinkable even in the heat .  it 's a well carbonated deep red-amber in color and topped by an ever-lasting light khaki head . lace covers the glass in sheets of foam that looks like fluffy , sticky , swiss cheese .  coats the tongue just right , insulating it from the alcohol .

nose is still incredible - just exploding with tart fruit ( currants but could easily be mistaken for raspberry ) and some hints of his wheat origin . this is an excellent summer beer and would be great with spicy food .  pours like a yeti , oil black , black on black no light thru this baby with a beautiful coco colored head that laces well man this brew looks goood .  wonderful mouthfeel .

taste is a yet another surprise , this beer is full of layers the smell is a surprise based on appearance and the taste is another surprise based on smell . hop explosion with a rush of pineapple up front with a bitter slightly funky finish .  a : a very smooth looking brownish red hue . perfect 2 finger head with nice lacing . and nice tight foam .  medium bodied and oily . simply exceptional .

s - wow ! really surprised here . light chocolate notes , roasted malt , toasted sweet whole wheat bread .  appearance : spitfire has it all - a gorgeous red-amber colour and a huge whipped creamy head , over an inch upon pour and lasting throughout the session .  mouthfeel is great with a very filling quality about it .

smells : sweet but spicy smells protrude though a spectacular wave of citrus and floral hop characteristics .  a- straw colored with a thick white head that faded but left a thin layer of white on the top . great lacing .  incredibly smooth and goes down easy .

oh , such a nose - just luscious with huge quantities of the very finest american hops . it genuinely is an absolutely classic american ipa nose . to my mind , you ca n't get better than this . a sharp , but extremely well balanced ipa .  pours with a plethora of off-white , fluffy head . some retention , but erdinger glass seems to continually generate head . nice lacing . awesome !  outstanding mouthfeel ! d - drinks like a champ for a ris at almost 10 % abv !

the complexity is through the roof , the balance is perfect . and it just smells so quality . coffee and roasted nuts as well as chocolate , caramel , and molasses , still with decent hop bitterness . nice ! i really enjoyed drinking this , and i really wish we could get it locally .  looks like big red in a glass .  m : the feel is super creamy which makes it near full bodied . this is the biggest difference between this bottled version and the on-tap version i had last year . the mouthfeel was a huge step up .

the beer was cloudy through the light and had an amazing floral aroma . it was like nothing i have ever had before . they must have just loaded in the aroma hops in this one . i was very excited to take a first sip . the floral aroma helped , but it was n't a pleasent bitter .  for a large-scale macrobrewery known for a rather unremarkable mainstream beer , this one 's a terrific offering . appearance is excellent , almost shimmering and golden in the glass , with a haziness reminiscent of unibroue 's `` blanche de chambly '' . large , active , bubbly head , with some very exciting lacing . overall , a wonderful beer to look at .  mouthfeel was very thick and rich . i almost wanted to chew it .

awesome aroma . pours a cloudy dark orange color , some nice head with decent retention . very smooth- from the smell , i was actually expecting a more pronounced hop flavor here , but regardless , this is an excellent ipa . mouthfeel- appropriate carbonation , buttery , clean . drinkability- i could drink this one all day .  black as tar . thick heavy head that leaves tracks .  m - very rich and full , reminds me of double bastard . dry with a nice low carbonation d - very well rounded , a little dry but bery easy to drink overall a great beer .

the nose is unbelievable ! the best i have ever smelt .  the pour was a dark mahogany with a three finger head that very slowly dissapated and left a thick foam on top of the beer throughout the drink .  the mouthfeel on this is quite decadent and smooth with a wonderful lingering finish .

this beer has an absolutely intoxicating aroma . just a spectacular aroma . the flavors in this beer do n't quite live up to the aroma , but they are still quite tasty . notes of honey mixes with nice malt notes and the finish has notes of higher alcohols that somehow do n't reach harsh , but ultimately provide some sharp balancing notes to the other flavors .  hazy gold with an enormous amount of white foam that chunks and laces everywhere that it touches .  velvety and soft-spoken , yet deeply sexy . more to the traditional side .

it is true to the style and smelled fantastic . it was called flowers and damnit it smelled like flowers ! overall it is worth getting if you can find one , very unique .  a - a taller-than-normal pour reveals the beer to be a clear dark brown color but in the glass it 's as black as night . the head foams up right away to a dense tan froth with great retention and dense , thick lacing on the glass . d - huge waves of lace and foam til the last sip , this extra stout looks perfect , tastes good , and feels fine which really makes it one easy drinking extra stout .  very smooth . mouthfeel is full and round .

it smells very good . effing amazing to be honest .  2005 , bottle # 227 out of 500 pours deep rich mahogany with a dense coating of tiny ( clearly bottle conditioned ) bubbles . incredible lace coats the sides .  m. perfect for style in all aspects .

a- choklat imperial stout pours jet black , no highlights with a small dark brown head . s- the aroma is the highlight of this beer i think . it smells unlike any other beer i 've ever had . the first thing i noticed was the huge chocolate presence in the aroma . but its not like a chocolate malt smell , it just smells like a candy bar or freshly baked chocolate dessert . there is a mild nuttiness in the aroma and maybe a little bit of hops hidden somewhere .  appearance : poured with an amazing white frothy foamy head that stood 1inch over the rim of the glass that dissipated very slowly leaving a beautiful lacing all down my glass . the beer is slightly cloudy yellowish gold .  super smooth and creamy body that glides down your throat like butter . so smooth and delicious that i had finished 3 pints in less than a half hour .

the aroma was amazing . smells like a perfect roast of coffee . also lemon zest and coffee bean aromas . overall , this beer is awesome . i really enjoyed this beer and i plan on buying more of it , if i can still find it .  pours a lovely mahogany -crystal clear and brown-red with a slight fluffy khaki head .  the mouthfeel was awesome . very heavy and smooth feel .

smell- glorious . if you took all the best smells in the world and combined them , this is what you would get . fruity and peppery , along with a little hoppiness . malty , but it 's the mix of fruit and peppers that i really notice . drinkability- excellent !  a - a deep golden ale with good clarity and a thick creamy head . loads of lacing .  the beer looks thick and chewy , but the texture is perfect for a brown ale .

amazing . even though the hops are not afraid to show themselves in the flavor , this definitely works as an english barleywine , as the malts stay at the forefront . feels resiny and creamy in the mouth without being overly thick .  a - very full , dark brown . surprisingly translucent when held up to light .  body is perfect for the style , rich and semi-thick with restrained carbonation .

aromas primarily of fried-bananas and other tropical fruits that yield a wonderfully intense and expansive bouquet . pretty much perfect . flavors include an overall oaky mixture of the previously-mentioned bananas , cabernet sav ( or franc ; too miniscule to presently and properly determine ) , and even a bit of bourbon and pumpernickle .  beautiful 3 finger tan to almost brown head rests on top of a black body . this is the christina ricci of porters .  carbonation is perfect , mouthfeel is perfect .

an incredible earthy , woodsy pine aroma brings me into the glass . candy like or cake batter . i have n't smelled a beer this good in a long time . with flavors to match the aroma , with scotch , carmel flavors as well . re-review 2008-05-11 : no pine aroma , more like wet wood .  ruby color with a fantastic head thats lasts the duration of the beer .  wonderful body .

smell : wow ! bright grapefruit & a smell of pure freshness , like walking through the woods after a light rain . it 's not the complexity of the notes in the aroma or whatever , but the overall vivacity & `` nosefeel '' that makes this so awesome . bitter & citric in the taste , piny , woody . bitter almost to the point of satiation , but inviting .  poured from a 12oz bottle into a pint glass a : pours a dark brown , almost porter colored darkness , with a thick 3 finger+ head . there was a strong amount of lacing throughout and the head stuck around .  palate is sticky and smooth . wondrous ...

the aromas in the beer are very sublime and enticing . the esters forge a fruity peach scent . this is one of the best smelling beers i have had .  very nice retention and great thick sticky lacing . excellent appearance .  chewy , and creamy , a perfect mild carbonation level for this style.. a lil warmth on the finish just to let you know , as chris rock would say `` slow down !

what it does do is offer a wonderful aroma . it smells like christmas inside that bottle .  pours out of the dark clad bottle pure black with just a few hints of ruby around the edges . the rocky tan head lasts forever and leaves a lot of lace patches behind .  excellent mouthfeel .

a wonderful cinnamon and allspice smell . it reminds me of one of the candles the wife burns in the head .  a massive , fake looking off white head leaves an awesome lace .  m - carbonation cleans the palate nicely , the tartness and funk does n't linger long . the carbonation is just spot on , love it .

aroma is wonderful , bakers chocolate , roasted malts , pretty darn strong , semi-sweet , deep , dark , burnt cookies or brownies , milk chocolate , chocolate milk , all coming across with a super nice dryness . one hell of an excellent porter .  bottle : poured a pitch-black color stout with a big foamy dark brown head with great retention and lacing .  creamy , smooth mouthfeel .

smell : was outstanding , one of the best smelling beers i have encountered : great caramel , honey , malt ... with hops in the distance .  poured into a snifter a : very dark pour which gives a huge head , coffee colored . fantastic sticky lacing all over the place s : roasted malts dominate the nose , but there is some coffee present too .  although it has a coating , luscious feel , it is not thick or syrupy .

the aroma is of a beautiful fresh hop . nice floral hop aroma with tropical fruit .  looks beautiful in a trappist glass . after the bubbles settle , it looks like chocolate milk with reddish edges .  truly velvety on the tongue . the mouthfeel is second to none , it 's that good . this is a very good stout .
beautiful fruity citrus orange hop aroma !  absolutely stunning upon pouring .  very smooth and full mouthfeel .

s - wow . dark fruitiness up front backed up with some sweet caramel/toffee with a touch of spice . normally if i like the smell i like the taste even better but theres just something hypnotising in that smell . still , it 's great and almost like liquid rum and raisin cake . good on the odd occasion .  a : this brew presents a perfect appearance , with a massive , rocky head , great retention , crystal clarity , and a light copper tint .  the richness and weight is perfect for me .

a lovely hyperactive citrus aroma greets my nose , with tangerine , grapefruit , and bergamot predominating . exceptional aroma for me , if only due to the affective evocations it elicits .  appearance is a clear orange to amber hue , head is a huge mass of effervescent foam that mostly sustains , great lacing all over smell is moderate caramel and toasted malts intermixed with fruits , toffee , and light sugar sweetness taste is mostly toast and roast malts , the toffee comes in midway as does slight caramel and bittering hops , finishes dry and malty with a hint of alcohol mouthfeel is light-to-medium bodied , thin and watery texture , mild carbonation drinkability is high , this is an amazing beer and what i would hold to be an exemplar of the esb style , alcohol is well-masked and this is well in the the session range , big props to the guys from the craft beer radio podcast for hyping this beer !  massive body , and silky smooth . fruity , creamy , wine-y , and then comes a stiff roast/coffee crack of the whip .

really spectacular aroma that calms my annoyance at losing so much beer . it comes together beautifully . delicious taste that just barely fails to live up to the aroma .  appearance : dark copper brown , great clarity , thick tannish creamy head on hard pour , some lacing aroma : upfront banana-like fruitiness , big hit of caramelly malt , some molasses , no hops , touch of alcohol flavor : mellow sweetness initially with a rich melanoidin roundness to the palate , toasty caramel sweet smoothness balances out with just enough hop bitterness in the semi-sweet finish , sumptuously tasty mouthfeel : medium-full bodied but not syrupy , gentle carbonation and a tantalizing alcohol warmth without any burning sensation overall impression : this is a supremely well-crafted beer , one of the hallmarks of the style .  coffee laden roastiness fights off beany vanilla sweetness and those accurate flavors remain held tightly together thanks to a round , well carbonated , cleansing malty full body .

s - smooth bourbon , with loads of vanilla and oak . t - malty and sweet , with just a little too much bourbon for my tastes . m - very nice on the tongue , with just the right amount of carbonation ( after it was all released on opening ) . d - it 's a great , well put together , complex beer , but it almost seems futile to rate the drinkability of such a rare beer .  very deep amber and clear . it was poured with a dense head that has n't budged in 10 minutes .  mouthfeel is exceptional and there is nothing objectionable here .

so vibrant and clear . the coffee is right up there as well . nothing short of an amazing nose . you even get a bit of the vanilla . this must be some really good coffee . d : really surprised by this one .  head is huge , retention is amazing and lacing is all over the place .  '' the mouthfeel was silky , the body full and the carbonation perfectly soft . enjoyable , but it 's really an american stout contrary to the label at the bar .

aroma - dark chocolate dominates the nose . overall - it smells much better than it tastes .  poured from a bottle into a dogfish snifter a- pours a perfectly transparent shade of yellow/orange with a big two finger white head that 's very puffy . looks perfect s- citrus hops with a big of a bite to them ... .lovely t- getting a lot of citrus , but it almost tastes like dishwater ... no real bite to the hops at all .  it was medium bodied and the carbonation was perfect . it was very enjoyable to just hold it in the mouth .

all supported by a lovely smell of pale malt . superb nose . t : : orange peel and lemon are huge in the foretongue .  huge 3 finger head with lines , legs and lace galore .  carbonation is spot on and really helps lighten the mouthfeel .

huge peppery nose with good hop presence and malty sweetness , one of the most phenomenal smelling brews i 've encounted .  appearance- pours a 1 finger head that has awesome retention . head stays the entire time and remains a dark off-white color . the beer has a deep brown color with no visible clarity . ties many other brews in the best appearance contest !  simpler flavor and wonderful mouthfeel enhance the drinkability ; but it is slightly boring .

the nose is up there with the best . a surplus of those juicy little green cones burst into the aroma with major pine and the bitterest of fresh grapefruit and orange . well balanced and i mean that this is how we hopheads like our double ipa 's , lots of hops with a good dose of caramel malt , but the hops dominate the character of the taste 75/25 . a hop bomb but nicely crafted and easily appreciated , seek this out .  appearance is exceptional due to the huge creamy , rocky , tan head .  mouthfeel was outstanding . the lush , creamy and full body was absolutely amazing .

where was this aroma when i had this on draft ? tons of vanilla , toasted coconut and bourbon notes meld with lightly roasted/sweet caramel malt notes of maple . t-lusciously sweet maple , bourbon , vanilla and oak are strong up front . touch of wood astringency and lightly spicy hop notes help balance the sweetness out . founders strikes again with another masterful barrel aged brew , this brewery simply knows how to barrel age beer ... .period ! i thought it a dud on draft ( or maybe it was just me that day ) but out of the bottle ... shazaam !  great looking beer .  just phenomenally satiny . in the mouth : satin , silk , creamy , smoothness embodied in liquid .

what a wonderfully smelling beer . mandarin oranges , cloves , bananas , peaches , tropical fruit , citrusy hops , this beer has everything ! the alcohol is noticeable as it warms up ( and as i get slightly buzzed ) .  unibroue trois pistoles pours a bright deep red brown , with a nice creamy light brown head that lingers .  body and carbonation are perfect for the style .

nose left no doubt as to the presence of peaches from nearby heller 's orchard , just down river . finish had a great tartness that was reminiscent of lindemann 's . yummy .  pours dark brown with ruby highlights . tan sea-foam head settles to a surprisingly thick film . lacings completely coat the glass , and absolutely refuse to slide down the glass . impressive .  m : quite thick and mouth-filling for an ipa , with enough smooth carbonation to keep things fairly clean . just lovely .

the smell was terrific , strong alcohol hints but definitely a lot of chocolate in there too .  poured amber colour with creamy white head which retains well and has good lacing .  the mouthfeel is full , warming and fabulous . flavor is full with lots of yummy esters holding hands with the sweetness and the fininsh is where i get the coriander .

aroma positively bursts with tropical fruit : pineapple , mango , papaya , sugarcane , apricot . it 's a hophead 's delight , and i am reveling in it . the flavor announces that the hops have taken over , and my tastebuds welcome the coming apocalypse . big , juicy hop cones spray sap and resin across the palate , palpable in their greenery but not overwhelmingly bitter . the fruitiness is not lost either , as it accentuates a slick backdrop of caramel & toffee malts . this may well be one of my new favorite double ipa 's .  a - beautiful beer . big bubbly head , slightly opaque yellow body with beautiful streams of bubbles rising rising throughout , nice textured lacing .  its thick and syrupy and full of body and character . the alcohol warmth is soothing as it makes its way to the back of the tongue , leaving a sweet resin .

the cascades really linger on in the nose - wonderful aroma without the lingering bitterness of some beers . exceptionally fine beer - has become a staple in my fridge .  a - huge true blonde foam with tons of lace and excellent retention .  the body is perfect . honestly .

smell : fresh hazelnuts , almonds , brazils , and chestnuts are the first thing i notice . an extremely harmonious nose ; everything is in its place , and every individual aroma compliments the others perfectly . taste : mind-bendingly subtle and complex .  well , it is black alright . even when i hold it to the light , like you are not supposed to , it is still black . very good for a moderately priced imperial stout . be it the over the top averys or the dominating stone and rogue .  m : lovely viscous feel . perfect .

awesome . taste- greeted with the normal citrusd peel , but more emphasis on grapfruit zest and some malts .  the brew pours an amber hue , slightly hazy , and is capped with a small wispy off-white head .  medium/full body with an extremely creamy texture , assisted by the fine carbonation from the bottle conditioning .

complex aromas make it very unique . is this a red beer or a light nut brown ?  a- pours a hazy orange color- its a great color . but there 's not really any head at all to this beer .  m : the carbonation is so perfectly tied to the spicyness making the mouthfeel very special . amazing mouthfeel .

pours a hazy golden color with maybe the best aroma of any beer i have had wild tart raspberries waffle batter , man it is right on with the aromas how did they do that ?  pours a cloudy tea and copper with sunshiney yellow highlights . the head is nice and thick , but very fleeting , gone before you can take a sip .  the mouthfeel is incredibly smooth and coating , leading to an extended finish that eventually coaxes out some espresso and a final touch of nuttiness .

smell is very nicely aged , deep aromas of molasses , dark fruit , and anise , with a boozy warmth if you look for it . amazingly complex , it 's right up there with the best . taste is very strong , sweet malt at first , then a hit of boozy flavors that i can only compare to jagermeister .  a- this one pours out a dark brown colored body with a quarter finger of beige head . the head vanishes rather quickly , and leaves behind random small spots of lacing .  mouthfeel is oh-so smooth , and drinkability is superb .

very nutty aroma with some surprising chocolate smells . t : caramel malts with some surfacing hops that balance the sweetness nicely . o : very good , i only had a single 19 oz .  a - black . hardly any head or lacing and not transparent in the slightest sense .  thick and chewy in the mouth - one can definitely understand the allusions to barley wines in previous reviews . hops tingle as you swallow . is it an old ale ? compared to other old ales that i have seen reviewed , i 'm tempted to say old ale ... but a marvelous cold weather beer in any event .

smell - strong smell of lemon zest and citrus . coriander , banana , and orange as well.. taste - strong flavor of coriander and orange .  a bright and clear copper and topped with a rather quickly disappearing bone white head .  the mouthfeel was the best part of this beer , very creamy .

s - delicious bready , malty aromas .  a : pours a dark mahogany with sightly less than one finger of head which quickly dissipates .  mouthfeel - this beer i have to say is one of the most pleasant on the mouth , perfect carbonation , little foam action , and little breakthrough of warmth from the alcohol .

5.0 s : awesome nose ! coffee is strongest , then roasted barley , oats , and bittersweet chocolate . i not sure whether this is a coffee stout or not , but it sure as hell seems like it since the coffee is so strong . 4.0 t : taste is also pretty damn good .  painted bomber featuring a flying pig , kinda pink floydish lol . deep dark mahogany with copper edges . not much for foam or lace with a ring surrounding thin wisps . the malts are pretty assertive upfront with a flash of dryness that becomes enveloped in in a woody smoke . i would have liked more smoke , like some of the bamburgs have , but there is enough to keep me interested and certainly enough to pair with pulled pork .  the feel is smooth , full , creamy and rich ( without being overly thick ) . nice texture , coating .

smell : the best aroma from a beer i 've ever experienced . still , there is a hint of alcohol and malt but very unorthodox for a beer .  poured into a snifter revealing modest airy head and an opaque brown body , not much lacing here .  mouthfeel - smooth , silky , lower carbonation ... in a word ... perfect . drinkability - so smooth and tasty , they would go down easy .

smell has that strong nice balance of rich malts and floral hops . a nice enjoyable hearty ale .  a : pours a 1 finger frothy , white head with decent retention . beer is a deep , clear orange . lacing is sparse and with little stick .  m- super creamy and smooth . the carbonation level is perfect . a nice clean and crisp aftertaste .
smells luscious and pineappley with a hint of coconut .  very minimal head . pretty average looking .  mouthfeel is fantastic , super thick and syrupy , perfect for the style .

s : the first think i can think of when i smell this beer is chocolate covered coffee beans . it is one of the best smelling beers to me .  pours a hazy pale gold , with a moderate but very dense foamy head .  thick smooth mouthfeel , very silky .

s : a great aroma of belgian yeast and caramel maltiness . t : alcoholic belgian banana and caramel malts create the taste but sweet and bittered perfectly . a great beer to enjoy , make sure it warms for the perfect aroma and flavor .  pale golden color-touch of haze . great aroma-really `` catty '' as the brits like to call it . grassy , straw-like . a very drinkable beer-one of the better offerings from magic hat in my opinion .  stellar mouthfeel .

the aroma is quite complex and very appealing- grass , a bit of pine and citrus , some hard to identify floral and spice notes , yum yum yum . grass , lemon , and ... watermelon ( ?  pours almost a chestnut colored brown but not the typical imperial stout ( or regular santa 's little helper for that matter ) used motor oil black - a bit lighter . 1/2 '' head quickly dissipates ; little in the way of lacing . maybe it 's because i 'm a sucker for a bourbon bomb but i 'm finding it pretty damn tasty .  m - great mouthfeel on this one , very light and easy drinking , alcohol is well hidden .

aroma is delightful -- floral , hoppy , with notes of sweet grass and rum .  a decent american wheat beer .  very soft carbonation that makes it feel creamy and silky smooth one of , if not , the thickest beers i 've had . love it .

aroma is sweet and spicy , with floral notes and definate coriander and also brown sugar and molasses . very complex nose . first sip reveals a silky smooth body with almost non-existent carbonation . no hint of the abv anywhere , and the beer is extremely drinkable and goes down easily .  a - pours a dark copper amber with a small , bubbling white head .  thanks to ba greggy for this one . the beer is very thick and smooth . not overpowering but just the right feel . the only thing that i have a problem with is the fact that this beer is so thick and rich , there is no way i would be able to drink more than 2 of these in one sitting .

some of the freshest hops i have ever smelled in a commercial brew ... quite reminiscent of a batch of homebrew deliciousness . assertive floral hops with hints of pineapple sweetness / tartness given possibly by the malt . very clean finish . overall : truly amazed at the smell on this one .  golden straw color with a thin , white head that fades quickly .  thick and chewy with all the perfect elements . the real stand out for me was the mouthfeel .

thought it would be too sweet from the smell , but the malt and hops definetly bittered the vanilla bean aroma .  a - pours dark brown with a tan head that dissipates quickly . a bit underwhelming , visually .  supremely smooth . it 's just silky smooth across the tongue , the carbonation working to prevent it from becoming syrupy .

has an absolutely wonderful fruity smell ... . some nice head on the pour ... .  a : really dark brown with a little bit of reddish tone . the tan head disapears quickly leaving a patchy , floating foam .  insanely smooth , creamy , and slick body with light-medium carbonation .

but , geeeez , what a wonderful aroma lurks underneath the mess . tangerine and grapefruit along with rock candy and toffee . pears and apples , raisinbread , and a meadow of wildflowers add to the divine nose . mouthfeel lacks carbonation ( it must be on top ) , but is medium bodied and has a unique fruity apple hops bite . taste is well balanced and very complex . much of the aroma is reflected in the taste , so i will simply say that this is one unique pale ale .  a : poured bright orange with a filmy head and an unusual amount of sediment . odd brightness which almost came through like grapefruit juice .  amazing balance in this beer . mouthfeel is full , and this is very drinkable .

s - the smell is delicious . malt , biscuits , dark fruit like plums and raisins , and alcohol . this is clearly more of a british barley wine than american .  the head is a dirty irregular film .  mouthfeel is awesome . full , luscious , and smooth .

smell is amazing ! wheaty graininess , bready , malty , with a hint of coriander spice , and some lactic tartness . it smells like a wit should .  cheers to brad for brewing a style that is seldom seen in the states . straw color with a mild cloudiness . very short-lived head with no lacing .  m - refreshingly tingly , with a slow and steady rise in volume , ultimately becoming quite creamy and dense . very appealing .

inviting . the taste is more of that berry type with hints of wheat malts , all sorts of berry offerings and a cereal crispy palate .  a : caramel color with large head that disappears quickly .  m. thick and heavy , strong and chewy , with plenty of carbonation .

s : compared to elder this is much less piney , however has a much stronger fruity/citrus aroma . strong notes of various citrus , pineapple , and mango . strong fresh hop smell like no other . t : not quite as mind blowing as the aroma . flavor includes strong tropical fruit and candy notes .  the beer is dark brown with a very thin beige layer of foam .  light-medium in body .

thanks to the crew at drakes for makin a hoppy beer i could enjoy and drive home after 4 of them . lots of citra hops in the aroma which sets you up for an ipa but surprise this great tastin beer is under 4 % really great session beer , if you like west coast ipa's try this one , just dont expect finishing kick .  the beer pours a golden color with a thin white lace head .  m- full bodied with medium carbonation . thick and almost chewy in the mouth .

s : smells delicious ! funky , belgian yeast and and cloves with hints of citrus , fresh fruits and sweetness .  the beer poured a dark brown , almost black , forming a very thin mocha head that quickly faded .  mouthfeel is great .
this beer smells so good i 'm considering replacing my current cologne selection .  pours dark brown with a slight tan head .  m - perfection , i love the way this feels .

right off the bat the smell gets you.. smells just like a pumpkin pie and that can be great for some people . its a perfect beer for when the weather is starting to turn cold as this beer will warm you right up.this beer really hit home for me , reminds me off good times and good company .  pours to a brilliantly clear dark-amber with garnet highlights , forming an average-sized frothy light-beige head with poor retention and minimal lacing .  nice , thick and just the right level of carbonation in my book .

copper to gold ... lots of light flickering through and a rocky 3/4 '' bright white head ... aroma is awesome ... truly great . some spicy cinnamon and grassy hops ... herbaceous in a very cool herbaceous way with a a hint of basil and nosefull of dill . peppery and delicious . awesome .  pours an amber clear color with nice initial size head . head dissapates quickly to a bubbly ring and leaves mild thin lacing .  feel is thick and creamy , with a light carbonation of fine bubbles that help give it a velvety character to it . this is a damn fine beer .

smells absolutely wonderful . very sweet but not overly malty or boozy . overall , an amazingly good dipa , and at a great price - i believe i paid $ 7.99 for the bomber at binny 's .  poured into a tulip glass . a - pours a thick midnight black with a small tan head . the head dissipated fairly quickly and there is no lacing . a little light gets through around the edges showing dark brown tint .  tight but low carbonation with a light to medium body . the mouthfeel is perfect ! very elegant flavors and seems to have great balance with the flavors .

smells like dark chocolate melted in a rich , red wine . unique aroma , appetizing . starts off with a bit of moldy age that morphs into coffeeground bitterness . underlying port character and molasses sweetness offers perfect balance .  this beer was served in a pint glass at the brew pub with a slice of orange . it has a light golden color with a nice head that is well retained . the appearance is n't that cloudy for a wheat beer , but okay for many of the american wheats i 've had in the past .  mf : silky and smooth but without compromising its thickness , which is needed as a foundation for the abundance of flavour . not too wet or dry , but the perfect balance between . not a unique mouthfeel , but an expressive suitable one .

this had a very amazing chocolate and malty smell that only got better as the bottle got lower .  this is a full flavor beer and should n't be compared to the weak tasting beers of the us . it is not for the average person because of its unique taste . i have heard of the younger crowd mixing it with lemonade..yuck !  mouthfeel - full-bodied , velvety smooth , and creamy with a semi-dry finish and moderate carbonation .

aroma is delectable and amazing . i get pine resin , citrus , and pineapple .  this is advertised as a `` pre-prohibition '' pilsner . yellow and slightly hazy with a white head .  very creamy , highly carbonated mouthfeel .

smell is a big whiff of dunkel bananas and bubble gum . not to sweet and the banana taste practically punches you in the nose . mouthfeel is watery .  appearance : pours into glass a dark full brown color with a good sized tan that dissipated fairly quickly , not much in the way of lacing was left behind on the glass , smell : sour smell of fruits with a sweet/rich carmal-coco tosty smell , plesent aroma , taste : taste has some complex depth , slightly nutty , sour fruit taste balanced out with an engaging coca/malty flavor .  m - perfect mouthfeel .

rather strong and `` fuzzy '' , that same fuzzy scent you get if you were to put you nose directly on a fresh peach and sniff . an interesting nose for sure . i liked it . flavors of apricot and citrus fruits , peaches , light bready malts and a kiss of hops melded together to form a really nice , above all refreshing beer .  a - pours between an amber and a brown with an orange hue . little to no head at all .  huge taste and mouthfeel . lots of bitter hot chocolate taste and viscous almost chewy feel to it .

although it smells amazing , fresh , and hoppy , there is little to no initial flavor ... wait for the lingering hoppy finish ! appearance : clear , golden , light foamy head smell : incredible . piney , earthy , hops .  ' the brew was a walnut brown with a thin cream colored head atop it . little retention or lacing .  mouthfeel is exceptional . big , small foam mouth , which smooths down , edgy all the way -- but never sharp .

it looked and smelled incredible . the taste went off the rails , tho .  clear copper with thin head and little lacing .  ( m ) - really smooth and creamy . the carbonation has subdued to a really nice level that balances it out to a totally silky beverage .
