one word , hops . taste.. very hoppy with flowery notes as well as a nice malt flavor .  this beer had a smooth pour and a good head , but not a long lasting head .  it is the mouthfeel ! nice and viscous without being too soupy . this enhances the creamy taste and makes it really feel like a true winter ale .

s - very complex ! grape , sherry and port wine-type aromas are dominant , with hints of raisin , nuts and esters . alcohol is apparent , too . very sweet altogether . m/d - hardly any carbonation . i look forward to trying another one a year from now !  a - fairly clear medium brown , not much head at all . nada on the lace .  carbonation is comfortable and helps the round mouthfeel to build an authentically belgian mouthfeel .

appearance - nice ochre-amber smell - incredible tropical fruit and hop . better than pliny the elder . tremendous . mouthfeel - medium body . a wonderful beer .  comes in a 1l growler combo-bottle - has a swing-top cap , and a crown cap . interesting bottle . pours an orangey-gold , slightly hazy , with an orangey-tan head .  mouthfeel is perfect , goose island is the best of the best in this regard .

the nose is pure amarillo hops .  a - half finger of white head . very cloudy . sort of a blonde/golden colour . considering it 's been snowing nonstop this was n't exactly the beer for the weather but a very drinkable beer that was no problem to get through and made me want another .  first sip reveals light carbonation that rolls across my tongue and a creamy , silky textured brew .

sour citrus goodness blends with balsa wood and hop pine to create perfect austerity . the sour nose does n't really translate - i hate t say it but i 'm getting some andre cold duck here !  just typed up a full review but due to the poor servers on this site , when i entered it it timed out . will say this imo , is a special beer .  mouthfeel is the star of this show -- thick , rich , round , full , all very slurpalicious .

smell - 5.0 powerful and very , very nice . smells of liquor soaked figs , overripe plums , aged port , damp wood and burnt sugar .  a : hazy brown shish body with decent head that laces very lightly . s : nose is quite yeasty and bready , as i apparently poured a bit of the sediment in the glass ( doh !  m - thick , heavy , sticky ... in short , decadent . as a straight up style exemplar , its feel is darn near perfect .

smells wonderful . a nice , dark fruitiness like cherry with dark chocolately , charred malts underneath .  pours a nice golden cloudy color with a big white fluffy head . lots of sediment but it 's not hurting the taste .  rich , creamy , and smooth mouthfeel . a bit of alcohol bite , and an excellent overall russian imperial stout .

the aroma fills the room with floral , piney hops as soon as the cap is popped on this gem . the aroma really opens up as the beer is being poured and starts to showcase some citrusy notes as well . really quite good , and i can see what much of the hype is about .  date : 18 june 2011 glass : sierra nevada xxx snifter type : 330ml bottle poured gently , 2-finger reduces to nice film , lacing is a little runny , color is deep crimson .  mouthfeel is really silky , solid , and smooth in the carbonation .

i had no idea what to expect but was pleasantly surprised ... dark brown with an orangey off-white head , the smell was amazing not even just for a beer just for a smell , boat loads of cloves , cinnamon and nutmeg , the smells of christmas ... . the taste was well preceded by the smell all those spices really hit you along with some fruitiness maybe something along the lines of candied orange peels and it has the depth of a coffee stout lying underneath it all , over all a very complex and interesting beer . honestly it does n't matter to me that much how it felt it was n't bad but it was n't perfect i would have liked it thicker but there was so much else going on that kept me occupied .  pours a clear golden/yellow color with a small had that could use some more retention and lacing is ok. aroma is well ... apples .  m - perfect carbonation in a perfect medium body , godly smooth .

the scent of this beer has spilled all over me and it is pretty good . the fruits range from grapey to tropical to lemon citrus , a great smell on this one . this is very good belgian craft , love it .  a : pours a glowing yellowish orange with a small white head with poor retention but some remains along the edges .  mouthfeel is soft and creamy smooth . just a hint of carbonation to cut through the abv .

soapy white head that dissipates quickly . s : i expected the grapefruit greeting of the ipa , but my nose was met with citrus combined with tropical fruit , almost a pineapple or mango and hint of floral . t : same blast of citrus and tropicals ; finishes a little bit quickly , without a lot of bitterness or drying , which i missed . a really fantastic beer and a lucky find since i understand hill farmstead is not found much outside of vermont .  pours black & smells like a , a ... tootsie roll . not much head , but a meager swirl brings it , & the massive smell , right back to the hop .  just about perfect for me .

( s ) - very fig-like with raisins . has a rustic feel . good flavor with an even better balance , smell , and feel .  a - dark red/brown muddy color that you ca n't see through at all . lots of floaties and no head with very little lacing .  with thick molasses and velvety feel to balance a bold and alcoholic content , this one hits me with a lingering hoppy bitterness on the finish of strong malt presence . seriously strong , often incapacitating ... but ever deliciously so !

fantastic . t - mild up front with burnt caramel -- much like the top of a creme brulee . the finish is drying with a hint of hops . slick , quick , and coating finish . nice .  a : pale straw body , with a very foamy white head .  also was surprised by how creamy this went down . this is a pleasure on the tongue .

aroma - very sweet at first with tropical fruits - dried mango comes to mind - and grapefruit . very complex nose that changes as the beer warms . taste - very soft , mellow mouthfeel .  my pour resulted in an easy two fingers ' worth of foamy off-white head with decent retention . the color was a slightly hazy golden-amber .  nice creamy mouthfeel , thick and pleasant and well balanced flavors of sherry , burnt carmel , toffee , roasted bananas and ripe stone fruit with hints of walnuts .

the nose on this is so pungent ! for all the fantastic flavors it had , it could have been a little too sweet , but some nice flower and rind notes return from the nose . great ipa .  it 's non existent . i do n't really care for wine but this smells great ! tast is very similar to red wine , though far more sweet .  the mouthfeel i think is perfect for the style .

s : holy hell this smells good . rich cocoa , vanilla & oak .  12oz poured into pint a- pours muddy brown , very murky . hardly any head at all .  the brew is incredibly creamy , and really coats your entire mouth . it 's fluffy to the point that it feels exotic .

such good fresh tastes and aromas . great easy drinker , good session , could sit back with tons of these on a warm evening .  500 ml bottle pours hazed dark amber/brown . managed to keep the sediment in the bottle this time .  i do n't find much to be said really , excellent balance , medium body shows a perfect carbonation to my liking , quite creamy lager , pretty crisp dry herbal hops finish .
very attractive smell . they could make this into a perfume .  darker than most . minimal white head is leaving minimal lacing behind .  mouthfeel is very soft and smooth on this medium-heavy brew .

nice complex but balanced smell . t : very complex . overall a very good , complex beer .  22oz bomber into 12oz mug a = once i opened it and saw thick , cloudy vapors pouring out i knew there were problems . tough pour .  touches of carbonation throughout , the mild breakups of tingling yield a remarkably smooth bevvy .

s : huge hop aroma . smells awesome . t : earthy hop oil , ripe ruby red grapefruit , lemon zest and fresh orange .  2006 ( about a year old ) appearance : poured dark black ... like there 's any other kind of black ... could use more head and lacing .  the mouthfeel is medium-full bodied with appropriately low carbonation , and a silky texture .

smells phenomenal . vanilla , oak , a tart undertone . awesome aroma . tastes nicely tart .  orange red pour , with a short white head . looks like the rest of their beers .  the texture is creamy and silky .

s : one of the best ipa aromas around with tropical fruit hoppiness of mango , pineapple , and passionfruit , coupled with pine resin and floral notes . pale malt with a little medium crystal sneaks in there to provide a little resistance to hop deluge .  poured from a 22oz brown bomber into a clear glass snifter . a : black body with beige , almost light violet 1/2 finger of head that fades quickly and leaves very scant lacing .  this is crazy , super tart and sour with a crisp carbonation bite .

aroma- incredible tropical scent . pineapple most notable . taste- disappointing considering the aroma . maybe i set my expectations too high.the flavor is as intense as the aroma , and that 's not necessarily a good thing . overall a beer that smells so good that the taste sort of disappoints .  medium hued amber color with small light-tan head , which thins out quite a bit .  it 's smooth in the mouth , but still lets up the high abv that 's lurking in the depths of this monster . it 's damn good . so smooth and creamy .

smell is huge . big roasted malt , coffee , sweet maybe maple syrup and toffee . very sweet up front . creamy lactose like sweetness hits right away . very enjoyable but only one in a sitting .  330 ml poured into a tulip appearance- poured a clear , honey gold color with a short lived white head . good retention and better life in head when swirled .  mouthfeel is the highlight of this ipa ; it 's velvety smooth and saves a bite for the back and sides of the palate . quite the juicy beer , very refreshing .

a-orange/amber ... leaves a nice lace on glass as i drink s-great aroma ... tons of toasted malts ... also some candied toffee ... i guess that is what toffee is : ) ... some caramel notes too ... very sweet aroma and a fresh hoppiness complements perfectly ... great smelling beer . t-where the nose is malt forward , the taste is more balanced ... some good hopping to this ... a citrus like grapefruit rind bitterness is evident..but it mingles nicely with the great malt backbone.. m-medium bodied ... .seems sessionable but still loaded with flavor .  appearance : pours a deep red/brown color with almost no head .  very velvety , creamy lactic mouthfeel . the aftertaste lingers big time w/ yeasty stickiness .

smell was immense and powerful , i could smell this brew several inches away from me . smell is pleasant , with notes of malt , apples , and yeast .  pours gold with a paper thin fizzy white head that 's gone in a flash .  appearance clear , dark orange ; off-white head that is about 1/4 '' tall - 4 smell banana , sweetish malts ; not overly complex , but pronounced and invivting taste & mouthfeel the mouthfeel on this beer is outstanding , further convincing me north coast knows how to give a beer a good feel ; full flavor from front to back , but with hard to describe flavors ( due to my limited experience with belgian style beers ) ... banana , malt , a little sour , slightly medicinal , caramel overall pretty darn good .

the smell is intense ; the spiciest smell i 've ever smelled in a pumpkin ale ! nutmeg and spice flavors are very pungent . this beer blew my mind with its complex flavor , but quickly became very cloying . this beer would 've been good with dessert . it is certainly unusual and worth a try if you like pumpkin ales .  so , this pours a little flat into my tasting glass , a dark red-brown .  '' m : really very exceptional . it has a nicely balanced carbonation and bitterness which make this one deceptively smooth for all its alcohol content . d : the mouthfeel is essential to me here since the taste is good but this one otherwise is below average .

s : one of the most unique aroma profiles with orange citrus , butterscotch , and musky herbal , earthy hops creating a huge sensory blast of woody , nutty , and sweet maltiness mixed deliciously with orange , herbal citrus . t : the muskiness in the aroma translates to a woody , nutty , herbal flavor that permeates the orange citrus hoppiness . d : overall this brew hits an interesting spot between english and american ipa with the musky , malty aroma saturated in orange , herbal hoppiness .  dark brown with barely a head even after the second and third glasses were poured rather hard . not much in the way of lacing .  m : thick , syrupy viscosity with light carbonation -- exactly as a beer of this style should be .

gravity cask @ gingerman in nyc . s : wet and juicy citrus hops all over the place : pink grapefruit & tangerine . has a sweet and really fruity malt background . t : loads of sweet pink grapefruit up front and then a big hit of juicy hop bitterness . d : had this on gravity cask , second day the cask was on .  poured into a tulip glass . dark golden color with a quarter finger of head .  perfect carbonation for the style .

aroma is quite fruit forward with pineapple , pine , grapefruit , malt still comes through though with hints at caramel and biscuits . taste is an amalgamation of flavors and aromas coming together to form one badass beer . all aroma 's transferred into taste , pineapple and mango coming through swinging in a sweet nectar . awsome as always .  black in color - no light coming through at all . no head or lacing , but this was from a growler shipped from nc , and could be different with a fresher pour .  mouthfeel - velvety smooth . ca n't think of better adjectives to describe the mouthfeel . wonderful . soft .

s : chocolate , a lot of it . giving it a vigorous swirl a very rich dark fruit ( cherries , raisons ) comes through , but with that nice chocolate over top of it . taking another , larger , swig the alcohol in the beverage stands out a bit more , and i get a nice warm coffee finish . m : i am a bit disappointed for here , it is a bit thin for what i was expecting from this this , but it coated the mouth nicely it just did n't have the thickness that i was expecting .  chill haze is pretty foggy ( this is a plus in my book ) .  body is refreshing yet almost full in its thickness and rich , creamy carbonation . overall it 's damn delicious and a great collaboration ; no surprise that there 's yet another beer with the dogfish head logo on it that i love .

very balanced and great complexity . definitely shows its age . the nose on this beer is absolutely amazing . one of the most dirty , stinky , and funky gueuzes that ive ever had the privilege of smelling . however , taste wise , its not much different than a well-aged classic gueuze .  clear , dark red overripe cherry coloration . no head , no lace . solid in the glass .  full bodied and lightly carbonated .

aroma is amazing , very complex for any beer . overall this is a very good offering from one of my favorite breweries and i think it has amazing complexity that is best enjoyed over a long period of time , letting the beer warm a bit and change over and hour or two .  a : pours a dark brown , nearly perfectly opaque ale . single finger light tan head dissipates quickly .  mouthfeel is on the dry side with effervescent carbonation that contributes to the crisp clean finish . its a fascinating brew that manages to be both crisp and refreshing yet still rich and satisfying .

a range of hop smells from sweet and citrusy to floral and piney . truly a treat for the nose . taste is surprisingly sweet , nicely balanced with the intense hops . not a bad beer otherwise though , worth trying if you love hops .  presented to me in a standard american pint glass the beer was a very light brown almost orange color topped by one finger of white creamy head .  first sip reveals a big creamy brew ... darkly sweet hoppiness upfront with fruity alcohol and rye in the second half . rich , creamy smooth body - big and coating . plenty satisfying overall .

the smell is what i liked best because of the caramel & chocolate , smelled like the worlds best desert .  typical amber color was topped by a decent head that left very little lace .  very nice mouthfeel .

lotr polotmavy 14 ( a semi-dark lager beer ) 4 clear dark reddish mahogany with lasting tan head that leaves lots of laving 5 unique aroma ; groll beers are fermented and aged in wood ( oak ) barrels .  bb 12-10-07 . good and nice white head and a golden beer with quiet some medium sized flocks floating around . remembers of great bavarian vollbier taste and can keep up with them ( minus presentation ) aswell as with the xx bitter and hexapoda .  smooth , medium body and carbonation , slightly chewy , with an astringent finish .

wow the nose of the hops . great hops with a hint of chocolate sneaking in as the beer warms . a very , very nice beer .  its murky yellow/orange appearance is the only remotely average thing about old harbor 's santo viejo pilsner .  mouthfeel is chewy and creamy .

s- freaking awesome . smells like a nice dark , rich stout with peanuts ! seriously , why has someone not picked up on this and gone rambo on this style ? that 's the next beer i brew , a peanut butter stout . i 'll break up friggin nutter butters and age them on that shit .  dark brown in color with reddish mahogany tinges . thin , bubbly , off-white head which dissipates in no time . nice carbonation , with a bit of haziness .  creamy and luscious body and wonderful layered complex flavors . pale malts , lead into corainder and tropical fruits with a yeasty belgian spice induced finish that lasts into a tingly carbonation with some hop bitterness . very nice .

love the aromas . sweet tropical fruits and florals . a little malt as well .  22oz into chouffe tulip . a- no head , mild creamy ring i guess , but nothing much . nice amber ale color . 2nd pour produced a bit more head , sany beach in color .  mouthfeel is exceptional , is medium to heavy in body .

awesome smell t : citrusy , sweet malty up front with a bitter , but not too bitter aftertaste m : seems a little overcarbonated , a little bit prickly d : one of the tastiest beers i have had in a while , would for sure buy this again .  i was quite impressed with what is my first dogfish head beer . maybe it 's written on the six pack , which is now in the trash . but might be better then what i am witnessing as i 'm sure my beer glass was run through the dishwasher , thanks to my wife .  the mouthfeel is where this beer really , really shines .

a great smelling ipa . smooth , almost fruity flavor , high hop bitterness in the back , some sweetness up front , nice palate connectivity .  looks pitch black with very little head .  m : very well balanced and sophisticated lambic , feels great in mouth , mouth puckers an enjoyable pucker d : it 's a sipper , but each sip invites another that 's for sure .

s - what a fantastic beer . delectable . t - an odd beer . initially it is quite non-descript , but as it warms it becomes incredibly enjoyable . it feels viscous and creamy in the mouth with a lingering bitterness and a spicy hop that plays with the beer 's thick , though not sweet , malt body .  the beer pours a slightly turbid golden-copper , with an off white head that lingers .  m - dry and quite bitter . perfect carbonation .

appearance : good , white foamy head , 1 '' off the tap ; dark copper color smell : awesome , fresh hops taste : at first it was really good , but i got a little sick of the hops toward the end ; kind of dry ; nonetheless , a good ipa taste mouthfeel : kind of a sticky head that hangs around ; other than that , it was pretty good drinkability : not the strength of this beer ; after i finished this one , i did n't want another , you get a little bit tired of all the hoppiness  poured into a nonic glass from a 12oz . stubby brown bottle with a twist-off cap deep reddish/brown lets a bit of light pass through.1 '' tan head qiuckly dissapates into a slight coating of foam .  spices are well balanced by the soft sweetness , mouthfeel is outstanding .

the nose assails you like a jackhammer , but a jackhammer that is fun and hammers little bursts of joy into your head . i was getting raisin and toffee at first , then earth , some malt , roasted meat , cigar tobacco , and english bread pudding . soooo complex ! the palate was disappointing after the amazing aromatics . mainly malts and dark fruit with lingering sweetness .  a bright white head faded from a quarter to nothing rapidly .  very creamy mouthfeel . again , marvelous mouthfeel , probably one of the best i 've ever enjoyed in that regard .

this brew smells awesome . i do n't even want to drink it , the aromatics are so satisfying alone . good stuff .  pours a very hazy amber-brown body with little kakhi head .  it almost tastes like an ipa , but with a darker malts and a more complex sweetness . the citrusy hops balance it out nicely . the beer is quite heavy , i guess it is following its `` scottish ale '' description here . it is so creamy and goes down nicely . almost perfect drinker .

carbonation is criminally low though ... aroma is ridiculously hoppy . lots of nice plne hops in there . smells great . lots of body in this one .  pours a muddy , amber color . somewhat low carbonation level but considering the abv i am not suprised .  m- i do love the creamy soft mouthfeel of the brew . carb is soft , but the beer is full . d- this beer perplexes me ... i would never had guessed this was a wit ... .more like a dubbel ... i guess that 's the pinot/oak flavors .

very complex and enjoyable smell . the taste is very interesting .  p : ruddy brown body , darker in the center . very small , light brown head . very fizzy . right up there with hazelnut brown nectar as my favorite brown .  this did not effect the mouthfeel at all it was perfect as is .

s : hops dominate , but do not smother , with floral and juicy citrus qualities . malt is soft and toasty , subordinate but not left out , while carbonic acid enhances the citric side of the hops and also imparts a crisp edge . the hop flavors are both titillating and palate-filling at their most intense , yet the perceived intensity varies with each sip and the different aromatic qualities seem not to be entirely copacetic .  i was slightly disappointed when pouring this beer into the glass , as it had a small , fleeting head and was a clear reddish color . after beginning to sip , however , my disappointment left about as quickly as the beer 's head .  m - the mouthfeel is amazing . really smooth and creamy .

smell - love the smell , might be because it reminds me of my first homebrew .  poured a slightly dark brown color with a thin white lacing barely covering the top of the beer . the head clung to the edges of the beer but did n't leave much for lacing .  its mouthfeel is incredible ; obviously this is enhanced by the nirto-tap . the positive was creating an amazing mouthfeel that fits perfectly with the style .

such intense complexity to the aroma , yet it keeps things approachably delicate . notes of graham cracker , molasses , toasted marshmallow , and black licorice . overall , cc4 is a great beer , but i like the non-blended versions a bit better than the amalgamation before me .  it poured a slightly hazy orangey color , very close in color to the label on the side of the bottle . despite the haze , it is pretty much clear . the head is supple , but recedes pretty quickly .  m - very luxurious mouthfeel to it .

s : big aromatics in this one , this could be one of the best smelling beers i 've ever had the pleasure of inhaling . almost smells like fresh baked raisin cinnamon bread . pretty complex . raisiny and sweet malts dominate , no signs of hops .  has a light golden color with a 1/2 inch head .  the beer didnt quite taste as good as it looked , but it was still quite pleasently sweet and i highly enjoyed the creamy mouthfeel it had .

smell is intense , the oatmeal and coffee dominate the scent .  very slight head , little lacing .  m : this has a great body for the beer . it has the consistency of motor oil which suits it nicely .

s : wow , seriously ? this is as tropical an ipa as i 've smelled . tons of citrus , namely orange , mango , and grapefruit . a good amount of pine encompasses the aroma providing much of the body with the pale malts . t : a little less fruity than the nose . i get a solid dose of orange , pineapple and grapefruit up front riding the wave of pale malt . good citrus flavor .  harvest ale 2000 review : pours cloudy mahogany reddish in color with a small beige head ; spotty lacing on the snifter .  m - very dry with perfect carbonation !

the smell runs the gambit from brett funkiness , pineapple , lemonade , some biscuity malty undertones , sour cherries , orange rind , and a slight bit of medinciney phenols mixed with faint all spice . the aroma has a certain weight to it and is delicious . the taste is actually a bit more focused and reminds me more of a syrupy lemonade with some brett musti/tartness mixed with granny smith apples .  a cloudy pour extremely light golden .  this exhibited a creamy mouthfeel .

smell is very nice . taste was not quite as complex , but still very good . really great stuff .  pored , walked away for a minute and nary a trace of head was let .  mouthfeel is incredibly full .. almost chewy .

s : this is one of the best smelling brews i 've come across in the summer ale category . i 'm not sure what kind of hops they added in the aroma portion of the brew , but it 's outstanding . unfortunately , it 's the best thing about this brew . t : really good . for a summer ale , it 's great .  12 oz bottle app- golden color with a one finger white head . sm- maybe apricot , but it maybe the power of suggestion .  mf : masterfully fizzy but light and balanced .

it smelled fantastic . t- the beer tasted less pungent than it smelled .  turbid , carmelized orange color ... interesting ... never seen one like this ... head is gone almost immediately .  the texture , in its sublime perfection , is creamy like a milkshake ... unbelievable .

first off this beer smells great ... it 's right up there with green flash for hoppy aroma and complextiy . this is very solid and drinkable do n't get me wrong but it 's under carbonated and there is too much malt finish to make it truly great . when the beer makes contact with your taste buds you get a nice hoppy dose of citrus but it fades so quickly and the carbonation flattens before you swallow the beer that you do not feel total satisfaction upon drinking .  poured a cloudy brown to reddish/burgandy color . did n't produce that much head but left some lacing .  the first sip reveals a velvety smooth body with mild gentle carbonation rolling right along through the swallow .

stunning citrusy orange-grapefruit-lemon-passion fruit and pine aroma . could sniff this one all day . exceptional aroma carries the day here .  honey golden in appearance with a frothy head at first , but the head disappears very quickly .  m : incredible mouthfeel .

s : great smell , full of roasted coffee , baker 's chocolate , and bourbon/vanilla .  bbd of 05/19/06 pours midnight black with a 2 fingers+ tan head that drops off pronto . no lacing or head retention smell : toasted malt , chocolate & frutiness taste : roasty malt , chocolate , fruitiness , with some oaky notes .  mouthfeel is awesome and is what makes this beer for me , this is a good tasting beer that is enhanced by a perfect creamy smooth feeling as it passes over my palate .

smell is of dark fruits , raisin , sweetness , a little bit of coffee .  appearance : poured with a large off white foamy head composed of large bubbles , which dissipated quickly leaving almost no lacing . the beer is slightly hazy with a orange/yellow golden color .  full bodied . perfect . the oats add some awesome smoothness .

poured chilled in ale glass a : cloudy , dark peach color ; good head ; decent lacing s : persistent , buoyant ; esters , booze , pear dominate t : sweet with overtones of pear ; light at first , moving to dry ale on the back end , almost too raw ; complex , flavorful beer a pleasant saison .  brown , mahagony , russet , with ruby highlights . head is miniscule and lacking . what is present is a tan ring around the collar ( or rim for this matter ) .  the mouthfeel on this brew was amazing . i ca n't imagine a brew being more full-bodied . mouthfeel is thick , chewy , almost syrupy and definitely absurd .

the aroma is a surprisingly accurate facsimile of creme brulee with caramel and vanilla and creme and a mild coco and roastiness underneath . most of the aromas are replicated on the palate with caramel vanilla cream with more roast and less sweet than the aroma . the mouthfeel , while pretty heavy , might have been a little bit better if it were more so .  poured from the bottle into a pint glass , beer is a deep amber color with an almost non-existant head .  medium body with perfect amount of carbonation .

the aroma is outstanding ! toffee mixed with a strong pineapple scent with a hint of grapefruit . this is an excellent dipa with a strong bitter wallop .  a : pours a nearly opaque black color . a small bubbly tan head forms , but recedes in a second . no lace . just a dense , black liquid .  exceptionally smooth mouthfeel and medium/full bodied .

the most remarkable attribute of this beer is the smell , and it might be the best beer i 've ever had in terms of smell . this guy has a very citrus and hoppy aroma - making for a very inviting smell if you 're an ipa fan .  it looks really flat , with a black center and brown edges .  this really has the acidity and fermentation of kombucha tea , giving it a great , crisp mouthfeel .

s - incredible . i 'm a fan of hoppy beers , so this is right up my alley . lots of great , citrus-y hops . based on the smell , i was expecting a pretty powerful hops flavor , but it 's actually pretty nicely balanced . nothing to write home about when compared to the taste and smell , but definitely not a negative here .  a - pours a clear amber with a decent white head .  it 's pretty full bodied and very smooth .

aroma : smoky , burnt chocolate . in fact , i think the smell is a good deal more delicious then the taste -- i could enjoy this one from the scent alone . taste : burnt chocolate , roasted grain , some sweetness . honestly , it was a bit of a letdown given the intense chocolaty smell , to be greeted with a taste that had more in common with burnt coffee that cocoa . i could sit and take in the aroma for a while , but the comparatively disappointing taste means i probably wo n't be having these too often .  pitch black in colour , except for some dark brown where the glass itself narrows and meets the stem . thin mocha head leaves a few tiny wisps of lace .  mouthfeel is the best part about the rasputin - just the right amount of chewiness and the malt and alcohol linger heavily on the sides of your tongue .

the aroma is heavenly ! ..think sweet , dark hazelnut coffee , maple syrup and vanilla . really amazing aroma . taste is initially brisk flavor hops , dark sweet malt , some burnt sugar , giving way to a chocolate and coffee finish .  a : standard pour yields a 2 finger frothy white head that dissipates quickly . beer is a cloudy sunshine yellow .  the body of this beer is incredible , and the alcohol content makes itself well known throughout the pint . very silky smooth and quite viscous for the style .

damn fine aroma . the flavors of this x-mas brew are subtle compared to the fresh ones i usually enjoy . this one 's got cinamon , ginger , soy sauce , evergreens , sap and fruits ... ..dark fruits . very nice . just a notch down from what i 'm used to .  a hazy handsome color somewhere between dark honey and light molasses .  velvety smooth creamy mouthfeel , moderate level of carbonation , medium to thick body .

delicious coffee smell , you can really tell its added for aroma . but a nice bittering finish to carry out the nose . d : a good beer to definitely be drank chilled . i am pleased that it is now in a 341ml bottle as opposed to the 650ml of old .  a - black and thick with no head , no ring or cap ; very little lacing s - french roasted coffee or espresso ; slightly earthy smell from da base ; some light toffee t - wow .  very dark with no light coming through and light head n : nose has lots of chocolate and sweet malts and a touch of hops t : starts with lots of chocolate and coffee , some sweet malts but very slight , a touch of hops are prevelant , some oatmeal taste as well , it 's got a sweet earthiness to it which is somewhat unique , a slight bitterness shines through m : it has a velvet feel in the mouth as it slides around , very thick and smooth f : a touch bitterness comes out in the end with the nice stout and oatmeal taste , coffee lingers on the back of the tongue , it has a sweet quality to start but gets drier as it fades and finishes really dry , its got a great smooth feeling in the mouth to go along with the great taste final thoughts : a great stout , it would be great if it was labelled as oatmeal or irish stout since it seems to have qualities of both , but listed as imperial it makes me wonder since its lacking a lot in the hop category .

the aroma is very assertive with candied fruit , sugared hops and a touch of alcohol . the hoppiness has faded in this one a bit . a really nice way to end an evening .  a : what 's up with cheap home-computer printed label ? anyway , pours dark , dark brown with virtually no head .  wonderful feel .

but here we go ... batch 8986 a : a nice transparent , light straw colored beer with a bone white head that quickly dissipates . this has the most crisp , citrusy , delicious aroma . perhaps the best smelling ipa in my opinion . i detect a grapefruit like aroma with a sweetness on the tail end . t : the hop aroma delivers . not as well balanced as hopslam , but never the less delicious . it is overall an exceptional beer , and among my favorite ipas .  i had this on tap at the map room into a tulip . the beer is clearish tangerince color with a light white head .  perfect carbonation , which i am growing to expect from oskar blues .

very unique nose . slightly bready as well .  a : golden yellow with a bubbly head that dissipates quickly and leaves very little lace s : beautiful cherry nose with floral hops subtle banana and vanilla aromas t : nicely balanced grassy , banana and tangy cherry flavour with an alcohol snap m : creamy , medium body with good carbonation and an oh-so-smooth finish d : a delicious pilsener from the country who does it best !  this coats the palate with a burbon goodness . just the right amount of carbonation .
the smell is overwhelming hops , mostly citrus , orange and grapefruit .  l - black color with a thin brown head that vanished in a few minutes .  mouthfeel : a perfect amount of carbonation .

this brew smells absolutely delicious . the first thing that came to my mind was fresh gingerbread cookies ginger , cinnamon , and sugary molasses sweetness .  poured into tulip from 12 oz bottle . very little retention , virtually none in fact .  amazing . 4.5 d - over the top , how much can you really have ?

stupendous nose . i found the taste to be not quite as amazing as the smell , but this is a really great and enjoyable quad . perhaps a little too much for my taste , but still really good .  appears a mahogany color with a small head that fades quickly .  mouthfeel is medium and very smooth with the perfect level of carbonation .

very nice complex , yet clean nose .  this pours a clear light amber with only about a finger of head and minimal lacing .  it was lush , creamy , smooth , rich , decadant and full . a very full bodied stout with a low carbonation .

the smell was wonderful . the taste was very nice .  a : black , tan head , very little retention or lace .  it possesses the best mouthfeel i 've yet to come across , rich and velvety , it just rolls over the palate and tongue , and goes down incredibly smooth .

really a wonderful smelling beer . really fantastic . nice , big fruity nose . very mellow flavors , but very nice .  pours a beautiful orange amber color , hazy after swirled and decant of sediment . a soap foam that quickly dissolves leaving no lace at all .  mouthfeel - 5.0 silky smooth , with very fine , lively , almost creamy carbonation .

smell : great aroma !  pours a very thin , beige head after the pour . but very quickly recedes . the color is the best part of the appearance of this beer .  the body is surprisingly thick and coating with a rich slick mouth feel .

smell : gorgeous hop bouquet ... juicy ruby red grapefruit , pungent green hops , light pine/spruce , sweet tropical and passion fruit aromas . one of the best smelling iipa 's on the market - hopefully this shows up in madison and stays cheap ( saw the oat for 2 $ more in madison today than in chicago ) taste : strong iipa here ... quite a bit boozy , moderate bitterness , ruby red grapefruit , citrus and lemon , tropical fruit , strong caramel malt presence , christmas tree ... yum mouthfeel : moderate bitterness , medium body , lingering bite drinkability : pretty good  on-tap at brewery : a - near opaque with a small fading tan head and spotty lace .  incredibly smooth and creamy in the mouth .

s - caramel , campfire , fresh grapes ( not an aged grape smell , which makes me think this will have a lot of life still ) , black cherry . overall - mute flavor , but the nose is amazing .  a- dark brown with hints of amber at the edges , small head which disappeared quickly and dissipated into a few sad bubbles .  mouthfeel - great mouthfeel .

it had a great smell and a smooth taste .  appearance : a hard pour into a pint glass ( where 'd my pils glass go ? ) reveals a thick head which quickly dies down to nothing . no lacing on side of glass either . slightly hazy lemony yellow color .  m : absolutely the best part of the beer .

wonderful aroma with hop floral and citrus fully rivaling the brett for attention . superb depth , refreshing . the hops and brett again tangle in the taste with the hops getting the upper hand .  clear reddish golden liquid . thin white head that disappeared very quickly .  carbonation is perfect and really adds to the beer .

this is a tough one to grade for me since its a pumpkin ale , and i hardly noticed any evidence of pumpkin in it . smell and taste are very similar and are just like fresh ginger snaps right out of the oven .  racer 5 is a cloudy orange ale with many small particles . the head is a fluffy , lumpy white one .  m = a truly exceptional mouthfeel , full bodied , great mouthcoating , frothy , luscious , creamy .

maybe the best beer smell ever to wander up my nostrils . this stout sit below a thick vapor that is sweet and boozy with anise , chocolate and coconut . smells a little grapey , like a heavy red wine . goodbye , beer , down the drain .  nice bright shiney red , w/ amber edges . mild carbonation , bit of a chill haze . pretty lifeless to this point .  the carbonation feels great on the tongue .

beautiful fruity citrus aroma of hops . fresh and ripe .  king henry pours a clear , almost pitch black dark amber . head is just a wisp of off-white that dissipates quickly . decent for the style .  the mouthfeel is incredible on this beer .

smell is powerful and complex , but i 'll try my best . sweet with caramel , brown sugar , some chocolate and some raspberry . it also seems quite vinous , i get hints of port and sherry . i also get a bit of alcohol in the finish , it 's not hot , but it is there . an exceptional beer and definitely a sipper , this is certainly worth seeking out .  pours a thick , milky look . black with a brown tinge . no head . brown film on top .  mouthfeel : no real aftertaste ( remarkable for a malt-heavy beer ) , carbonation is excellent and it plays well on the palate .

s : powerful floral and grassy hop aroma . fresh & outstanding . t : big hop flavor - citrusy mostly . out of balance at first but a sweet malt backbone exerts itself a bit as it warms .  a : super dark black/cola with no light getting through . absolutely no head at all and therefore no lacing .  it pours a brilliant gold , and the mouthfeel is very thick and chewy .

smell is fragrant and wonderful like fragrant burnt sugar with hints of orange . mouthfeel is pretty smooth , very nice .  poured a medium amber color with a one finger off white topper which soon turned into a thin film and left no lacing to speak of .  mouthfeel/drinkability- absolutely sublime texture in the mouth ... it 's medium bodied with a richness matched by the beer 's stunning palate .

canned pumpkin and nutmeg . like other st big beers , a tremendous smelling beer . t : somewhat heavy on the spices and less on the actual pumpkin and earthy squash but the sweetness is far from artificial . maple syrup , graham crackers again which is fantastic . best way to describe the taste of this one is a well made pumpkin pancake .  the condensation inside the chilled glass may account for the weak head and unusually sweet flavor i encountered . as the brew warmed in my mouth i could discern the craft-brewed complexity of this very drinkable , tasty ale . it could have used more bitterness , but i think it was the low temperature of the beer that was masking the bitterness .  mouth : excellent mouthfeel is the first thing you notice , tingling all the way through the mouth like tiny pin-pricks that i can actually continue to feel long after swallowing .

smells fucking amazing . giant sticky hops , pineapples , roses , and marijuana . like mixing centennial and cascade hold them up to your nose and breathing deep . tastes good . very good . the hops are more aromatic than anything , and the smell serves to blot out much of the amazingly sweet maple syrup malt that takes over most of the start and lasts throughout the middle .  a : hazy golden-brown , very little head ( or retention or lace ) .  m - nearly full bodied but despite that and the abv , it is extremely smooth and leaves just the right amount of flavor behind leaving you wanting another sip .

aroma is strong and inviting , caramel malt balanced nicely with orange scented hops . i really enjoyed the luscious aroma or orange/tropical hops and sweet malt . it 's a very unique pale ale , and i was glad to get a chance to try it ...  deep slightly hazy orange color with a slight white thin head .  good , creamy body with a low-medium carbonation is very nice for a ba imperial stout that is not overly sweet .

s - amazing ! very floral aroma that actually smells like walking through a rose garden . t - the taste is very different from the aroma . it was funky and spicy with a bubblegum flavor . d - this is a very good beer . i loved the aroma with flowers and rose water .  a - very aggressive pour had a 1.5 finger head that dissipated quickly . very dark brown in color with tan head . only real downside was the lack of head .  the texture is perfect , though .

a very interesting barleywine . the nose is typical barley wine - some caramel , candied fruits , and a host of other goodies . truly unique - nice job to weyerbacher .  poured a dark reddish brown into my st. bernardus goblet . the head was smallish and did not have great retention .  m : outstanding , deliciously creamy , thick , rich for an ipa .

375ml bottle bought from beermerchants.com ... 2009 bottle poured almost pitch black even when held up to the light ... dirty mocha brown head poured quite very loose and bubbly and faded instantly to nothing ... no lacing.. aroma - very strong sweet oaky bourbon to the fore straight away , very woody and earthy , lots of fresh vanilla , roasted malts , hints of tar , cigar smokiness , rich stewed dark fruits ( blackcurrents and prunes ) , molasses and burnt brown sugar , alcohol is pretty noticeable , fresh black pepper taste - tons of roasted and charred malts mixed with strong molasses / black treacle sweetness followed closely by warming bourbon , lots of vanilla , liquorice , defnite cigar / tobacco smokiness , rich dark sweet fruits ( prunes , figs , raisins , blackcurrents ) , very earthy , espresso , light soy notes , alcohol definitely comes through , dark chocolate ... feel - smooth and slick although as with the ordinary old viscosity not as full bodied as i would have expected ... suprisingly drinkable for a 12 % brew although you definitely notice the alcohol after one bottle.. overall - an amazingly complex stout ... highly recommended .  can , generously donated by a buddy of mine , as a cloudy , amber-brown . one inch head of dense , rocky foam that settles very slowly . the only drawback from this beer 's appearance is that it 's color seems a bit too dark for an ipa . smell is very hoppy with spicy , evergreen aromas .  instead , i got this pefect , autumnal fruit beer , which , though it smells kind of like apple jacks , had an exceptional mouthfeel , and a rich apple kick that coupled nicely with the astringency of the lager .

originally i was going to give the smell a 4.0 but after hovering over it , just enveloping the aromas i give it a 5.0 its just amazing , so full and complex it makes my mouth salivate over it .  put me in a bad mood as i was cleaning up the mess on the counter . fortunately , it pours medium copper with lots of head , but settles down quickly .  the taste is an initial malty sweetness , followed by bitter hoppy alcohol , followed by dry chewiness . this brew has a great thickness and presence , and the carbonation is not too much to interrupt things . excellent .

... pours a brown dark brown colour ... has oak , chocolate , cherries , tar and other grab bag candies ... tastes like cherries a bit ... bold yet still quite balanced , a great brew indeed ... quality and crazy mixed in a 750 bottle..  a 1 finger white head dissipates fairly quickly to a thin film .  just perfect . this is one of the better stouts that weyerbacher has done .
smells really good . appearance : golden color , nice white head , clear .  golden/amber pour , some yeast floating around .  a very smooth and creamy cask ale , that goes down very well .

really impressive hazelnut aroma when your nose gets within a few inches of the glass . taste are just as strong and bold . exceptionally clean finish which leaves you wanting more .  a-pale transparent orange with almost no head . s-holy crap .  m - very creamy . just a small sip seems to coat the inside of the mouth very well .

quite unique , but i 'm very impressed . the taste is a lot lighter and less robust compared to the aroma .  poured into a sam ultimate glass . clear , golden color with a wispy white head that dissapates quickly . hey ... i thought this was a wheat beer- all i can smell is hops !  palate is perfect , rich and chewy .

s- mmmm . the smell is creamy and sweet , at first it made me think of hazlenut coffeee and starbucks coffee ice cream . this is very drinkable i could do 2 or 3 of these .  although disappointingly served in a 0.4l glass at an exorbitant price ( $ 9 ) , it was a tasty lager , but not completely ticking the boxes for a true munich style dunkel .  mouthfeel is perfect . smooth and creamy , light carbonation , just absolutly terrific .

fresh floral and citrus nose , the smell is fantastic in fact .  pours a nifty orangish color with average head .  full bodied for the style , definitely one of the fullest dipa 's that i 've ever had . nice carbonation levels as well .

the aroma is perfect . it has a warm and rich malty scent that is sweet with crystal malts and toastey with roasted barley . it has awesome aroma and flavor ; a great drinker .  ) on the nose appearance : cloudy for the style . dark golden color ( not straw ) , a little dark for the style ?  mouthfeel is complex ( and the best part about this brew ! ) - full of variations in feel , thin and fruity , then rich and creamy . carbonation is an afterthought .

a bit of citrus and sweet caramel mixed in only makes this better . top notch !  it 's a simple beer , no doubt . it 's poured with about a fingers width of head , a hazy copper color .  mouthfeel is luscious and creamy , very well done there ; average carbonation .

the smell on this beer is very complex . overall , it smells like an arts and crafts store around christmas time . absolutely fantastic . unfortunately the taste is not as great as the smell .  pours out a black body with a good size milk chocolate looking head . alcohol legs are very noticable , but virtually no lacing on the glass .  the rest : another solid beer from ommegang ; good balance and a great body .

smells like porter heaven . great , spicy scents of cinnamon and sweet chocolate malt . it almost smells like they put some artificially engineered scents in there , in a good , science-is-progress kind of way . the balanced flavor and great smells make this a pretty appealing brew .  hazy gold , with some sediment ( my bottle could 've been aged -- no `` best by '' date present ) . thick , slow head and decent lace .  creamy and full bodied throughout . one of the creamier feeling beers ive had from this style . exceptional .

smells like bacon ! only one things smells like bacon and that 's bacon ! many smoked beers smell like liquid smoke or a burnt-down house or a campfire , but this one smells like ... say it with me ... bacon ! yeah i overdid that a bit . the smell is also sweet , not as `` sweeeet , it smells like bacon '' or `` well , is n't she sweet '' but in the `` sugar is sweet '' usage of that word . all those smells and yet it works . awesome ! if you do n't like rauschbiers than you wo n't like this one .  pours a light rusty-red color with a few bubbles on the initial pour and not much in the way of a head or lacing .  mf : thick viscous body , creamy mouthfeel , low carbonation d : i have tried many of dfh 's wild experiments when it comes to unique ingredients , and found that some of them fell short and ingredients got lost ( theobroma comes to mind ) .

smell : the smell of this beer is beautiful . fruity , sweet , spicy , and incredibly inviting . taste and mouthfeel : the fruitiness of the smell is nearly gone , and spicyness takes charge . as with all good belgian beers , this is very unique . the taste is unlike any other pale ale i 've had .  appearance : ruddy brown , very scotch ale like . no head at all , even with a vigourous pour .  mouthfeel , on the other hand , is amazing . perfect level of carbonation and great water quality .

i 'm most impressed by the incredible aroma but i 'd buy this regularly if it was available in my market .  sitting in the glass it just looks fairly average .  exceptionally creamy mouthfeel , medium body .

just like wine it is meant to accent and add different characteristics than take the lead in flavor . one smell of this brew and you can tell it is nearly a perfect length of barrel aging . roasty chocolate aomas , with vanilla and black currant esters . mollasses as well as the slightest bit of prune , are accented by the subtle oak aromas that seem to be nice and toasty . very roasty and a long finish that is very tannic and chewy . nicely balanced and largely complex . i think i would have rated a little higher if it were n't bone dry . nice burn in the chest .  a - clear amber with a quickly dissipating head s - minimal hops here .  the mouthfeel is the ultimate strongpoint on this beer . it is ridiculously creamy and very chewy , complemented with the perfect amount of carbonation .

nose is wonderful , citrus , melon , pineapple , and piney hops jump out and stay in full force for the entire glass .  warm amber color ; sufficient but not bountiful head .  very smooth . just the right amount of carbonation .

wonderfull beige head and anorangeamber beercollor with fine haze . nose shows mega brettarome , sweety horse in flowery fields and wonderfull balance between the freshness of esters & spices and on the other hand the bretty arome . thinking this brewery just started gives me good hope and wants me to try more of this newcomber .  pours a murky dirty brown with a 1/2 inch foamy tan head that quickly fades to nothing .  mouthfeel is near perfect with carbonation playing second fiddle to the robust malts .

big waft of bourbon is the first noticeable aroma followed by chocolate , light coffee and burnt caramel . smells amazing ! flavor is nice blend of chocolate , roasted malts , dark caramel , bourbon , vanilla , booze , and oak . definitely the roastiest strong ale i 've ever had . carbonation is very light but it 's nice and does n't really need anymore for this style , but a touch more would be welcome .  500ml bottle bought from gapwines , belfast ... poured a very pale straw yellow colour with a slight haze ... white head poured pretty loose and frothy then faded to wispy coating with thickish edging .  the mouthfeel is just amazing , it enters smooth and goes down smooth .

perfumy and very fragrant . spicy fragrant taste .  on tap at the bavarian lodge in lisle il a : a dark singel but that 's cool . not much of a head with below avg retention but that 's cool too s : traditional belgian yeast atoms with lots of flower and fruit esters . possibly artificial color added to appeal to those who like darker belgians but that 's col .  first sip reveals a rich and firmly textured beer of elegant character . an encore presence by the hops closes out the taste in a long and seamless finish . faultless balance , beautiful complexity both in the nose and on the tongue make this beer , in my opinion , a perfect desert beer or soothing winter warmer .

nose is simply amazing for this beer . this one is underrated and worth seeking .  pours deep mahogany to black with a 1finger deep tan head that drops away quick . no lacing & minimal head retention smell : choclate & slight iron smell taste : choclate & roast grains up front .  like all chimay beers , it feels great on the mouth : foamy and thick .

smell is big , fat , and rich . only that gorgeous nose is enough to keep you going for more .  2003 version , bottle no 08746 , 250ml bottle into my rochefort glass . the beer is a medium , watery , muddy unattractive brown with no carbonation , not that any was expected on a 7 year old ale ... the aroma is strong and very nice , caramel and figs jump at me right away . overall just very sweet ... even after 7 years this is pretty alcoholic , ca n't imagine what it would taste like new . lots of brown sugar and prunes in this . pretty good , oddly reminescant of a stronger , alcoholic , and watery trappist quad ... the feel is too light and watery for me without must lasting flavor , a slight warm finish ... fairly easy to drink for 12 % . overall , this was pretty good for an old ale , a little strong right now , even after 7 years .  mouthfeel is really very rich : like a good stout on the palate , smooth and full , thick and chewy , but it 's got that pilsner crispness .

s - no lie , one of the best aromas on a beer , ever ! tons of resinous , sappy , piney hops along with pineapple , grapefruit and lemon . basically a massive fruit salad of smells ! t - juicy grapefruit and grassy , piney hops meld well with the doughy caramel malts . damn good beer !  brought over by w113raf pours murky and yellow .  fantastic carbonation persists in mouth-feel .

big nose , filled with charleston chew chocolaty filling and some dark plum pudding . nice ... very nice . has a light , airy feel when drinking it , very creamily meringue like . i dont get a whole bunch of rich , yeasty esters but it still maintains a nice complex profile .  pours a dark reddish brown color with a quickly departing off white head that leaves no evidence of its existence shortly after .  m : medium-bodied with a soft , silky mouthfeel . the thick , creamy head gives a great texture to each sip .

if you expect banana nut bread you 'll get the taste of it but you wont be eating bread . s : this was perfect , it truly smelled exactly like what i expected . i loved the smell considering i love banana nut bread .  pours a dark , cloudy golden-amber . i like them cloudier .  mouthfeel is incredible , maybe an even better quality than the taste .

gorgeous oily hop nose , citrus and pine .  yellow with an orange hue , and a thin white head that fades quickly , leaving some patchwork . decent lacing .  the mouth feel is outstanding , to the point of being lip smacking and among the best i 've had .

just an awesome and complex aroma ! all of the same on the taste buds but there is also a hint of cherry syrup .  got this from bottletrek , bbd of 06 08 pours chestnut/ebony with 1 finger of tan head . average head retention & lacing s : chocolate & roasty malts t : chocolate , a bit of iron , slight herbal hops up front .  well done feel . i so enjoy the heaviness of the feel and how it combines with the fruit flavors .

holy smokes , this is loaded with pungent hop aroma ! i do n't see it as a `` double '' or `` imperial '' ipa , but more of an incredibly aromatic ipa . superb ! the small print : there is a mild plant-like ( chlorophyll ) character to it that can appear from time to time because of the massive quantity of hops used ; and the brilliant nose might not carry over into bottles that have a little more age on them .  a : standard pour yields a single layer of coarse white bubbles atop a cloudy grapefruit beer that dissipates quickly . lacing is spotty and with moderate cling . a solid offering from cantillon and one worth seeking out .  velvet mouthfeel ; tongue coating and heavy .

this is the best smelling pumpkin beer i have come across . the beer smells almost exactly like sugary pumpkin pie ( happens to be my favorite pie ) , i have no other way of describing it . this is one hell of a treat for my big nose .  poured from 12oz brown bottle into a clear pint glass a : brown-black with thin light-brown head that dissapates quickly but leaves a fair amount of lace s : chocolate , faint coffee , and nutty aromas supplement the roasted malts -- smells delicious .  m - the body of this beer with the carbonation is perfect . tiny bubbles , so you have that nice creaminess with a fantastic , medium and not overpowering mouthfeel . d - because there is so much coffee slammed into this beer , it leaves your mouth a little dry and overwhelms the palate , so i 'm good after one bottle .

smell : very nice complexity in the nose . spicy , fruity , yeasty , and sweet all at once . more rustic in character than la fin du monde , which is not necessarily a bad thing .  a- pours a dark brown color with highlights . overall , the color kills the appearance .  molasses and toffee sweetness m - rich and chewy caramell . low carb form the bottle and slightly dry d - wonderful !

appearance - is pretty typical , small head , black and opaque smell - beautiful , vanilla chocolate , so rich and creamy smelling taste - similar to a chocolate malt with vanilla mouthfeel - creamy and thick and very drinkable , i wanted more .  has a nince dark copper color , but had little to no head at all .  this is really a very good beer : the finish , the mouth feel , the carbonation , the body , are quite exceptional . it 's the taste .

nose was milk , creme , coffee and vanilla beans .  pours a clear straw yellow . an aggressive pour left me with a small white head but it did n't last very long .  m : very smooth , sticky , and thick . light to medium carbonation .

s - a nice , pungent pine hop aroma with strong grapefruit character . the aroma is excellent and it is easily the best aspect of the beer .  this is what i got out of it : the appearance was unfortunately watery , with a medium black/brown body and a 1.5 inch tan foamy head .  smooth as velvet , i love what oak-aging does to impy stouts .

s : holy crap , this is incredible . a massive burst of citrus hops hits immediately . d : like most dogfish beers , this is a very interesting beer and i am glad i tried it but , i do n't think i will pick up another of these .  pours a dark murky black with a thin tan sheet of lace on the top .  mf & d - sticky and delicious . just the right amount of carbonation and alcohol content to keep the porter balanced .

smell : chocolate rain-ish , can smell and almost taste graham cracker , slight toasted marshmallows , i pick up more graham cracker , boozy aroma - you know your gon na get hit with the alcohol in the taste .  about a quarter finger of frothy light tan head . poor retention and no lacing .  the mouthfeel is exceptional , big thick viscous and sticky and is amazingly velvety over my palate . really quite incredible .

s - i knew i had to get this one when i smelled it from across our table . a tiny bit of sweet caramel malt comes thru but this one is really all about the hops . the taste was n't as good as the nose but i still really enjoyed this one . d - very good . i really like racer 5 quite a bit and this version was even better . a touch one dimensional with all those pungent hops but that really is n't a bad thing .  pours a golden amber , and you can immediately smell the citrus/grapefruit scent . overall , it would be really hard to improve the taste and mouthfeel of this beer , and very drinkable .  m/d - full bodied and very creamy/smooth . excellent feel .

again , wow . fantastic .  on tap at bob 's into a pint glass ... pours a light brownish red , pretty clear on the edges , a light off white head that has ok retention , not much lacing ... light aroma mostly malty caramel , bitter citrus fruits and only a hint of rye , which is good in my book ... taste is decent , a pretty hoppy rye with a malty backbone .  i think it 's the mouthfeel that sets this beer apart from the others . silky smooth with some alcohol kick and lively carbonation .

the aroma is strong . there is a lot of dark fruit , caramel , flowers , oak , and the right amount of bourbon . once i get used to that i can detect caramel , more bourbon than there is in the aroma , not as many floral notes , more oak , no fruit . i like this taste , but it is nowhere near as harmonious as the aroma . the mouthfeel is full bodied with appropriately low carbonation , and a silky texture . very nice feel . unfortunately , whereas the aroma is a harmonious blend of strong smells , the taste is a bunch of in-your-face flavors that work together but have no real grace .  a : pours a nice dark pumpkin orange hue with no sight of a head .  m. incredibly smooth .

rich aroma of chocolate , coffee , dark fruit and a hint of alcohol . the aroma is every bit as good as any other ris i have sampled . absolutely enjoyable ris from weyerbacher .  a very small head forms despite a vigorous pour .  mouthfeel is thick and creamy and everything i could ask for . the tartness keeps pulling you in like a siren , and i am totally captivated by her song .

s - chipotle comes out immediately along side semi sweet chocolate , coffee grinds , hints of anise , light hickory smoke , and chocolate liqueur .  bottle poured into a pub pint glass , cloudy dark red in color with a small , tan head .  it has an exceptional silky texture to it - similar to a nitro effect . just enough carbonation .

pretty good beer , not a huge bitter-beer lover but being on the low end it 's pretty enjoyable and wouldnt mind grabbing some in the future .  a : small white thin head . deep golden brown and yellow .  fine carbonation bubbles and a full body give an excellant texture . coats the palate beautifully . more of a bourbon lovers beer than a stout lovers beer .

aroma : this smells really delicious . there 's grapefruit , sweet orange , apricots , peaches , and cotton candy sweetness .  had this on tap at a local restaurant . appears to be a little less cloudy than a typical hefe .  the mouthfeel and the drinkability of this beer are the stars for me , it was so smooth and almost milky ( in a good way.. not like gagging thickness or anything.. just very smooth ) .

whiffs of cotton candy and sweet cinamon bread come to mind . sweet cookie dough and biscuity malts . great aroma . the mouthfeel seems a little empty . the taste does not follow through to the extent that i 'd like with the aroma , but some nice qualities to exist . sweet candied tones and the `` menage a trois '' of figs , raisins and dates .  aggressive pour into snifter ... a : pours a jet black with a small one finger mocha colored head , big bubbles and falls very quickly into a thin foam ring around the edge of the glass .  mouthfeel is extremely smooth and velvety .

s- the nose on this brew is reminiscent of orange marmalade . it also exhibits some sweet vinous notes , and some citrus hop aroma . further examination reveals a touch of honey playing-around in the background ... t- wow !  1/5 inch head of an off-white color . poor lacing and poor retention .  this beer feels like it belongs in my mouth and is very delightful . i certainly could drink this beer all night long : d

s : lovely perfume-like odor .  poured a turbid brown/tea color with a minimal tan head .  the mouthfeel is very much like drinking liquid chocolate or marshmallow fluff . so rich , creamy , and very full in the mouth .

smell- absolutely incredible smell , it blows you away . sweet and flowery . taste- great tasting double ipa , the hops , the tartness , the honey ! they are all quite present and an absolute delight . overall- great beer , definitely worth the try , will now become part of my standard grouping of ipas .  appearance : pours a translucent golden body with a small , white head . drinkability : it 's really great smelling stuff ! i had to be restrained from pouring out the growler onto myself so i could continue to smell this beer for days and days to come .  oh , before you even get a dose of those lovely hops , that heavy belting richness makes its presence felt , with a slick , thick , chewy texture coating the mouth . once it 's there it releases its bomb - a phenomenally astringent hop bitterness cascading over the tongue . apart from the thick body , there 's almost no whisper of the malt backing , but that 's ok. that 's what this beer is all about .

the second thing you notice as you are pouring is the fantastic aroma of coffee and chocolate . especially when the aroma was so promising . the mouth feel is weak bodied with sufficient carbonation .  a - clear amber , with about a finger of light tan head . retention is moderate with moderate lacing . i was definitely expecting more in the head/lace department .  very creamy , smooth , and full bodied mouthfeel . this is definitely a stout that i could drink quite a lot of given it 's mild but good flavor and fantastic texture .

damn , this smells good . big roasty malts compete with all that chocolate on the palate for quite a while , with nondescriptly bitter hops and a little alcohol warmth bringing up the rear . while the chocolate on the nose smells sweet and milky , in the mouth it 's an equal mix of bitter and sweet , which is just awesome . very well balanced , and you could drink it until the 11 % abv says otherwise .  poured a very clear , very crisp looking golden . a short-lived white bubbly head with very large bubbles diminished to a few patches of froth and a scant ring .  perfect carbonation , i wish all pale ales were this way .
massive floral and citrus hops , it combines with a toasty malt caramel as well .  this beer pours an opaque dark brown nearly black color .  excellent mouthfeel .

it 's nothing like tequilla , and instead smells like dessert . brown sugar , massive maple , custard ... hard to believe you could get this out of agave . let 's see , it 's really sweet , and really tasty . you could make creme brulee out of this beer . i want to say maple donuts are what this beer reminds me of .  a : pours deep yellow with sticky white head .  carbonation is perfect ; sharp , but not biting .

quite possibly the most appealing nose i 've ever encountered . creamy , thick and slick . by no means sessionable , pumking reigns the realm of `` one and you 're done . '' the perfect autumnal warmer . treat yourself to a pint over thanksgiving dinner , or while masterfully carving pumpkins on all hallows eve .  pours like 15,000 mile motor oil with 1 finger of cocoa colored head . average head retention & lacing s : dark chocolate , raisins , & a touch of leafy hops & then some figs & oak notes as this warms t : rich dark chcolate , a touch of roastyness , a bit of leafy hops & charred grains up front .  medium bodied with low carbonation . amazing mouthfeel with one of the most balanced , robust , and pleasantly malty flavor profiles of any barleywine .

the nose is superfruity . it smells like a fruit beer . it has pears , apples , peaches , apricots , grapes , oranges , berries , an injection of sugar and malt , and a subtle hint of spice . the flavor brings a lot more malt , it actually tastes alot like an american belgian-styled beer . it is still quite fruity on the palate though . it made me fall in love with it with the smell , but sadly the flavor did not hold up .  a - dark , near black , not much head . tan ring . very light spotty lace .  the mouthfeel , on the other hand , is wonderful : creamy , smooth , full-bodied , with moderate yet lively carbonation .

s : amazing , get a ton of hops . citrus and pine just exploding into your senses . t : getting a lot more pin than citrus in the taste , a great piney taste though .  head is a little short , and a kinda pale tan head . retention is mediocre , lacing is minimal , but there is some there .  the lack of carbonation really helps the mouthfeel of this .

smell is insane hoppy , whole spectrum of hoppiness , grapefruit , pine , caramel maltiness , some floral , super hoppy , lots of amarillo goodness , bit soapy but still very powerful and fragrant , malt takes a backseat . good at first but that aspirin flavour takes hold after half a glass , aroma was pretty ace though .  @ raleigh times pours dark orange in the dim lighting of the bar with a head that goes away all too quickly .  it has a velvety mouthfeel .

smell : the aroma of this beer is definitely its strongest attribute . great hop/floral character with the typical grapefruit and citrus notes . i thought that the smell of this beer was also a bit sweeter than most ipas ; there is almost a bit of honey detectable resulting in a nice balance between sweetness and bitter hops . taste : the first thing i noticed was the nice creamy texture of this one . again , i could have used a bit more malt presence to balance things out . drinkability : very refreshing .  lightly cloudy , dark golden color .  it 's full bodied and smooth with a very clean finish .

aroma is wonderfully full of sweet malt , dark fruits , light fruits and spices . aroma may be the most balanced combination i 've ever had the pleasure of enjoying . not so shabby ... kind of nice .  poured into a tulip . 3.0 a : opaque peach/ruby red color . nearly three fingers of white , fizzy soda pop head that falls fairly quickly and leaves no lacing behind . aside from the appearance , this is solid all around .  m : mouthfeel is great . full-bodied , yet not too thick .
definitely a good collaboration . collaborate some other time !  a - deep copper , no head , a bit disapointing on that front s - little oak , little hoppy and some malt .  very refreshing .

i have no idea what to rate the look ... rich caramel and honey aroma , with hints of aniseed and sweet licorice ( yes they are different ) . it has an amazing aroma , and big characteristics about it , but the bitterness from the hops just leaves a really , really strong taste in the back of my mouth . definently worth it for something incredibly unique .  poors a much clearer copper then i would expect with a big clingy head .  i love the mouthfeel of this beer . i love that thick , syrupy feel .

s - bananas , clove , spearmint , yeasty bread rolls , honey , vanilla , toffee , earthy herbal tones , sweet rolls , white chocolate/macadamia nut cookies , yogurt covered pretzels , carrot cake icing , t - smooth and delightful , with a subtle tangy and spicy yeast that quickly gives way to buttery wheat rolls , caramel , vanilla , and toffee . lacking in some of the funkier aspects of a weisse .  poured into a shaker pint glass bbe dec 2008 a- mahogany body with lots of floaters , creamy 1 finger head that reduces to a crown , minimal lacing .  creamy , full bodied feel to it . really outstanding .

the smell was just fantastic . a bit of roasty aroma , french vanilla , oak , caramel and toffee , with hints of bourbon in the background . very nicely balanced , and the bourbon aging compliments this very well without dominating . not as roasty as i would like , but still nice .  appearance : nice clear appearance , good orange/brown color .  feel is a nice creamy smooth medium-full with an excellent soft tickling carbonation .

smells hoppy , fresh , and fruity , with a slight floral touch . somebody could write a review about the scent . absolutely wonderful fresh tasting with a hoppy bite .  pours a hazy tangerine color . decent flow of carbonation coming from the bottom of the glass to the surface .  mouthfeel : best mouthfeel of any wit i 've ever had ; this has the milkshake-thick , smooth mouthfeels i 've heard described as ideal for the style .

great aroma ! t- the taste like the aroma is a lot of rye and malt up front . d- overall , i really enjoyed this beer .  this pours a burnt orange with a nice , two finger head that dies down to almost nothing with no lacing .  m : leaves a nice stickiness that is not overpoweing .

the aroma was just amazing - sweet kandi and floral elements i can only assume were from the hops .  black like used diesel oil , head was small ( despite a pretty rough pour ) and brown , did n't last that long and left decent lace .  perfect balance of sweet and bitter with a creamy smooth mouthfeel .

aroma : smells amazing . tons of grapefruit and sweet cotton candy in the aroma . drinkability : this is an amazing ipa , full of great west coast hop aromas and flavors . it 's easy drinking , and quite delightful .  '' a : dark brown or black , but is not hazy or cloudy . a large white head which stuck to the glass .  medium body with a thick and creamy yet mineralic texture . perfect combination of lively and fizzy effervescence . finish is dry and tart with just enough lactic sourness .

smells wonderful . hops , and some hints of malt .  cloudy , the color of hay . full of very small and rather large bits suspended in there . bone-white head goes quickly .  mouthfeel was incredibly creamy .

first thing i notice with the smell of this one is how hoppy it is - wow , the huge blast of citrus makes me think i 'm smelling an ipa or something . awesome . i had a hell of a hard time trying to find anything i did n't love about this one .  somewhat hazy honey-yellow with a white head and poor retention .  incredibly creamy and light .

the aroma is amazing ! it was hard to pull my nose away from this one . the whole hop gamut fills my olefactory senses . huge hoppy beer . it 's a damn good beer .  750ml bottle poured into a tulip . ( a ) - pours a hazy yellow color .  mouthfeel : creamy smooth medium body with superb carbonation . swallow is velvet . tasty and the mouthfeel is truely a dream . goes down easy when you enjoy slowly .

apples , pears , citrus notes . their is also a pleasant malt balance in the nose . t : sweet fruit notes and a bready yeasty flavor , slight spicy notes and balanced malts throughout m : creamy and medium bodied with high carbonation , alcohol balances the body and keeps the tongue entertained d : alchohol and sticky creamy mouthfeel reduce drinkability a tad , none the less , these characteristics are what defines this beers mouthfeel notes : a certainly interesting take on the style that i will definitely order again  poured on tap into a pint glass this beer pours a deep black in color , but where is the head ? said film is soon swallowed by the sea however , not to be seen again .  this probably has the best mouth feel i have experienced to date .

hell yeah . f'ing chocolate , hazelnut and of course coffee , with a minimum of roastiness . every now and again , it 's great to have an imperial stout that is n't roasty to all hell . whatever coffee they use for this , it seems like a light , bright roast ... dare i say it , a breakfast blend . ok , obviously there is a shitload of coffee in here , but the underlying beer is n't half bad either . i have become a coffee stout fan , actually ... .yeah , mr. farmhouse ale likes to cross over to the dark side every now and again , for sure .  a : pours deep dark brownish black hue . there was no head , no carbonation , and no lace .  awesome thickness , yet not throat-closing thickness -- more like smooth milkshake thickness , where carbonation does n't feel like bubbles , but simply a collective , chilled push down the throat .

arroma : what a bouquet ! this is one of the freshest , hoppiest noses ever to come out of the bottle . if i could drink this through my nose i would . taste : this is basically a stronger , more full bodied version of arrogant bastard ... which is already pretty damn strong and full bodied .  it 's a witbier . lots of witbiers use mystery spices , and this one happens to use one that 's pink . that said , it pours a slightly hazy pink-amber , with a thin , bubbly pink-tinged head . the hibiscus is very well integrated ; in a black glass this would be classic witbier with a hint of something exotic . it 's a testament to psychosomasis that so many are writing this witbier off as alcopop .  mouthfeel/drinkability- just when i thought the perfect mouthfeel of a belgian ale was locked up with tripel karmeliet , this beer dazzles with a sublime , gentle texture that lasts throughout the entire duration in the mouth . absolute perfection , it further emphasizes the already impressive quality of the beer .

it is a big bold german style hefe with a wonderous banana aroma mixed with what i really believe to be brett . now , i know this is not really true to style at all but this smelled like heaven -- all funky et all . the flavor was definately a bit of a let down , as the brett character was not as prevelant , but i could see that it was still there .  a very curious winter seasonal out of kalamazoo , one doesnt normally associate the dead cold of winter with a nice refreshing wit but i applaud bells individuality on not limiting the style to a thirst quenching summer beer . poured a very light hazy yellow with a half inch or so of head that gave way rather quickly .  t - bananas , caramel , and mild dates swim around sour-yeastiness and vanilla , concealing well the alcohol that lies beneath ... m - very , very smooth , medium body massages the palate and dries the cheeks . d - nice , very nice , do n't know if i 'd get it again , but very nice .

smell is truly exceptional . sweet raspberries and malt .  the head dissipates quickly and leaves no trace on the glass .  the texture of this stout is incredibly smooth , possibly the smoothest , creamiest stout i 've had .
