s - quite a powerful hop aroma . beautiful citrusy , bright character . d - i like it . great example of how a beer should be built for a hop lover .  a - clear dark brown that 's near black in the glass with dark brown amber highlights . a quiet pour gives off a small off-white head with little retention and a thin right left over .  very full mouthfeel even feels a bit oily on the tongue . super smooth in the mouth . truly excellent drinkability here .
very balanced . easy drinker .  murkey dark red , with glints of blood red against the glass . small head with little lacing around the rim .  the mouthfeel is wonderful . silky smooth .

the aroma is amazing i get a little bready malt deep under the white wine and bubble gum aromas .  the beer had a hazed golden/orange color to it with a -finger of bubbly white head . retention was good but lacing was only spotty . whoa !  mouthfeel is smooth and velvety with carbonation perceivable at the very end of the swill .

lots of character in this nose . i pull off some roasted malt , dark chocolate , fresh cut wood , caramel , molasses , fig , and a tinge of brown sugar . overall this beer is very good .  a : this poured a cloudy light straw color with quickly dissipating white head .  the mouthfeel was the best part of this beer .

the smell is pretty awesome . just a thick rich , perfect scent for the baltic porter . it is a nice beer , the flavor could be better , but overall it is enjoyable  from swing top growler into snifter ... a- looks like a quad with no carbonation . an incredibly vigorous pour gives a few sparse bubbles .  had on tap at the blind tiger in nyc , pint glass appearance : mild haze to it , light amber color , great head poured smell : citrus , piney hop , sweetness from the malt taste & mouthfeel : brilliantly smooth within the medium body .

really wonderfully complex . body is medium with a velvety smoothness and a lively carbonation .  poured with a lavish brown head which was easily fluffed up with a swirl of the glass . the color was copper-almost brown and clear .  the body is perfect .

everything sweet and wonderful that you could imagine . gets more complex as it warms . t - chocolate and roasted , smokey malts . not super complex but finishes wonderfully . m - slightly thin but it ups the drinkability .  pours a bright golden color with a flourish of a white fizzy head that disappears almost immediately .  ever so rich and creamy in the mouth with soft and forgiving carbonation . medium-full in body .

smells incredible , like hickory or mesquite smoke and just a hint of the malt reminding me this is a beer and not beef jerky .  poured an almost clear golden-brown with a fairly substantial frothy head that subsided quickly but lingered in some form the whole time .  mouthfeel is medium bodied , extremely smooth , and lip smacking .

very enjoyable . the taste is sweet at first but then the bitterness hits .  a - hazy golden color , minimal head retention and lacing .  very enjoyable , with a medium body and creamy carbonation that is perfect for this beer .

nose has plenty of nice hops , lots of citrus , bit of tropical fruit , light fresh hop resin , grapefruit , pineapple , guava , lots of fresh tropical fruits . taste starts a bit creamy actually , a light malty base starts to come through , bringing a slight sweetness , but that is quickly cut down by the heavy hops , a strong bitterness starts to come through , lots of fresh musty hop resins , some tropical fruits , lots of citrus , light orange rind , hop oils , it even starts to get a little astringent , and the malty base has disappeared really quickly , leaving the hops alittle flat , almost like drinking hop water .  bottle - opaque black brew with a medium head that dissapate too quickly .  simply luxurious on the tongue . the drinkability is also very good .

head was a finger+ and a yellow/brown color ( grey poupon dijon mustard ? ) . smell- hickory wood smell and a hint of coffee . very good !  no head at all , but that 's probably due to the servers pushing it out in favor of more beer in the glass . was a light orange almost yellow color .  the mouthfeel is perfect for a stout .

it has a terrific aroma , fresh , floral , strongly hoppy . outstanding nose ! good though . hops were good , a bit more balance would have been better .  pours a nice mahogany colour with a thin light tan head . poor head retention with not even a thin film present after about a minute .  mouthfeel is superb , very rich and creamy , gently coating the palate and then closes with a clean , dry finish .

i love hops , and you get strong nostril stinging hop aroma up front . actually smells similar to a hop flower . t- surprisingly sweet , very strong . clearly much stronger than your average beer but still very drinkable .  a - pours a slightly hazy copper with an amber hue , thin layer of head , no real retention and no real lacing .  m- oh so crisp and so damn smooth over the medium body .

smells awesome !  kind of a mediocre hazy yellow with no real head , but i do n't really care too much about appearance so long as the beer is good , and this stuff is wonderful .  really excellent creamy mouthfeel .
s : what a wonderful aroma . at first peaty malt and toffee .  this pours a transparent medium amber with a half finger head dying away quickly leaving no lace .  excellent mouthfeel for the style .

i love the smell on this brew , chocolate covered raspberries . how can you go wrong ? the flavor is like the nose in a lot of ways but with a coffee twist so it keeps the raspberry sweetness in check .  slightly hazy and light orange / copper in color with a very thin white head that almost disappears immediately .  m ) rich , almost slick . rich , long mouth coating .

s : what a wonderful dessert smell ; a combination of vanilla , caramel and coffee ice cream . t : taste is super sweet roasted toffee malts with a generous helping of vanilla and some powdered cocoa , even . it tastes sort of spot on as a creme brulee , but i think i might have liked the aroma better than the taste here .  appearancel pours copper with many bubbles along the sides of the glass and a fairly large off-white head that dissipates slowly and leaves little lace .  mouthfeel is very good and creamy with good carbonation levels .

considering how bitchin ' the venom was , i wanted more a- deep amber with a thick creamy eggshell head s- smell was amazing ... .had a little more complexity than dfh 90 with with some etoh kick t- not as strong as the smell led me to believe .  another beer given to be from sideswipe . pours a deep black . no lacing .  mouthfeel : medium body with colossal carbonation make this an incredibly creamy beer . de dolle gets this perfect for me yet again .

one of the best smelling beers i can remember . those citra hops really bring it on the nose . tons of tropical fruits . just great stuff . taste- follows the nose . it 's downright tart . however , it gets a little muddled . i had one and really wanted another . this is a very good beer .  pretty much impenetrably black in color , with almost no head .  the mouthfeel is exceptional -- thick , chewy , syrupy , andincredibly smooth .

s - pine tree . big piney hop presense , and a little floral and grassy . very good stuff .  not a clue what it really was ( blank bottle ) at first but after reading the neck label , very happy to have . pours a beautiful chestnut brown which is impressive and a tall head ( a bit thin though ) . the beer seemed a bit hazy though , and the head fell very quickly .  perfect mouthfeel , actually .

it smelled wonderful . very sweet and aromatic , almost sour . it tastes pretty good too .  water vapors rising from it after and very aromatic of the tart cherries , mulling spices , and a little malt . color is maybe suffering as it 's got some brown in it - kind of a reddish brown .  mouthfeel is like silk with slight carbination .

i spent a lot of time taking in the complex aromas that hit the nose with this one . i was able to pick up loads of the toasted malts but also hints of apple and honey , and various spices i could n't single out . the complexity on the nose played very well balanced on the tongue . the alcohol hits , but it is very well disguised by the heavy ( but nowhere near overpowering ) malt sweetness .  appears clear gold with little head retention .  m - fantastic . perfect amount of carbonation , just enough to tingle the palate , complementing the sour flavor .

easily the best pumpkin beer , ever ? mayhaps . but the aroma ... oh my lord , the aroma . this is awesome . this is everything aroma in a beer can be . the taste is almost as shocking as the appearance in how it comes across ( frankly , after the aroma , a deep , hazy , dark brown color would have been my guess if i had n't seen it first ) . it 's a pleasing and easy drinking experience .  kudos to great divide for creativity . anyhow , belgica pours a non-threatening pale gold ( like a lager ) , but the sweet and spicy floral notes are prominent and welcoming . with an outlying hint of citrus underneath .  very thick and full with a near perfect carbonation . a bit dry in the finish .

the aroma was intensely pumpkin-pie like . sweet , spicy and yummy with lots of nutmeg , allspice and clove . the flavor was similar to the nose yet a bit dryer and more subdued . malty rich and a touch sweet up front . super spicy ( nutmeg and allspice once again ) in the center . pumpkin and brown sugar notes came through as well . a touch of hoppy bitterness was noticeable on the very dry , spicy , lingering finish . this was a very tasty and enjoyable pumpkin ale that hid its alcohol content remarkably well . i am a huge fan of pumpkin products of all types , yet for some reason i am usually disappointed with pumpkin beers .  this beer poured a dark golden straw with a tinge of reddish orange in the background . the head looked good , but quickly subsided to a loose knit lacy ring around the edge .  m : for some reason , the mouthfeel is great ! perfect balance of body and drinkability .

hershey 's chocolate syrup , as made by ghiradelli 's . slight kiss of bourbon and cherry scents , on the back end . best chocolate smell , from a beer , ever . decadent . extremely tasty . too rich for everyday drinking , though .  poured into a tulip from a 750ml bottle . a - pours a deep gold with a small head quickly disintegrates into a small ring around the glass , some lacing but not much .  the mouthfeel is creamy and frothy very smooth for a beer with so much flavor and strength .

smells fantastic , huuuge hop aroma . overall , this beer is very good , but i wonder if hops are dried before using them in beer for a reason .  hardly any head at all , even with a somewhat aggressive pour , gone quickly with no lacing to be seen .  the mouthfeel is gorgeously creamy and full , one of the best beers i 've had for feel .

the initial smell is sweet but there is a touch of charred wood which was very unique ( a good unique . the initial taste was very sweet , almost sickening .  pours a cloudy murky reddish brown with a one finger bubbly beige head that slowly recedes .  m- very creamy , milky texture .

pumpkin walks hand in hand with musty malt down the spooky nasal alley , when out jumps sweet heady spices ; clove , nutmeg and cinnamon . the trio beat up the other two and leave them in a ditch . the haunting cries of cinnamon become more evident as this beer warms , as does the toastiness of the malt . o : great witches brew with a lot of soul .  2006 version pours copper with 3 fingers of sand colored head . some lacing & head retention s : sweet malt & brown sugar t : sweet malt with hints of caramel & brown sugar up front .  whoa was it thick ! an outstanding beer , i was extremely excited to be able to say i 've tasted it . as it warms in the glass , the bite grows stronger . maybe this brew would be better appreciated by some experienced brewmasters , i thought it was a good beer but i ca n't justify rating it an a+ or 5 , because i would n't buy a bottle again . the two beers that ultimately create this beast are exquisite , but this monster was n't for me .

the nose kills me it 's so good , making me very excited for the first sip . i could just stick my proboscis all the way in to the bottom of the glass and drink this through my nose it feels like . definitely a winner . great yeast character in both smell and taste .  i 'm not sure if this is meant to be an actual belgian wit , but it does n't really look like it , with an only slightly hazed brassy yellow body and patchy white head .  the mouthfeel is some kind of amazing . this brew is thick , chewy , ultra creamy smooth and goes down like heavy cream . if you like your imperial stouts with an unapologetically brash , bold , slightly raw taste , but with a refined , well-mannered mouthfeel , then you 'll enjoy expedition stout immensely .

smell - delicious citrus high notes with an almost overpowering burst of hops .  in the middle it feels like sweet packets of oil filled tropical fruit juice bursts in the mouth . finish is quite bitter in a grassy/grapeskin way . note : good and solid but not unique or innovative .  there is nothing very `` complex '' about it , just a bitter hops taste and perfect mouthfeel . as mentioned , the mouthfeel for pale ale is perfect ... . perfect amount of carbonation and easy to pour .

the aroma is loaded with dark toasted malts with caramel , toffee and dark fruits . wow , the malts seem to explode into your nose . the taste like the aroma is dominated by the toasted malts with plums , toffee and caramel . wow , this brew is nothing short of delicious !  a : poured with a nearly black color , like light is getting sucked into it . no head , barely any lacing .  m : nice medium body with a light carbonation , perfect for a geuze .

s= like a lovely barleywine i guess . i was loving the nose on it . the taste is sort of strong sweetness to it with the caramel and a small bit of toffee coming through .  not much retention , but a bit of delicate lacing . pretty forgettable .  mouthfeel is where this beer delights ! so smooth and round , you want to swirl it around in your mouth ! mmmm .

the aroma was delightful , like a boquet of flowers with a sweet pale malt backbone , and a slight resinous tinge . i was slammed by the first sip , belly warming alcohol lets you know this is not a beer to mess around with . in my notes i wrote `` its boozy like bourbon or cogniac .  muddy orange-amber color with a 1/4 '' off white head , recedes but comes back with a swirl . leaves a little patchy lacing .  exceptional body .

s : nice , big candy caramel malt , some dark fruit hints and very good backing of citrus hops . big but very balanced . t : caramel malt , little hint of some dark fruit , faint citrus and slightly pine hops , fair amount of bitterness in the finish .  appearance : thin white head that dissapears quickly , dark brown but red in the light ( an `` amber '' bock that 's a dark lager ? hmm ) a nice color though .  i love the creamy texture and the suprising full body .

a : pours an orange color with small head , slight lacing down the glass s : smell is amazing ! ! very citrusy hop scents abound . very slight biscut scent as well t : slight biscuty taste up front with a citrsy bitter bite at the end m : medium bodied oily mouthfeel d : this tastes as fresh an ipa as you could get ... i 'm sure its not ... i live in washington and its brewed in pa ... great beer tastes just like i 'm at the brewery .  a- dark amber beer , a fine white head that fades quick s- clean nose , a piney hops aroma ( very strong ) , undertones of biscuit .  excellent texture with refined carbonation that leads to a pleasant creaminess .

the beer is dark and only on the pour could you see the dark amber color . the head hugs the glass very nice one of the best heads i 've seen in a bottle big nose on this beer it whafted to my nose while i was pouring it . there is a lot of aromas coffee with roasted malts and a mellow vanilla that works perfect together to start this is a dry stout not an imperial or big stout wit that said this is a great beer . the beer starts slightly sweet . a roasted nutty flavor enters .  beer pours a cloudy middle-brown like the ice teas you see in the plastic bottles . head is active and fizzy , like a coke , and it fades just as quickly . following the tart shock i picked up a nice blend of spruce/juniper and pear .  m-this is full bodied , extremely smooth , very inviting on the palate , it is quite creamy and carbonated just right .

smells absolutely fantastic . super-hop odor with sugary sweetness too .  a-pours a dark brown much lighter at the edges with almost a orange/red tint . no head present at all .  m - creamy mouthfeel ; very smooth and full d - this was a pretty solid brew from schlafly .

smell-like a slice of pumpkin pie as soon as i opened the bottle the aroma of nutmeg , cinnamon and of course pumpkin , exactly what a pumpkin ale should smell like .  from a brown bottle with a artistic painting of mostly naked people . in a word , wow . pours a somewhat unatractive poopy brown , the only negative .  mouthfeel is crazy ! amazing .

s- mmmm , ruuum . but , the smoke still comes through underneath the rum . t- this is really quite nice , almost liquor-ish because of the lack of carbonation ( there is just the tiniest amount ) nice smokiness upfront with the sweet tanginess of the rum dominating the palate in the middle all the way to the finish .  it poured very heady with a murky with a hazy-straw color .  mouthfeel is full , thick , smooth , perfectly carbonated .

nose is a perfect balance of malt pollen , floral hop , and citrus fruit .  pours a clear golden-orange with a loosely-formed white head , very little lacing left in the glass .  m : you tell this is a big beer just by the feel , it 's almost like i 'm chewing it with each sip . the carbonation is right on as well and finish has a touch of dryness ... perfect for a dipa .
smell is lovely chocolate liquer-like maltiness .  very pretty . clear .  perfect carbonation .

quads smell great . how many brews have a more complex nose than this ? i could wear this as an aftershave as the spices are strong .  a : jet black , no head s : traditional russian imperial stout , dense , licorice , oxidation , great t : dense , true russian imperial stout , cloying , deep burnt caramel taste , great beer , tastes like it has been aged for several years d : very good m : excellent  mouthfeel - super smooth and silky . low carbonation and a big body .

smell is great , incredibly hoppy , this must be very fresh .  750ml into a tulip . pours a somewhat muddy deep mahogany . minor medium bubbled tan head .  m & d : perfect carbonation make the mouthfeel nice , but the alcohol limits the drinkability of this beer ... not that i could n't easily drink a few of these in one session ( if only ! ) reccomended !

big fragrance , banana , malty sweet , hint of caramel . very tasty brew , a good beer to sit and sip . vol . rating .  pours a hazy gold body with a white head the quickly falls .  light , non-overwhelming aftertaste which i like , combined with a perfect amount of carbonation .

it 's fun a enough just smelling this beer , ca n't wait to drink it !  appearance is a bit disappointing on tap as there is no head .  the mouth feel is beautiful . covers every square inch with a silky sheet and balances it out with a good dose of carbonation .

s - wonderful aromas of honey , pears , lemon peel , floral hops . i really like this . t - smooth , controlled sweetness . d - just an awesome beer , i 'm so glad i can get this locally now !  on tap at bailey 's taproom poured into a snifter with virtually no head .  perfect creamy texture and good body and carbonation .

aroma : smokey ? coriander rules ! all in all , enchanting . appearance : oddly , viewed from the side it showed significant hazy , but it was clear when viewed from the top .  poured a red copper color , with no head , but had a potent hoppy aroma .  the mouthfeel is stupendous . rinsing this around the mouth gives a great tingling sensation that beckons more swishing about each swollow .

s : smells amazing ! hops immediately hit the nose and give you a first-hand experience of why it is called `` hopslam '' .  pours a hazy amber with hardly any head at all .  taste : very smooth , lemon must , dried grass , herbal , mild barnyard funk , slightly tart , earthy , bone dry . very drinkable as the tartness does not overstep the rest of the beer . bottle conditioning proves to give the brew ample smoothness . funk is modest and unfolds a bit more when the liquid warms up . a great geuze that wo n't kill you palate , a remarkable beer .

aroma is brett funk , cherries , raspberries , lemon and other red fruits ( even ripe tomatoes ! ) . taste starts very tart and lactic acid-like . amazing brew from cantillon , very complex yeast profile .  kinda opaque body , no head on my one ounce taste .  mouthfeel is rich , smooth , and silky . soft carbonation .

nose is strong , intense , dark fruits about to rot which someone spilt port wine upon - wonderful , very interesting . full bodied chewy mouthfeel . i 've no idea what the six herbs and spices are but i applaud the choices , excellent complexity . phenols can be the bane of a belgian , here they are aggressively , exquisitely blended .  got a new 12 oz bottle from beeronthebrain , this one is a different animal ( reviewed 21 apr 08 ) , this one makes me think dunkelweizenbock , tons of rubber band & fruittyness , a bit less boozeyness , less nose & better head retention & lacing . all in all certainty different , but not better than the 1st sample tasted in nc , late july poured an effervescent ruddy brown/red ( cleared quickly ) with one finger of off white head . average head retention & lacing s : booze , fruittyness & apple skins t : booze & apricots up front .  m : surprisingly light and smooth . excellent for style .

smells like hops first , then rye and a bit of medium caramel malt . beautiful nose . i 'd go crazy if i smelled this but could n't drink it .  a- this one pours a light copper with 1 finger of white head , some retention , moderate lacing .  indulgent , creamy mouthfeel . and i really ca n't get over how pleasurable the mouthfeel is .

the aroma is heavenlywith a boatload of skunky tropical fruit hops . there is skunkweed , mango , pineapple , grapefruit and pine in there ... wonderfully full and fresh . mouthfeel is smooth , sleek , with a dense body .  a : poured golden amber with a thin off white head w/ no persistance / lacing .  mouthfeel is perfection , smooth , crisp , with just the right amount of carbonation ... and the tartness in the finish leaves you wanting to pour more of that big bottle .

first pumpkin beer this year with a good head . the smell on this beer is intense . it smells like a very aromatic crumbled pie crust with light cinnamon with a whipped cream aroma .  poured a deep coke cola brown with a small off-white/beige head that settled into a thin lacing .  marvelous mouthfeel , so smooth , full bodied and mouth coating .

s - aroma is near perfection . there is definitely some underlying jp funk in the beer with slight tart notes . the belgian aspect to this beer is awesome in the nose . hints of banana bread some cinnamon rolls and gingerbread . awesome nose . t & m - wow .  the beer is a hazy pale golden color , not quite as cloudy as some wits i 've seen . head was about 2 and a half fingers thick and pure white with poor retention .  mouthfeel : very smooth body , easy to drink . nicely carbonated .

the nose is a sweet and sour explosion of tropical fruit , pineapple , fresh garden herbs , bright juniper pine , and bubblegum . the slightest breath of alcohol , caramel backbone , and some spice seeps through as it warms . a joyous aroma , i 'd like it in a body wash . the flavor is a tropical and herbal hop jungle . the malt bill is caramel and a bit buttery .  a- a pale golden color that pours with a small head , and several small bubble trains ( like champagne ) . m- a medium body , but i had this crazy sensation of tiny bubbles running through my mouth ... kindof like the micro-carbonation you get with nitro beers ... this strange carbonation seemed to give it a much creamier texture than i would have expected .  mouthfeel is superb , creamy , velvety , perhaps the best i 've had for this style .

s : this beer kicked me right in the nose and said hops ! ! ! m : super bitter , it says so on the bottle , not my preference , but it truly lives up to this , the rating i 'm giving this is very generous .  a - poured from a growler about 2 hours after purchase . minimal head . copper brown with a slight haze and a red tint s - grassy , yeasty but also sweet t - hoppy at the start that moves to malt and leads to a sweet finish with a little note of alcohol m - extremely pleasant mouthfeel , the previous reviewer said it best , its silky in the mouth then warm on the throat .  mouthfeel medium-full body with creamy carbonation . i am really impressed with the body on this beer .

s- lots of juicy hop aromas coming from this . flavors do n't live quite up to the nose , but are well done . love the big hop aroma , wished for a bit more hop flavor .  a - pours a dark brown with with no head or visible carbonation .  very creamy mouthfeel for a hefe , which i enjoy .

very aromatic ! an quite unique to me . it has some musty yeast , cloves , and hints of orange .  a - poured out a clear , burgundy/copper color with a small , tan head that had lots of bubbles .  m- full bodied , creamy , thick luscious mouthfeel .

every sip is beautifully complimented by the floral , sweet scent in the glass . more of a beer experience than a beer indulgence ... nice to say i tried it , and enjoyed it , but not at all drinkable on a multi-bottle level . i see it 's charm , and i 'll bang it.. but i will not propose .  a - a nice cloudy brew thats mostly orange with a bit of a brownish tint to it . quarter inch head fades rather quickly but there is some decent lacing .  rich , full , thick , round mouthfeel , with a soft carbonation that is really terrific .

unbelieveable aroma . straight hops ! nice aroma ! seems to be lacking flavor up front but finishes great . grapefruit , pine and some unusual flavors that i enjoyed but simply could not identify .  another great tap at 38 degrees , on to the beer : looks reddish violet in the glass . no head formed on the pour , so one could confuse this as fruit juice upon first look .  good moderate carbonation and a crisp , dryish , oily slick , chewy , creamy smooth full bodied mouthfeel .

s : citrus , very bright ! spicy yeast , apple and pear cider smell , some nutmeg .  the appearance of this almost reminds me of killians ( my old mainstay ) , due to it 's lack of head , and deep orange coloring .  smells great , coffee and chocolate notes right up front chocolate & coffee flavors , dry and bittering at the end mouthfeel is very smooth . much smoother than i remember when i had it last .

s - reference quality barrel-aged barleywine . surprisingly little overt alcohol too . m - full-boded , sticky , chewy , and just plain weighty - perfectly suited to the flavor profile and abv . d - i finished this faster than the other two , lower alcohol , beers .  pours dark orange with a head that is reminiscent of a b-movie .  taste is also quite yeasty , lemon zest as well , the carbonation is bubbly and soft , not harsh , incredibly creamy and smooth for a hefeweizen .

the aroma is a stand-out , a very complex mixture of ripe fruit , tobacco with a hint of smoke , chocolate , molasses , vanilla , brown sugar and various spices . a very nice scottish strong ale and another bottle may give it a better score .  a - poured with no head , no visible carbonation .  mouthfeel is exactly what it should be for this style .

smell kills the idea that this is a stout right away . big floral hops smell that just blows me away . this has to be one of the best smelling beers ever . some sweet malt comes through in the background but it is really the floral smell that stands out .  almost zero lacing as well . i was expecting aventinus but hoppy but this brew looks more like a hefeweizen .  m : great silky smooth feel . definitely a creamy feel .

i think i 'm in love : ) hops , hops and more hops in the aroma ... miam miam ... i 'm thirsty . i get grapefruit in the aroma . the foam sticks very well to the glass . i good imperial ipa .  2005 bottle , fun graphics , from spiritus fermenti amber and red body , looks prety nice but poor head retention and lacing .  fantastic ! d - i could easily reach for another .

smells incredible , good enough to eat !  appearance - slightly hazy amber body . medium small llight tan head with good stick and medium retention .  m : a perfect 5 in mouthfeel ... and i feel strongly about that !

yummy berries !  i have to admit that i bought this beer because of the bottle , but i am very glad i did . it poured with very little head and what there was quickly went away .  m - super smooth and creamy . i rate this exceptional compared to some of the other tripels i have had - it is surely the strongest aspect of this beer .

i love the aroma of this beer ! just a hint of diacetyl butteriness , but i really did n't find it objectionable . mouthfeel is surprisingly thin , with some grapeskin-like astringency on the finish . drinkability is very good . a 22 oz .  pours a thick cola brown to light black no head or foam what so ever .  mouthfeel is very nice , i enjoyed it a lot .

wow . just wow .  ) taste : just too syrupy ... lambic was overpowered by the taste of del monte canned peaches in heavy syrup . lambic tastes come forward if you let it relax in your mouth for awhile . quite metallic . drinkability : would have been even easier to drink had it not been so sweet .  m/d - full bodied and very creamy . lively carbonation carries the beer through your mouth .

no real lacing but it does have some legs smell : smell is decadent ; probably one of the best smelling non-sour beers i have encountered . overall/drinkability : one of the best-smelling non-sour beers i have encountered , but the high abv and hugeness of it really detracts .  a - pours a hazy , rusty amber with a piss foam head into the snifter . this beer just looks unpleasant .  mickey 's ice has an amazing mouthfeel to it , one of the best in my opinion . the carbonation comes on strong then fades to a creaminess .

s- super funky , nose hair curling , acidic vinegar . amazing . past the sourness is an amazing plethora of red wine , green apples , sour cherries , oak , berries , lemon , sweet grapes , more oak . smells amazing . t- not as tart as the nose suggests , but sour as shit nonetheless . o- another amazing sour from avery .  beer has a slight chill haze . a bit lighter in color than i am used to , but it has nice character .  mf - this it where this beer shines the most to me . very nice carbonation that tickles your mouth as you savor it . also reminds me in some ways of an eisbock albeit less vinuous and more carbonated and roasty .

very enticing ... s- thank you surly for this aroma that i have now gotten to experience . in your face grapefruit , pineapple , oranges , and just a tiny bit of pine/wood to add some complexity . i literally sense no malt sweetness in this to back up the hop aroma like you get in other beers , and that is great by me ! t/m- very bitter forward . o- very good ipa .  appearance : pours a slightly hazy , deep amber body topped only by a thin ring of white bubbles .  m : close to perfect : rich , thick and creamy .

intense smoky aroma of cured pork , proscuitto , smoked ham , even bacon . a very nice smokiness , later on it lessens in concentration allowing some bready malt and rye aroma to show through .  a : poured into a snifter a rich and deep dark brown but a very thin , tan head .  body is creamy and rich , with mild carbonation , pretty strong abv , but alcohol is not dominant in the taste i enjoyed this beer the more i drank , very impressed .

this is a great smell for a beer -- a strong ale with sweet pineapple ( not tart ) , burnt raisin and roast hits .  i was very pleasantly surprised to find this in cans . dealing with trash when you have to haul it 30 miles up in the hills of nc is n't fun when it 's bottles so that limits your options for decent beer . very drinkable , smooth full flavor lager .  perfect mouthfeel for an ipa.. substatial , chewy but not syrupy.. drinkable but nowhere near being called 'light ' .

i get the strong scent of deep woods to begin - green , piney vegetation , quickly followed by the continuing characteristic from their holiday beer - a thick and wonderful spicy gingerbread . no year is ever an outstanding beer , but it never lets you down either - consistently good .  it appeared a little lighter than i would have expected with a reasonable head .  a nice , balanced beer with a clean taste and a smooth , exceptional mouthfeel .
smell is fantastic , pure belgian .  a : clear amber . not much head - could be due to pour .  the mouthfeel is fantastic if you sip and swish ever so gently .

it feels very uncomfortable .  appearance : the appearance was a nice redish brown typical bock look . there was not a good head however .  mouthfeel - superbly smooth and creamy , especially due to the carbonation . overall drinkability - this beer is all about the smoothness of the mouthfeel , and inoffensive characters .

s : fruity notes of sherry , some alcohol , fresh fruit , cherries , peppers , some wood and spices . biscuits and toffe , and also some strawberries . very hoppy .  ruby chestnut hue , with a light haze . initially thick head readily recedes into a thin , meager beige ring .  palate : full bodied and medium carbonation . great feel . full bodied and enjoyable .

bomber poured into a gruss aus munchen mug ... both received from zorro in the beerfest bif a- deep orange with red highlights ... big pillowy off-white head that leaves great lacing on the way down and takes a while to subside ... looks delicious s- intense and complex with some elements atypical of the style ... big sweet fruits ... caramel malty goodness ... spices ... clove ... raisin ... and big earthy grassy hops ... smells like a great oktoberfest but bigger and hoppier t- similar to the smell ... but everything is soaked in booze a little too much for my taste ... finishes with a hint of toffee and chocolate ... burns a bit on the way down ... still tastes like an oktoberfest though m- tiny carbonation bubbles feels good on the tongue ... despite the heavy sweetness it does n't feel syrupy ... medium bodied d- limited by the booze and the burn on the back of the throat this is an interesting take on the style ... and one i 'd love to try a different version of  served in a foothills pint glass that is mine to keep a crystal clear copper orange with a thin head that diminishes to nothing .  mouthfeel is dead perfect for the style , full and solid .

dry as the day is long with a rich , complex hoppy nose , long in earthiness and fruit with pine and cotton candy . on the palate this is a bit aspirin-y , a nice , medium body and a finish that 's almost crackling with resin . less than pliny the elder , and it 's far superior to their standard ipa ( `` far '' being relative , that 's a solid beer as well ) .  pillowing , fluffy head . i had no orange to garnish my glass with so i did feel a bit let down . mouthfeel is nice and solid .  thick , syrupy and silky smooth with just enough carbonation to tickle the tongue . goes down so easily - incredibly smooth .

s : wonderful . chocolate and coffee and malt . love it . first 5.0 i 've given in a review in this category . t : good to very good . having trouble separating the taste from the mouthfeel , because it is much more thin and watery that i expected .  thin amber with a ruby hue . frothy , white head that quickly evaporates to a small pool of bubbles .  : ) silkly smooth mouthfeel ! awesome .

smell was incredible . tons of rich , dark chocolate and some coffee . surprisingly hoppy and quite dry ( almost bitter ) on the back end . this definitely was not one of the easier drinking oatmeal stouts i have tried , but it was one of the most interesting .  a-gold with a tint of amber . thin cream head . fairly light for an ipa s-impressively strong hops and citrus presence . m-medium carbonation with a great creamy finish d-hmm i actually like this a lot ... .i 'm very confused by the other peoples ' reviews ... the taste is n't too complex but its otherwise a great drink . i could have many glasses of this with complete satisfaction  the mouthfeel is unbeatable . it is almost chewy and just enough carbonation .

m-thick chewy thorough coating of the mouth o-good beer with exceptional aroma that does n't completely carry over to its flavor .  with a vigorous pour the beer left a small white head that left little lacing on the beer and the appearance is a nice golden color . this beer is very light and decent carbonation make this beer a very drinkable beer for the summer time .  mouthfeel : this is where it shines . smooth and heavy and very warming .

s- i really love the nose on this one . brown sugar and raisins start it out with a nice sweet base . fantastic . t- the brown sugar and raisins that i could smell come back in the taste and lay out a nice sweet base .  pours a cloudy brown color with high carbonation and a thin lace of head around the edges of the glass .  mouth is light-medium bodied excellent carbonation .

the smell is the first thing i noticed after opening the bottle . even before pouring the smell of intense hops wafts from the bottle . overall all a great beer , but not one i would session .  poured into a sam adams imperial tulip glass ... 2010 d bottle . a- pours pitch black ... 1 1/2 finger fizzy tan head that disappears quickly and leaves no lacing ( kinda like cola ) . not much to look at and admire . other than the fact that it 's nothing special to look at ... it sure is something fantastic to smell , sip , talk about , and appriciate !  the beer sits in your mouth with a crisp , well-rounded feel and swallows with a tingly freshness that is quite delightful . the taste is a tad leathery ( this is a positive thing ) and the crisp dryness is not overbearing .

wonderful aromatics ! overall impression : a wonderful holiday tradition .  it 's a cloudy amber in color without much head .  the mouthfeel was exceptional , heavy bodied with a warming alcohol presence .

open bottle and pour into glass and immediately catch the great aroma . pours a nice , lightly hazed , dark orange , with a decent head , leaves great lacing on the glass . this beer has an incredible aroma , a great , bright , hops/citrus/grapefruit/floral smell , very strong , but not too much for the style . great hop dominated flavor , with a decent malt backbone to support the hops , very nice . leaves a nice hop aftertaste , not too bitter though .  appearance was surprisingly dark with a ton ( as in too much ) head which spilled everywhere .  mouthfeel is so silky .

really nice intense aroma with piney hops , citrus , sweet malts , and brown sugar .  poured this 750 ml brown bottle into a tripel karmeliet glass . the head was lumpy and white , leaving tiny lace and a ring .  mouthfeel is also top notch . low carbonation that goes down very smooth .

smell is sweet and very fruity , scents of fig , apple , tobacco brown sugar , rum , brandy , raisins , and dates . extremely complex , too much really , it is like a mouth full of fruit juice concentrate .  1/6 inch head of an off-white color . poor retention and poor lacing .  m- exceptional swirl inside your mouth , allows the flavor to be enjoyed even more .

smells of apple skin , young pears , a slight funk , and a fresh fallen rain on a field of wild grass fill the nose . i 'm getting excited . with gorgeous lacing that looks like a painting of a true belgian saison .  a - dark brown with hints of ruby when held to the candle light . this one supports a head that is only a half of a finger before reducing quickly to a collar of flimsy tan foam .  m : mouthfeel is fantastic . very creamy with just the right amount of carbonation .
wow this really has a lot going on in the aroma !  poured a slightly hazy gold . average white head .  mouthfeel was exceedingly smooth .

straw yellow with a nice white head . smells really floral , fruity , white peaches , juicy . not really intricate , but fruit forward and a solid sour . not much funk overall , but a really nice , crisp and well done sour .  picked up a growler last night - poured into a pint glass - first brew from mad fox , i 'm excited . a - a slightly hazy light orange body . the head starts at about a finger of white foam that dies to a thin film that leave little lacing .  the medium - heavy mouthfeel is perfect for this type of beer .
smell- very fruity . huge smell of pineapple and citrus .  decent retention and decent lacing .  overall = exceptional mouthfeel but the taste is just average .

this is wonderful . t- a lot different than the smell .  pours a nearly black color , hardly any head or lace ... perhaps a slightly off bottleif so it did not effect the flavor much .  m : full bodied with an awesome carbonation feel .

smell is huge brandy . lots and lots of brandy followed by a strong sweetness . one of the most drinkable barrel aged beers i 've had and one of the best smelling beers i 've ever encountered  pours a chestnut brown red , with no head -- even after a vigorous pour .  mouth feel was exceptional , with a naturally carbonated soft bubble feel on the tongue . not to strong on the hop flavor department but the mouth feel is exceptional .

more precisely , it smells like my french press when grounds have been in there for a day or two -- very bittter , very impressive . taste is candy-sweet , and heavily rosted , like ingredients have been roasted repeatedly .  pours a deep amber with little head that quickly becomes a good lace . there is also visible carbonation bubbles and a quick swirl brings that nice head back .  the carbonation is spot on , it carries the beer extremely well on the palette . this drinks like a slightly hopped up brit but not so much to kill you with hops .

aroma is quite amazing - it smells like a fresh baked pumpkin bread or cookies . has a really rich spiced bready smell with a nice blend of spices . too sweet and just way too much in general .  the nice little head is the saving grace but to be honest not a very enticing looking beer .  silky smooth and creamy mouth feel . such body without being cloying .

amazing . the taste is full of cherry as well , and just a bit of tart flavors going on .  a : pours a dark , slightly hazy , hazel-amber with a very thin white head that reduced into a faint collar leaving no lace . looks a little bit like soda .  superb feel .

smell is huge . molasses hits up front , dominating all else . everything is taken to the next level by the great alcohol aroma . taste is sweet , fruity , and boozy , nowhere near as complex as the smell . super roasted , the only balancing factor is the bitter alcohol on the finish . drinkability is actually quite good , if you 're in the mood for a strong old ale . overall , not the best i 've had , but a good beer nonetheless .  a three way split into a tulip glass.the color was a mirky light golden color , like a belgium style ale.the head was a bit off white , with a soapy looking foamy head , diminishing to a coating on the top of the glass .  the piney hops dominate the flavor , but a snappy finish makes it 's hard to gripe too much . exceptionally well balanced . in spite of the bold hops , it drinks with amazing ease .

immense aromas of alcohol , vanilla , burnt malts , woody hints like oak , dark chocolate . overall , this was an intense beer for me and it had some great qualities .  the appearance is of a pretty typical pale lager .  exceptionally viscous and savory body starts creamy and full on the tongue , developing a wheaty wetness and light carbonation , ends dry .

the aroma was amazingly complex , with sour cherries and bread-dough , plum , ( maybe some raisin ? ) and mild malt . the taste was focused on sour cherries and mild roasted malts , chocolate and alcohol . overall a fantastic beer , and a great surprise .  pours dark mahogany with a 1.5 '' tan head . not much lacing or head retention smell : big malt roastiness and cofee notes taste : fruitness is quickly overan by toasted malt assualt .  pours a rich crimson color with a creamy off white head that stays put thru out the duration of drinking it , deep caramel aromas along with some milk chocolate quite sweet.absolutely sublime creamy mouthfeel just glides down smooth , flavors of caramel and brown suger hit ya up front but there is a decent dryness midway keeping it from getting to sweet.i wouldnt say earthy maybey more herbal in the finish , its quite heavy a one or two and done for me.this is a doozy a great winter beer , it would real warm ya up , not that i need that down here in nc .

absolutely beautiful aroma that reminds me of the finer czech pilsners , not that that is surprising . in short , a superb smell . the taste is harshly bitter with almost a hot pepper bite .  a dark brown/reddish beer with a faint head .  m - the feel is surprisingly rich for the genre , smooth and oh so drinkable , nicely done !

the smell is wonderful . grapefruit and pine . love the smell , but let down by the taste .  pouring into a glass results in a ruby red color with barely any head .  first thing i notice when drinking it is the fabulous mouthfeel - so soft and creamy yet a rather thin body .

the smell on this brew is fresh hops , almost but not quite citrus , and a sweet malt forward honeyed tingle . the flavor has some spiciness to it but on the whole was actually quite unimpressive i thought , including the mouthfeel in that i was suprised at how thin and bland it tasted and felt .  12oz brown bottle , i really dig the graphics on this one . quite frankly im a bit too eager to drink the bastard to look very hard , though . not as opaque as i had expect , looks like a decent ipa . a very clear burnt orange with just a hint of amber . not a whole lot of bubbles coming from the bottom of the glass , but theyre definitely there . not a whole lot of lacing action , but there is some . the amber is almost an afterthought .  perfect carbonation , sits in the mouth just right , a touch of oiliness , slightly drying in the end , and all around wonderful .

i was able to enjoy this one , but i really wish the taste had lived up to the aroma .  almost no haze at all to this golden-ish brew . fluffy bright white head is `` to specs , '' but i want to know that this sucker is alive and well .  mouthfeel is wonderfully thick .

i thought it delicious . aroma is tons of pineapple , and is totally delicious . flavor is also quite good although not quite as good as the aroma .  pours a burnt orange/light amber with a thin layer of happy , little bubbles . the ale forms a ring around my glass . there is also an extra soft scent of maple syrup .  mouthfeel is perfect , thick and creamy but not too syrupy , and with none of that trub you sometimes get in the bottle , maybe im just not used to drinking from a tap .

really a very unique and pleasant nose . the taste for me on this brew is all hops .  light passes through when held up to a lamp as a very dark red . slightly assertive pour yields almost no head . average at best .  the mouthfeel fits this beauty of a beer - it is thick and pleasingly rich . the full amount of suggested aging did this beauty wonders .

absolutely decadent . the taste is not nearly as decadent but still very good . the oak really stands out as a great flavor here .  pours a clear and crisp very pale straw color topped by a fizzy there-and-gone white head . enough funk to make things interesting .  perfect carbonation .

s - as soon as the beer started pouring you get the classic smell of an ipa and with pliny the smell is exceptionally strong . the aroma of the pine in the beer drew me in immediately .  dark amber color .  mouthfeel is perfect .

smell : a smorgasboard of aromas starts attacking you from the moment you open the bottle . chocolate ( s ) , coffee , caramel , alcohol hitting on you with no mercy . fantastic ! i love it anyway .  pours a dark golden yellow with flashes of red and green tint . a slight film for a head with slight lacing . there is a large malt presence with some orange , and peach in the nose .  perfect bitterness and carbonation . exceptional .

finally , an american w-bock that nails the nose ! mega bananas and mad cloves , bro ! some chocolate , but takes a backseat . mmmmm , flavor is damn tasty as well .  pours a dark brown color that is boarderline black . a bit cloudy but not bad . a soft tanish to white head that faded quickly and no really lacing to speak of .  m - perfect texture , it seems somewhat oily and it slides over your tongue like a sweet hop blanket .

pours dark brown , ruby highlights.the aroma on this thing is outstanding . huge hop aroma of pine and citrus jump out of the glass . it really detracts from the drinkability too .  poured into my brand-new fantome tulip . a- golden yellow , thin head , tiny bubbles on the outer ring .  mouthfeel : nice creamy thick body drinks exceptionally well ! drinkability : the abv and the flavor profile holds this one back for me but the mouthfeel helps in the drinkability department .

very pleasing , very playful like a baby pig with wings ... good persistence of aroma .  a - pours a nice , clear amber , with a finger or so of head . barely any retention , and not much in the way of lacing .  the mouthfeel on this beer is really creamy and smooth ( it has this milk-shake texture to it ) with medium to high carbonation and moderate to heavy body . although it lacks a little complexity of the usual coffee , oak and vanilla notes , it makes up in mouthfeel and drinkability .

first off the smell on this one is amazing . i smell vanilla , nutmeg , clove and of course pumpkin . still , if you do n't fall within the states that schlaflys distributes to , this is a good second .  poured a hazing orange-golden color with moderate white chunky head .  carbonation is moderate with a medium-full body yet still decent drinkability . the one thing that really stands out with this fest is its remarkable smoothness , definitely the smoothest octoberfest ive had .

the aroma was incredible and the taste was nearly as good . i will have this one again for sure !  it 's appearance is light orange with a whispy fading head .  much lighter body than the bottle of extra stout i just had ; also a little more tart which was what i was looking for . roasted malts and hard water . mouthfeel is where it really shines . smooth like silk . goes down like water .

super rich . t - some alcohol heat up front , bourbon , dark fruit and licorice .  pours with a nice thick black body , but with a thin head , much thinner than most stouts .  m : quite thick moderate carbonation , love it .

the nose is beautiful . molasses , coffee , oats and almost a berry-like aroma .  poured a warm and cloudy russet colour with a fading caramel cream tinged head of no real staying power .  body is big and very creamy and smooth . mouthfeel of melted velvet .
the aroma is of delicious coffee and chocolate flavors .  appearance : amber color with 1 finger of head that fades quickly with minimal lacing .  goes down incredibly easy with a silky mouthfeel .

smell- flowers , belgian hops , honey , and candi sugar . extremely fragrant and balanced , with a superior fullness to the aroma . taste- a most graceful and balanced display of all ingredients , with not a single element outdoing the others . very good , but not perfect . outstanding and well worth the money .  a : pours a clear golden yellow/orange with loads of visible carbonation . head is small , not long lasting , creamy texture , & white color .  generously carbonated feel . goes down like nothing .

smells good ... real good . sweet chocolate , touch of roast , lactose and some definite oatmeal . one of the best smelling oatmeal stouts i have smelled , hits all the right notes . taste does not quite live up to the nose , but still a decent offering .  poured from a 12oz bottle into a tulip . this saison poured a hazy golden/amber color with a minimal white head that disappeared almost immediately .  head retention is poor , almost non-existent , a little dissapointing smell is not what i was expecting , surpisingly subtle , with a nice malty sweetness taste comes as a wave , roastiness , coffee like , followed by mellow sweet malt , bitterness like dark chocolate lingers in the mouth , pleasant after taste wonderfully full mouthfeel , thick , fits the beer 's complex flavor the alcohol is apparent , but not overpowering , easy to sip , not exactly quaffable , but pleasant

very inviting . flavors were mostly sweet , with fresh-from-the-vine honey crisp apples , nutmeg , cinnamon , and a touch of marachino cherry juice . solid on the drinkability meter for a 9 % beer - good combo of aromas and flavors , but the aromas were the real winner here .  pours a murky orange with a 1/2 inch white head that fades to nothing .  m : this is one of the thickest stouts i 've had in a while - very similar to dark lord in it 's heavy , cream like thickness that coats the mouth very well . d : good drinkability , but it 's definitely a sipper .

one of the better smelling beers i 've come across .  this avery offering pours a hazy yellow with a very thin white head ( little to no retention ) and light body .  m - perfect . perfect for an imperial stout .

smells pretty damn amazing and changes as it warms up . i 'm very glad i had to chance to try this , but i prefer kbs .  750 ml bottle , served in a big wine glass at 61 f/ 16 c. attractive deep copper color , clear in the first glass , slightly hazy with tiny suspended particles in the second glass ; surprisingly clear for the brewery . small yellow tinged head that eventually ceases to exist entirely .  mouthfeel- super creamy , lower carbonation and silky smooth .

aroma is amazing with the hint of cherry , of course . beautiful amber color and pours well .  pours a dusky , golden-peach hue with a bit more yeast haziness than is appropriate for the style . plus , the minuscule egg-carton white head recedes quickly to a thin wisp and ring of foam ... not much lacing or retention .  m - perfection - just enough hint of carbonation to tickle the tongue .

s : great smell , so complex . really sweet and hoppy . malty over & undertones . excellent nose . got ta be the best part of this brew .  appearance : pours a very clear golden straw color with minimal head , lading , and retention .  m - slick and warm on the palate with an oily texture and chewy mouthfeel . this stuff glides down the throat with ease . d - this brew is exceptionally smooth and creamy , making it extremely easy to drink .

one of the best smelling beers i 've ever had . this is amazing ! and canned pineapple ! or pineapple sherbet , with a metalic ( aluminium , i dont know why since it 's a bottle ! or maybe i 'm just used to good ipa 's . it is good , but not definitely not outstanding .  a fairly aggressive pour leaves a very small film of white head on top .  f - medium/full bodied beer that 's creamy smooth for sipping .

minimal head retention & lacing s : raisins , dark candi , charred toffee & oak t : boozey raisins , tropical fruit , dryness & more booze up front . charred toffee , pineapple , oak & vanilla as this warms . finishes dry , with more toffee , booze infused apples & raisins mf : syruppy with minimal carbonation , too hot booze-wise not a huge fan of calvados , liked the norman cider better .  pours a dark brown with a thin tan head that is short lived .  the mouthfeel is great , perfectly coating .

the smell is wonderful , fruity at first , and then chocolatey , with maybe a hint of coffee .  this poured a nice clear copper with a little white head .  magnificent . drinkability is only average , as this is one once in awhile brew , not intended for or enjoyable on a regular basis .

smell - absolutely wonderful hops smell . its best qualities are appearance and wonderful aroma . taste and drinkability are a little challenging but tolerable .  pours a cloudy lemony amber color with a thinnish white head that seems to dissipate quickly . one curiosity is that all of the hill beers i had were very cloudy , not sure if that is the way they are supposed to be or if we had trouble pouring .  mouthfeel is phenomenal for a regular ipa . thick like a dipa , and very smoothly carbonated .

the aroma on this is fantastically interesting . the lavender is really the first thing i pick up , being a fragrance enthusiast before a beer enthusiast , notes used in perfumery always stick out to me . there 's also some nice citrus aspects here , and a touch of sweetness , probably attributed to the honey .  a : very dark amber , almost brown . no head to speak of , and what there is retreats to a ring around the snifter immediately . the beer appears a bit murky . this is a great american beer .  one hell of a mouthfeel with this beer .

the massive , whipped egg-white head on this tarnished gold beer offers up an awesome bouquet of fresh lemon . lemongrass , herbal hops , sour yeastiness , white pepper , and just a touch of pine or maybe even juniper .  pours black with a thin tan head . it left a little lacing at first but not much overall . my only criticism is i would have liked a little more head retention and lacing .  mouthfeel is exceptional . perfect amount of carbonation and such a smooth beer going down .

s- an amazing smell . really amazing . dark fruits , cherry . delicious dark milk chocolate- fudgy . o- an incredible smelling and tasting beer , but not quite perfect on the mouthfeel . still a really awesome beer .  at any rate , this beer is a cloudy peach-caramel with orange accents , forming a thin white head with poor retention and lacing .  it 's mild to medium body with the really great mouthfeel makes me want to swish the beer around my mouth before swallowing .

there is a distinct smell of fresh grapefruit that is unbelievably pleasing to the nose .  i was already a fan of belgian beers but this revolutionised my ideas of what a fruit beer could be . there was not a great deal of head but fizzy enough.the character of the beer was like no other i had tasted .  the mouthfeel is where this beer really shines and seperates itself from the pack .

definitely one of the top 5 hop aroma beers i have ever consumed . it is so so so inviting from the aroma . i totally love beers with this full citrus hop aroma . the taste is totally different than the nose . it makes you think initially that it will be bitter and hop centric but then the malt character makes a huge stand and controls the main flavors your tongue perceives . it is quite pale malt dominated and i really appreciate this because overly resiny beers make me gag . i could pound this to no end which is dangerous considering the abv , lucky it is quite high in $ $ $ so this will limit my consumption . this is a very tasty and simple straightforward dipa .  the beer had a light tawny body , with a thin but persistent glass ring , but unfortunately had weak lacing .  the mouthfeel is medium bodied with appropriately low carbonation , and a silky , creamy texture . the mouthfeel of this beer is one of the best i have encountered in a beer .

this stuff honestly smells stellar ! it smells like christmas .  this one poured the traditional choc cloudiness with a somewhat dull caramel orange/brown . the head was pretty modest considering the vigorous pour .  the mouthfeel was great . very smooth , thick , and rich .

plums are right out front on the nose . more than i expected actually but it works very well with the other dark fruity esters typical of the style . pleasantly yeasty while the alcohol is detectible in a brandy-like aroma .  the body is opaque topped with a tan head of small bubbles . little retention and lace .  the mouthfeel on this beer was truly exceptional . i 've never had a beer with such great viscosity that managed to avoid being sticky .

huge cherry and oak on the nose , followed by an earthy mustiness and barnyard funk . a bit boozy . a damn fine flemish sour ; ranks with the best .  a : light dull gold .  throughout , the carbonation is perfect -- not too much , not too little , just right , and the overall mouthfeel is full , creamy , and well rounded .

it is wonderful . notes of oak , barnyard funk , and vinegar . virtually no lace , but nice oily looking legs . this is amazingly tasty . for $ 9 per bottle , i glad to be ableto pick this up whenever i want !  a : light hazy straw yellow . half finger white head with decent retention and lacing .  the feel is right on for the style .

s : it smells great ! very citrusy/fruity and somewhat spicey .  a simple golden colored brew that is perfectly clear and bubbly . the head on the other hand is less than with a not very showy cream colored froth that seems to evaporate .  mouthfeel : medium to full bodied and incredibly smooth . just a hint of carbonation tingle .

smell is fantastic , floral hops and a sweeter citrus smell fill my nostrils with goodness .  poured from a 22oz into a pint glass ( shared with coastiefish ) appearance : quite dark , rich brown color , and poured 'thick ' but not too thick .  the mouthfeel is incredible for a red ale , just so thick and smooth .

aroma is amazing ( it was perfect when it started but as the beer warmed it fell off , still giving it a 5 ) . it is so hoppy , piny and wonderful overall . no harshness , the level is strong but not overpowering . its great . beer is medium to light in a body with a creamy mouthfeel .  a- thick foamy head , lots of bubbles . not a huge fan of the color , it 's like a moderately pale apple juice .  gorgeous mouthfeel .

s-tropical & citrus fruits and hops dominate . i could have sat there for 10 minutes with my nose in the glass , but many beers to get through on this night so i carry on .  pours red-amber , with limited carbonation and no discernible lacing .  mouthfeel is crazy smooth and thick .

nose is rich thick and chalked full of browny like chocolatey sweetness , which is a lovely experience all its own .  a-bright copper with a thin off-white head that flares up with agitation but quickly reduces to a thin veil and leaves zero lace .  mouthfeel : full-bodied . medium carbonation . very soft and velvety on the tongue , like the texture of melted chocolate ice cream .

absolutely beautiful . it was heavier in my mouth then i thought it would be , which cuts down a bit on the drinkability , but still good for two or three pints probably .  12 oz bottle poured into a nonic . pours a chocolate brown-amber color with amber highlights and a thin tan head that remains for less than a minute .  m : i have to say that this was the most impressive aspect of this beer . oftentimes porters end up a little too thin-bodied , but this one had a very full body , and combined with the very nice carbonation made this a pleasure to drink .

aromas are great , and very powerful . noticed them from the pop of the bottle .  stout pours with no head . no head . expedition stout is not the darkest , but truly opaque and black .  creamy , smooth mouthfeel goes excellent with the flavor profile .

hood uses over 3oo pounds of pumpkin and winter squash per batch of this beer . the squash is then roasted to caramelize its fruit sugars and is brewed with a judicious blend of molasses , cinnamon , allspice , nutmeg , and ginger . pumpkin ales have a long history of being brewed in colonial america . this beer smells and tastes like a-1 steak sauce , and though this may sound odd ( and unappealing ) , its actually intriguing and palatable . this is a fun beer with great appeal .  pours hazy , a translucent coppery orange in color . good sized head develops but dissipates quickly and with all the sound of a soda head disappearing .  mouthfeel was silky smooth with a mild bitterness on the tongue .

s : very chocolatey , pleasant nut , cotton-candy esters , dark caramel , herbs & a hint of citrus . d : very good , but a little big to session .  a- clear caramel colored body with a thin white head and some lacing .  m : the carbonation is gentle , making for a perfect silky , but thick , body .

good hops smell but that takes a back seat to vanilla , blackberry , wheat , port ... i need to drink this now !  poured into a tumbler it forms a 10 mm yellowish white head that leaves nice lacing . the color is light amber with slight cloudiness .  mouthfeel is a regal velvet ( likely due to the oatmeal ) , coating the mouth with a smooth creamy layer . so smooth . excellent .

this beer had some wonderful aromas of scotches , alcohol , fruits , chocolates , and more and it tasted like more of the same . rogue should start making this stuff again .  ( a ) - pours a clear yet cloudy orange color that produced a decent white head with decent retention behind it .  m - very full bodied , nearly stout full .

the aroma was delicious , full of pineapple , citrus hops , floral hops , tropical fruit esters and a little alcohol . the complexity of chinook , columbus and especially the citrusy simcoe hops was quite enjoyable . the mouthfeel was semi-smooth , the body medium and the carbonation medium as well .  pours a super clear golden straw color . head fades to a small ring and leaves no lace behind .  m - beautiful mouthfeel and impressive balance for such a powerful brew .

smell is amazing tartness , wild funk and light fruits with some sour grapes in the background . the grapes could be from the esthers and funk or the chardonnay , smells like wine . finish is a little more funk with a light vinous tinge on the back end . far more tame than i expected , i 'd love a little more aggressiveness .  another trailblazer from pierre celis . malty sweet , yeast , and a faintly musty aroma . hazy brown , with a fading head , some pleasant mustiness comes through here as well . spicy , yeasty flavor , with hints of fruitcake .  mouthfeel is phenomenal , like liquid velvet down the throat , and with a good bit of carbonation to tingle the tongue .

the scents are amazing ! i notice a woodsy , kind of floral or piney smell , with a great hoppy undertone . man this smells good . mouthfeel is definitely better than average for an ipa -- balanced , yet light , intricate nonetheless .  bottle into red wine glass . pours a pale gold orange , with a thin , soapy off-white head .  the best part . smooth as butter , no alcohol detected . fantastic beer , the barrel aged version i 'm sure is outstanding .

smell is really nice . toasty nutty malts and a blast of cascadey hops .  pours a clear ruby color with a small khaki colored head that quickly settles into nothingness , looks flat .  m : awesome , aside from the hops , it may be the best part of the beer .

silky smooth mouthfeel , incredible floral/citrus hop aroma . taste = too much orange .  12oz bottle poured into pint glass - thanks to biglobo8971 for this extra pours a tepid , hazed burnt orange with literally no head , retention , or lacing .  almost like adding a slice of lemon to water . mouthfeel is rich and luscious . this is really an enjoyable beer .

s- bananas and clove ( like with a wheat beer ) , and a big nuttiness . duh , it smells like fresh baked banana nut bread .  a : poured into a pint glass : no real head to speak of , but a nice orange-amber hue , a bit lighter in color than i 'd expected .  m & t - first impression was really just the perfect carbonation , great frothy and fluffy mouthfeel and just all around benefit to the palate . very nice , but the mouthfeel was absolutly pefect .

appearance clear orange/yellow body with carbonation that drops instantly ; massive and rather sturdy , billowy white head that comes forth in a big pour ; fabulous lace smell bitter and more bitter ; big fat hops ; a bit spicy ; and a light dose of alcohol ; this is what i want from an ipa taste models the nose with more malts ( caramel , bread crust ) coming through midway but the citrus hops still run the show ; pink grapefruit and grain aftertaste mouthfeel moderate body for an ipa ; smooth base and a crisp edge ; very light hop sting balanced with a light oily sensation drinkability damn thats a boatload of hops ; theres easy turnover ; the hop stick smacks hard but if you 're the hophead , it 'll spin you back around easily so youre ready to roll again high hop tide warning ! this ones good from 50 yards .  pours a clear golden color with a decent head that settles to a small lacing . typical looking pilsner .  mouthfeel is very luxurious and pleasant .

there 's also almost a medicinal smell to it . by far one of the best smelling beers i think i 've come across . i had random smell flashbacks over the next few days ... t : just like the smell , dark candied fruits really dominate .  unfortunately , little lacing is left as i drink .  m : the mouthfeel is well balanced .

this is a really nice stout obviously rich with strong coffee aroma and flavor . the aromas are huge . like a big piece of double chocolate cake and an esppresso . a very drinkable stout . too bad it 's just a seasonal .  the color is nice and dark - i imagine a dark scotch ale with the added darkness of charred barrel ageing . head is short lived . not really getting any lace here .  very nice d - i would drink this all night if i could , but at 11.5 % , that is n't exactly possible .

s - very impressive aroma - chalk full of pine and complex citrus hops .  appearance - well , beside the lack of head i noticed that it 's really not all that dark . it looks nice , just not super dark .  the mouthfeel was amazing , drinking the beer it had the typical bite of aftertaste that normal ipas have , but i took a drink right when we left the pub and i still could taste the hops about twenty minutes later .

s- i love the aroma , this one is packing a lot of hops . overall , i think this is a very good dipa that i 'm glad i tried .  poured a cloudy yellow color with an average frothy off-white head that mostly diminished with fair lacing .  mild carbonation , super creamy body , smooth .

smells of every imaginable hop aroma - i was blown away by the bottle version and somehow on-tap it 's even better . i love the way this smells . tastes similar to how it smells , just not quite as intense .  a : deep dark brown to black in color . no head but a sparce line of bubbles barely formed a ring around my glass . no lacing .  superb . d - this is a tasty beer , but the fusel alcohol character and high alcohol in general make me appreciate it less fully .
