a- beautiful crystal clear honey color with mild white lace . s- honey , raisins , toast , biscuits , almonds , barley , alcohol , cane sugar , vanilla , fruit . very spicy , very alcoholic .  notes from 5/14/10 pours a hazy dark brown with a slight red hue . head and lacing are nearly non existant .  m - the feel is as smooth as i 've ever had . unbelievably impressive ! the feel of this beer is really what sets it apart from every other dubbel i 've ever sampled .

s -- grapefruit bomb . there was also a wonderful pinecone and resin smell . this is one of the strongest beers i have smelled . t -- definitely able to taste grass , pinecone , and hops .  batch # 9386 ( a ) - pours a hazy goldenrod color that produced a mediocre white head that dissipated quickly .  m : mouthfeel is awesome ! slick , heavy and chewy . it gets fluffier and chewier as i swirl it in my mouth .

s : holy chocolate and coffee batman ! this is extremely interesting . i 'm not sure if i 'm drinking a chocolate latte or a beer .  ap . pretty , clear , golden brown with minimal head .  and the hops are well placed and enjoyable m- probably the best thing about this beer almost chewy , think , and creamy , with a long lasting bitterness d- very nice balanced easy drinking dipa , a little different than ones ive had lately , not an over the top hop attack that hides some of the flavors .

smells like a crazy bouquet of citrusy hops , but i can still detect a hint of malt . this may have the best aroma of any beer i have tried to date . perfectly balanced . body is perfect for the style .  a-pours a very carbonated bubbly golden yellow color . a little pale , with lots of bubbles rising to the top . the head is thinner and bubbly and dissipates quickly without a trace left . it is quite malty forward and lighter on the sweetness ; but it is pretty solid .  gentile mix of flavors , not super complex , but with an incredible silky mouthfeel , and an oragne glow that makes it look great .

a bit of a disappointment given its amazing aroma but still very good . mouthfeel : medium-bodied and well-carbonated .  10 ounces served in a snifter a - looks to be a deep brown that reveals some reddish tint when held to the light . there is really no head on the beer to speak of . a decent sized ring around the glass sums it up nicely .  love the feel in my mouth .

s : the nose is great . it is almost reminiscent of the cantillon funk smell , which is great . smells very tart and sour . overall : it is a solid gueuze , smells better than it tastes , but it is still good .  vey dark amber/ruby in color , with almost no head at all .  mouthfeel : wow is this stuff smooth . very silky and perfect carbonation .

smells like a lemonade/orangeade mixture but in a really inviting way . not sweet or sugary like the aroma would suggest but that just must be from extreme dry-hopping and the oak somehow . bitterness is perfect , no traditional hop aromas , no earthiness , pine , woody , flowers , just fruitiness . crazy .  pours an effervescent amber/copper with a finger of cream colored head . average head retention & lacing s : citrus hops , light breadyness , pineapple & lemon grass t : follows the nose , nice grapefruit snap , slight breadyness & some woody/herbal hops hiding in the background up front .  the mouthfeel is excelent on this one though , very smoothe and crisp and very drinkable .

s - wonderful citrus hops .  a : clear , golden yellow , white head , very little retention or lace .  mouthfeel is great , really silky and smooth , perfect carbonation , very dry and a nice warming sensation .

nose is fantastic : huge and sweet , dried fruit , cotton candy , maybe some aprioct and kiwi in there too . surprisngly light alcohol , given the abv . overall , a delicious and really unique saison . maybe not one i 'd go for every day , but an excellent beer nonetheless .  big cheers to gnomeking for this pours a slightlty hazy amber/tea coior with a 3 fingers deep sand colored head . minimal lacing & zerohead retention .  insane drinkability ; perfect body , perfect bitter/sweet balance , and did n't even seem alcoholic .

intense complex sweet malts . earth , brown sugar , molasses , spice , dark honey and walnut and hazlenut scents . very enjoyable , sweet , smooth and pleasant . -oelergud  poured into a stemmed pils glass it forms a fluffy white head that eventually falls to an outer ring .  the mouthfeel really shines here , it 's bright and crisp and creamy . good body .

s : huge hop aroma . big citrus hops and inviting sweetness . smells as good as any dipa i 've had yet .  fairly average in appearance .  mouthfeel was perfect for me ... .slightly tingly , but at the same time silky smooth and gentle on the palate .

dissipates after about 2 minutes.. smell - orange zest , maybe some banana , coriander , citrus.. has a nice sweet subtle smell , i like it .  the beer pours a golden color with a thin white lace head .  m - thick and creamy , very full bodied . complemented by the right amount of carbonation .

s - cinnamon , vanilla , wood , bourbon , chocolate , custard and i swear a bit of curry spice in this sweet and fun aroma . i 'm picking up some minerals , cherries , and prunes too . d - after the really attractive nose , this beer was a huge letdown . underwhelming , and not worth the money spent .  pours a orangish brown with a off white rocky head that quickly dissipates . does leave a nice lace on the glass though .  this is a big bodied , chewy brew with medium carbonation , and a full palate .

very much exceptional . incredible ; this stout , like parabola is just ace with the chocolate .  reviewed 8/31/2009 ( bottle ) : orange clear color body , small creamy off-white head , diminishing .  m - mild carbonation precludes an incredibly smooth and delectably creamy body d - fantastic .

the odour is lovely . rich malt , milk chocolate , slightly burned grains , alcohol , sweet-bitter citrus , candy .  appearance : the beer had a nice nitro head when served but the head discipated and left a little lace . i was n't sure why the head did n't last that long with the nitro .  mouthfeel is smooth and fantastic as is the drinkability .

a giant tan head forms and for the first time ever i 'm almost worried about my snifter overflowing . smell : fruity and tart . hay , apples , and cherry . this was awesome and i 'm glad to have a whole growler of it .  a hazy yellow in color .  soft and very creamy feel , this is a dream to drink .

complex in the nose . similiar to an old ale . lots of vineous qualities . dried up malt , english hops , alcohol , cherries , and bits of bitter chocolate . nose finishes meaty , with figs and subdued whisky . aggressive and young . very good beer now , aged in a bottle for a year or 10 would put this beauty over the top .  this one poured out a slightly hazed ruby-orange-amber color .  mouthfeel : amazingly prickly carbonation after all this time -- a nice counterpoint to its velvety body .

big hoppy nose , with fresh oranges , and a bit of cut grass . sweet and hoppy , playing less off the flavors of the nose and adding new ones like grapefruit and pine , with a sharp pepper bite to close .  vigorous pour of this 12-ounce bottle into a new belgium chalice produced a small tan head over a cloudy hazy dark amber-walnut body . head quickly disappeared into a thin ring .  very earthy and dry . notes : excellent balance , but a very mild smoke beer .

s - hop aroma is wood , not necessarily pine as some others are . exceptional smell . t - just as it smells the hops and malt blend perfectly .  pours a murky copper with a small , moderately lived head with very light lacing .  m - smooth , a delicate sudsing that tickles the palatte , and quite refreshing with a subtle warming effect from the alcohol .

the aroma was simply amazing . sweet and complex with strong notes of green raisins , dark fruits , figs and molasses . slightly woody and `` old . '' compared to the aroma , the taste was a bit of a letdown initially . brown sugar and molasses notes came through strong . raisins , prunes and dried figs were also quite apparent . this beer drank like a charm .  nearly black in colour and a bit murky as well .  luciously smooth and creamy in the mouth , soft carbonation across every cubic centimeter .

s- perfect . a hop monster being over taken quickly by malty goodness . t- amazingly hoppy and bitter , but still almost balanced by caramel malt that makes it delicious .  this golden beer was quite nice . clear in color , ok carbonation but not much head .  very full , creamy body that 's quite impressive for the abv .

i love that as soon as i removed the crown of this beer the aroma of brett seemed to permeate the kitchen , and then the house as soon i poured this in a glass . the aroma really explodes with brett , but i also get a bit of lactic notes and a slight tinge peppery leather . the flavor here is the low point on this beer , as the aroma can not be topped and it really looks amazing .  a - hazy light yellow with a little bit of white head at first that went away immediately .  the mouthfeel is perfect . it is slightly carbed but still rather flat .

smell & gt ; absolutely fabulous . i want to eat the nonic glass . it 's malty and rich . sweet like turbinado sugar , with a smidge of alcohol .  pretty much a typical looking german lager , dirty gold in color under a thin head that sticks around a few minutes before its almost total disappearance .  pure velvet mouthfeel here , no better bock .

overall , this is a very good beer with an unbelievable chocolate smell and taste .  draught @ ctriver brewers fest : this one poured a fairly clear , orangish-golden color . there was a small white head to it .  mouthfeel/drinkability- the smooth , foaming mouthfeel is perfection for the style ... it swells and quiets to the point of not being able to discern bubbles at all .

the aroma is full of citrusy hops with a tinge of lemon balm .  a - it pours a transparent golden amber with a thin white head that disappates fairly quickly s - fruity , citrusy hops upfront balenced fairly well by a mild , but sweet , malt backbone t - a great balence of pine and citrus hit you up front and quickly fade into a semi-sweet finish m - light bodied and refreshing .  m : silky and creamy . d : i 've never had more than one chocolate stout at a time , and so i do n't know if i would get sick of a beer if i overdid it .

aroma brings bright layers of pink grapefruit , lemon zest , mj , apricot , tangerine , etc ... this is one great smelling beer . this ipa has nice balance between bitter and flavor in regards to the hops . not quite as bright and juicy as the aroma led me to believe , but rather , a little rough around the edges , which is n't all bad in an ipa .  in a pint glass , it 's too bad they did n't go the extra mile and have a weizen glass . the beer is hazy yellow to orange in colour , and had just a thin ring of white head . the glass was filled near the top though , and that may have hindered any head retention .  taste and mouthfeel : it 's incredible what the bourbon did to this beer . the mouthfeel is superbly creamy .

the aroma is slightly sweet , citrusy and hoppy with a hint of malt .  a - poured an essentially solid brown-black , a small mocha coloured head did n't last long s - the chocolate is there but smoothly subtle , there are biscuity roasty malts , and even a little banana , very interesting t - starts with a roasted coffee , then the carbonation clears that out to leave the smooth chocolate and bready flavours , and there is just a little tartness m - it is chewy but still a little thinner than many stouts , there is a bubbly tart feel that eventually left my mouth feeling nicely coated d - well it is a stout , but relatively thin for style which enhances the drinkability , and the flavours are generally subtle but they work nicely together , could definitely enjoy a few bottles  mouthfeel : medium body with tingly carbonation and a dry finish .
aroma was good . pumpkin pie spices .  pours dark brown with a small quickly fading head .  mouthfeel is honestly fine , medium bodied , good carbonation .

it has a nice aroma , inviting you to enjoy its bountiful pleasures .  pours a dark ruby colored beer into my stone old guardian glass ; i pour rather slowly and receive no head whatsoever , so , thinking quick , i grab a clean spoon and give a hearty stir ! a finger thick head builds with the agitation , and hangs around for a minute , but leaves no lacing .  a medium-light body with good carbonation . nice texture .

a gift from a friend-of-a-friend , who tells me it was the ipa . s : prominent floral aromas , followed by pine and citrus . t : lemon/citrus , pine -- your typical fresh ipa aromas..at first .  two finger white head with average retention . leaves very little lacing on the glass .  the mouthfeet was soft and light , and the overall beer was close to a cream ale , but without the cooked corn flavors .

o : while the beer smells good , the flavor is a definite let-down .  pours a clear golden yellow with a lively white head that forms nice , but thin lid on the brew after a while .  medium to full bodied and smooth .

smells strongly of cascade hops and light spices , which is contrary to the taste , very light in flavor .  a : pours a cloudy orange with a tiny tint of red . ridiculous white and fluffy head .  has a fairly refreshing clean finish , and nice body .

the smell is of luden 's , which i enjoy . the flavor is super syrupy and thick with a cherry candy flavor .  33 cl bottle into an orval chalice , a : pours a ruddy sepia with small white head , solid retention .  big mouthfeel .

minimal head retention & zero lacing s : big time grass & lemon . t : grassy with hints of lemon up front . more lemon & whear tartness as this warms .  looks really ruddy/cloudy , an amber/brown .  the mouth is light and carbonated well .

the aroma is bready caramel malts and melon with some piney resiny hops .  pours a cloudy golden orange almost honey like color . big frothy white head , that disappears very quickly .  m : medium bodied , relatively light on the carbonation . it feels like a nice fall drink .
smell is sweet and fruity with the expected coffee and chocolate aroma .  pours a coppery gold with a white head that disappears in a hurry .  m - nice mouthfeel . does n't feel thin .
smell : vanilla and some caramel . no oak at all .  spinnakers blue bridge double pale ale pours a bright yellowy gold with almost a non existent head .  mouthfeel is medium and appropriate .

the aroma was very sweet and of chocolate .  street , now chuo park avenue , outside gate two kadena ab , okinawa . i really like this beer . this is a great hot weather beer and brings back great memories .  mouthfeel= good mouthfeel drinkability= average .

draught at brewpub , copenhagen . toasted malts , milky chocolate , banana , nuts , butter and pears in the aroma . medium-bodied with notes of toasted malts , banana and acidic green apples with touches of fudge . malty finish of over-riped bananas and fudge with disturbing notes of green immature apples .  a : orange , slightly cloudy , quite a bit of `` sediment '' floating around .  it does have that nice slightly creamy mouthfeel that bitburger and a few other quality pils have .

smell is definitely all spice and coriander . very strong .  a pale golden/amber ale with a decent lacing , sea dog opens with a delicious bouquet of fresh blueberries .  the mouthfeel is nice and smooth and finishes clean .

d - ya this started off good with the smell , but just went down the drain with the taste , pretty unpleasant and the mouthfeel was just bizarre .  a : decent . good creamy head with a few thick bubbles that is slow to go down , matching a somewhat cloudy orange/rust/amber body .  ah well ... mouthfeel is fine - it 's not as heavily carbonated as originally thought ( from the head ) . smooth and even .

the nose has strong and pleasant hop character - which is the best attribute . interesting appearance and aroma ... but once this thing gets in your mouth you 'll forever regret it .  a - nice black color , dark tan head . reddish see through color at the edges . not quite dark enough imo but its only the look s - vanilla , boubon , soft oak , ahhhh ... t - vanilla , bourbon , soft oak , sweet malts .  medium , almost creamy mouthfeel with low carbonation .

the smell of malted milk balls , a touch of hazelnut syrup , & a ticklishly sharp edge of caramel & nutmeg .  chouffe houblon dobbelen ipa tripel is a very cloudy , pale yellow ale with many particles and a huge , white , rocky , foamy head .  3.5 m quite beefed up by the hops presence and the malt which is welcomed .

just a little thin and not quite as interesting as the nose suggested . apples and husky malt in the finish .  blame the growler , as this beer had better head and retention directly from the tap . the beer is muddy looking , with a light brown melted caramel color to it . things get much better after the appearance .  the body is on par for the style and is nicely carbonated .

s - an herbal/woodey/almost cedar type smell wraps the malts up and kind of mixes with some citrusy hops . it 's a bit fruity smelling , almost some pineapple , not bad .  it was a pretty enough golden straw color , almost with a greenish tint . the bottle that this was poured from was stored well , and it was poured carefully , yet the beer had bits sediment suspended in it , which did n't settle out .  mouthfeel is pretty good but at this point who cares ?

s : some citrus and pine hops with a bready and moderately sweet backbone .  pours a cloudy yellow/gold with a pure white head that is large but fades quickly . head is sort of soapy , and there is no lacing because the foam simply slips down the side of the glass .  not knowing this was in the `` russian imperial stout '' style category , i was expecting more of an american stout , only with a little more body and alcohol . the texture changes over time as well : in the earliest stage , this one is thick and creamy , but it becomes lean at the finish . this and eel river 's triple exultation would be enough to satisfy the most discerning beer drinker 's palate for some time .

s- almost like how i would invison a dark chocolate syrup smelling ; very sweet . also has a huge scent of malt . no real hop scent detected .  a - pours a slightly hazy orange/copper with half a finger of tan head and one incredibly disturbing looking floater . head has decent retention , but does n't leave much lacing .  the taste is bitter , more of the citrus but it just taste wrong or something , it 's not very pleasant and leaves this as a long , lingering after-effect , mouthfeel is medium and decently carbonated .

smelled of tart citrus and floral hops .  a : pours a dark amber color with a half-finger of head that recedes into a light film on the brew . no lacing to speak of .  the funky yeast just does n't quite meld with the hops . its very spicy on the finish as well , and it feels like the hops and the natural spiciness are fighting with each other for control of your palate . light and zesty on the palate in a good way .

the aroma is more enjoyable than the taste .  served in a goose island chalice , matilda is a dull dark gold with a light wisp of white skim .  mouthfeel : medium-bodied with lots of carbonation and smooth .

smell is piney , earthy , woody , resiny , caramel , tropical notes and bitter . a little underwhelming compared to a fresh bigfoot though .  pours a golden color with virtually no head .  good on the mouthfeel , but rather one dimensional .

( s ) - dry , with alot of fruits of fig , cranberry , & cherry . light sweetness of honey & butterscotch . ( t ) - fruity , with the same fruits from the aroma . bitter .  pours an almost pinkish golden amber and topped with a pock marked virgin paper white head . leaves a cap but like none lacing .  feel is good - creamy , medium bodied , well carbonated .

i see the future ... a buzz ... some ps3 ... a mostly opaque caramel brown color in the body with an off white large bubbled head with a tinge of gold . the aroma really comes strong with dark fruits , some fig , plum and currant . there is an acrid off-flavor in there , which is entirely distracting , like iodine .  pours out a deep and dark ruby colour ... thin tight head , with some minimal lace .  the feel is almost chewy and very dry .

s- nice english ale smell ; sweet floral hops piled on a firm foundation of hearty grains .  lots of fine sediment . small barely-there head with light watery lace .  mouthfeel - light-medium body , well balanced carbonation .

nice . some butter shows up in the nose as it warms .  made an average appearance , poured a barely opaque ruby hued milk chocolate brown with a small foamy off-white head that quickly settled into a thin lacing , moderate carbonation .  the palate is smooth . the aftertaste is absolutely repulsive .

smell : strong dark sweet fruits like raisin , figs etc..sublte belgian yeast taste : sweet , biut no overpowering .  a trace light in color for the style , but it has decent head retention and a nice fruity/malty nose and palate .  it 's the opidomy of light , the smoothness of velvet , and the price of mexican dreams . degrading this beer comes at a great insult to anyone with a ba , mba , phd or techinical certificate for the lessor of us . i swear the old texts , properly translated , would describle jesus actually making water into natty . it 's constant . this beer is the appertif of beers .

the aromas coming off were initially very strongly of molasses with a slight coffee undertone , evolving to a more balanced nose of molasses and malt .  head stays for a good while s- smells identical to apple pie .  mouthfeel pretty good , medium carbonation and mouthfeel .

no real head ( it is on cask afterall ) s - rather sweet . malts , chocolate and maybe a little fruit . some malts and chocolate but not nearly as good as the scent . m - watery with only the mildest of tingle .  appearance 3/5 very dark brown and clear with garnet highlights and a medium head that dissipated into a thin collar rather quick and left some lacing .  very clean finish and very easy to drink , it goes down very smoothly .

nose is sweet cocoa , coffee and some lemon grass . this was a trojan horse stout ... looks wonderful , smells nice ... .thick chewy mouth feel to die for ... then a taste profile let down ... salt , metal and blood tastes do not belong in stouts i drink .  a : solid black ; the carbonation is not pronounced , with the head dissipating relatively quickly s : sweet , luscious , lively aroma ; i detect grape overtones t : beautiful taste , much like a barleywine style ale , but , as you know , wheat as the base of the beer ; sweet , well spiced m : thick , rich d : very inviting a beer to brood by .  carb level and mouth feel is actually quite pleasant , though .

caramel , floral and toast aroma . notes of wood/oak . toasty taste , burnt/carmelized sugar , bread and biscuit .  a : amber orange , hazy , no head s : there are citrus and floral/pine notes present but not pungent like other ipas ... looking forward to the taste t : very mild hoppy/floral taste , a hint of honey , and a citrus flavor throughout .  m -- mouthfeel is soft to crisp with a light to light-medium body .

extremely hazy to start . big fruity nose , heavy with oranges .  12oz brown bottle , no freshness date or lot code to be found . decanted carefully to leave as much of the yeast behind as possible . still slightly cloudy , very well carbonated with tons of streamers rolling up from the bottom . small white head 's not really to style .  m : thick and heavy , but not cloying .

best buy date is october 2009 aroma - a slight bite but 95 % of this beers nose is made of blackberry , which is nice . appearance - cloudy yello with no real carbonation visible .  excellent beer . i was forced to try it this summer as i searched for something decent among the bcm at the local gas station near the beach . this style is usually a bit too hoppy for me , but after about half a glass - i was really enjoying it . bitter yes , but probably appropriate for this style .  interestingly enough , the mouthfeel is rich and creamy -- what i wish so many other hoppy/piney beers could achieve .

light caramel , sweet creamy chocolate , sugary chocolate biscuits and mocha coffee redolances play on this beers bouquet , hints of barley and molasses vie for attention but are not competition for the overwhelming coffee and chocolate perfume . overall , this is a good standby sweet cream stout .  pours a very thin looking wheat ale . there is a nice golden color and a thick white head , but it does n't have the good unfiltered look i like in a wheat beer .  m. mouthfeel is where this brew plays it safe with a nice even carbonation and medium soft body .

on first sip , this beer grabbed me . i liked it right away but after a few sips the sweetness got to me . it is very thick and syrupy and all i could think of was dr. pepper . once the thought of dr. pepper was in my head thats all i could taste and i could barely finish it .  double banger , all right . questionable start , a clear amber / orange , but head was hard to get unless you aggressively poured , then a ivory top arose , but only for 5 minutes or so .  smooth and soft , mouthfeel alone is not bad at all .

the smell was very pleasant with distinct roasted malt characters and even what seemed like burnt wood .  the appearance was hazy , as expected in this style . i was a bit disappointed with the poor head retention . while the head lasted , it was an off-white colour . no lace .  m - spot on here . medium body , good carbonation .

smell : strong bitter coffee ... smoke ... sweet sugars ... chocolate ? nice and sweat but if i wanted weak coffee i would n't use a french press with fresh ground beans .  note : now titled the chef 's wicked chocolate beer appearance - 3.0 dark brown , almost black in colour with a beige head that faded fast .  it is quite smooth .

smell is nice , biscuity , caramel , very toasty malt , touch of chocolate and roast , a bit of brown sugary sweetness , but more of a nice bready and biscuity malt character . aroma is nice but the sour character is not good .  poured with no head , characteristically of most old ales . nice malty color ; the aroma is of very sweet malt and alcohol for sure !  mouthfeel was the most notable portion being medium/light , crisp , and coats the mouth nicely .

smells like dark fruits , raisins , malty with some brown/burnt sugar .  pours a lighter amber color with good clarity . the head was ok with tight white bubbles .  finish is cool and crisp with lots of carbonation .

bought in a 750ml in northern kentucky , there was no head at all when poured into a goblet . the taste is not at all what i consider a belgian trippel . the lack of carbonation , abv , and excessive fruitiness remind me more of a malt liquor than a belgian style . overall i was extremely dissapointed .  half a finger of even dark white head that has semi long retention and leaves little lacing .  the palate is smooth .

s - smell was unique . alcohol mixed with some sweetness and spiciness .  the head corresponds to this , relatively flat with some slippery lace left behind . the color is light brown where light does pass .  m - smooth with a slight carbonation sensation .

lost abbey tasting glass a - medium-to-dark amber , with a decent brownish head , but not much lacing s - toffee and brown sugar , with a hint of apricot t - sweet malts are present right away , but it 's also noticeably watery .  the beer poured a cloudy golden/honey color with only a finger of white head and only minimal lacing .  the fizz lasts the perfect amount .

also has an interesting dry , earthy aroma . quite promising . taste- not to bad .  appearance : a two finger head that is frothy and foamy with poor retention .  the beer is light and refreshing with just medium carbonation , so it leans towards the smooth side .
very rich smelling in a subtle way .  appearance : medium golden yellow , leaves soap style suds on the glass while drinking .  mouthfeel is light with good carbonation .

$ 2.75 from pints o'plenty . some rich raisiny notes . vanilla . bready . i like it . taste : so yeah , sweet , caramelly , and raisiny with a bit of toast .  a : poured a hazy straw into an american shaker pint with a white head that did n't hang around and left no lacing .  banana , pear , perhaps a citrusy taste as well m : good creamy mouthfeel d : i think what throws people with this beer is the appearance to it , looks like a miller lite .

the aroma is pleasant - noticeable pumpkin , some spices - clove , cinnamon , and nutmeg ? overall an interesting brew , the aroma is nice , but the flavor is n't .  a - pours a clear golden yellow w/ a finger of head . dissipates pretty fast .  m - it was crisp , sharp and smooth . a light bodied ale with a dry finish .

smell is powerful mango . fruit bursts forth . but very sweet .  pours a clear , mild amber with little to no head .  mouthfeel - i actually have no complaints in this department . it 's comparatively crisp and the carbonation is appropriate .

smell : caramel spice cake with a hint of grassy hops taste : caramel spice cake , up front , with a developing stone fruit character by mid-palate ; after the swallow , the caramel sweetness tends to dominate mouthfeel : medium body but too fizzy drinkability : two bottles on the same day from french broad and one a bigger gusher than the other ; just not very happy with this brewery right now and , while this beer is a decent drinker , it is a bit too sweet  fraoch is a light amber ale with a bubbly white head that mostly diminishes .  medium-light body with a pleasant carbonation and an apparent slickness and oiliness .

the smell was good with a nice bready yeast fresh bread smell , but that is about the best i can say about this one . will not buy again  took a growler of this home from john harvard 's in pittsburgh . a : pale golden in color , very clear . seems a pretty solid pils .  a light texture at the front , that gains weight as it reaches the back of the palate to become more medium bodied . the comforting look , pleasing aroma and solid feel can not bring this beer up .

smell is strawberry jam/jelly , biscuit , and strawberry candy . overall , this is a pretty average beer with a better smell than taste .  a - clear on the pour , it 's black in the glass with a tall but short-lived tan head .  the malty flavor remainded in my mouth minutes after tasting . i had a trappistes rochefort 8 a couple days ago , and i am not certain of the age of this beer , but it tasted like a younger , more crisp belgian beer .

provides plenty of aroma ... fruits , oak with a hint of the high alcohol content .  5.2 % abv a basic : light yellow body with minimal head . no frills look really .  the medium bodied beer , feels pretty good , with a nice creamy quality to it , and a complimentary amount of carbonation but the spices pretty much ruin any redeeming qualities the beer may have .
the smell is that of a sweet tart berry fruit .  anyway , appearance is classic white wine .  mouthfeel - a full body whit lots of carbonation .

it is a pleasant smell though , let 's see how it tastes .  poured a clear golden yellow . the small , fizzy head quickly faded to a film of lace .  good mouthfeel ; much more lively than the original pour indicates .

smells strange for a weisen . smells nice . does n't taste very good .  a- one inch light tan almost white head with weak head retention and no lacing .  m - medium bodied , crisp , good carbonation . this aspect of the beer is fine .

s : not what i had expected . cherries smell tart and at the forefront of the beer . interesting . t : abv is way to naked here .  pours a very light orange / yellow color with extremely light ( almost clear ) yellow highlights .  ehh.. let me start by saying i adore irs 's . the anise , in my humble opinion makes this beer taste absolutely terrible . do n't get me wrong , you still get the nectar like , frothy delicious chocolate experience in the background , which is almost good enough to save this beer for me . theoretically the sweet/bitter flavor of the yeast should play off of and enhance the chocolate and coffee flavorings , but it does not . a change in proportions could make this a great , unique brew .

nose : sweet hoppy smell . all pine and pineapple .  rather dark , almost venturing into flanders with its reddish-copper hue and disappointingly small head .  m : solid in this department , full for a brown ale , even a bit creamy , with somewhat heavy carbonation .

aroma was actually real good . sweet apricot , granny smith apple , almost like a desert wine .  notes appearance : nothing too distinct here just a nice golden look .  the mouthfeel is tasty and slightly creamy for a pilsner , but i am liking it .

overall : this smelled pretty good , but the flavor had qualities that i very much dislike in many high abv double ipas .  nice head , but not long lasting .  mouthfeel is again average . fairly light with a decent amount of carbonation .

very pleasant . maybe i got a bad bootle , but this was the bitter-est beer i have ever tasted .  bottle at 42* into a franziskaner weizen glass . a : this pours a bright golden color with a half-finger of fizzy white head that dissapates quickly .  mouthfeel -- medium-bodied with quite mild carbonation . very interesting .

a : cloudy pale yellow in color with a nice white head , very yeasty looking . s : sweet malt with spiciness in the aroma . t : very sweet and bitter at the same time , with an orange zesty finish .  a : pours a murky dull orange color with pretty much no head ... there are carbonation bubbles visible on the side of the glass . whatever the case , the few big bubbles of off-white head do leave some patches of spotty lacing on my glass .  body is quite good and so is carbonation .

the smell is very nice . the taste is of sweet malts , there is no fruit notes and a very faint piney hop taste that is almost nonexistant .  '' poured a clear straw color , with a modest whie head that dropped in milliseconds . not a terribly great looking beer .  m - full and smoothh d - this is a decent stout .

it 's not too spicy but there is a sweet , yeasty banana aroma that is satisfying enough .  l - brown w/red hues in color , the small beige head went away in a hurry not leaving much of a ring or lacing .  felt good , good carbonation , but not very drinkable . raspberry .

aroma was sweet enough to be pleasant , but not so sweet that it smells like a calorie stuffed dessert .  clear and tawny colored , poured with a small white head that dissipated quickly .  the mouthfeel is quite good .

quite full , and rather pleasant . the first sip knocked me back with a cringe ; overpowering tart came through like a train wreck with a bitter , sour awful finish .  a hazy golden wheat color with very little head after the bartender handed this one off to me . it quickly dissipated to almost nothing . while i 'm not a huge fan of saisons , this was one of the most enjoyable that i 've had and would certainly be a recommendation i would make to others just trying this style for the first time .  the body is light , but this one 's got a pretty decent mouthfeel ; it 's creamy and smooth .

this beer smelled pretty good , but the flavor is horrible .  a- dark orange , bordering on brown , with a very thin tan head that dissipates rapidly .  a little astringent . smooth mouthfeel , close to a porter consistency . nose and smooth mouthfeel make up for it .

smells of some pumpkin pie spices : cinnamon , clove , allspice with a strong malty aroma . no hop character in nose .  the widmer hefeweizen pours a slightly hazy light gold color and comes with that light citrus aroma you get with most hefs .  all that being said it felt quite nice on the palate with good levels of carbonation .

s-smells of vanilla and cinnamon spices with oaky and dark fruit notes . t-cinnamon and very overpowering dark fruit notes with some cheap cognac notes .  the color was a nice amber . even with the increase in pour there was almost no head at all .  fruity , yeasty smells are overwhelmed with sourness . there is some sour fruitiness up front , which is quickly overwhelmed by a vinegar-like taste , finishing off with a bit of bitterness . i really wanted to like this beer , liking more saisons , and various sour beers , but there is too much of a vinegar-like taste for me in this beer .

smell : roasted malt , sweet molasses .  pours a cloudy reddish brown . with a quickly dissapearing white head .  not entirely pleasant . mouthfeel - creamy . very nice drinkability - berghoff makes a somewhat uninspiring line of beers .

opaque light yellow brown with a light orange hue . smell is huge -- fragants of sweet honey , mellow almonds , nutmeg , etc . fairly balanced between other flavors -- some nutmeg , cloves , a touch of cinammon ?  pours a clear , medium straw colour with very little carbonation or head .  mouthfeel is smooth and creamy , however .

pretty good . light roasted malt flavors greet the tongue , followed by a milky sweetness .  sorry brewguru but this is what the style is suppose to be . highly carbonated and bracingly sour . the only bad thing you can say about it is that it doesn & # 8217 ; t have quite the wild complexity of a cantillion or a hansons but still a knockout gueuze .  feels good in the mouth with average carbonation and the beer coating the mouth without sticking .

the aroma is intriguing , as it has a huge fresh wheat character initially , along with some cheerios like maltiness , some fruity esters , and a touch of the banana/clove yeastiness typical of the style .  a : pours a nice clear red color , not very much head no lacing down the glass s : sweet fruity/candylike malts .  mouthfeel : very clean and crisp with a light body .
smell : nice , clear springtime smell .  slow pour into a chalice yields a one-finger tan head over a dark brown almost opaque body .  light bodied , smooth and crisp .

the smell is very strong of raspberry , though the taste itself is of beer mixed with raspberry seltzer water . there was a high ephervesense that really detracted from the enjoyability of the beer .  god bless scotland pours up a red amber color with barely any off-white head .  the body was pleasantly full and round .

s - tons of raspberries , good amount of wheat and malts , hint of hops at the end . t - tons of wheat and bready malts .  hard pour yielded a one finger temporary head which fades to nothingness . gentle carbonation , no lacing .  m - full bodied , nice carbonation level , and a pleasant warming effect .

this one starts off with a big , spicy , sweet aroma . just a bit of lacing hangs around .  a - pours a clear copper / brown color . it does appear to be lighter in color than i would expect from an amber ale . got almost an inch of head that disappeared pretty quick .  crisp and heavy on the palate like fine bourbon .

crisp hoppy smell with some citrus .  deep cola red with ok lacing and quick settling tan head .  3.0 mouthfeel - nice heavy mouthfeel , smooth like silk . the carbonation level is pretty low , but i drank it warm so that could have cut it down a lot .

s : not bad , much better than the appearance with a strong orange peel , light banana and dusty sweetness , quite good , very nice , i just hope it tastes as good .  a- a clear orange liquid with some amber hues .  mouthfeel is comfortable for this style and it is very drinkable if you are looking for a sweeter ( english & lt ; ? & gt ; ) styled pale ale .

s : smell is promising , get a huge jolt of pine and citrus on opening the bottle , once poured a mint and spice mix comes out . hop flavours are overall tasty , but were definitely muted , compared to what i expect in this style , prosaic compared to what is coming out of san diego right now . has good pine notes , but too much peppermint takes over in the end , making the flavour 1-dimensional and boring .  beer is a cloudy orange-honey color without much visable carbination .  i had high expectations with this beer but it sorda fell flat.i shared this beer with my buddy john.i drank this from a brandy shifter.burnt orange , just like fall colors.nice off white head that fell to a ring pretty fast.the smell was boozy , hops and some spices.the taste was the same as the smell but with a nice malt backbone.the mouthful is smooth and sorda on the thick side.nice carbonation.i liked this more as it warmed up but this is nothing i would seek out to find again .

smell- a very fruity and a little spicy nose .  brutes a beastly beer brewed with american barley , wheat and corn , fermented on oak for months with brett and finished with three types of champagne yeast . excelsior ! pale sunflower with a very slight haze , topped with a one-finger head of puffy white that fizzles away to a gaunt , bubbly ring .  mouthfeel : crisp and clean , it feels more like a pilsner than an ipa , which , in my book isnt necessarily a bad thing , but it is unusual . overall : alaskan made a half-way decent ipa here , but it seems much more suitable for a hot night in georgia than anytime in alaska .

the smell is pleasing , if straightforward .  interesting pour - quite murky with a small head , with a whisp of white that persists .  the mouthfeel is well balanced , carbonated well and not sticky at all .

smelled very herbal slightly sweet with a hint of malt , and tasted mostly the same .  i poured this beer into my tumbler at 50 degrees . the beer was cola colored especially with the amount of carbination stuck to the glass .  mouthfeel is full .

very nice aroma . medium thin body and stinging mouthfeel .  decants a dark an lovely black with a thin creamy head that was rather shortlived to say the least . overall not much to look at .  see also my review of the big dipper dipa . i am a cbh fan , but this beer tastes virtually the same as the big dipper dipa which had a bready , yeasty taste that overshadowed the flavor . is there some sort of house yeast that is being used here that is giving off these flavors reminiscent of a belgian yeast strain ? although it finishes with a fairly firm bitterness , the hop flavors are muted , not fresh or tasty and there is a funky and rubbery finish .

the smell of fresh sweet bread aromas are quite nice . the taste starts out just like the smell , yet it fades to a disappointing bland taste .  review based on notes consumed about a month ago pours a hazed caramel with a sliver of sand colored head . stays murked up , average head retnetion & lacing s : breadyness , toffee & much orchard fruit t : toffee , oakyness & hints of caramel , & a touch of boozey pears & apricots .  i hate that most of beer advocate disagrees with me about this but i do n't get the hype over this beer other that the fact that it seriously looks like motoroil and has a super thick mouthfeel .

it has a pretty pleasant aroma at first pour , and reminds me somewhat of a munich helles .  poured from a twelve ounce bottle into a tulip glass dark , cloudy brown in appearance , with a short head of foam aroma-malt and spices taste-spice notes and roasted malt-very smooth and well-balanced overall , a well-balanced , flavorful dark ale .  the mouthfeel has nice carbonation but the smell is bland .

smells almost like dr pepper and dunkle weizen combined , their yeast is kicking out some nice olfactory spice .  appearance : i was expecting something slightly more orange/amber , but instead , this pours more yellow-golden . nice fluffy head on the pour , but it dissipates quickly .  mouthfeel is big surpy almost very full but how could it not be considering the malt in this beer .
it smelled sweet and biscuity ; maybe even a little bit of fruit .  hazy yellow orange .  carbonation was spirited making for a tingly mouthfeel .

s- citrus and floral hop aroma with little to no malt charcterisitic t- light and lager-esk with a nice medium hop characteristic m- very light body with a spice at the front , malt covering about mid palate and hop finishing that is citrus and floral throughout d- very drinkable at around 5 % and very light for a nice summer session  one , it is inexpensive . it is a solid staple .  very light nicely carbonated .

nose is typical belgian , fruit , yeast , malt , not bad at all .  the beer pours a very dark black with hardly any light showing through on the edges . it looks very oily , and pours with no head what-so-ever which is disappointing .  m : mouthfeel is creamy and slick . let me say would have enjoyed the mouthfeel a lot more had i been consuming , say , a milkshake d : so thick , so chocolatey , that it took a lot of effort to finish this off .

aromas of hops were powerful , leaving little room for the traces of malt and spice that were present . the hops were present and in high quantity , but were far too flowery and light , lacking the hop-oil and bitterness i was looking for .  jet black with a small head that fizzles to nothing during a rather hasty session .  mouthfeel is good and the drinkability is below average just because of my personal opinion of the taste .

s - roasted malt with a little burnt malt as well .  bottle : poured a dirty beige color ale with a large fluffy head with ok retention .  head poors thick and has good retention though s - nice hoppy aroma t - strong hop flavor , but i find it unbalanced , i like a good hoppy beer , but the best in my opinion have a good malt balance m - the only aspect of this beer that i truly consider high quality is the mouthfeel ; it is smooth and dry , very good .

really quite piquant , and very fresh . otherwise , it 's quaffable and drinkable , and the appearance and nose are good . but it 's certainly lacking .  a quarter inch of tan head makes a hasty exit as soon as i finish pouring , leaving no trace behind .  m- medium bodied with ample carbonation .

i enjoyed the smell but the taste ruined it for me and the taste is what it is all about .  it 's colored like most belgian darks , but it has an immense amount of floating material ( what i thought looked like hop petals ) .  m - medium bodied , smooth beer , good carbonation , finish is where all the bitterness is in this beer .

belgian yeast esters define the aroma .  not familiar with helles bocks so take this with a grain of salt . i might say more about the nose if i knew the style better . nothing wildly distinctive about the flavor , nothing that calls out to the palate , except for good balance between hops and malty-ness .  m - english style carbonation ( soft ) and lighter bodied . appropriate for the style .

s : lots of apple aroma with some pear rolled in to boot . rich malty sweetness .  the appearance is that of your average brown ale minus the head .  mouthfeel : fine . refreshing . nicely carbonated .

pours a hazy golden yellow color with some ripe banana hues and some very pale golden yellow notes when held to a light source . citrus aroma with hints of peppery spice , corriander , bready yeast , orange and lemon peel , lemon zest and subtle floral notes . tons of lemon juice , lemon zest , corriander , bready yeast and subtle floral notes . it is not very balanced with a lot of zesty peppery spiciness , citrusy lemon juice and very subtle bread notes .  body is a golden amber color topped by a small creamy white head thar quickly recedes to a thin layer .  mouthfeel : medium body with smooth carbonation and a dry finish .

a- hazy amber , nice white head , just a little bit of lacing s- smells like a pine tree ... almost like that spray christmas scent for fake trees t- very bitter , for an ipa i expect flavor along with bitter , but this brew finds a way to just taste bitter throughout the entire drink .  the appearance is nothing special , dark black , no head to speak of , but looks a bit syrupy .  m : light body with mild carbonation .

spicy aroma , notes of white pepper and lemons , grassy and earthy , coriander , bready yeast and slight caramel . i was left feeling disappointed , particularly due to my initial enjoyment of the aroma .  well , as did evel , let 's give it a whirl . the brew pours to a yellow bronze with a nice creamy head .  m - nice chewy mouthfeel , what i 'd expect for the style .

the bouquet is quite appealing with a strong breadiness and light citrus notes . despite good looks and a solid smell , this only gets a slight pass .  poured from bottle into tulip glass a- another dark brew with a decent head that disappears quickly .  i expected so much more , almost like a club soda with flavoring ... m=dry , nice carbonation , feels good d=not really .

actually smells pretty good . very clear and light straw colored .  a : a nice amber color with an off-white head .  mouth was thick , not much alcohol , but that sour-grape aftertaste took control and finished as if it was champaign . there are a lot of flavors in this beer , but nothing really to rave about .

body looks a bit thin , and the beer seems to lack the head and lacing i would expect from a craft brewed english brown ale . s : nose of this brew is fairly well present roasted and choclate malts with some biscuit in there as well . t & m : starts off with a mild roasted malt flavor and then fades to a somewhat choclate and kind of a soda flavor mixed in , as the mouthfeel gets very carbonated for the style .  on tap at belmont station ; served in a tulip snifter . a - pitch black ; tan head that dissipates quickly ; no lacing .  the mouthfeel is well carbonated , light , and smooth .

s : the initial aroma is quite nice , big deep notes of chocolate and coffee , creamy hints of vanilla and marshmallow . t : the dark fruit character that i picked up on the nose basically dominate the flavor . starts of sweet and becomes quite tart .  12oz . brown bottle into tumbler a : dark brown , near opaque ; short-lived coffee-colored head ; some lacing , but not much .  medium body and the malts do not linger as much as expected .

smell- a very nice smell . sort of smells like starbucks .  in a pint glass the beer was a hazy , almost turbid orange tan color . the medium-sized tan head dissipated quickly .  mouthfeel is medium and highly spritzy with tons of champagne-like prickle .

s : coriander and orange rind up front followed by a sweet belgian spice and yeast aroma . t : similar to the smell , there 's coriander and orange rind up front followed by a belgian yeast and spice flavor .  pours a hazy orange copper color with a bit of white head .  thick , smooth , lightly carbonated .

surprisingly fruity nose is the dominant feature . it really is the bitterest thing ive ever had .  appearance : hazed orangey brown with a decent thin lacing .  mouthfeel is medium bodied , with lively carbonation .

the smell is very sweet with candy sugar , caramel malt , and some spiciness .  i 've had sam adams blackberry witbier , sam adams cherry wheat , lancaster brewing compnay strawberry wheat , and god help me bud lime but this is one fruit i did n't need in my beer .  the body of the beer 's great , and pretty ideal for the style .

aroma : very inviting aroma of bananas , citrus and coriander . good amount of yeast in the nose too .  got caught in the nasty storm last night at the train station downtown so i popped into the little bar at the station to see what they had . poured a nice golden amber with a tight head .  the mouthfeel is creamy and the finish has a creaminess to it as well .

s : really juicy . it kind of comes off like a west coast barleywine .  10/02/2011 750ml bottle 1981 vintage served in a cantillon tumbler . i 've tasted a 1997 cantillon gueuze & it was too oxidized & musty ( still amazing ) a huge thanks to a gentleman in geel , belgium for finding this in the back of a basement . appearance : corked 750 , no cage , cork rotting on top after removing foil cover , carefully removing the cork a portion of it stayed in the bottle & effected the pour . crystal clear with the appropriate pour but slightly darker than a typical gueuze , think esb color . i honestly had low expectations for this beer . so glad to have the opportunity to drink this .  the flavor has all the same spices with some sweetness and hints of the alcohol . i really do n't enjoy the flavor of this beer and i really expected a lot more from it . the drinkability suffers from the spices , but the alcohol is very well hidden .

s- the smell is the best thing about this beer and maybe set me up for the letdown on the taste and feel . the smell is caramelly , and warm . t- for a brief second the flavor is there and then it just disappears into nothing but water .  the beer poured dark brown-black with no head .  while i thought the mouthfeel of this beer was quite good , i was not a huge fan of its sour grape and champagne flavor .

the smell was really nice with a natural honey sweetness . overly sweet and very cloying in my opinion .  pours a cloudy light yellow color .  the smell is malty , with noticeable alcohol and more hops than seem to be present in a sip . there are a lot of flavors in this mix -- fruits , caramel , chocolate -- and these flavors pack a complex punch in the smell and taste , as does the alcohol , which causes sensation up the nose . overall , it was too sweet for me , like figs buried in sugar . i suspect i would have enjoyed the malt flavor greatly if the sweetness and alcohol were taken down a notch . i do n't consider this highly drinkable : 500 ml was far too much for me to finish .

very reminiscent to a sauvignon blanc i feel . mouthfeel is also somewhat jellyish.. quite odd . my girlfriend , a non beer drinker , though , loved it .  it may look like prune juice but man is this a good beer.you smell the chocolate but taste mainly the coffee.it 's been 20 minutes since i finished it and still have that sweet coffee taste in my mouth.this beer was enjoyable from the first gulp to the last sip.i definetly will be buying this again !  mouthfeel - 4.0 fine , nearly creamy carbonation is just right for a wheat ale .

like an entire pine tree shoved down your throat .  the beer pours dark red/brown/black , depending on how it is held to the light . the only signs of head is the slight ring around the edge .  i dunno i expected more from this m - medium bodied with a decent amount of carbonation .
the aroma is very hoppy , citrusy but flowery , not so piney .  a rather pale looking yellow beer , with not much carbonation evident .  m : full body with little carbonation .

a lot going on in the nose : lemon , spices , grass , a hint of other fruit , and a slight sour tang , especially when opening the bottle .  kind of a murky rust color with a thin cream colored head that clings to the glass on its way down .  m- good thick syrupyness , i do enjoy this aspect of this beer . the really only redeeming quality is the good mouthfeel .

there are times when you say `` aw what the heck '' and i did just that for orange flavored beer . the aroma is oranges - period . could n't smell a hop or the first thought of malt .  appearance - the six pack i had was full of floating yeast , while this is basically harmless , i generally do n't enjoy things floating in my beer . the pour is a dark maize with a thick head that shrinks down to a nice lacing .  medium body with a nice mouthfeel .

aromas of chocolate and espresso would lead one to believe that this beer will taste great .  a very nice ale , if not fantastic . appearance was hard to gauge due to its coming in a brown ( but rather pretty ) bottle .  mouthfeel is a smidge lighter than medium with a great creamy feel . the mouthfeel was very nice , but the flavor suffered from the sourness .

the similarity between this and my homebrewed braggot are striking . the spice is big on the nose and upfront in the taste , but it fades instantly to a watery blandness by the middle . i wonder if this is a braggot as well since the flavor is so overwhelmingly similar .  a brilliant white two-finger head fizzles away to a thin lacy cap that leaves minimal lacing .  medium body very crisp and a bit creamy .

smell : smoked malt is accompanied by sweet dark fruit .  drinking pretty darn good right out of the bottle . murky brown color . nose is slightly sweet , burbon with a super thin head .  m : oily mouthfeel , good body to it .

poured chilled in 5-oz tasting glass a : little head , dark brown , good carbonation , ok lacing s : roasted barley , like a chocolate bock ; persists t : chocolate-bock-like biter but sweetish ; vanilla and roasted grains are very strong it 's an unusual brown ale but , imo , to close to the other beer i 've had , the cubano , and not a good direction in which to take this style .  black in color with 1/2 '' head that quickly reduced to surface foam . too bad the pour did n't look better .  light bodied and soft mouthfeel .

aroma is earthy from black malts , with pleasing chicory notes .  clear , still orange with a fat 3 finger head that fades over time . no lacing , decent retention .  the dry , champagne like finish along with the funky yeast was pleasant , however . mouththfeel was right on with the style , and was my favorite part of this beer .

seems very dark for a 'pale ale' s : nice american hops aroma .  my first sampling was a pint at the pourover pub at the nantahala outdoor center , with subsequent pours from a growler fresh from the brewery in bryson city a - dark appearance for apa ; a dull copper that looked more like what i expect from an ipa than pa s- detect a hint of pine amongst the hop aromas , again more indicative of an ipa t- thankfully , taste did not match what i expected from the smell as it did not have the thick pine-resin flavor ; it was much milder than expected and more appropriate for pale ale style .  the carbonation of the beer was good , like a pilsner should be . the beer was light , but not watery . an innocent beer that would offend very few .

smell is resin , pine , and some citrus ( pine dominates ) .  notched in 2007 ( larger ) and 2010 ( smaller ) - i suppose that it means that it was made in 2007 and best by 2010 ... not sure though ... in any case - pours hazy/murky orangeish amber with some lacing . pretty muddy-looking - head does n't last too long , though it holds on a bit - lacing saves it some .  body is full and has good carbonation .

nose is a rich roasted coffee with an actual creamy character to the nose that smells very much like very fresh roasted grains/coffee and an almost sweet toasty light molasses character . pleasant and a bit unique in the nose . pleasant and a bit different .  much lighter in color . some amber tints , not much lacing or head retention . looks can be deceiving .  mouthfeel - somewhat of a thick body with medium carbonation .

common beers galore with your usual heineken/newcastle additions ... but thankfully there was at least one batch ale offering , the bonus being i 've yet to taste at this one . floral , slightly medicinal with hints of peppermint , cherry , and toffee in the nose . mint-like grassy hop character upfront , with the same medicinal mint/fruit character found in the nose . very sweet cherry and light toasted oats character .  not much of a head ; dirty white in color , and it fades fast .  it tastes nothing like a real peach . i would compare it too a jolly rancher piece of candy . i do like the fizzieness , and crisp finish , but thats it .

i guess that the big hope nose that the bottle boasts are still pretty subtle , noble type hops . i was ready to enjoy this beer after the nose , but unfortunately it was very disappointing .  the bartender poured this one into a glass for me , and it was a nice rich caramel color , but no head to speak of .  mouthfeel is silky and lightly carbonated .
very aromatic . surprisingly little malt , but definite hop presence .  a : pretty nice golden color that is spot on for the style .  m - good thickness and consistency .

rather nice bock scent .  poured from the bottle into a pint glass , beer is a hazy golden color with a thin head comprised of many fine bubbles .  a low level of carbonation with a smooth and creamy mouthfeel .

aroma ( 4 ) : extremely sweet . candy apple , bubble gum strong . berries and plums can also be detected . liefmans provides a beer masked with fruit sweetness , for all those who do n't like the malt , hops , or yeast of beer . cheap-pricetag ( even here in canada ) and drives the fruit flavour home .  i drank this out of the bottle because i did n't have a glass . extremely drinkable .  m : fairly light-bodied and lively . good .

aromas of oranges , light pine , citrus , spices with some malts . tastes a bit of a let down vs. the aromas . notes from 9/13/05  this was an amber-colored beer with a medium head . interesting taste , a little citrus , a little malt , a little hops . i thought they worked quite well . very good mouthfeel , and quite drinkable .  mouthfeel has a nice medium body and full carbonation .

extra credit for this unique situation .  appearance : pours an almost clear amber color with a small layer of off white head that goes away completely .  the moutfeel is big and bold , full bodied but again , overpowering on the pallette .

the aroma is mostly sweet roasted malt with some caramel notes and just a touch of earthy hops . the sweetness that the aroma promised must have checked out early , becuase i ca n't find it at any temperature in this beer .  a-dark amber body , slightly cloudy with almost no head save for a slight ring of bubbles that leaves some lacing . there is a low level of carb that breaks things up a bit and keeps the feel from totally taking over .  nice mouthfeel , but i need much more than that .

s - roasted chocolate notes with an alcohol brisk like glisten . very coco and roasted malt . not much else in there .  appearance : brown colour , no head .  the mouthfeel is a nice , decently carbonated , finishes a little dry , but overall good .
a sniff reveals maple syrup .  pours a hazy , copper color . decent retention and decent lacing .  medium bodied carbonation .

smell was big on berry like fruitiness which apparently is the pomegranate . a bit too mild flavored for me overall , but interesting .  pours an effervescent caramel with some sand colored head . average lacing & head retention s : superb oaky bourbon notes , then a a whiff of dirt ?  the palate is super smooth .

surprisingly rich aroma . smells primarily of vanilla .  a- pours a clear yellow color with ample carbonation bubbles , a 1 finger white head , and no sediment . in about a minutes time , the head recedes to a thin cap .  m : decently carbonated but morphs into a nice creaminess . pleasant .

aroma : nice porter like smell , some mild hops , a light but firm chocolate note .  pours a small white head with a clear orange body and fair lacing .  the mouthfeel was surprisingly not too syrupy , but at almost $ 7 a bottle i wo n't go back for seconds .

the nose was solid , but boy does the taste/body suck .  beer was a dark copper color , with just a few bubbles for a head .  the mouthfeel was balanced enough , but for me the drinkability is very bad , as i struggled to finish one bottle of this ... cheers to beerluvr for the bottle and the experience !

light aromas of figs , lightly browned caramel , chocolate and tropical spices ( nutmeg , cinnamon , ginger ) all hemmed in by that idiosyncratic yeasty unibroue smell .  nice copper color , but a lot head out of the bottle and low retention ( alas ) .  the mouthfeel is actually decently creamy and well-carbonated .

nice aroma of malt , caramel and coffee .  pours a deep brown with slight reddish hues . the head has decent lacing , but this beer quickly settles as i swirl it around the glass . the very fizzy head reveals a tart cherry , slight vinegar , oak , and acidic aroma .  feel is smooth and thick .

the smell is still pretty good .  appearance : pours a thick , black color with no head and only a little lacing .  the hops jump right out from the bottle and sting your nose as the beer pours into the glass . do n't get me wrong there are plenty of hops , maybe too much , but i think as an effort to try and dry out this beer , the brewer added a lot of simple sugars which created more alcohol , and then to counter or mask , he added more hops . the finish is dry and clean with very little lingering hoppiness at least for a iipa . i was very excited to see this brewery 's beer being distributed in ohio . we do n't see many style defining west coast iipas in the midwest so it 's a real treat to find something that stretches your palate . even though this beer deserves low marks for drinkability , its intense aroma was worth the eight dollars i paid for the bomber .

very nice , not as sour as some gueuzes , the mustiness prevails .  thanks marcatgsb for this beer poured into a la chouffe tulip a - almost opaque very dark brown/black , half finger dark tan head and some lacing s - very sweet , molasses , vanilla , bourbon , oak , chocolate milk and more sweet t - vanilla , sweet coffee , milk chocolate , alcohol , earth , lots of oak and wood , molasses , some bourbon flavors , great slightly toasted malt and a very little but nice amount of hops m - chewy , full bodied , medium minus acidity , well balanced , great complexity and long finish d - this is a dream of a stout .  m : pretty good . some creaminess , enough carbonation to keep it from getting heavy .

eyes ... light caramel hue , one finger of white foam that recedes quickly , lacing is very good , just a very average looking brew , which is not a detriment really nose ... nice piney citrus notes right off the bat , grapefruit ... amarillo hops ? underneath they smell a little green and herbally ... and really fresh . for just a regular ipa the smell is very nice taste etc ... the carbonation is a bit lacking which impacts the mouthfeel negatively , mild hop oils flow , barely any ibus felt.. i wonder how this is rated in terms of ibus but the bitterness is missing , ditto the hops for the most extent , this is also a bit watery for my tastes .  totally amber and extremely transparent with no head , just a ring of scum .  m - moderate carbonation and smooth . dry finish . refreshing .

s- the malts are much stronger than the hops in the nose of this american barleywine . lots of caramel and toffee . somewhat fruity as well .  a - just under one finger of dirty white foam , with a tinge of pink appears on top of the slightly hazy , reddish brown body . it settles quickly to a thin film with a few fish eye bubbles .  it has a medium body and a smooth mouthfeel , with the sour flavor laying on the tongue slightly . inbetween a medium and high carbonation , but fairly drinkable .
rich malty aroma with deep notes of sweet chocolate . good .  nice beige head that dies too quickly for my tastes . nice reddish brown color , quite clear .  mouthfeel is pretty good .

s- big roasted malts and some nice cocoa and chocolate . the honey comes through pretty good .  a- by the looks of it , it does n't look like much . above average lacing .  emphasis on the hops really drew me in a- a full amber body of a beer . nothing but malt . you need some type of hop flavor when you write six hops on the label though m- creamy and overwhelming taste that attacks your mouth . i do like this aspect of it d- just being honest ... if your battle cry is hops , you need to have some . the unstoppable malt attack makes this not enjoyable .
it had a very strong vanilla and coffee odor that was sweet overall .  a -- nice light brown color . decent head that goes away fairly quick .  mouthfeel is a medium - light with good carbonation .

s - smells of sticky sweet dark fruits , chocolate , coffee , and some roasted malts . the smell was pretty good but was n't digging the sour taste it had to it .  on-tap at the catskeller , 4/14/10 a : pours a murky , muddy chocolate color .  m : the head adds a nice creaminess to this drink . body feels medium .

s : slightly floral with strong notes of lemon and citrus . just a touch of hops .  pours a surprisingly deep brown with minimal head and nothing by way of lacing . not the best looking beer , i must say , but the color is quite nice .  the mouthfeel was reather smooth and easy-going .
very spicey aroma , like black pepper . very malty nose , no hint of hops at all .  a : jet black , very thin , tan head that is quick to fade .  m- medium mouthfeel . good carbonation .

normally not a fan of fruity beers , but the new glarus raspberry tart is superb so i thought i 'd give this one a try as well . smells like a cherry pie with some hints of yeast and wheat . taste is not as good as the smell . cherries up front , but there is a bit of funk taste along with it .  22oz bomber poured into tulip a -- an opaque-ish dark orange without much head ... .decent lacing s -- light smell but definitely completely composed of hop aroma ... slightly citrus , not much pine here t -- hops jump out at the beginning and stay ... not much balance to this one .  not quite as malty as i was expecting based on the nose , just some toasty caramel . medium body with moderately low carbonation .
smell - pungent aromas of sour wheat , a little banana .  it tastes exactly like the beer equivalent of sauternes . lightly carbonated . no noticeable head .  the body is fairly good .
the belhaven was floral , perfectly present : not too strong , not too weak .  dark mahogany highlights with thin tan head and no retention .  very crisp , no real aftertaste .
dark grainy bready aroma as well as a decent spiciness .  pours a medium orange amber with a thin white head that quickly fades .  the mouthfeel was good .

wow , what an aroma . smells just like stewarts orange cream soda . maybe a hint of ale in the smell . wow again !  12 oz pour into a pint glass , looks very thick & black .  mouthfeel is medium to almost thick . creamy . carbonation is big and loopy , coating the mouth , but at the same time this is not characterized as chewy .

as i love islay malts , this smelled wonderful ; smokey , peaty , salty , with a hint of ethyl and wood . a sickening rubbing alcohol/creosote/paint thinner combination is all i can describe it as .  pours a ruddy dull deep reddish brown , minor coffee colored head .  mouthfeel is good , decent bodied lager with the slightly herbal hoppy finish to stop it becoming too predictable .

smell : rich malt smell with a faint bit of hop/floral note .  i 've been drinking beer for 20+ years now and always come back to heineken.i 've brewed my own for years in the late 80's.the taste is exceptional.some call it skunky but i feel it has hoppy and yet a malty flavor that is light and somewhat dry.what can i say , i like it.i 've also had better but i feel this one deserves credit.it is entirely smooth.i enjoy stout and pale ale also but heineken ca n't be denied .  the beer leans towards full bodied but with crisp carbonation so it does n't feel so heavy .

sweet fruity scents , some burnt sugar notes .  average lacing in dropplet form on the side of the goblet & a good film more so than actual head retention s : caramel & toffee with a slight smokeyness .  mouthfeel : nice light mouthfeel with a decent amount of carbonation .

a strong bourbon aroma overpowers anything else , perhaps this was aged in whiskey barrels ?  poured from a bottle into a tulip . beer is heady , yellowish light brown head that falls away leaving little lacing on the glass . i have to object to this beer at this point and penalize it for chill haze . this is classic chill haze , this is a professionally crafted beer , add a protein rest for your product 's sake . watch the chill haze guys .  mouthfeel is creamy and soft , medium bodied .

the smell leaves no doubt that this is a pumpkin ale . strong pumpkin and spice aromas are about all you can detect . unfortunately , pumpkin and spice are about all you get in the taste as well . it 's easy to drink and kind of refreshing but it seriously lacks any complexity .  pours a deep copper color , almost brown , with reddish highligts . very little head and lacing , though that is expected from a growler .  great feel . creamy and heavy , but not in a bad way . the feel is great , but the aromatics and flavor depth are lacking .

smell : mildly sweet like brown sugar with some dark fruit , i 'm picking up raisins .  the cloudy , hazy yellow body on this one has some fairly active carbonation bubbles . this is a nice smelling beer .  a really nice creamy feel to this which matches the beer , not the style imo .

smell : hops and oak are predominant , hops yield a floral nature and the oak yields notes of scotch malts ; reminds me of a subdued and less complex 'sink the bismarck ! taste : begins oakey and smokey , but whatever stimulation that is brought forth is quickly subdued and undermined by the peaty-malty taste , hops clash and are surprisingly bitter compared to their smell , finishes with an unpleasant combination of bitterness and oak-peat . overall : disappointing ; either i was mistaken thinking that an oak-aged ipa may have kept fairly well beyond its best by date ( maybe a 2/2/10 date drank in august 2011 is a little too far past best before ) , but it still seems that the ipa characteristics are far too subdued to be enhanced by oak .  color is a copper color , lighter than the ipa is . a very solid , above average tasting apa .  mouthfeel is pretty good .

a nice aroma of toasted malt and baked ginger snaps slightly thin on mouthfeel taste : some caramel sweetness and fragrant hop spiciness with a thin , ok wimpy malt base .  22 ounce bottle into tulip , 2011 release . pours crystal clear golden orange color with a small off white head with decent retention that reduces to a thin lacing ring . minimal lacing on the glass .  mouthfeel : the body is on the thick side of medium . the carbonation is tingly with a dry finish .

heck - i 'll cut to the chase . twang ! ! !  `` double chocolate coffee oatmeal stout '' poured very aggressive leaving a quarter inch of tan head that dissipated somewhat quickly and did not retain well at all . black color , minimal carbonation .  clean mouthfeel , good carbonation , crisp , refreshing , and easy drinking .

no past due date , but i think the bottle passed its shelflife , not through a great hoppy aroma , not through appearance which was cloudy grapefruit with a white head and lacey , but through taste alone .  a - pitch black . dull .  m - medium body and moderate carbonation .

smell - interesting smell and not what i would have expected . it smells like a lambic , which is weird . overall - it 's tough to rate this , since the initial flavors are n't bad and the aroma is actually nice , if not kinda weird .  it pours a deep chocolate brown with virtually no head . it looks like motor oil but the smell tells you it is n't .  mouthfeel is medium bodied , with a fairly long , sweet finish .

body looks black but as i pour i notice it 's a really dark brown smell : lots of chocolate and cocoa powder with a hint of fruit . very mellow .  the color of the beer is dark reddish brown , but dark amber when held to light . pours with a creamy tan head that unfortunately dissipates very quickly and leaves no belgian lace ; ergo either low quality hops or i need to take better care to use a beer clean glass .  the medium body is smooth and prickly , and leaves an almost medium finish - nice .

strong smelling . sweet upfront , with a sort of biscuity malt backround . more complex than i expected .  tap at o'briens sd : a - deep brown with a minimal head and just a touch of lace .  mf : medium bodied , with just enough carbonation to keep it a tad crisp and refreshing .

s : tart , acetic , funky . vanilla , oak . nice ! weirdly drops right off into oak , vanilla , maybe some cinnamin , wine barrel .  pours an orangish amber color with a ring of head around the edge and little to no lace .  the mouthfeel is the strongest point , which is pleasantly carbonated if a tad slick .

the aroma is clean and citrusy , a mild lemon aroma , and a hint of grapefruit .  however ... when i poured this brew alot of sediment ( chunky hunks ) were floating in the glass .  m - stout . robust .

the smell is very nice , not a coffee bomb as other imperial stouts try and push on you .  pours slightly hazed light amber with a very thin hed that immediately becomes spots and disappears .  mouthfeel was also smooth and lightly carbonated .

scents of malt , roasted coffee and vanilla ; maybe a little wood as well . taste is much more subdued than the nose and somewhat disappointing considering the boldness of the nose . also detected a little bit of a citrus-quality , which threw the coffee flavor completely off .  12 oz - & gt ; saison dupont glass a ~ pours a very pale lemonade with excessive carbonation and large bubbles . not great lacing .  the mouthfeel was good with real depth .

whereas most coffee beers have coffee that overwhelms the malts , or the coffee is not good to begin with , this aroma is a wonderful balance of well brewed coffee and porter , with the black patent and chocolate malts coming through .  pale yellow appearance with lots of head the fizzes away quickly .  the mouthfeel is done well , pretty thick , with low carbonation .

the smell is very promising . nice aromas of pineapple and biscuit is evident .  clear , yellow/gold . large head initially that is gone fast . can drink a lot of these because there 's little to it .  mouthfeel was nice and light and easy to drink .

smell is smooth and rich bourbon and oak , mainly and is quite nice . taste is a touch tart and perhaps fruity , but not cherries per se , and of course some bourbon and definite wood character .  appearance - light amber . short white , fizzy , quickly dissipating head .  very good for the style .

beer shares the bottle with yeast ( nice ) . smells of pine , grapefruit and a little grass , without much malt coming through . tastes interesting -- sharp , lots of hop oil , and strong grapefruit and pine due to the interesting mixture of hops .  pours an exremely pale straw color with a thin , white head that 's waving goodbye .  mouthfeel was the best part of the beer to me . lightly sticky with a good amount of carbonation to make it feel slightly creamy and smooth .

i really had high expectations for this beer , given that english strong ales are totally my thing , and that this is an 8-year old corked english imperial stout and cost $ 5.49 . the first whiff is reminiscient of that plummy , raisiny flavor of classic dark english barleywines . ( that 's really what this beer should be -- - a roasty version of harvey 's elizabethan ale . ) the flavor , unfortunately , fell flat .  poured with a thin head that was gone in seconds , zero on the lacing .  m - full bodied with a clean finish .
