nice malty nose of raisin fruit and caramel cookie sweetness . i wish it smelled a bit more intense as i like what i am picking up .  a - transparent , pale yellow body , with a pure white tiny head .  huge caramel malt aroma is kept in check by an equally huge grapefruit accented aroma ... simplistic , but i if you like those smells ... its ambrosia . finish is citric , grapefruity and wow massively malty . if i liked massive quantities of hops and caramel malt , id love this ... i dont though and it gets boring to me like i imagine big doses of flavors i like would get boring to someone who didnt like then as much as i do .

smell is interesting ... i get tart , so i assume this is going to be a bit sour ... i also get prunes and maybe some berry , along with a tinge of belgian yeasty clove .  appearance : looks like your typical macro lager . pours a translucent yellow color with lots of carbonation bubbles .  mouthfeel is full though and a little creamy .

pumkin scent with strong doses of cinnamon .  very pale golden body with a white head that dissipates quickly to a thin foam with thicker islands of head floating atop . lace is somewhat decent , tiny to medium bubbled . full bodied lager , leaves a good coating and feels pretty smoth .  feels good in the mouth , mostly sweet to start , but there is a hint of bitter at the end of the swallow .

the fine and inviting smell got notes of coffee and toffee and a peculiar touch of dry digestive biscuits .  12oz bottle from abe 's of beth. , pa a- very thin- like cheap cola color . reminds me of a quality macro .  stands for `` panty dropper '' . unfiltered , brewed with apricots , 4.5 % abv . it even tastes like mead with a pronounced fruity acidity , but in a blind tasting i could n't tell you that it was apricots . mild bitterness with a wierd off-flavor . not as fruity as i was expecting .

i did so because i knew i am not a fan of fruit beers . aroma is all raspberry .  341ml bottle poured into pint glass may26 2010 a pale straw yellow with a few bubbles and some suspended particles and no head or lace s the same fruity bread smell in qv only with some booze t what i smell but with a boozy chemical flavor that i ca n't place but it may be a good thing i ca n't place it m a little thin and not the smoothest finish d hard to swallow , not one i would drink again my 6 pack mixer is finished and i 'm not too upset it 's gone .  i dont know if they have sour tarts in va , but this incense of baby and elderly lambic beers has a unique flavor . it has definite lambic feel to it .

the smell is full of roasted burned tones , oats , bread , coffee beans .  a : a clear , raisin-brown colored liquid . no head to speak of , almost no carbonation to be seen .  it is very smooth , though , although that 's one of its few positive notes .

pretty good smelling beer .  the yeast had broken down in the keg and leech out a bready/yeasty flavour in the background , and there was loads of proteins and the like permanently suspended in the beer , but it was still a good beer .  mouthfeel : very light and crisp .

12 oz can poured into a snifter fridge temp 2008 appearance : pours a transparent brownish orange color with a 1 '' tall , off-white head with good retention . smell : heavy pine , grapefruit and malty sweetness . this one smells a lot like a dipa .  poured a medium golden color with just a bit of tan colored head . the head disappeared almost immediately and did not provide any lacing .  carbonation level is high , giving the body fullness but also making it lively on the tongue . flavor profile is a bit exotic , with grapy/berry fruitiness , spice , and molasses . thins out on the smooth and moderately brief finish .

aroma : knickerbocker red presents with a sweet nose . there is a little woodiness in the nose as well . taste : the initial taste has a sweetness .  best enjoyed before : d/11 crystal clear pale yellow-gold with a thin , soapy white head . light , crisp , and refreshing , but even at trader joe 's there 's a number of beers i would choose over this for summer thirst quenchers .  m : smooth and balanced . body is light-medium .

s : very fruity , almost like juicy fruit gum . cardboard , floral and a bit of caramel .  there was virtually no lacing . the color was redish amber .  mouthfeel : medium bodied , the carbonation was right on the button as soon as i cracked the bottle .

the nose is nice enough , hints of oatmeal sweetness , toasty caramel , and lightly roasted malts that produce a note of chocolate and coffee .  looking at the menu and seeing buck light as one of the buckhead breweries staple brews , i grimaced . even after i got the beer , i had really low expectations . extremely pale ( described as `` straw '' on the menu ) it had very little in the way of appearance or aroma , but the first sip proved surprisingly flavorful . this has very little compelxity and could never match a good not-light beer , but it 's quite possibly the greatest light beer ever made .  medium body and syrupy with a good amount of carbonation keep the beer from being too heavy .

sweet , tart and tangy , a very strange tasting brew . pungent floral , not at all agreeable .  pours a light clear straw like yellow color with an initially very nice and tall white foamy , full bodied looking head that all but totally dissappeared 2 minutes after being poured , leaving little to no lacing . it is easy to drink the same way seltzer water is . better than some of american macros i have had , certainly at least slightly better than budweiser ( one of the other line of beers brewed by anheuser busch of course ) the last time i had it , but certainly nothing special either .  the feel is rather rich , oily and frothy like many other barleywines i 've had . ultimately , the one-note , intense hop bitterness dorwns out everything else .
it smells pretty good .  as i drink more beers this is still my favorite light beer . the importance of this beer is that it 's drinkable and cheap .  good fizziness - not too much or too little .

s : i actually recognize green tea , a lot of it , lighter pine hop , overall aroma is lightly sweetened green tea .  has a very pale yellow color with a 1/2 inch head .  body is good and so is carbonation .

a much bigger aroma then the 90 minute . t - i really hope i just had a bad bottle of this . i will give this beer credit though with the aroma , it smells absolutely epic but the taste really really hurts this one .  not terrible . much lighter in color than anything i 've had that did n't state `` light '' on the label .  it has a good mouthfeel , thick but creamy , goes down smooth .

i smell ripe fruit in the nose and hops in the background ... very nice .  appearance : holy crap , this beer is overcarbonated . every effort is repulsed by a tremendous avalanche of bubbles -- i waited until the head died entirely , then attempted to fill the glass several times with no success . i have no idea about quality control/consistency with watch city , but it looks like they rarely bottle their beers . anyway , other than the head , it 's a thick , cloudy dark brown .  medium , creamy mouth feel with light to moderate carbonation .

s- smells of strong hops and lots of citrus . t- the taste did not live up to the smell . tasted very bland , weak hops , very bitter on the end .  appearance : very clear and somewhat watery smell : very light , and has not distinguishing features taste : it goes down very easy , and does n't leave a bad taste in your mouth feel : it is very foamy , and develops a head easily drinkability : it is easy to drink it in succession , and have a normal aftertaste .  m : medium bodied with some crispy carbonation in the finish .

as i poured this dark rich liquid into my clear beer mug i was struck by an overwhelming sweet aroma . while i usually like my beer with a sweet overtone , this one was just too much .  this beer for the price is actually quite good . really transparent yellow tinted coloring .  ( m ) light to medium body with a creamy feel .

the aromas are bold of molasses , roasted malts and caramel .  a- bright golden yellow with bubbles floating to the top .  on the palate , medium-bodied , nicely carbonated , but not an easy drinker .

it smelled good , dark malt , german hops .  a : it poured a gold colored body with a very weak head of less than one finger . the head was bone white and disappeared fast and without any lingering lacing .  mouthfeel : thin- to medium-bodied and very smooth , especially for a wheat beer . especially not when there are so many great wheat beers out there .

smells lightly of brown sugar , some faint tropical fruit and spices -- coriander and ginger , producing a little tingle on the nose . tastes bitter , which is a surprise given the nose and the style , and mainly of bitter grapefruit rind , bordering on bitter melon .  pours a semi-hazed bronze with a pinky of fast falling pearl white head . zero head retention or lacing s : white pepper & lemon t : white pepper , coriander , & grainy bread .  mouthfeel : the mouthfeel although sticky and overly sweet is not harsh at all in terms of alcohol bite .

regardless it does n't taste stale or skunky in any way . the hoppy nose is its high point . plenty of citrus and pine coming through here . smells like it could be a typical northwestern ipa in fact .  rather hazy , reddish amber beer wit a creamy two finger white head with poor retention . zero lacing .  mouthfeel was medium-light and easy to drink .

smell is sweetish malts , caramel and chocolate .  i 've had so many bottles of rolling rock in my life i ca n't even begin to imagine . besides having a bad ass painted bottle , it is one of the most drinkable beers in my opinion .  mouthfeel is good , medium body and good carbonation .

appears a dark mahogany christmas spiced ale to share with your friends during the winter months , this one also has some honey additions . lacing left behind is fine and even , i ca n't really complain . aroma has more spices with some ginger accents with cinnamon and cardamom some sugar malt with minimal hop presence . i highly discourage leaving out hop components in craft beers the majority of your audience looks forward to hops even with a nice winter warmer . this one has an over carbonation that i ca n't get over , along with the over spiced character dominating this party . if you 're actually able to make it through a bottle you should earn a badge of courage not a shot at your next sample it 's rough all the way through .  appearance : i 'm not impressed at all with this . some ok lacing , but no foam retention at all . looks like watery coffee .  m- medium body with good carbonation .

smell of overpowering mint , dark chocolate , roasty malts and a sweet presence of residual sugars .  pours yer typical macro color - an off yellow with a skunky , cooked veggie smell , not very impressive up front .  mouthfeel has a nice body , decently cleansing .

very nice . t : slightly sweet and not much bitterness .  after 45 minutes of pouring , breaking up the head and pouring more breaking up the head pouring more , i found that the beer was dark amber to brown and pretty hazy , but this could be due to the fact that interrupted pouring and violent explosive carbonation drove all the sediment off the bottle of the bottle whatever .  m- there is a very slight creamy note to the light body that gives it a nice mouthfeel .

still , it has a great spicy hop nose and a very decent head .  delirium nocturnum 11.2oz bottle into chalice appearance : dark brown with a lot of floating chunks . the carbonation floats the chunks about in a unappealing look .  m- pretty smooth with pretty high carbonation overall this beer reminds of an extreme great laker burning river .

s - chocolate cake , roasted malts , smells quite nice . there is a nice bit of char and wood in this one . good stuff .  a : bright , clear straw yellow . poured a 1 finger foamy white head that dissipated quickly to a skim that disappeared in a minute or two .  mf= medium bodied with a fairly high carbonation level for a cask ale .

very pleasant . t- the wheat comes through very clearly , with a dab a honey to make the brew less aggressive .  heineken pours a light straw color with a one finger white head . the head fades quickly and there is no lacing down the glass .  does have a nice , smooth mouthfeel , which would make it easy to drink , if i cared for the smell at all .
dark color- and a nice dark fruit smell with coffee .  ( a ) - pours a clear yellow color . produced some white bubbles .  has a good body , definitely fuller than most ipas . some creaminess .

s- banana for days . malty and sugary as well . quite a smell . t- banana bread ... obviously .  poured into a pounder glass aggressively it barely makes a head to note here . no retention or lacing .  500ml bottle poured into tulip mar27 2011 a pours out black with some oil like globs towards the bottom of the bottle , thumbs width of mocha head quickly falls to a thin film leaving a partial ring of lace followed by some unorganized patches s worcestershire sauce and soy with a little booze and mint , not what i was hoping for t slightly better with some smoke , woody earth , vanilla , cola and whiskey but that worcestershire is hard to miss after you catch wind of it m fairly thick and creamy with just a little heat that could be better concealed but still feels good o lea & perrins would be proud , that worcestershire smell and flavor is holding this one way back hard to believe that before this hit the barrel it was one of my all time favorite stouts , i love the beer geek breakfast but this one just did n't do it for me , not a bad brew but i 'd rather drink one before the barrel aging edit : after reading some reviews i suspected i got a bad bottle and tried another .

pint glass from cask . they used interesting hops in this , as the name implies : sunflower and fresh-cut grass dominate the nose .  appearance : straw yellow .  oddly , it is drinkable to an extent , probably because of the smooth and semi-creamy mouthfeel .

fleur has a pretty color and it smells good . however , it 's all downhill from there .  pours like every other macro lager , and smells like every other one two ( `` pilsener '' be damned -- there are no noble hops to be found here . if it looks like a bud and it smells like a bud and it drinks like a bud , is it not a bud ?  toasted malts , citrus , some pine , toffee , grainy husk as well m- good body , smooth , creamy smooth , good carbonation d- enjoyable , interesting take on an amber , but not all to desirable .

the smokey aroma is noticeable already . the taste is so heavily smokey , it is overwhelming any other tastes and aromas . mouthfeel is ashtray-y .  it looks piss poor , no head , particulate-laden brown swamp .  m & d - mouthfeel is nice due to viscosity but the tart twanginess is not attractive .

the smell is pretty good . it is a bit syrupy but other than that it has some nice spice aromas , fruit , and a hint of hops of the herbal variety .  straw yellow pour , white head , aroma was of corn , grits , mild flowers .  decently carbonated beverage with a mild body .

aroma is surprisingly good , with some ripe fruit notes and that quintessential banana character .  pours golden with 3+ fingers of eggshell colored head . zero lacing & head retention s : corny with dextrose & perfumy hops as this warms t : lemony hops & sweet corn up front .  m : very light and crisp , moderate carbonation .

the nose is really quite nice , but the rest of the beer fails to live up to it .  i guess i realized that in college , this was a great beer to drink out of the bottle on keg nights , not in a pint glass in a restaurant . this was literally as clear as water .  mouthfeel is medium bodied , some effervescence and a lingering bite .

was a little surprised by the color of this i thought it was going to be a golden color.poured a light mahogany with a light tan head.aroma browm sugar , malts , dark fruits , sweet . flavor , the flavors did not come close to the aroma , everything was on the weak side , got malts , some hops , sugar . to bad the flavor did not live up to the aroma . it was a easy drinking beer .  pours a pale , clear yellow . 1/5 inch head with no retention and no lacing . fits the style more of a fruit/vegetable beer than an american adjunct lager ( at least on taste ) .  md-thick body and mouthfeel . appropriate carbonation .

s : sharp sour acidic aroma is the first thing that grabs your nose . mild raspberries , pool toys , modest wet straw and moldy funk . seems to lack any real depth of a typical lambic .  a : almost no head . very pale gold .  m : medium bodied and lightly carbonated . rather smooth and appreciably oily in the mouth and goes down silky . appearance is decent and feel is actually very good .

s : dark and milk chocolate . some dark fruit .  very pale in colour , nothing special to note in the smell . the taste i would say is more like an above average macro lager , it lacks ale characteristics .  mouthfeel is great , smooth , mild aftertaste , does not have the pasty roof of your mouthfeel like other shitty macros .
looks like a normal beer when you pour it , smells rather tasty .  very light looking lager .  the mouthfeel is good though with a medium body .

this one is more of a blend of spices and a good pumpkin aroma rather than being all spice or all pumpkin .  a - looks a lot like a malt liquor . honestly , it fizzes like soda and has a brownish hue to the yellow color . looks like steel reserve .  m : medium-bodied , nice smooth and even carbonation for the style - helps deliver the peppery flavors all over the palate .

s : smells roasty and slightly matly sweet with a hint of floral hops .  somehow i had zero head on this one . literally . no lace either . still in date and everything else seemed fine just no foam at all . nice brownish amber color for whatever that 's worth .  even though the menu at goose island says that sticke alt is usually a unadvertised `` secret '' beer made by alt brewers in dusseldorf to reward its regulars , it does n't explain that sticke alts are usually made with more malt and hops and brewed to a higher alcohol percentage . and after tasting it , i see why . at 4.5 % abv , its is a little low for a sticke and the hops were nearly non-existent . aromas were rather off putting with a stale malt aroma dominating . this was a very sweet cloying alt with not enough hops to balance and the aftertaste was reminicient of a ringwood brew . they could just take their hex nut brown ale and call it an alt and be closer to the style .

the aroma was of malt and maple smoke . somewhat promising , so i moved on .  certainly a curious beer , with a taste that is flowery . not sure if the chrysanthemum replaces the hops as although there was a taste it was not overwhelming . very light straw-coloured texture with little carbonation . beer does not have any real body to talk of , and with the low alcohol content has little to carry it .  good and refreshing crispness in the mouth , which provided some balance to the flavor .

the aroma was of a sweet orange/bread malts and spicy hops .  my friends always make fun of me for drinking it saying that it is worse than drinking old milwaukee warm , but i disagree . it is a good light bodies beer with a sweet kind of taste to it . very good .  mouthfeel is good , but drinkability is low due to the creeping sourness and port notes that just do n't work with the underlying flavor profile .

some head retention & lacing s : bready & fruity ( apricot jam & marmalade ) t : some apricot , caramel , leafy & woody hops up front .  the colour is a lightly hazed thin orange , the head does not really exist , only a minor glass ring .  nose is a creamy butterscotch sweetness , and palate of creamy sweet butterscotch with a balanced bitter and a touch of gypsum . absolutely one yummy ale and a must try for anyone . bass pale ale has been on my list of beers to buy when the price is right . bass pale ale is a good tasting pale ale that has been around for a very long time . well , i just went through a twelve pack and lo and behold this brew has turned to banta podo , it is nothing at all what it used to be !
s : sour cherry , lambic smell .  a : bright yellow lemon/lager coloring with no head . i sure did get a lot of floaties too .  mouthfeel : all is well and good .

roasty , bready malts on the nose , decent citrusy hop presence , and a prickling of warm spice .  ) a : pours a 100 % transparent straw color that produces a very fizzly and carbonated head that lasts for about 30 seconds and leaves no lacing along the glass .  m- good carbonation and quite smooth .

the aroma was of mixture of malts with hops , very good in balance .  this is a solid beer for the price . when they say extra pale on the front of the bottle , they mean extra pale . it has almost no head and it really does n't smell like much of anything . this beer seems to be the choice of many non-beer drinkers that normally drink liquor because it does n't have much of a beer taste .  good feel here , this is a decent body with good carbonation .

very light color in the glass , after i pour it , one thing that i must admit is that the smell that came out of the glass was amazing ! overall if you are seeking for a `` liquid dessert '' this might hit the spot but not something to drink the whole night .  into a big ol ' mug , the color and smell were not overly impressive . same straw body with fizzy head and a slightly odd smell . i think i found a new cheap summer beer .  '' other than that , it 's water . it provides a subtle tartness that 's far more apparent in real belgian belgians . the tart , twangy , dark-sweet mouthfeel is actually a good one , particularly within such a watery-light medium . again , aligned with expectations from a macrobrewery , the carbonation is more than ample . the feel of full moon is its superior attribute .
aroma is an aromatic blend of caramel , toffee , dark ripe fruit , molasses , malt .  appearance is meh , straw yellow , no real head or lacing .  light bodied and smooth yet dry .

a - deep orange haze that fades out to a milky yellow , almost reminiscent of widmer . s - very strong blend of banana and clove , which was quite sweet .  falstaff is typical macro yellow color .  well carbonated .

s : a little bit of caramel and vanilla , light bourbon aromas , some darker fruit , and a little bit of molasses and brown sugar .  very pale yellow in color , almost lemonade like . pours with a sprtizy head and stays fairly well carbonated .  very creamy mouthfeel , but i must admit that this brew was far too heavy for my taste .

smells lightly of wheat and more of a malt fruitiness with a nice dose of banana . that dominates the nose .  pours a pale golden , straw color . white head that dissipated rather quickly . aroma is grainy and reminds me of a typical american adjunct .  smooth somewhat creamy and drying mouthfeel , i have had much creamier kolsch and want something hoppier as well .

winey scent , as advertised is the vanilla and perhaps a touch of raisin .  just looked and smelled the part of a yellow beer . cinnamon might make me think of pumpkin pie , but not pumpkin itself . tough to drink , and at the price , better options . seriously , blue moon 's is better .  m - light body and low to moderate carbonation . a nice crisp body .

smell was very enticing and aromatic with a malty/chocolate aroma .  poured very dark with absolutely no head .  smells kind of like dishwashing liquid , very soapy , but distinct of certain hop combos ... or so i 've discovered over the years . there 's an even malty / big dextrin sweetness and medium-mouthfeel , but the depth of flavour is one dimensional . hops come in as a gentle bitter citric tingle on the palate , then turns into a faint tea-like character as it fades into the malty blandness . hops are a bit oily . earth flavours run through the middle . finish has some residual hop and soap-like flavours . or perhaps the way the hops played out , combined with the dull malty flavours , rubbed me the wrong way ?

s - this beer smells nice . citrisy , slight pine , a little earthy .  bbd of jan 08 , picked this up on a whim , let 's see how it rolls : pours a spritzy golden with 3+ fingers of white head . zero head retention & lacing s : fruit juice ( apricot & peach juice ) , maybe a hint of honey & not much else t : peach & apricot juice with some metallic twang up front .  the mouthfeel is good . it is a low bodied beer with good carbonation .

a bit thick and maybe overpowering , but it 's distinct and interesting . the taste itself is much , much more bland .  while it is refreshing ( along the lines of seltzer water ) it really has no taste or smell to speak of , a wedge of lime or lemon is an absolute necessity for this to be enjoyed , it belongs in the same category as maybe gatorade or some such , but beer ?  very true mouthfeel for a lager .

the aroma was very malty with a huge nutty quality and i could almost smell the butter melting in the pint glass .  got a bottle left over from some competition botteling that founders had done to some of their non regular brews . no head . no lacing .  at the least the mouthfeel is , typical of apas , nice and creamy .

nose was heavy sweet . a bit of floral characteristics noted .  i drank this sitting in a hot tub at my hotel after a long day of skiing . this beer is about as clear yellow as it gets . like many beers of the type , it was loaded with carbonation that stings the tongue and covers some of the lack of flavor .  good carbonation .

strong hoppy scent - citrus and spice - but not overwhelming . slight alcohol in the background .  12oz can poured down my gullet . nose is well , macro lager bland meh nose .  taste-crisp and light , a decent amount of hop and rice flavor does come through , finishes smoothly on the palette , not the best thing i 've ever tasted but at least flavor is there . mouthfeel-nice enough , flavor is there and goes down smoothly , not overbearing and not too light . drinkability-as good as any other lager i 'm sure , you can have as many as you want at only 5 % alcohol .

s : first thing i get is the grainy smell i get from most pilsners . background i get some tart fruit , and apricot and maybe light peach .  served in a can from brick store pub , atlanta , ga a : pale orange with no head . seemed to look like a flat watermelon soda than a beer .  m : medium body . moderate carbonation that finishes with some fizz on the tip of my tongue .

s - nice roasted grains , chocolate , etc but a bit mild .  poured into a 12oz tumbler appearance - very pale straw yellow appearence , with a finger head that disappears fairly quickly smell - in terms of smell , the only scent i picked up was a mild bread/yeast smell .  m & d- i do like the mouthfeel , it matches the style nicely .

s : hmm , abv is quite apparent and reminds me of some belgian beers , slightly sweet and fruity . cough syrup .  pours a cloudy , maize color . 1/4 inch head of an off-white color . slight retention and poor lacing . overall , weak appearance and body , but good blend .  taste is good , mouthfeel is quite good .

the smelled like caramel and tasted a biy t like it also .  a wavy copper-yellow , light burnished peach-orange tints , sparsely bubbled through the body , with an immediately and fully diminishing white head that creates little to no lacing .  appearance dark for an ipa , like iced tea ; minimum head that drops fast smell very little smell , but i detect candied fruit and caramelized sugar , but very little hops taste & mouthfeel flavor is full , but it has no real character or pronounced hoppiness ; thick , oily mouth feel which is quite nice ; it 's hard to think of this as even a form of an ipa ; it 's more like an old ale/strong ale/ barley wine -- it 's really syrupy sweet and artificially fruit-flavored overall it 's just a bit too much sweetness for me .

s ) interesting notes . i get banana , as well as rich caramel & toffee ... banana bread even . almost school chemistry estery ... .  appearance is a light straw color with a quick fizzy head with carbonation rising to the top that fades quickly .  m - mouthfeel is nice and full and goes down nicely d - pretty decent dunkel .

smell - get that yeast up front with fruits in the back very pleasant to smell .  slightly hazy amber brown in color . the small white head disappears within a minute or less ; there is no lace to speak of , carbonation is quite mild .  m : nicely bitter , typical ale feel with alcohol front and center , no foaming action . t : overpowering alcohol made this seem like i was having a shot , the licorace flavor and hops fruitiness were strong but a bit of a can taste and a thin malt flavor ended it .

smell : just like coffee . mouthfeel : thick beer , as what you would expect from a stout .  pours pale gold with a small suddy head .  there simply is no malt presence here what so ever . sierra makes a few of imo the best ipa/pale ales on the planet . instead the citrus flavors just take an off turn . this one goes down pretty quickly . the alcohol is present and the hops are brutal ( very good thing ) and it goes down well . i like this beer and it is certainly the most enjoyable of the beer camp , but this is one of the weaker double ipas out there .

smell : nice aroma of fruits , caramel , malts , and slightly bitter hops . too bad , because it seemed promising from the look and aroma . with the taste , i 'm not even sure if i can finish this .  pours a hay coloured yellow with a dish watery head that dies really quickly .  m - it was crisp , sharp and very smooth . a medium bodied beer with a dry finish .

smells nutty and chocolatey , alcohol is coming forth the most alcohol i 've ever tasted in a porter .  it pours reddish-brown , with next to no head , no lace and no collar .  i get tomato , celery , black pepper and then a wave of cedar . the hops were definitely present in it , but i could n't get past the heavy cedar flavors . sorry , but not to my liking .

s : a dark , roasted smell with some coffee undertones which was quite enticing .  cloudy , whitish yellow color .  some how the spices dont drown out the actual beer . m- light , prickly , crackly and drying . very crisp despite all the insane herbs and spices . d- not as drinkable as a normal saison . this beer is wildly herbal and spicy .

aroma was strong and solid , by far the best feature of this beer . slightly sweet bread with a very specific hop ( herbal and pine-like ) punch . i continued drinking it , hoping it would mellow out and i would find it 's wonderful hidden character , but all i can say is that this one is not for me .  pours a slightly hazy straw like yellow with a quickly dissipating foamy white head that leaves no lace . looks more like carbonated apple juice than beer .  mouthfeel : adequately fizzy .

s : nice aroma of roasted oats and bitter but sweet coffee flavors . t : decent sweet roasted oats to begin , but the flavoring simply disappears too quickly .  pours a very pale gold color with a small white dome and minimal lacing . kind of dull looking actually .  yet , fragrance is almost soapy . mouth feel is creamy . this beer has an unusual consistency for an ipa ; it is smooth , almost silky .

aroma is clean , yeasty with citrus and light skinned fruits . no funk of much measure , earthy hops .  o'doul 's pours a clear light straw with no head .  m - nice medium-full body and creamy . low carbonation .

boozy nose with with some decent roast and chocolate character .  dammit , i was so excited about this beer , right up until i poured it . looked weird , pale and milky and raw like the bruery 's mischief on tap . like something that 's been souring under a leaky washing machine over the summer months .  m- pretty light body , nice carbonation . i am a fan of less carbonated beers and this one is perfect for me as far as carbonation goes .

s : sweet banana , sweet bread/yeast , grapefruit . t : tart , bitter , slightly grapefruity yeast . o : ok , but extremely overrated .  a : pours a golden straw color with a near non existent head that dissipates in a matter of 15 seconds . no lace to speak of .  mouthfeel is decent , not too thin or thick .

s - coffee , vanilla , and sweetness from the roasted malts t - tastes like a cheap vanilla coffee .  appearance : yellow with a thin white head ; not too impressive looking smell : skunky cereal smell ; typicaly macro smell taste : slight malt presence ; skunky presence ; i 'll give them a 3 though becuase this is one of the best macro lagers i 've had mouthfeel : light bodied , could definitely have a few in a night drinkability : good  it had a very smooth mouthfeel , surprisingly similar to what i 'd get out of a tap . the taste however was watery to me .

smell - floral hops mix with a nice malt aroma .  basically a cheap version vanilla version of blue moon . i wasted 40 bucks on 11.2 oz bottles of cheap crap !  damn this stuff is sweet and syrupy . while the beer is very smooth with a long finish , the sweetness in this beer , coupled with the high alcohol , is just overwhelming . i really think a bit less alcohol and sweetness , and a lot more hops , would do this beer a world of good .

not really overdone and definitely a pretty good smelling beer . well spiced without losing the brown ale base of the beer .  poured in a yellow color and with a finger of quickly disappearing foam .  pretty good .

strong and sweet aroma of treacle / caramel , roasted malts , molasses , bakery and chocolate . nice !  the beer pours a light straw color , forming a thin white head , that quickly fades .  there is the lemon zest flavor , but i also get apple cider vinegar and just sour , sour , sour . the sour flavors aside , i will say the beer is pretty light on the palate with the abv . very well disguised . shared this bottle with 4 other people thank god , including a guy at the table next to me ( belmont station cafe ) drinking some gueuze . he was quite grateful , noting the beatification was much better then his gueuze .

aroma of citrus , bread , and caramel malts .  appearance- on the first pour this is far less cloudy than it will be shortly , with the yeast addition . straw yellow and thin , the snow white head roars loudly to about two fingers and settles over the first two minutes to zero . it became slightly cloudier ( not nearly as much as i 'd expected ) , and the head droppped even faster than the first time . no lacing at all in either case .  a sweeter fuller tasting brew than maybe a budweiser m- medium bodied brew , carbonation was pretty good .

the smell is hard to describe , lots of stuff is going on here . spices of different kinds . odd .  pours like ginger ale , which coincidentally is frequently sold in the same trade-green color containers . well ... okay , i had to stop laughing and give it a try . it did take me 2 years to stop laughing , however . it 's nothing exciting , and if it 's cheap and i 'm having a cheap party , i 'd buy a few 6-packs .  m : well carbonated and it feels full in your mouth .

smell - spices , hops , caramel . taste - malt , caramel tate , but ends with a bitterness sourness taste at the end .  a - it looks like any light beer , a very clear yellow with carbonation rising around the edges . it was very inviting , but i had a long day and any beer would have been .  the smooth palate is really the only thing that stands out about this . i would drink it but not buy it again , i could easily kill a six pack of it because of the smooth mouthfeel .

smell has a great bit of toasted malts and nuts . taste is big let down from the nice smell , flavor is very thin and watery with just a bit of nutty flavor with a little toasted grains and a mild earthy quality .  pours a straw yellow color with a thin white head and little lace .  milky , filling , decent carbonation and not overly assulting ... pretty decent feel .
it had a nice dark chocolate smell , with a touch of bread .  typical cheap pale lager .  it was very much on the thick side .

the smell of the beer had a decent spiciness to it and got me a little curious to taste it .  this is a decent , fairly enjoyable lager , but very basic , thin , characterless , and not even `` brown '' . dark gold , just slightly darker than a normal pale lager , it has rather ugly big bubbles , a medium off-white head that soon vanishes to leave a few foamy bubbles .  good smooth mouthful , did a good job on carbonation .
good . t : a little awkward blend of flavors attacking my palate .  pours a very pale yellow/gold color with a white head that is quickly gone .  mouthfeel is heavy , slick , and coating .

robust caramel , sweet raisins , dried cherries .  actually , as far as `` drinkability '' , bud light has nothing on this beer . this beer actually has some color , and a bit of taste . in the end a very watery , smooth beer .  mouthfeel is nice and creamy-thick .

s. honey with some oxidation ; similar to david bell is 21 .  a steady pour generates a few centimeters of foam . doa after a minute , it looks just like apple juice .  m - light bodied and dry just like a dry irish stout should be . medium carbonation with nice carbonic bite to aid in drying sensation .

smell is very light and fruity , with a sweet almost strawberry hop aroma .  this light-bodied , low-intensity ale refuses to assert more than minimal amounts of carbonation , head , lace , or flavor . it is brown with ruby highlights and ventures little further than the threshold of dark chocolate flavor .  not bad , but not spectacular either ; one might use the term `` '' average '' '' here . mouthfeel is good , being crisp , clean , and smooth , and finishing a touch dry , which leaves one desiring another sip . overall , a decent witbier that i would n't ever oppose drinking , but it certainly would not be first choice in the style .
quickly dissapated leaving a little bit of lace s - cherries dominate the flanders sour aroma .  looks kinda like muddy water .  medium bodied and highly carbonated and crisp .

fresh aroma of citrusy and piney hops with a mild hint of malt .  this beer pours a clear dehydrated urine yellow color .  one positive is the full bodied presence of the malt , although the carbonation comes across as lighter than expected .

resinous and citrus hops on the nose . a good amount of earthiness , as well .  absolutely no retention or lace .  easily the best part of the beer . refreshing tingly carbonation with the wheat providing nice texture and some length .

the aroma was very malty and sweet .  pours an extra clear light straw . thin and soapy head with poor retention and scarce lacing .  mouthfeel - the mouthfeel was pretty good . even tho the head was essentially nil , the carbonation was very active which was noticeable in the mouth .

it 's a subtle scent and quite pleasing .  other than that , there 's no head at all , no lacing , it 's hazy , and has bits of sediment in it .  m : average , fine ... . good carbonation , nice density and thickness .
aroma of hops , caramel malt , and orange peel .  typical macro lager in appearance..light yellow with a small white head .  good mouthfeel , and went down well .

being on a real chocolate stout kick , i must say i was extremely disappointed in this beer said to be brewed with `` chocolate , molasses and lactose '' . it smelled right but tasted very average . the smell and first few sips had some notes of cocoa powder but that taste quickly disappeared and turned into a moderate imperial stout .  we had it in copper harbor michigan along with planked fish . it is easy to drink and you can have a few or more without getting too filled up .  there is a definite hop bitterness that tries to balance out any sweetness that is left over , but gets lost in the wash. that being said , it 's bold in the body and has a pleasantly smooth but lively mouthfeel .

there 's an average amount of lacing left behind on the glass . aroma is oak , pine hops , vanilla , caramel and some citrusy hops . however , the taste is n't as appealing as the aroma . the brew tastes like floral and pine hops , oak and caramel malt , but the flavors are subtle and seemed to be watered down .  i was excited when i first saw this in my downtown beer store , but it seemed to fall when i popped it open at home ... pours with a lack luster head , and has a molasses , toffee strange sugar aroma ... 1 in 5 americans has genital herpes ... some nice flavours and abv is well hidden but it does n't really do it for me ... happy to try it , happier i wo n't have to again !  m-has a tart , creamy medium carbonation with a slightly dry finish d-well as much as i do n't like it as a witbier , i do n't think this beer is all that bad and it does seem to go down easily .

the scent seems to give me the impression of summertime .  limp puny yellow , you can see the carbonation . meager white head .  mouthfeel : the carbonation of this beer makes it super crisp with a dry finish .

smell of chocolate with a light coffee and smoked note .  certainly looks and tastes better than bud , but then again , so does almost anything else . if people are willing to pay that price for this pale imitation , let 'em . this was n't even as good as the sapporo i had before it .  m - medium mody and moderate carbonation .

aroma is lots of malt sweet caramel some toffee lots of citrus hops hit the nose at the start but soon fade under the malt .  clear bottle is a light golden yellow that leaves no head in the glass .  this beer has a full body as would be expected in a slightly sweet beer . the carbonation is low .

s-amazing smell of berrys but oh so sweet . t- good for the first few but after 2 or 3 its off to the dentist .  poured from bottle into pint glass appearance - a very pale straw yellow color with white head that fades very fast . not a great look for a brew , but standard for a light i would say .  m : lighter side of medium body , medium body , slick feel with a sticky finish .

pleasant , interesting smell , medium malts and lots of fruit - apple , green grape , melon .  it 's a sickly red color , no head , and a barely tolerable flavor .  body is medium with nice carbonation and a semi dry finish .

the taste is also very beer , but that special smell is also expressed in the taste .  the beer was absolutely flat with absolutely no carbonation .  mouthfeel is medium to full bodied with low carbonation .

smell is saison funk spice and a pronounced pepper note . nice flavors , not enough of them . could drink many of these , solid summer beer , but flavor and substance are lacking .  nice . pours a crystal clear pale yellow color with a brief flash of foam that is gone before i could even take a sniff .  m - medium body and moderate carbonation .

s - nice mix of bread , malt and roasted coffee , no hops -- just right for the style .  a : pours a slightly murky pale straw body with almost no head .  f - medium bodied with good carbonation , refreshingly smooth .

the smell was the best part of this beer . this would be a good summer beer .  pours borring clear and yellow with little head , like a standard crappy macro .  the amount of bitterness is perfect for an american pale ale but the type of hops they used disagrees with my palate 100 % . their website said they used summit , nelson sauvin , and alchemy hops in this beer . i 'm assuming its the summit or the nelson sauvin hops because i like their ipa and it has alchemy hops in it . would be a great beer if they used something like cascade instead . but then i guess it 'd probably just taste like sierra nevada .

looks pretty light on the pour , very little head that 's gone quick . smells very strongly of hazelnut , maybe even kind of peanut buttery .  fizzy yellowy brown in color .  m - feel pretty spot on for a wit .

s - dried bananas , dry wheat , lemon , spices . t - lemon , clean wheat , banana , lemongrass , coriander , floral hops .  a very murky brown with almost no head .  mouthfeel : thick and creamy with low carbonation . has an element of smoothness to it .

smell : it smells better than it tastes ; i was expecting something of better quality after i took a whiff .  pours a clear yellow with a thin white head that vanishes , leaving a few bubbles . you can tell there is not protien or gluten in this just by looking at it .  the mouthfeel on this beer is very creamy and pleasant , however this beer seriously taste like they made a guinness and then ripped out all the good taste .

aroma : candy like tart granny smith apple esters , mixed with the tartness is a mild spicing that i picked up in there . my one complaint is the beer is one dimensional with regards to malt and hop character those are overshadowed by the apple esters .  not head really , and its smell is pretty average as well . easily one of the better cheap beers out there .  just what i expect from a fantome .

s - sweet malts with a bready yeast aroma dominate .  pours a pale straw yellow with a couple fingers of head .  less then exciting , sub par for an ipa . flavors are more citrus , the carbonation makes it brighter , and the obligatory pine is noted , more balanced then other ipas , i would say this is more balanced then most `` east coast '' ipas , really borders the pale ale territory , which is what i always thought this beer was . i remember liking this beer more when i was just getting into craft , either my palate has matured past c hops as a preferance or i got a lame batch .

s -very yeasty , and floral . with strawberry tones . the smell is the best part of this beer by far . t - hoppy , i think it was fuggle hops . d - not bad .  a-pours a cloudy dark amber color . there is basically no head that i can conjure up and no lace left behind .  it does go down smooth , nice carbonation .

aroma is nice fresh hops lots of pine needles with under lying orange peels . taste is not as nice as aroma its all hops little to hot not nice and piny and bitter like most ipa 's .  the appearance was not very good at all . if your looking for a cheap beer that has a nice buzz this is your brew !  fine and litle ginger mouthfeel though probably from the other used spices . well balanced & carbonated brew that 's a pleasure to drink if you can catch it in your glas as it is very rapidly out of the botle ... .

smell : deep roasted malts ; very oaty and raw ; nice coffee-esque scents .  poured out a yellowish gold . not too much of a head to brag about although i do n't think this style of beer is supposed to have much head .  m - good feel and smooth d - it was worth trying but i wo n't be getting it again tried both the bottled and tap .

pours a reddish orange color with white head . nose is dominated by raspberries with a little grassy bits as well . very raspberry flavours almost tastes like slushie syrup .  pours a short , shirt lived white fizzy head . beer is an orange golden color . low head retention , no lacing .  m. medium bodied with low carbonation .

hmm odd beer here . too much fruit on the finish just out of whack really . spicey and an almost rye flavor on the finish as well .  no visible carbonation and no head , so obviously no retention and no lacing .  m : full-bodied , frothy carbonation , pretty smooth , easy drinking for its size .

pretty nice and sour , i like the nose quite a bit . i actually liked the nose quite a bit , but the taste went downhill as it was very bland and lost all the white wine and brett from the nose .  a : light yellow , clear s : typical american adjunct lager grainy smell . o : i could care less about how good or bad the beer was ; i was on vacation and having a beer , away from the bud light dominated cruise ship .  m : full body , smooth texture , medium carbonation .

good yeasty aroma .  pours a fizzy light yellow with a little frothy head that diminishes quickly . pours like most macro beers .  ever since , this has been a complete struggle to drink and one i wont go back to . it 's a good looking beer with good texture , and probably a valiant effort for people who do n't get onions from the hops .

smells of roasted vanilla-bean-coffee with a shot of chocolate syrup . palate starts with in-your-face roasty sweetness .  baltika # 9 is a weak pale yellow in color with an average-sized , bright white head .  it has a very thick mouthfeel and a kind of grapefruit like flavor .

s : loads of chocolate and cocoa with hints of vanilla and molasses . cheap , shitty , chocolate mixed with alcohol .  the doppelbock is a lot lighter than others i have had . the beer poured with a very small white head and disappeared quickly leaving no lacing . from the looks of it , i am not overly compelled to take a drink .  medium body , medium effervescence , good aftertaste where the malt comes out after the hop start .

big pride of ringwood hit ... this reminds me of my childhood when my dad would give me the dregs of a longneck ... for nostalgia , i give smell a good rating .  had an actual pepper floating in the bottle , a big one too , 3 inches long . poured a very yellow color and overly fizzy - reminded me of mountain dew . as a result it gets higher marks , because it is supposed to be hot and spicy .  pretty good for style .

smell : floral notes with a deeper and more dank earthy-malt aroma . taste : funky , bitter , nettle-like taste with malt background .  a- very light , almost clear straw color . white frothy head , initial about 2 fingers on top , quickly diminishes to just a light film . must be something positive with the water up in canada .  mouthfeel is crisp , and somewhat clean , well carbonated and fairly refreshing .

honey is potent in the nose , bread and caramel . too floral for my liking .  appearance : cloudy , light-copper color with an unusually large amount of suspended particulate matter . small , white head disappears quickly leaving average lacing .  m : nice and light , rather bubbly .

smell is complete caramel . taste is extremely weak when considering it 's very strong aroma . while there is a very sweet sense of caramel , it 's bland for the most part . overall , despite it 's good aroma , it 's not an impressive brew at all .  a- hazy dark yellowish color with a awful lot of bubbles s- faint scent of pumpkin and spices t- very light pumpkin flavor tastes more like a wannabe oktoberfest style with a metallic aftertaste m- light , watery kinda overcarbonated o- not terrible but it did n't really taste like a pumpkin ale .  a buttery mouthfeel which is unique and nice . medium body and medium carbonation .

aroma is also great . rich and complex , coffee grounds , dark chocolate . great coffee beers smell like fresh espresso , this is a bit stale though . again , more stale grounds than fresh espresso .  bottle ( bottled on 10/27/2011 ) served into a nonic pint glass pours a pepsi cola brown color . black lager ? head size is miniscule , with about zero retention . apart from the appearance , schlalfy made a faithful rendition of the style .  fairly full in body , awfully fruity for an ipa with distinct apricot flavors .

s : sour and funky , fermented green apples and cherries with some spice and faint smells of chardonnay . t : like the smell but more cherry and chardonnay with some hops in there as well ( but not much ) .  has a very pale yellow color with a 1/2 inch head .  appearance - poured with a thin head that quicly dissipated to a whisper-thin ring around the glass , very dark brown with a hint of crimson when held up to light smell - malts , brown sugar , spices ( sage , juniper , rosemary ) , picking up some slight green apple taste - coffee or dark chocolate like bitterness , getting the same spices in the taste , hint of alcohol , slight hops but are quickly overpowered by the spices mouthfeel - full and creamy drinkability - would only be able to drink one of these at a time a very interesting beer and a great effort from the three brewers .

s : spicy smell of coriander/anise . yeasties in there also but not as strong as the spice .  spit thin head on a piss yellow body .  this is my first review on beer advocate and i will try to do my best with reviewing beers . a very sweet taste goes down very smooth .

aroma is a light sweet malt backed by a mild spicy hop type aroma .  poured out to a pale yellow color with a short lived foamy head that dissolved in mere seconds .  m- medium body with a moderate carbonation .

the beer smelled of oranges and grape fruit and had a few spices .  a- pours a 2 finger soapy , seltzer water head that recedes pretty quickly leaving no lacing .  mouth : milky smoothness . bit frothy .

smell : reminds me almost of one of my homebrews . the smell of spice hits the nose right off , followed by a mild hop and malt combination .  on tap at brewery in cleveland , ohio a not much of a head and `` piss yellow .  -original gravity : 1.052 -final gravity : 1.013 -abv : 5.2 % -abw : 4.06 % -attenuation : 74.2 % -real extract : 5.04 p -calories per 12 oz : 170 -malts : two row harrington , wheat malt , vienna malt -hops : east kent goldings , spalt spalter while i like the fact that bbc ( or anyone for that matter ) makes a kolsch style ale , i dont think this ones that great an interpretation . the fairly delicate , softly carbonated body is subtly malty , but even more subtle so that this lover of subtlety can appreciate . the slightly zippy , almost citric tail is pretty much what ive come to expect from american-style kolsch beers , though not having had a real koln kolsch , i dont know if this particular flavor is present in the classics .

it 's a pretty clear yellow color with no head , it does have a great wheat & blackberry aroma to it which is very appealing , and the taste seems almost watered down compared to say one of dogfish heads fruit beers .  appearance is a rather bright yellow , very clear , no head retention to speak of .  medium mouthfeel .
smell : some nice floral hops with some notes of pine .  a : basically looks like a macro lager , perhaps a slight hint of haze .  medium body with moderate carbonation . quite smooth .

nice aroma . orange juice & other citrus smells with some sweet fruitiness and bubble gum . i like my wits light , refreshing and easy to drink to beat the summer time ( or here in nc the fall ) heat .  on tap at vagabondo in cph denmark a - pale golden color but frankly not much color to the beer .  nice creamy body as it goes down .

the aroma was mostly wheat from the bottle , but when poured the cherry was very prominent .  there 's no head , lacing or any other staying of carbonation at the top of the beer , coupled with the colour of apple juice makes it receive a poor grade . anyone giving it a good rating is probably drunk .  mouthfeel is pretty nice , i would think this beer was thin , but it is n't .

smell : nice tangy chocolate aroma to it with a subtle malt compliment .  500 ml brown bottle dark brown beer with a fizzy head that disappears as fast as you pour it .  mouthfeel is fine , would n't suggest , there are far better ipa 's out there .

brown bottle , no freshness date appearence : cloudy bronze with a thin head , small lacing . smell : blossoms , pomegranate , grapefruit , pale grains . taste : citrus , pine , finishing with a nice drying herbal spiciness .  a - golden color but looks watery ; head disappears immediately ; big bubbles .  the texture in the mouth is quite good , remaining effervescent and enjoyable throughout this tasting .

first smell gives you a nice fresh floral hop burst . this one started off promising but on closer examination it is lacking .  pours a straw yellow - light lace head .  in a pinch i 'll take yuengling 's lord chesterfield over this , but both are poseur craft beers with crisp carbonation , appreciable hop bitterness and easy drinkability .

it has a wonderful blueberry scent , but unfortunately the blueberry also overrides the wheat beer taste . it 's exactly as good or as nasty as that sounds .  pours a brilliant golden colour with a half-finger head that dies down very quickly to almost nothing ; not even a cap remains .  good tingle all over the tongue and a bit in the throat .
there are some nice cinnamon , nutmeg , and pumpkin smells .  appearance : very hazy brown colored . does not look appetizing .  good sensation in the mouth .

s : most prominent on the smell is the vanilla , it masks roasted malts and a hint of coffee . t : the taste is pretty disappointing .  *did not like would not buy* app : dull copper not attractive , nothing magical about this beer .  full body and medium mouthfeel has some chew to it followed by some cloying .
not much to look at but the aroma was very inviting . soft malted brew that has a very nice hop presence .  this is really an ugly looking beer .  light/medium mouthfeel .

s- might be the best part of this brew , comes in strong with pumpkin pie spice and cloves and nutmeg . smells like a pumpkin pie .  nothing too special , just your typical macro lager , only lighter and crisper . in the summer when you want a change from the typical macro , this is a good choice .  has a creamy mouthfeel and was mildly complex .

smell - bitter , grapefruit , flowery smell .  pours red/brown , hazy , zero bubbles or head of any kind . the complete lack of carbonation makes this taste like a juice/vinegar combo .  fairly smooth . would n't be able to guess that it weighs in at 6.5 % .

spicy wheat aromatics that are slightly perfumy . quite complex herbal and spicy notes in the background .  road dog poured a deep amber color , almost brown but translucent . i expected darker from a beer that touts itself as a porter . there was no head form the bottle so none to dissipate .  m - i really like the mouthfeel of this beer . it is perfectly carbonated and that takes over when it first hits the tongue .

smell : grape-grass and sweet alcohol . very wheaty with just a touch of vine fruit ... seems like it might be a flavored witbier .  nice full colour label with a 1940s-style pinup girl infront of an image of niagara falls . i only note this because most ocb labels look like garbage . pours a clear , if not slightly translucent golden colour , with little in the way of head beyond the initial pour and no lacing . relatively unattractive as a craft beer .  this beer was quite thick in body but not too smooth .
smells pruney with a background of hops and alcohol .  had at the brewery tour , color was typical straw and had very minor head .  m : medium body , with good carbonation gives a pleasant feel .

this beer smelled like something i was going to enjoy ... t..unfortunately , the taste left a lot to be desired .  the appearance is pale gold with a thin head .  the mouthfeel is on the heavy side of medium bodied , and it glides down your throat as smooth as hell .

s : very bold pear esters , some mint , apple blossoms , floral , mostly roses . l : cloudy burnt orange , nice off-white creamy head , great retention and lacing . very disappointing , especially since i loved all of their other beers .  that said is has a weak head .  m -- -medium bodied with good carbonation .

aroma is clean and candyish and a good amount of malted doughy sweetness with brown sugar , caramel , and powdered donuts adding to the aroma . simple , clean , and an unlasting , quick , impression of a basic malt profile is really all there is to it .  shoulda drank from the bottle so i would n't have seen the fact that this is not a stout . dirty brown water , hazy . medium head , not real creamy looking in the head .  mouthfeel is actually pretty good .
smell was very good very rich and almost fruity .  pours a light yellow color with a faint head .  mouthfeel is nice , feels full , with good carbonation .

s : very vineous , winey , with a touch of oak and red berries . t : oaky goodness up front with a big blast of sour .  pours with a very pale yellow body topped by a medium thick quickly disappearing head with a good amount of lace left behind .  mouthfeel/drinkability ; the mouthfeel may be the best thing going on with this beer . full bodied , and close to syrupy in feel , with a very low carbonation .

smells pretty good with huge roasted barley notes that give it a coffee smell it also has a slight chocolaty note to it with an oceany note in the back . very pleasant indeed .  pours hazy pale orange into a pint glass , super fizzy white head is gone in seconds , no ring , no lace , nothing .  mouth feel is smooth and crisp with an average carbonation level .

the best part about the beer is the aroma , which is fresh and biscuity , and certainly has me pining to taste .  note : there was a lot of soild yucky looking sediments in the bottom of the glass .  m - very nice feeling , no aftertaste .

the smell is piney , but not overly so , and i get the sense that the hops are going to make it bitter .  pours a yellow color , with a greasy haze ( like pickle brine ) . head is pretty insubstantial .  mouthfeel is lively and crisp but smoothes out . your tongue feels the bitterness at first , but it does n't last long , which makes this a pretty drinkable hop-focused beer .

smell definitely of blueberry with enough malt to know that this is a beer . overall i do n't believe that taste lives up to the smell .  strange beer , sold for a dollar at the local hot-spot . there was definite maltiness in this one , something along the lines of a light bock , no kidding . a cheap and effective beer .  the mouth is full . adequately carbonated , the flavor is malty but it 's not matching up to the nose well .

it has a very interesting and good smell to me . very crisp and refreshing to smell . taste , unfortunately , does n't quite live up to the smell 's standards .  it poured into my pint glass and formed a large foamy white head that dissipated after 2 mins . it pours the pale yellow of a coors or bud , but with clouds of yeast inside .  nice medium- to full body . smooth .

scents of wood , berries ( mainly raspberries ) , sweet dark malts and caramel . cloying , sticky raspberry and malty sweetness combine with a major lack of carbonation and a very thin body to achieve complete unbalane in my opinion . too fruity , too sour and too sweet .  pours a light golden color.. memories of bud light in a glass come to the forefront.. it has to at least taste better than that .  mouthfeel : light- to medium-bodied and pretty smooth . good amount of carbonation to go with the stronger parts of the flavor .

smells of yeast , wheat , lemon , and apricot .  a finger of off-white foamy head , quickly dissipating . orange in color , murky , big chunks of sediment .  the alcohol is quite heart-burn-a-rific , the mouthfeel is good - `` light/medium '' but the taste is just missing something.. if i knew what..i woudl tell you .

smell : nice smell !  schlitz malt liquor pours a pale fizzy yellow with a fluffy white head from a brown thirty two ounce bottle .  good mouthfeel , with just the right amount of carbonation . found the flavors to be very mild , and it took a lot of sips to really get the full feel of this brew .
( s ) - a nice piney citrus zest of lemon , lime , and pineapple . almost dry and oaky too .  very pale pour with a thin , fizzy head .  m : juicy with just enough carbonation to tingle the tongue .

fresh yeast and malts , with some faint bubblegum . bitterness that bites at the wrong places .  pours a dark brown with red highlights . soda-pop carbonation quickly fizzes away leaving no head or lacing at all .  m : moderate body , moderate to high carbonation . appropriate for style .

has a distinctive belgian character about it but the heavy stout characters are also there , raisins dark fruits , dark swwet caramel and sugar . very appetizing with some chocolatly notes also . holly crap is this carbonated , way way too much . it becomes a bit easier to drink , still very carbonted though .  appearance : pours with an average amount of head which quickly dissipates , leaving virtually nil by the middle of the beer . lots of moist lacing . pale yellow colour , lots of unusually small bubbles .  the mouthfeel was decently thick . this beer needed carbonation and some balance to it .

definite apricot aroma pouring through .  on tap in a goose island chalice at bodega on 10/7/11 clear , pale golden color . poured no head , save a pinstripe ring of retention . meh .  note : this is the review of creamy mcstout , not the cream stout . says on the menu it has a `` special ingredient to make it taste more like bailey 's irish cream . '' that special ingredient tastes like it is vanilla syrup extract , and a lot of it , and it really brings down the beer . in my opinion cream stouts have enough sweetness on their own , but this syrup blunts any of the potential subtleties found in the flavor . it was dark , rich , and smooth , but too sticky-sweet and one dimensional for my liking .

cloudy dark reddish-brown . s : dank and citrus hops . smells like an ipa with no malty `` redness '' .  packaged in oct 2006 pours chestnut/mahogany with a pinky of tan head . no head retention or lacing s : coffee t : chocolate & coffee mingle up front with dryness & toasted/singed grain .  mouthfeel was pretty good , it was medium bodied , on the thick side , and quite creamy .

n : very good pumpkin aroma along with caramel and light spices ( mostly nutmeg . ) t : the spiciness is upfront with cinnamon and nutmeg .  clear copper color with a thick head that 's quick to vanish . no lace , shameful retention .  mouthfeel is pretty good , though .

balance leans towards the hops , but smells good . medium bodied and fairly flat/smooth .  this is a pale gold beer with not much head and liveley carbonation . i ca n't smell anything really beyond the giant lime wedge that was perched on my glass so i 'm giving it the benefit of the doubt and rating it average .  mouthfeel was good , as the carbonation made it 's way to the tongue and was well received .

nose is pleasant , rich , and chocolatey .  a : it looks like a cola . there was no head whatsoever , just a dark brown cola looking , undercarbonated beverage .  light bodied , relatively smooth and dry .

smell : after popping the top , a fruity aroma enveloped the area , and continued while i poured . during the pour , a light hop smell was also noted . pear notes could be found with deep breaths , though very small .  very pale in colour - not at all a good start for an ipa . i do n't mind the cloudiness at all though .  carbonation is right on and adds to the fullness of the beer , however , the `` hop '' factor of the ipa is overpowered by the malty bitter bite at the end of each sip .

poor retention and lacing ... strong aroma , like an cask conditioned esb , toffee , lots of pale malts and a little grass . light chocolate milk notes come through as well , interesting ... taste is totally english , light overall , burnt toffee on the front , light grass hops that are not as fresh as i would like .  the color could best be described as piss yellow .  it has a nice and creamy mouthfeel , like a boddington 's or tetley 's , it just does n't taste that good .

smelled good , bright citrus tart ipa . taste was good but it was impossible to ignore the lack of carbonation .  a bit thin in the mouth ... geez , such a simple dumbed down beer .. some lacing ... needs more- everything .. '' make me a bike , clown !  m : nice light mouthfeel .

i do n't smell the alcohol at all . the beer smells very good , but it is quite mild considering the style i 'm disappointed with the taste - i get a biting cardboard taste that quickly turns to poorly balanced bitter citrus .  pours a clear light amber color , lighter than i am used to .  the taste really reminds me of a malt liqour , mainly olde english , but not as bad . smooth mouthfeel .

smells citrusy and piney with a hint of sweetness .  of the three generic beers ( coors light , bud light , miller light ) this is the worst , but it still gets the job done . it is very drinkable , and you could spend a weekend with a 24 pack of this and have a good time .  taste is ... well , minimal . it 's creamy and smooth going down ( so i suppose a great session beer if you like the taste ) but there 's just not much flavor . i would call it watery if not for the nitro creaminess .

has a wonderfully malty pilsner smell .  i picked this up on a thursday night looking to try something new its not a horrible beer or anything its just nothing special just another run of the mill ale .  clean , smooth , and light mouthfeel , and here we go again , light carbonation . everything about this beer screams light .

smell- citrus aroma and slightly spicy .  i always am a little wary when the lettering on a beer label is n't in the roman alphabet , as generally the `` cyrillic beers '' like greek , ukraninan and the like are n't so good but lets see if this russian lager can turn the tide . baltica cascades into a very light color reminiscent of apple juice and also features almost no head and a strong , grainy scent .  moderately heavy and smooth mouthfeel .

smell : oranges , cloves , crackers , spice . taste : corander , vanilla , orange , bananas , light malts , alcohol .  quite the unconventional hefeweizen in every possible way , this beer pours a clear , light yellow with no head at all .  the mouthfeel was thick , had some good carbonation but just was n't thrilled by it in the long run .

the aroma was of lots of fresh blueberry , bready malt and hints of dough , which combined produced an effect similar to a blueberry scone !  long trail ale was entirely unremarkable . it carried no head ; in fact a scant film only vaguely hinted that the beer might conceive of such a thing . it 's drinkable , but only something i 'd select if it were a lone micro standout in a bar of macros .  mouthfeel is soft over the tongue , and drinkability is not bad .
smell - definite smell of hops and wheat , some very deep spices as well .  pours a less-red-than-expected- color with disapointing head retention for a wheat .  pretty good body .

nice amber color but head flattens out . it 's all in the sugar and heavy-weight flavor . i 'm a big malt fan but maybe this needs some crazy oriental flavors to go with it , or some seriously hot spice to cool down .  appearance : pours a pale yellow beer with a thin white foam lace that dies quickly .  mouthfeel : it 's just about right .

smell : strong coffee/sweet espresso .  pours a lightly hazed golden yellow , thin white head forms and immediately fizzes away to nothing , no ring , no lace , nothing , does n't look good in that respect .  mouthfeel : medium carbonation and medium body .

very fragrant . floral , sweet , hay , & grass . nice american interpretation of an english pale ale .  similar products , similar comments : another product of ambev , this beer is also a commercial lager style . a pale lager beer , with low bitterness ( around 12 ibu ) , original gravity around 11,5 plato .  m- medium body and carbonation .

i was hoping for something better since this was going to be a mild , easy drinking beer . unfortunately , this malty mixyure has the consistantly dull feature of avery brews ... a sticky malt flavor that lingers unpleasently on my pallate .  at a recent madison mallards game , given the choice between 40-ounce cans of miller light , budweiser , or schlitz , we opted for the schlitz . this definitely had more flavor than full-strength bud or miller , and was obviously drinkable , as it was made to be . still , it was watery and reminded me of freshman year of college . '' the reissue schlitz is similarly memorable .  mouthfeel is good . decent beer .

big sweet coffee , plum , raisen smell with some bitter chocolate as well . the mouth is thick and flat.. i am shocked after seeing the reviews here.. but for me it is a flat , overly intense beer that really lacks balence.dissapointing for me ... not drinkable enough to have another .  paid $ 5.99 for a 12 pack of cans ... the appearence is a somewhat hazy golden color with a medium-large white head that decipates quickly . the beer has no lacing what-so-ever !  more like a cider , apple-ish and very sweet , low carbonation . mouthfeel is full and round .

good whiff of raspberries on pouring , much more subtle after that . smells quite promising . past that , however , i 'm afraid it did n't work for me .  and massive chunks of floaty things swimming about as they settle to the bottom of the glass . i am not sure if there is something with freshness going on here to produce those large floating masses , but thankfully they settle and do n't bother you . minus the floating chunks .  mf- good medium body with the right amount of carbonation .

small tan-ish head smell : very dark with raisin and fig aromas . quite interesting ... not as roasty as i thought it would be . this has a very baltic porter character .  pours with a pale golden body topped by little head or lace .  the mouth is smooth -- light to medium in body .

the nose is full of big citrus hops , with tones of floral and grass . this is very boozy , in my opinion .  a : darker than straw , poured a one-finger-thick head that , well , quickly is overused ... speedily ? dissipated , leaving no lacing . t : unobtrusive and unimpressive .  fine carbonation , and very dry , tight mouthfeel .

aroma : its best feature with notes of yeast , wheat , banana and sweet malts . taste : citrus , yeast and wheat .  upon the first sip i am reminded of a becks or a heineken , but shortly thereafter i am hit with a definite reminder of its malt nature . i must say that this is by far the best malt liquor i have ever tried . it is much lighter in the mouth , without the repulsive taste of familiar malts ; it is also smoother in the throat , as well as being lighter in the stomach than any other malt liquor i have tried . if you want a cheap , pallatable , 6.87 % serving of alchohol you cant go wrong with this selection .  creamy smooth , heavy , and warming . super sweet , lots of whiskey ... not as complex as it should be since the bourbon flavors pretty much mask most of the malt .

smells malty with a hint of chocolate and nuts . alcohol is very present in the nose as well . flavor is kind of ghost-like ; wierdly bland .  pours pitch black with absolutely zero head .  medium mouthfeel .

smells good . chocolate covered cherry candies and hints of blended whiskey .  pours a pale , straw yellow , no head .  nice and heavy feel . too big and lacking flavors from the malts to balance off the alcohol and bourbon .

the smell may be the best part of this beer . the taste is something atrocious .  extremely pale straw color topped with some white head that quickly disappers .  m - the feel was nice and even when i swished and swallowed . probably the best part about this beer .

smells like it is going to something really interesting , but does n't taste like much .  bleck , tons of floaties even with a very calm pour , hands down the worst part of belgian beer is all the damn floaties !  the mouthfeel was warming and thick .

this one pours with a huge foam head and smells good and toasty with a hint of vanilla .  looks pretty dead all around but it has a sweet toffee aroma with a hint of floral hop maybe .  this was best part of this beer .

s - extremely sour aroma with very vigourous apricot aroma .  it is very economical and some might say you get what you pay for , but for a cheap macro , its fairly good .  mouthfeel is medium to full .

the aroma is right on for the style . the appearance is dark brow with an almost nonexistent head . the flavor is like the aroma but watery which really hurts it .  purchased a six pack in avalon with a few other weisse beers to bring in the summer . do n't remember seeing any best before notches . must be filtered ; poured a clear yellow with faint carbonation , if any . your average hefe and wo n't offend most folks . really could n't hold its own up to the other two weisse we enjoyed over the long weekend .  very thick and viscous with a fairly light amount of carbonation .

the smell is of citrus , and , like the appearance , is richer than can be expected in this style . perhaps , my expectations were set too high after seeing and smelling this beer .  clear amber with pretty much no head .  everything tastes kinda dusty , kinda dirty ... the body is a hefty light , with a light moderate carbonation and a dry finish .

hop spice is accented by the sweet scent of dried apricots . refreshing . odd rollercoaster of grain mash followed by an almost watery tastelessness backed by a return of the same graininess .  i was sorely disappointed . smells like a cross between rust and old malt . taste is overpowered with corn , just like bud and miller and coors ... what a suprise for 10 $ a case . yes , its better than the `` big three '' macros , but no its not a `` good '' beer . mouthfeel was like seltzer water , mixed with corn .  the mouthfeel is pretty good anyway .

both sourish and hoppy characteristics , caramel . whole thing does not work as i am not tasting a bitter .  this kolsch pours with a golden body topped by a thin head with little lacing .  the smell is rather odd , but that 's a lambic for you i suppose . taste is quite sour , which i am not used to in my americanized lambic drinking . an interesting approach to the style .

fresh hops with a grassy/piney scent make a strong first appearance . not sure if this is even possible , but the smell seems to die off rather quickly , and the fresh hop scent is gone .  appearance : served a light amber with almost no head ( that was n't the bartender 's fault ) . the amber color was alright though , crisp and clear , similar to the taste . smell : for the most part i could n't smell anything , partly from the lack of head , and partly because the hops were minimal and the malts were light . mouthfeel : interestingly good carbonation despite the lack of head .  mouthfeel - very carbonated , but good smooth texture overall .

nose is like candied pineapple ; candied fruit ; fresh fruit cake ; mouthfeel is rich and creamy and mouthfilling .  355ml can poured into a pint glass a - pale yellow colour , thin white head that dissipates quickly s - smells grainy , hints of wheat and barley t - tastes pretty decent for a light beer .  full bodied and nicely carbonated .

smell is piny with hints of roasty funk . very hoppy smell .  looks like very little carbonation , i can see a few bubbles , but not much .  i ca n't really appreciate much else in the flavor because of the bitterness . still , it feels good going down after the initial taste and i appreciated it more at about 2/3 full .

the smell is malty with some fruity notes and some alcohol near the end of the sniff .  this is almost completely clear with a hint of yellow , like i just washed my tea bottle . the aroma is almost nonexistent , just a hint of grain . the taste is very light , a hint of grain and corn . going down it 's almost like flavored water but you can down a lot of it . if you 're looking for quality , look elsewhere .  crisply carbonated with a moderately light weight on the tongue .

smells strongly of pine hops and straight up alcohol . not a very spicy smell .  definitely unimpressive for a porter .  the mouthfeel is light-medium bodied with lots of creamy carbination ; probably the highlight of the beer .
