a : dark rusty brown red , two fingers of light khaki head , thick lace webs remain s : sour cherry is the most abundant aroma along with a strong vinegar back bone maybe a touch of barrel t : light sweet cherry and vinegar mixed with a load of musty wet carboard and cough syrup , not much sour at all , actually rather sweet m : light body with a decent amount of carbonation d : overall very big let down , this stuff is not good , there are much better beers out there to represent this style , it will be a struggle to finish this bottle  bottle clearly states to swirl the leftover yeast and pour it into your glass which imo is a really big mistake . most of the time there is a inch or two of yeasty sediment in the bottle which yields a gross looking beer .  nice carbonation but remains smooth going down ... not bad at all ... this is a stout ... .by nature not all that drinkable .

s- i enjoyed the smell as i noticed hops at first and then picked up some sweet , caramel malts . it started off somewhat bitter and overly carbonated .  the amoeba floats around for about half the glass before dissipating -- i named it mortimer . cloudy brown color .  good carbonation makes for a crisp and clean mouthfeel .

s = light earthy notes of noble hops poke through the smells of fresh grains and hay .  opened the flip top bottle poured a reddish orange color with no carbonation .  the mouthfeel has a nice full body , with active carbonation .

s- really sweet aroma , vanilla , dark fruits , raisins , plums , sweet caramel , brandy , slight alcohol presence . t- wow not what i was expecting , really unusual sour notes , some vanilla , some brandy , vinegar , some malt but the sour taste overpowers everything else .  extremely light straw in color .  even so , it was pretty decently textured and carbonated .

very 'varietal ' nose with some sweetness and spice jumping out .  i could see this needed an aggressive pour right off the bat as it looked like apple juice but in the end formed a thin fizz that is never to be seen again .  it drank fine , well carbonated and smooth but i would n't drink this one again . it 's too bad because i love goose island .

s - lots of roastiness , roasted barley , slightly acidic , floral and spicy hops .  this is a very cheap beer . but out of all the cheap beers this is n't a horrible choice , especially when you compare it to the bud 's or miller 's , it is actually better .  i do like the creamy mouthfeel this beer has , but by now , it is too late .

actually this is listed at bjs as an imperial stout . so lets see.. pours a dark red/black body , with an off white nitro head . smells of coffee , toffee , some chocolate and figs .  on pouring it makes a loud fizzy noise similar to soda . a vigorous pour barely produced a head large enough to cover the surface of the pale golden beer , and the head was gone by the time i put the glass down .  m : nicely carbonated and feels good .

the aroma combines the smell of hops and a real citrusy lime character with a bit of malt sweetness . i am not sure that i will like the flavor as it appears from the aroma that it will be quite sweet and not so hoppy , as they seem to be mainly of the aroma variety .  a - bright yellow , no head what-so-ever .  mouthfeel has a pleasant sheen to it , but the flavour is either thin or phenolically unpleasant , so it does n't have much to work with .

the smell is undoubtedly big on cinnamon with nutmeg vying for attention . this is a pretty straight forward beer .  benelux atoka.on tap at the brewpub appearance-a golden yellow appearance with minimal head . the beer actually looks flat , just sits there without much action , which makes me a little nervous .  it has a medium to full body , with ample carbonation , a prickly middle and dry finish .

it has a smell of pumpkins and spice , almost exactly like pumpkin pie . i seem to come back to this every year and it 's probablly just because it smells so good .  pours just like an mgd , but maybe with slightly less carbonation . drinkability should be improved over mgd for sure , but you know what i would rather save my money and just buy mgd , because this beer resembles it way too much . overall , this beer is not worth the price , it 's only a tad better tasting than your cheap o ' mgd 12-pack . go with gi 's honker 's ale , ipa , oatmeal stout , and nut brown ale instead .  smell - malt smells dominate , chocolate msotly from what i can detect , not overpowering , in fact it 's very pleasant to the nose . the first thing i thought of was wine , sour and not pleasantly so . frankly i do n't like it . overall - a beer that 's exceptional in every area except the most important one : how it tastes .

the aroma is actually fairly nice . i get some lemons and wheat , as well as a very inviting tartness .  a : pours a cloudy yellow-green with a fizzy 1/2 finger head which rapidly disappears . d : perhaps on a very hot day , if i were parched beyond measure , then this would be acceptable .  texture is quite fizzy and lively .

raspberry is much more pronounced in the aroma than in the flavor .  drinkable beacause it goes down easy , since it has no real taste . from a college standpoint , this is not good since you can get drunk quicker on the same priced key ice or natty ice , which tast better too . better tasteing cheap beer can be had quite easily .  m- nicely carbonated and puckering o- not too bad

n : nose actually has a lot of coffee , roast , some sweet syrupy malts , dark malts , a touch of vanilla , touch of chocolate . t : starts with a lot of coffee and roasted malts , some chocolate , some fake vanilla flavors , really fake infused vanilla ... very watery too , damn , i was excited thinking this was pretty good until the taste . terrible !  pours a clear sunshine and hay yellow . no head or foam and very sparse bubbling .  decent enough mouthfeel .

strong smell of granny smith and cortland apples mixed with red wine . taste was nothing like the nose . i picked up some vanilla as i searched more into the flavor . hard to pick out the pumpkin although there is a squash like flavor beneath the spicing .  i do occasionally seek out an american light lager , but this will be a bit extreme for me . bottle at fridge temp into a room temp weizen glass . quick rising white baking soda fizz comes up to about 3 '' and quickly falls to a thin ring and skim of varying bubbles . surprisingly good lace on such an anemic foam . the beer is a very pale straw .  mouthfeel is good . slick and smooth .

the aroma had the light spicy yeasty smell which is true to to german weisen style .  straight from the bottle , with a lime . i can see the beer is yellow and transparent . past that it 's a little bready , but it 's technically an adjunt lager so i was n't expecting much here . it 's a cheap american-style lager with a mexican name .  a nice slick mouthfeel with a bit heavier heavier viscosity .

oz bottle of this from bottle king in livingston for about $ 5.99 , and i must say , coming from a high-caliber company like rogue 's , i really was n't too impressed with this stout sample ... expected more , and was let down by an overall lack of flavor and complexity ... appearance was about average , poured a jet-black , ebony color with minimal tan head ... smell was complete with burnt , dark chocolate , espresso , and liquorice aromas ... taste was typical stout , with dark-espresso and cocoa flavors that was more bitter than sweet ... taste seemed pretty watered-down and somewhat more bland than i was expecting ... definitely had much better stouts before this , and the overall taste was more average than anything else ... i would n't say this was a bad brew , just was n't to my liking and not one i would try again ... would n't recommend this one ...  d- if you are a poor bastard like me and you wan na get drunk for cheap and smoke too then this is your beer .  mouthfeel - a good mouthfeel . smooth and slightly oily , crisp carbonation , one of the better areas of the beer .

poured a light copper/amber with no head to speak of looked flat to me , the aromas on the other hand have plenty of life very juicy and fruity with orange really sticking out with some `` wet '' grain underneath.flat feeling in the mouth just not impressed in any way there , quite sweet the flat feel just makes it unineresting to even finish there is a little fruitiness to it but nothing can save it for me , i 'll stay away from this in the future .  appearance : clear straw yellow with a thin , fizzy head . looks like your typical macro .  mouthfeel is very smooth .

smells are bourbon , that 's all . tastes like jim beam , vanilla and some cinnamon at the very end , not that good . i love bourbon beers , but this beer did not have the malty backbone to balance out the booze .  one finger off white head after an aggressive pour . head dissipates to nothing in less than a minute . lighter carbonation .  m : light body with a very well done carbonation feel .

smell- very nice almost wine like scent .  sadly this beer was not very good and barely resembles a saison in appearance , flavor or aroma . appearance is a clear light gold with a whitish head that disappears immediately and leaves no lacing .  m : medium bodied with a medium level of carbonation .

3 years ago it was a hop bomb with a backing of sweet apricot to cool off the hops . so smooth . two years ago it lost its apricot and just became a hop bomb . this is really dreadful stuff , a mix between sour milk and rotten apricots .  it pours like day old champagne . reminds me of stuff i used to play drinking games with . the `` suspension '' of yeast is disgusting ; the beer 's not uniformly cloudly , just filled with specks of crap . it smells good , but looks skunky . it feels a little like miller genuine draft , not as bad as icehouse . very sharp and piercing , over carbonated . it 's drinkable , but not really a hefe at all .  the interesting thing is that the body did not feel light ... . actually pretty full .

s - roasted caramel , some grapefruit , light alcohol , and bittering hops . the smell was good , but there was no complexity in the malts and the bittering hops took over .  hitachino nest white ale is a slightly hazy pale straw-colored ale with a white head that quickly vanishes .  it 's syrupy and thick with a snappy carbonation , and the combination of the taste and the mouthfeel are not quite cloying .

the smell is strong and pungent and rather pleasing . overall this is not a bad beer , but then again , nothing special either .  i received my beer with no head and was barely able to generate anything . it had aa clear yellow color . this beer was served too cold , but as it warmed up it became a decent lawnmower beer . i would reach for one of these to quench my thirst in the summertime .  light bodied with good carbonation for the style .

in the nose , big grapefruity hops and sweetness . a smooth bitter beer with a clean feeling .  i actually thought i received the wrong beer when it arrived at my table , seeing a slightly cloudy liquid , looking like a light pilsner in color ( it was dark bar , so they may have been some orange , but certainly nothing purple ) , and with hardly any head .  it had a medium feel in my mouth and good carbonation .

smell is neat , rich and malty , raisins , caramel , grapes , brown sugar , some biscuit , a touch of chocolate milk and light roast , lots of sweet fruit , a bit herbal , pretty intense chile/pepper aroma , pretty spicy .  the beer appeared a pale golden color with noticeable carbonation following to the top of the beer . upon the pour , the beer quickly produced a very big , 3+ fingers , white , foamy head and it dissipated and quickly as it was produced . no lacing to mention .  mouthfeel is spot on , carbonation zing .

strong , spiced , bubble come aroma . man , you can smell that belgian yeast good . super smooth mouthfeel , kind of thick .  poured a pale yellow , dirty gold color with a sickly , broken head .  mouthfeel is smooth and warming .

aroma is figs , dates and plums . once those smells are in the nose the malts come out to play , biscuity and sweetish .  this poured a pale straw colour with a decent amount of head that vanished before i could blink .  the mouthfeel is nice and dry with a good body and carbonation level .

nothing exceptional about the appearance . sweet , malty , sugary smell . and the taste is sweet , and creamy .  pours out a dull and murky caramel/apricot color with a lot of floaties . not much to look at .  mouthfeel : surprisingly clean and dry , especially in the finish . lip-smacking and smooth , with airy carbonation ... but unfortunately , it does n't do much to lighten the heavy sugar load .
it had a nice wood scent to it .  pours a hazy golden with almost no head whatsoever .  mouthfeel - medium . crisp .

smells of burnt wood or coffee maybe and dark roasted malts with some chocolate undertones . very light body , but on the creamy side of things , and the taste packs less of a wallop than the smell indicated it would .  a- pale , clear yellow with a thin white head , and minimal lace . bud light lime did a better job on this .  m 4 the best part . medium plus body , creamy carbonation .

the smell is utterly different from a normal hefeweizen .  poured a very light yellow with a light white head .  this one has a `` bottled on 8-5-08 om it . i like the dating of beers . taste is warming , alchohol burn warming the inners . malty , raisins , figs and woodiness . i am tasting the mettalic aftertaste in this.good beer if i could get paste the metal .

s- hop aroma is strong . sour yeast/sweet malt resembling apple juice .  the appearance was murky and uninviting with a very poor head .  t & # 8211 ; it tastes a lot like a macro lager , and a little like a wheaty spicy belgian-inspired summer beer . blue moon is probably better in some regards , though i guess not on an overall basis ( i have n't had blue moon in a , well , you know ... ) m & # 8211 ; pretty crisp and refreshing .

grainy malt aromas with a lemony citrus twang and hints of spices .  the appearance is a disaster -- uncontrolled head makes pouring a chore . fizzy looking body with carbonation bubbles all over the cloudy light brown beer . the head sinks down after what seems like forever and looks scummy .  m- dry and crisp with good carbonation .

other qualities are herbaceous and slightly musty in the smell . making it 's least attractive features stand out even more is a bitter hop profile featuring juicy herbaceous qualities .  this brew has a slight malty aroma that arose from a very small head of fine bubbles and a light yellow orange colored body .  maybe i had chilled mine for too long , do n't know but i found very little going on in my mouth to make me like this . the only positive comment i can make is that the taste did surprise me in that it was far smoother than what i was expecting . m. light , clean and much smoother than i imagined .

looks like a typical straw-yellow pale lager , but actually smells of clean malts with biscuit and toast aromas .  pale straw with fluffy white head that dissipates quickly leaving hardly a trace of bubbles above surface .  medium bodied with sufficient carbonation .

smell is actually quite nice . very yeasty with a wallop of banana and candi sugar .  because it poured out pretty flat with no head .  mouthfeel is good as this beer is light on the tongue and not very thick when it goes down .
s - cheap strawberry jam , syrupy malt , heavy alcohol , and spice .  absolutely no lace at all .  m - very smooth with good carbonation , well rounded .

there are sweet notes and lots of roasted malt .  a : crystal clear yellow brew , small head that dissipates quickly . no lacing .  the body is on the fuller side of medium with a low carbonation level that gives some wateriness . pretty good .

smell- a mature integration of hops and malts are clearly displayed here , with the alcohol strength and some light smoke weaving a tapestry within . like a fine wood-aged spirit , this has enormous depth . taste- a balanced showing of malts and hops , strongly presented individually ... however , the aftertaste lingers a bit too long , with its pungency dominating . not even with that scrumptious wedge of stilton .  this beer is pretty plain to look at .  m : medium bodied with crisp carbonation .

s-smells strongly of oak and smoked bacon with some very mild caramel .  it pours a pale yellow color with a hint of sweet malt in the smell .  feels good in the mouth , but , the taste is ... unfortunately awful .

pours light clear copper with some really nice lacing and retention ... the aroma is is all honey , but still light . the honey has a bitterness to it which is unique . a new aroma i 've yet to come across , bitter honey ... the taste is really disappointing as all the honey on the front is gone and replaced by very bitter hops .  there should be a warning to shuffle this up like a hefe because the chunks were big , and the ones that settled at the bottom melted with a cloudy film . for and apa , wierd , wierd wierd . it was a very cloudy orange and as stated before , seemed like a hefe .  m - medium to full body , creamy carbonation .
it does smell nice though .  this golden lager pours with large lacing and bits of scary sediment .  m - fine . right where it should be . my favorite part of the beer .

smells really good actually . the smell is great minus an off element and if that cough syrup taste gets cleared up this could be a great amber .  i do n't know if they poured my beer and let it sit while they waited for the guiness , but there was absolutely no head on it . very disappointed with the appearance of this beer . despite the unattractive look of the beer and unremarkable flavor , i would definitely have had another .  m : medium in body with a medium carbonation .

smells of roasted coffee , chocolate , toasted/roasted malts , sweet & bitter coffee .  served on-tap at hot tomato 's in new haven , conn. a : poured a very clear , golden straw yellow color with a very thin head of fizzy foam which left almost no lacing and retained pretty poorly .  m : sort of interesting here . i actually like the mouth feel .
juicy and nice . taste : what the heck ?  busch beer pours a typical macro fizzy yellow from a twenty four ounce can .  the carbonation and mouthfeel were good , however .

smells quite fresh , even with a trip round the world behind it . perhaps it did n't survive the journey too well , given the smell is good and the rest struggles .  look is kind of orangish cloudy fecal matter brown . it does produce a head so some marks for that . it does n't look very satisfying .  taste/mouthfeel : medium body with nice carbonation .

smells like cocoa . earthy & bready with a hint of coffee . this seems to be more of a strong porter in my opinion .  poured a very light amber color .  it drinks much more harshly when cold . now is all wintertime spice . and cherry , of course . otherwise , it mirrors the nose being the most palatable . whew . quite an experience and one that everyone should have ... once . props to unibroue for coming up with this , but i 'm not so sure it works .
s - big coffee smell , obviously , with some dark chocolate and roasted malt .  pale gold in color with decent fizzy carbonation .  mouthfeel is full and syrupy will sufficient carbonation .

on tap at the surly goat in hollywood : sits a pale cranberry with gold color when held up in the light . astringent hoppy aroma with sour cherries and a bit of alcohol .  the pour had little to no foam , and the color of it was reminiscent of a light beer .  a slightly creamy mouthfeel with moderate to low carbonation is present throughout .

otherwise clean and very nice . body was medium-to-full ; lots of hop flavor .  root beer brown with a significant amount of sediment in the bottle .  moderately balanced bittersweetness with a nice mouthfeel and light carbonation , but when its coming from something that smells like cheap melted hersheys , wax and preservatives , who cares ?

scents of champagne , the white grapes are very pronounced . strange thing here , i have always really liked tremens , but the first thing i noticed in the warmed glass of ale was a taste similar to adult cough syrup ... not the yummy flavored ones that you would sometimes take an extra swig of ... more like nyquil or the ones you feel the need to do a chaser after .  12 oz bottle pours a hazed and sedimentated dark brown color . absolutely no foam here and darker than most bws i have had .  medium bodied .

s - coffee beans , liquorice , coal , raisins , cherry .  i have to say , this is one of my prefered `` shit '' beer of choice . light and able to be consummed one right after the other , not to filling , yet a decent amount of flavor .  mouthfeel is good . it 's got a decent thickness with nice carbonation .

the aromatic flavor in the nose is quite intriguing -- some kind of english hard candy with menthol and fermented prunes ( footnote : `` gravity 's rainbow '' ) .  i love autumn and winter up here in cleveland and any beverage that can supplement that is fine by me . regardless ill give it a whirl . appearance : pours a light orange gold , fairly transparent and very little head that dissipates very rapidly . looks like the beer in commercials where bubbles are constantly fizzing up .  m : medium carbonation , light body and a nice dry creamy finish .

in the nose i got a strong bananna and clove hit that i liked .  a- it looks really pale with a tiny white bubbly head that dissappears quickly s- it smells a lot better than the miller light i just had .  smooth moderate mouthfeel and not too filling - not a bad beer , too .

the nose reveals citrus alike aroma that probably originates from copious use of coriander .  appearance is very red with a light red/pink foamy two-finger head . looks more cheery soda than beer to me .  mouthfeel : crisp , clean , and refreshing .

nice sweet hoppy aroma with some citrus that even my gf liked .  low carbonation and pitiful head but a really good mix of hops and malt giving a very smooth easy to drink beer .  medium-thin body , nice effervescence .

s- i and my wife both agreed that there was no smell ... at all ... .crazy i know t- warming , malty-caramel ... .sweeter than i was expecting , but very tasty m- malty/creamy d- easy goes down  a- poured from the bottle almost completely flat . no head , nor lacing , and only the faintest visible traces of carbonation where a collar would normally form on the beer . the body was an attractive opaque ruby-tinged brown , but the lack of any head was dissapointing .  thin mouthfeel .

i 'll be honest , i did n't smell anything . it smells like an empty glass . maybe some dark malts , but nothing stands out .  a : semi hazy straw yellow , smallish head , ok lace . d : other than the chunks of shit ( not floaters , but 2 bb sized turds ) , was big time drinkable .  the mouthfeel is too undercarbonated and watery .

it reminded me a lot of your average over the counter macro brew . smell : the first smell was n't quite right and the taste confirmed the initial diagnosis . there 's not much there and the smell certainly does n't pull you in . taste : the taste is a bit lacking , nothing strong or overwhelming but nothing bad about it either .  the color looks like my piss after numerous beers . looks like water only slightly yellow .  the mouthfeel is way too light and thin .

australian for beer ? `` australian for beer '' depends on where in australia you are . compared to american lagers it does have a nice bitterness to it . do n't kid yourself and think they drink this swill in australia though . it 's as australian as schaefer is american .  poured a lighter yellow color with a smaller sized white head .  the palate is thin .

served in a wine glass , the color was almost see-thru yellow , fairly pale . odor had a slight skunk to it , but nothing off-putting or enough to raise an alarm and send it back .  a thirst quenching na beer nothing offensive in the least .  nothing at all in the middle except an annoying hard carbonation , watery . finish - a bit nutty , astringent and very mild fruit esters overall - this beer is not bad , but very average in taste . i liked most aspects about this mild except for the taste which i felt could have had more roundness and a bit more plump , just too watery .

pale gold color , fluffy white head , just a hint of skunk familiar with green-bottled european lagers that you get here . there 's still that light sweet grain , but there 's some honey and a little bit of spice , too . really good lacing , too .  poured out flat , no head ( again , bad bottle ? ) amber color but not attractive in the glass . someone mentioned canadian whisky , yes that flavor is there , but it was the cheap stuff that makes you shake your head violently after it goes down .  the feel was too thin . what smoothness there was came more from thinness than anything else .

aroma is really weak .  2 fingers of fluffy head completely disappeard within a minute . this is the color of apple juice s understated to the nose , just a bit of a hoppy/ maly armoa t : not too good .  very little mouth feel or body and not much that reminded me of the beligians i miss so badly .

s - caramel , malt , and like a previous reviewer mentioned , kind of a mushroom aroma . odd . t - malty , somewhat sweet , bready , a light touch of hops .  as far as rice beers go this one was not to bad its better than bud crap and its better the color is weak the taset is smooth and crisp its clean and you could do a lot worse than this beer there is not an over power smell of rice to adjuncts .  mouthfeel is really quite thin , with the flavour kind of releasing itself more from an emanating aroma than any substantial body .

s- corn adjunct smell .  i was at a pub in halifax when the waitress asked me if i 'd like to try a `` bud light lime '' . my fellow craft beer drinkers will certainly agree that this particular pint does not rank highly in most of the usual categories , but here is the bottom line : it is highly drinkable , pleasantly carbonated , not cloyingly sweet , and very refreshing .  m : i know this is big , but there just way too much residual sugar here .

the thing that stands out most is the great taste , and the thing that i dislike the most is there is no smell and the color is similar to water . overall a very good beer and i recommend this beer on a hot day while watching a baseball game .  a - clear , gold , and without any sort of visible head . no lace , no love . this looks like crap , smells good , and tastes decent enough while the mouthfeel is attrociously thin and bubbly .  rather thin for the style ; almost like soda rather than a stout .

the nose is disappointingly weak , with alcohol by far the most prominent presence . the flavor is a vast improvement , if still somewhat pedestrian for the style . exit 4 is n't a terrible beer , and i think the idea of marrying a tripel and american hops has promise , but the execution falls short when compared to top class versions of the style  if i 'm going to buy a cheap beer at a bar , this is probably what i 'm going to get . do n't drink this with a lime , it does n't need one .  the mouthfeel is thinnish and very watery .

it even smelled like bud light or something you would find in the dixie cups of a beer pong playing college student . smell - again , it really smelled like a light beer , perhaps bud or maybe even coors or miller , they 're all the same to me .  this is the best cheap beer for the money . with its recent surge in popularity , it seems they 've started selling pbr in big ol ' 30 racks , instead of the standard case . it really does n't even smell that much better than your average crap beer ( if anything , it smells more like beer than most macro crap , which usually tends to smell like water ) . note : pbr is the official beer of geologists .  chalky astringent mouthfeel .

the nose contains some slight malt with some slight skunk and alcohol , along with some citrus/spicy hop presence . skunk is present but not overpowering . the skunk did n't totally kill it and it was definitely thirst-quenching .  a : a rusty dark brown/red color . literally no head , just a smattering of bubbles around the edges . no lacing or retention of course . the complete lack of carbonation really hurts it for sure .  m- horrid ! lacked any body whatsoever . i mind as well have been drinking seltzer water that had no carbonation . d- given the water-like mouthfeel , it went down pretty easy .

in the aroma , small malt and a hint of earth .  a : ca n't say much since its staying in the bottle , but from previous encounters i can assume it will be the typical pale color with little to no head and lacing .  mf ) watery , thin , and lots of carbonation d ) pretty good for this style !

very faint grassy/skunky smell . t- a little floral/grassy with a little hint of citrus . d- once you get past the skunk its pretty drinkable .  appearance - looks like a traditional rye beer . murky and opaque sour brown in color . three inches of head that are quick to disappear . very musky and swampy looking .  however it 's not very complex and is lacking body . thin and somewhat lost to where it should be .

smells like wheat , but there is , i hate to say , a wierd somewhat bologna smell . something is just not right in this department . you could drink a lot of these if you can get past the smell .  pours a pale straw colour leaving a thin head that is gone quite quickly . frankly it looks like any domestic lager to me .  dayton , oh alefest : this beer had a small sized tan head that consisted of mostly lasting fine sized bubbles.the body was cloudy with no carbonation observed.the hue of this beer was brown with a nose of malts and some hops.the flavor was acidic and bitter which had a lingering effect to it.the mouthfeel was very tingly , thin , watery and light bodied.there was good lacing with this beer .

very clear , bright yellow , with heavy carbonation but no head retention ... aroma - stale and a bit boozey , some hints of grain and hops taste - tastes like a cheap american beer , but i 'd take this over a bud or miller any day , if only to drink something regional and local .  a : golden color with a thin quickly dissipating head and barely hazy for an unfiltered beer really it 's completely transparent .  pouring out in a sweaty yellow with high carbonation and zippy flavor , lionshead light offers enough personality and taste to get you past its weaker qualities ( gritty mouthfeel , odd aftertaste , general banality ) and is definitely there for you when you need a night of drinking without the cost of high-quality suds .

i must admit i have somewhat of a soft a spot for this beer- i drank it often my senior year of hs , liking its toasty malt flavor while most of my friends stuck to the flavorless bmc varieties- i guess this is technically a coors offering . lets see how it holds up now : a- color is a beautiful red color , with pillowy , quick-developing head that fades rather quickly , leaves very minimal lacing s- tinge of fruit , mustiness , at slight bit of toasted nuts- nothing really stands out or is impressive- rather bland aroma t- stale bitterness up front , which fades into a skunky maltiness , finishes with a creamy , somewhat pleasant taste with minimal hop presence m- carbonation is somewhat heavy up front , leaves a very watery mouthfeel d- the light flavor of this beer makes it somewhat easy to drink , but the skunkiness of it prevents me from wanting to- perhaps i had an older bottle .  pale yellow beer with a moderate white head that fades to nothing .  carbonation is stupidly high .

s - smell is made up of simple grains with a touch of citrus . barely anything here .  had another pool 'n darts night with some friends , and we thought we 'd continue with the cheap beer theme . pours a very clear pale yellow with a small popping white head on top . no retention or sticky lacing at all .  mouthfeel was light to medium , slightly oily , fizzy with light astringency that turns to harsh astringency on the finish .

i had this a few days ago on cask at doyles in jp ... and i remember pretty specifically how i would rate it number wise , but some of the details of the appearance , flavor and smells have left my brain . i remember for sure that the smell turned me off completely . it had a bodily odor to it , and i have no idea why .  poured into a jackie o 's snifter on 7/2/11 shared by mbpbugeye bottled 2011 , 158/210 what an ugly beer . murky , dark plum color . bubbly head thins quickly to nothing more than a tight collar . no lace . stray tellings of booze as it warms ; not particularly bourbony though .  as stated , the body is on the watery side of light . a poor showing from a brewing giant .

i had this beer poured from a can into a pint glass ... a : bright golden yellow color , with a large white head and good lacing ... s : light , but i am definitely getting rice , and some slight hopping ... t : mostly just adjunct malt , with some pils malt and a dearth of hopping ... m : dry , and crisp ... d : a decent brew , but nothing to write home about .  an india pale ale insofar as this is precisely the type of swill that was being guzzled off the black market when i visited that home country of mine two years . with its closest counterpart perhaps something like kingfisher , alexander keith 's ipa is a clevel cover for what is a light british pale ale like boddington 's at best or a good commercial adjunct lager at its worst . though up front a watered and honeyed herb wash coats the tongue and seems very british , the finish fades into the lingering stale flavors that come from mass produced beer . piss colored and wholly uninteresting , this beer 's saving grace is its compatibility with most spicy , citrusy , or fried foods .  m : whoa , way too carbonated , reminiscent of the swill called bud light i used to drink as one of the ignorant unwashed .

has the green bottle skunk on this one .  a : super dark brown colored beer . even with super aggressive pour , near no head ( mocha colored ) with really bad retention .  the beer is very thin bodied , so much so that it almost seems to develop a tartness .

hugely diacetyl aroma , so much so that its like artificial butter on movie popcorn .  i picked up a 32 ouncer at circle k because i was feeling like something simple and cheap . color is pale yellow with a fizzy head .  ah coors ... pours a honey color with a nice head , and lace . the look is the best part of this beer . smell is of light skunk.mouthfeel is watery and flat . taste is light with a hint of spice . the beer was not awful , but i would not go out of my way to buy this beer .

white head and no lacing to talk about . smell , again , is grainy ( what sort of malts do these guys use ? formaldehide , maybe ? taste is crisp , naturally .  anyways ... pours a very pale straw colour with a head that quickly fades away , leaving a small film of foam on top .  could barely detect any spices , very thin body .

it pours a slightly hazed orange amber topped by only an intimation of white foam . the nose ... is apparently missing . i do n't really know what to say here . overall , a decent brew , nothing close to special , but definitely drinkable .  appearance : phoenix fresh pours a very light yellow-gold colour with a large , white head that does n't last much more than 10 seconds and leaves no lace .  the flavour is rather thin and feels watered down .

copper bell lager is a simple american lager , brewed with next to no hops and corn adjuncts . i would n't hesitate to cook with it , or have a can after working in the yard - that kind of beer . this is less than miller lite , and less than the 6ers of most beers .  poured a little pale , very thin head .  this was a strange one for me - i was only able to try this one bottle and i have thought it might have been infected pours muddy dark amber brown with a huge huge head ( my first thought of infection ) that left lacing all down the glass smells of some apples ( # 2 ) but could be raisins - get some brown sugar and oatmeal taste - has lots of roasted malt and chocolate which surprised me - cinnamon and other flavors that reminded me of xmas - those same raisins/apples that seem a bit off mouthfeel - was lacking - the body thin and was flat ?

smells like light malts , tastes light with lots o bubbles .  not any head retention , but what i did see was off white , but totally vanished seconds after the pour .  but the bottle i had was too carbonated which gave it a bad mouthfeel , blocking the tastes .

pours a crystal clear light ambered gold , two finger off-white head that leaves small bits of lace , light carbonation/ has a flowery hop aroma , butterscotch , and an unpleasant note of wet dog .  pours a somewhat-hazy light copper color . no head .  thin . thinner than their lager . kind of sad , really , as the thin body nearly ruins this otherwise nice stout .

kind of a stinky aroma with and emphasis on malt .  appearance : light golden in color with only minimal head and lacing .  hops are also low played , like lemon juice and water . thin and oily . carbonation is low , though the yeast inside looks pretty done .

extremely dull smell but not offensive . malt , grain and a tiny bit of sweetness . taste is pretty solid for the style ... lemony hops , a bit of caramel sweetness , light bready/cereal grainy malt .  poured a deeper golden color with a huge sized off white head . lots of big fuzzy and unattractive floaters that 's making me second guess drinking this .  m : light on the carbonation , thin & watery .

the aroma is slightly sweet yet sour with a hint of hops .  aside from that , it pours yellow with a small , quickly dissolving white head .  very little aroma , mouthfeel 's watery .

the nose , however , is weak at best . i get the slightest hint of earthiness , some crystalized grain , and a touch of pine . everything is there , it 's just ... well ... weak ! i feel like i 'm struggling to get a whiff of something here .  a basic clear yellow lager with minimal head which dissipated quickly .  thin and watery . it began pretty cold - a bit more than i would have preferred , so i let it warm up , but that did little , if anything , to produce more of a body .

smell is no good . metallic . above average drinkability if the smell does n't put you off too much .  33cl brown glass bottle with standard pressure cap served into a n'ice chouffe stem-goblet in low altitude los angeles , california . a : pours a half finger head of slight cream , fair thickness , and bad retention .  this is not a beer for beer drinkers , pseudo-aficionados , poseurs , whoever ... this is a beer for people who want cheap inebriation , but for whaterver reason do n't want malt liquor . lightly hopped , it has the mouthfeel of water that has been lubricated with the syrup of unfermentable sugars .

smell reminds me of bud light , and nothing more memorable than that .  still not near a top of the line pumpkin ale imo pours amber with 2+ fingers of sand colored head . zero head retention & lacing s : slight spiceyness , more metallic notes , all spice & nutmeg grow stronger as this warms t : slight pumpkin taste , a bit of cinnamon & metallic favors up front .  m- one thing that can not be salvaged , of course , is the thin body and high carbonation .

the smell is malty with fading skunky hoppiness .  this beer is very pale , a golden orange if you will . its head is small , white and disappears quickly .  mouthfeel is way thin , and drinkability is just not that great for me .

super hoppy aromoa . smells a little like weed mixed with an asian grocery store ... .and a pigs head . a little too funky .  pours like any other aal , real light gold with a big fizzy head .  mouthfeel - watery , no bubbles , flat . drinkability - obviously not very drinkable for the fact this is 98 % flat .

no aroma from small taster sample .  poured a deep reddish brown ( not even a little bit black ) with just a very faint ring of light tan head that had zero retention or lacing .  let down in the mouthfeel however..very sticky and cloying .

there is a faint malt smell present , and maybe some roasted nut , but it 's hard to tell . the smell is not very distinct or pungent . judging by it 's presentation , color , and smell , you would think it would be a burnt , nutty flavor . the smell is weak and it feels almost like water going down .  the beer poured a hazy gold color but made no head whatsoever - just a thin white rim . despite the lack of much head , the beer still left some nice lacing on the glass with each sip .  the main favor is water with some bland barley and only the slightest hops . imo , this is not a bad beer , it is a thirst reliever . if one is drinking beer for flavor skip this one but if one is truly thirsty , this is a decent pick . if one is ever in stockholm , grab one of these at the nearest 7-11 after a day of walking about the city and relieve yourself . save the flavorful beer for a special occasion .

a pale yellow color with a thin , white , bubbly head , that recedes rapidly has a very light malt grain or alfalfa aroma . but it 's very refreshing and it does n't seem to carry that metallic aftertaste that you find in a lot of american macros .  a : amber in color with little to no head . no lacing .  very very carbonated sort of like your common soda .

smell is mild at best . there is n't much except for a somewhat stale bottle depository smell .  pours in the glass with a deep golden body topped by nothing at all .  mouthfeel is not so good , since the beer is basically flat .

s - barely any . smells a bit like beer , nothing prominent . however as really cheap light beers go , this is great . one of the best of the really cheap beers .  kirin ichiban is a clear and sparkling pale yellow lager with a small white head that quickly fades .  the mouthfeel has way too much carbonation and detracts from the smoothness of the flavor .

s - not getting much of anything off of this at all t - booze , brown sugar , tea , oak , with a touch of bourbon m - average , i do n't expect a lot out of a scotch ale , but somehow i expected more out of this beer .  pours a pale clear orange color with lots of bubbles clinging to the glass . there is a thin white head that even with a generous pour only brought up a 1/2 a finger head and no lacing .  the taste is average with a slightly bitter aftertaste the mouthfeel is lacking . it feels a bit watered down .

s : very malty smell , but really not much smell to it .  a - on first pour , it seems and sounds almost like cola -- the head is n't huge , maybe a couple of fingers , but crackles angrily and falls away pretty quickly . it leaves pretty much nothing , not even really a ring . swirling does n't produce much at all . no lacing , obviously . this has just the right amount of coffee in a beer for me -- almost as if you added a couple of tablespoons to the glass .  a surprisingly thin body with a sharp , tangy effervescence on the tip of the tongue . watery .

the smell was typical for an imperial stout .  this beer pours a pale cloudy yellow with virtually no head . it is bud light colored , but cloudy .  first of all the palate was very thin , with hints of chocolate and a slightly smoke flavour .

no hop bitterness , not much flavor or smell to speak of .  pours very light yellow with a thin , fizzy white head . it 's not undrinkable , but i 'd stick with something cleaner tasting such as pbr or genny cream ale when i 'm looking for a cheap 12pk of cans .  mouthfeel - thin , a little oily from the hops , with very strong carbonation that hits you in the palate towards the finish the drinkability of this beer is very high , it is smooth , and makes a much better impression on people than budweiser , a good transition beer , but not too much to write home about .

s - bad nose of corn and husky grain .  it poured very flat . the little bit of head that did develop on the pour quickly disappeared into nothing , not even a lacing along the glass .  m- extremely thin , too carbonated .

s - very faint of the barrel it was aged in . faint rasin and citrus .  this stuff looks off-putting , like a cloudy something or other that sat in a urinal a couple of days . this is probably closer to a true hefe than a lot of them out there ( shiner for example ) , drinking it out of the bottle will insure the appearance does n't get to you and all in all a reasonably pleasant beer .  m - not much carbonation ; watery d - no reason to drink more than one .

almost no aroma to speak of . odd collection of tastes .  looks good but i expected more of a head .  m-2.0 : watery and thin . the above average hops just ca n't compensate for the weak body and thin feel of this brew .

s : well , there goes my love . corn and cooked vegetables . light earthy hop aroma that quickly becomes virtually imperceptible .  nice head . corn flavor .  m : 2.0 a very watery beer , while the flavors are constantly present there are no real stand out characteristics in the feel . d : 3.0 goes down easy thanks to its thin consistency .

s : small scent of hops , though i do n't get much on the aroma at all .  presentation- 16.9oz nice looking antique-like bottle . full 3/4 inch frothy and creamy looking head ... leaves slight traces of lace .  a text book pilsener-which is a positive note but the bready quality is not full . finish is clean but it has the after-taste of the gaterade power water . drinks ok , and i would enjoy this on a hot summer day-just a bit pricey for a miller lite clone in a nicer bottle .
smells like , uh , beer .  a nice looking , orange pale ale with a sudsy head and slightly muted hop aromas .  the mouthfeel is way overcarbonated and harsh .

aroma is grainy , fruity and sweet . light hops .  a : fairly clear orange like color with a nice fluffy head . good lacing as head dissipates . good looking beer .  the drink started with a quick hit of malt sweetness followed by a hint of carbonation . the overall feel of this one was very american macro crap to me .

the smell..the smell was nothing but bourbon and booze to me . perhaps my nose is unrefined , but i did n't detect much else . very astringent smell to it that i did not like at all .  poured from 12oz bottle a - dark rich amber with soft bubbly head and loose lacing .  really thin , like a light beer . best thing from this brewery .
not much on the nose . right to edge of the tounge with welcome caramel flavor .  a-pours a nice clear yellow-gold with persistent white head , nice lacing .  mouthfeel : on thin side .

no citrus/pine aromas . i love it when an ipa 's aromas jump out at you on the pour . thankfully this one taste much better than it smells .  january 2006 batch poured into a tulip glass . very , very black in color .  the mouth-feel is quite thin and it feels as though each mouth-full never quite materializes .
the usual stale sour malt nose , but somehow sweeter .  city brewery 's winter porter pours out a dark brown color with a tan head .  mouthfeel seems remarkably thin here , even for style .

s - slight banana notes ... .but a generally awkward smelling beer . not impressed .  appearance : poured a hazy brown/salmon color that produced a small light pink head that disappeared leaving lots of bubble rising to the top . very unique .  mouthfeel was very light in body and watery in texture with a flat carbonation .

it smells hoppy . also , it smells sort of like grass . i smell no malty aroma at all . i dont think i like the aroma at all .  appearance - this poured a hazy orangish-yellow in color with a nice , full , white head that showed good retention and left a film on the inside of my glass .  however the body of the beer let it down , very watery , no head retention ; this very quickly started to remind me of lager .

the aroma has an unfortunate cooked corn smell , but the flavor is dominated by a pairing of nutty and roasted malt flavor that are quite nice .  the head retains nicely and leaves fluffy swaths of lacing on the glass . it is truly a shame that such a nice appearance was wasted on a beer this poor , but it 's just like your mama told you ... you ca n't judge a book by its cover .  mouthfeel is flat with too little carbonation .

s : very neutral . it 's difficult to pick much up on the nose . very faint aromas of toasted malt , cocoa , cream , and toffee eventually make their presence known . underwhelming .  a beautiful label does not make a great beer . pours a rich , dark , deep ruby red , almost brown but not quite . good head and good lace .  mouthfeel is very tame , no carbonation in mouthfeel , though overall there is carbonation in the beer .

smell is a little funky at first . s - skunky , not impressed .  pours a tawny color with light fan head . looks good , but the love ends there .  the flavor is only surpassed , or should i say , harshened due to the over carbonated mess of a mouthfeel - i 'm left with a harsh boozy almost acidic/sour flavor in my mouth .

s : light grassy hops and a bit of indistinguishable sweet malts . not a big fan of this smell ; it 's weak , but more importantly , it 's not particularly enjoyable . t : taste packs a large punch both for the style and considering the weak smell ; a dominant flavor of freshly cut grass , which is far more intense than i expected . '' sweet malts also show up once again ; they 're so light and sweet that they taste almost like corn , although i know this is n't the case .  reddish sherry colored . creamy short topping . imagine mulled wine steeped in a thousand tea bags .  carbonation is fizzy .

smell is overpowering and almost skunky . skunky bitter hops smell that fills the room .  appearance is a pure coppery orange with non-existent head and lacing . more than a little thin , but the nearly neon-orange hue is kind of cool and carries the day .  smell-fairly clean , i do detect some malt but not much else , no hoppiness , alcohol , or otherwise . taste-fairly tasteless , some malt does come through again but for the most part this tastes like water . drinkability-somewhat malty and low abv , you could pound these that 's for sure . overall-yawn , sorry for the not so detailed review but this is another not so detailed light beer , even from an ok brewery like pocono .

it smelled bland - lightly toasted , sweet malts ( no hops detected ) .  pours a sturdy brown-black and is capped with a big umber head ; lace is deposited in small spots .  f - pretty limp , even more than i remember . like stout-flavored water .

colour is a very light copper and the only smell was a faint dry hop off of the initial pour which disappeared quickly but returns at the bottom of the glass . i would recommend this to somebody who is just breaking into trying new things and are used to the typical american lager , namely my father in law .  appearance : cloudy hazy gold , tightly carbonated with nice white head that dissipates quickly . good for style .  the beers got a big body , almost too big for its style . its not terrible , the body is really killing this one for me .

pretty weak on the nose - slightly nutty , slightly yeasty aroma , with a good whack of sweaty armpits or wet leather . not great .  this beer poured well into the glass a nice ruby-brown colour with a decent off-white head .  nearly flat and medium-bodied , the mouthfeel becomes slick towards the end and the drinkability suffers .

smell is almost non-existant . any sort of detectable smell is merely mediocre , and mostly uninspired . taste is decent for the style . very uninspired and not welcome in my mind .  a : light yellow brew with a nice 1 '' of rocky white foam . good retention and huge lacing .  t/m : very thin ... highly carbonated ... gives more of a champagne quality than a sour yeast ... lacks body . just fizzy . lacks body .

well , without being rude , i 'll just say that i 've been smelling a lot of really good beer lately and the smell is ... dissimilar . unoffensive .  appearance is good for style - clear , copper , good head retention .  the taste is pretty much the same , grains . there is a sharp bite of carbonation , and the coldness is getting to me . this is the beer that defines drinkability , they go down like water .

aroma was kind of like tobacco and not appealing . nothing ipa about this beer .  500ml bottle shared by bobsy - you always bring the best stuff buddy ; ) pours a murky orangeish brown with 2-3 fingers of foamy , soapy sticky head that leaves some lacing as it recedes .  it was certainly interesting and different , sadly its mouthfeel did n't do it for me .

almost smells like a sweaty sock .  the color was excellent however a nice amber red , bright yet opaque .  the mouthfeel is medium and watery with almost no carbonation ( seems to be common of ep beers ) .

smells a little dank , and leafy . not really appealing to me . i hope this is n't a bad omen for the whole beer .  nice lightbrown head and a dark beercollor . nose is lots of yeast autolysation giving it a kind of soapy nose next to the good caramel and banana aromes .  ok mouthfeel is pretty bad . thin and watery .

those nitro cans are an impressive packaging for the right beer the smell is really quite weak .  deep copper ... burnt orange . decent head , retention and lacing .  m : mouthfeel is oily , almost cloying .

no aroma . one dimensional .  well , this seemed an odd color for an ipa . looks more like a bitter or something . aside from that , it 's a rusty-orange color with a frothy little head . seems to be some chill haze . great lacing .  very thin and watery .

sadly enough not much else going on .  a - lots of white foam froths up from the grenade pour . decent retention is surprising and sticky white lace coating the glass is even more so !  a little too grassy , and excess carbonation , not nearly enough hop bite . thin body .

s : this beer smells overwhelmingly of cat piss , no two ways about it .  appearance : amber-brownish color , murky . lacing looks good on the glass .  m : mouthfeel ruined it . way too fizzy , drinks like a coke .

the smell is somewhat sour / doughy . a quite uninteresting pale lager .  i sampled this beer at a friends house , and i was intrigued by its look and where it came from , but that quickly turned to disgust when i tried it , it had a `` unique '' taste that i couldnt quite pick out .  light roast lingers in the finish , not much bitterness , but again a very thin body detracts majorly from this beer and keeps it from being recommendable .

the smell is sweet and lemony with noticeable nobel hop in the scent . grain and more so corn are major scent components . fairly strong cooked vegetable aroma .  a - pours with a quick-dissolving white foam that settles to a thin ring and some filmy haze , leaving behind spots of lace .  hops and malts fought each other for control and left the mouthfeel watery and thin .

i dind't notice much of a smell at all .  it may be a dark wheat beer , but it lacks the sweetness or spiciness that i expected . it creates a fair supply of head and lacing , but the aroma did n't contain anything noticeable .  tastes very watery . low ratings on taste and mouth feel reflect the lack of flavor rather than bad flavor .

a - medium to dark amber ; almost no head , but what little bubbling there was at the edge of the glass managed to leave a slight bit of lacing s - there was nearly no aroma , and what was there was nothing distinctive t - good malt/hop balance with pleasantly surprising bitter finish m - far too thin and too little carbonation in this sample ; a bit of a sticky finish d - though it will not be mistaken for a world-class brew , this one is easy to suck down since it is thin and flavorful ; without the sticky finish , it would score a half-tick higher  a : translucent dark orange colored beer . egg shell white head that leaves a decent lacing on the glass .  rather thin . left a grimey feeling in my mouth .

no matter how hard i sniffed , i could pick up no aroma . the taste is slightly roasty and bready with a little floral hop character with a sneaky bitterness .  this brew has a clear , amber body that is typical of this style . the nice creamy head is actually better than most of the german o-fests i 've seen . smells watery , and oxidated ( though when i drank it i knew it was not oxidated ) .  the mouthfeel is medium to light bodied and watery .

the nose is molasses , chocolate and burning rubber . very strange aroma ... the only thing i can equate it to is when the motor seized up and burned out on my rotary tool ... unpleasant .  i 've tried this beer alot of times , but i 've never got a proper chance to review it , so here it goes ; the beer pours a golden color with a nice white foam , the foam settles to a thin lid of foam after a while .  way too much carbonation..and the mouthfeel is too bubbly . even if the carbonation was done well , i do n't think this would be anything better than an `` above-average '' porter .

it has a tall white head that shows above average retention.. smell : is not that pleasent . it does n't smell fresh and there 's a slight vegetable smell to it along with an herb aroma . not a very strong smell though .  a : dark brown with a thick white head that disappears .  light mouthfeel , overly carbonated . this was n't bad , but it was too thin .

ok , here 's the one thing that turns me off about this beer : it smells terrible . the odor is of wet flour or some god awful white bread dough .  we sat down and ordered some appetizers and i heard the server rattle off some beer choices . i heard mole stout and said to myself `` well that sounds like something i have n't had before ... '' looks like a nice heavy milk stout or imp stout with a dark body , dark head , and a certain viscosity . then i tasted it ... holy crap this beer is like a perfectly good milk stout with a tablespoon of tabasco mixed in . this stout is terrible . it looks good , smells good , has great characteristics , until that overwhelmingly spicy flavor hits you .  mouthfeel is equally uninspired , with body on the lifeless , watery side .

i really do not understand how this beer has a b+.. granted , i feel bad saying how much i disliked it ( especially considering that i often like nogne a lot ) , but the flavors and aroma to this beer were just soo weird that i found it quite unpleasant . the smell was like flowers and ammonia.. like urine . taste is very complex and interesting but very flowery .  appearance this one looks the part . the body is a deep , hazy yellow and the head frothed up big time .  almost a gelatinous/soggy grain feel . the carbonation cuts it as best it can .

grain provides the smell and most of the taste .  appearance : the ale pours with a healthy two finger head . it has a nice dark black color with hints of red throughout . i ca n't tell if there is any sediment in here .  there is no body to this wit . it drinks like a cheap lager leaving very little for the finish .
s - faint grassy and grainy sent but not much otherwise .  a : poured dark brown with a moderate head .  flat and watery mouthfeel , very thin , no body .

s : steely , dark citrus hops and malt , a metallic , fishy undertone .  this beer left nice lacing though , and it left traces at the sides of the glass like rock layers at the niagara escarpment .  low carbonation leading to flat mouthfeel .

very strange .  the beer looked promising , had a cloudy tannish-yellow appearance with a nice 2 '' head . upon tasting the beer she made a grimacing face , which surprised me , expecting this homemade hefe would be pretty top notch .  m : mouthful was disappointing , bland and thin .

smell was very sharp and a bit sour , reeked of adjuncts .  g : grolsh pint glass a : clear amber body with two fingers of white head . good retention and decent retention .  watery mouthfeel ... i felt the lack of body a little disappointing , i was expecting far more creamyness .

nose is class ab style ; toasted stale malt aroma , followed by a pungent corn mash scent .  like pilsner urquel , overrated . nice colour and too mildly bitter , i would n't go out of my way to try this beer again .  except for the very poor mouthfeel , a great beer , one that i would recommend from the bottle .

smells like a typical lager , grainy , corny and tastes somewhat like corona though a bit better .  a foamy , frothy tan head builds aggressively on top of this beer . looks like a coffee milkshake sitting atop the black beer . lots of sticky lace . a much better looking beer vs. the flavor .  texture is far too thin and watery .

smell is unimpressive with an alcoholy tinge .  pouring dark brown with a dense tan head that recedes to a disk , this beer leaves some patchy lace on the side of the glass . quite attractive .  the mouthfeel was too full bodied for the style and was a major negative point .

it has a very bitter , dirty aroma . i hope it 's just the glass i 'm drinking from ... t - despite it 's smell , it tastes rather nice . i usually make a judgement call on the first smell , so my expectations dropped when i got a whiff . if anything , the beer is full of surprises , both good and bad .  appearance : extremely pale yellow colour , as clear as water . active carbonation is shown from the large amount of bubbles rising to the top , a big white foamy head forms and leaves a one fingered white lace for most of the time the beer is around before it is consumed .  and the mouthfeel is oddly thin , does n't fit well with the boozy vibe .

smell - very faint . overall- though the smell is faint and there are other better tasting wheats out there , it 's a nice easy drinking wheat and i definitely will seek it out especially in the spring and summer .  a : the pour is just about black in color with minimal brown head .  thin , spritzy body .

very faint and sporadick bubbling . smell is a light yet somewhat sweet malt offering .  nice colour , nice head ( not much lacing ) , but taste that lasts as long as it takes to swallow .  carbonation is too strong , nearly soda-like , with a plastic-y feel that coats the mouth . lightly sticky .

the smell is pretty basic , but with a tinge of alcohol .  pours out to a clear very dark ruby , forming a meringue-like dark khaki head with very good retention and lacing .  a thin beer , it 's a bit watery with a heavy orange and clove taste . the smell and flavor of this beer is great , but the mouthfeel really takes away from it .

smell : i think it is fair to say that this beer lacks in the smell department . i caught a little malt but that is about all . taste : an agreeable taste/flavor which is fairly mild .  pours a nice golden with a big rocky head .  the feel is pretty terrible ; flat , lifeless , sweet with some metallic bitterness . it is sweet from the dark fruit which is nice but no carbonation just kills this beer .

my bottle was 5 months old and had a slight musk smell to it , but nothing like the skunk i ran over on the way home .  the color is defiantly a rich blue color as the name might imply .  m : the lack of malts hurt the mouthfeel and the endurance of flavor . i realize that apwas are meant to be light , refreshing quaffs but gumballhead , in my opinion , would benefit from a slightly beefier body and thicker texture . the amount of carbonation is average or below and leaves a little to be desired as well . d : despite the low mouthfeel score , gumballhead is still an excellent brew and i would purchase cases of it during the summer months if only fff would distribute to pa , the greedy sobs .

the smell wasnt very eloquant , it reminded me of some sweet beverage , i cant even target a specific smell . the taste wasnt that bad , nothing great , but very refreshing . a shy soft hoppish taste was present but nothing to throw myself on the wall .  mac and jacks reformulated their ipa from what was once a nice super hoppy version of thier african amber . the only thing it had going for it was it looked nice in a glass . this second beer i too sent back for an african amber which was as good as usual .  mouthfeel : smooth but horribly dry , especially on the finish , which is reminiscent of a stale cracker .

it smells of corn with maybe some lemon zest and that aroma that comes with macro lagers .  oh brother ... smoked salmon on a campfire greets the sniffer . pickled herring and cigarettes on the taste .  m : incredibly light body .

smells of alcohol , some malt and an unpleasant ground corn . on a side note , this beer is best consumed out of the bottle ( and with some chips and salsa of course ) because of the aroma ( smells like a cheap macro to me ) is not appealing .  this was a solidly less-than-average beer with a pretty label and too much hype . it had an attractive copper color and a puffy head that looked comfy enough to float a beach raft , but it had an odd lack of aroma .  a - this beer poured a light golden color , crystal clear , that produced a foamy white head that disappeared quickly and left no lacing on the glass , not surprised s - the only notes on the nose where malts and lager yeasts t - this beer had a one dimensional taste to it , as one would expect from a regular lager , not a harshness i get from adjunct lagers , but still pretty lame m - this beer had a very thin watery body , and was loaded with carbonation d - this beer would be a very drinkable beer in the summertime to quench the thirst , if not for the high amounts of carbonation , which seems to accompany most abitas .

initial smell was negligible , after warming , it smells ... .watery .  a- this one pours out a hazy golden orange colored body with a small white head . lots of carbonation bubbles can be seen racing to the top of my glass .  unfortunately the mouthfeel is like that of a soda just going stale .

the smell is metallic and somewhat fishy . i thought this was a decent light beer ( except for the fishy smell ) .  a : slightly cloudy pale yellow brew . pours medium white head with fair retention . good lacing .  body is very thin and rather watery , and the finish is akin to a watered-down lemon-lime soda .

s : scent has some malt and grain . a little skunky in this case , even after some warming .  appearance- nice hazy orange with rather large , creamy head .  the taste is allright ( besdies the odd must ) , some roastiness in here but the thing that bothered me was the mouthfeel .

s mildly soapy aroma .  although it looks good in the glass it did n't have a multi-beer drink ability that i like .  super fizzy carbonation works for this beer but i still wish it was n't so fizzy .

slighlty gariny rye aroma with a slight sweetness and a strange egg undertone .  poured with a nice , large , foamy , frothy , fluffy , white head that lasts a while and good lacing . color is a pale , clear yellow with lots of small bubble trails .  a weak attempt at a flemish sour . the beer has good light redish color and the lactic sourness is present but it is thin and watery . no hop aroma or other funky lambic type aromas , just a lactic beer .

smelled like pretty much nothing , and the taste is similar to that of seltzer water .  pours a lively head . colour is quite striking , a vibrant rusty orange - looks good .  m - a little too carbonated for my liking - sharp and harsh bite and burn to the lips and upper palate .
too often nitro hides the aroma .  poured dark amber , with a light tan head .  very thin in the mouth .

the smell was a bit more hops than anything else i could detect .  bottle pours a clear , rich , pretty copper color with a small white had that thins .  thin , thin . m - very low carbonation & i do n't like that ! needs more carbonation ! feels thin and slightly creamy then stale going down .

a great beer for a hot summer day after mowing the yard or doing some other hot sweaty yard work . really has no aroma to speak of .  black body when sitting in the glass , brown held up to the light . creamy off-white head of a finger or so that fades into a thin layer .  mouthfeel is bad . it burns there is so much carbonation .

s : very weird smell , it actually smelled like a wet dog . i could n't get more scents out it since the wet dog smell over powered .  this beer poured a bright golden straw color . it had a decent head which lasted halfway through the beer .  mouthfeel is thin , typical saranac . why do all their brews lack body ?

s - extremely light honey and a tiny bit of kit .  appearance : cloudy , honey yellow color with 2 fingers of head that faded slowly with a nice curtain of lace .  slight caramel flavors present mouthfeel : thin and highly carbonated .

grass , burnt bread and stale coffee on the nose .  has a great dark black color to it , was disappointed with the smell or rather lack there of .  the mouthfeel is very lively , very slippery/oily and buttery . too carbonated , which is strange for a stout . drinkability is ok given the high abv , but the bitterness , aftertaste and carbonation cancel that out somewhat .

i kind of smelled vegetables in the nose and some sweetness but not much else .  appearance- hazy straw colored . this was bottle conditioned so that would explains the haziness . good lacing .  very thin .

the aroma is malty without much trace of hops . at first i thought this might be the temperature it was served at , but as it warmed up a bit , the scent did n't improve at all . if the aroma was improved i might have been inclined to try another to get a better opinion .  20 ibu 's ? clear pretty dark rich bright gold color .  the mouthfeel is medium to light bodied and pretty watery which washes out the flavors .

the smell is on the weak side but i note some sweet malt . further sips only enhance the taste of grain and it makes for a rather dull , imo , lager that has a pretty decent colour for the style .  the appearence of this beer was good , a very nice golden color with a great head that lasted well .  mouthfeel was a bit thin and slippery .

smell is hollow much like an american lager . not much there ... taste is crisp , grainy-sweet with a slight noble hop bite .  the cinnamon and nutmeg in this is way to overpowering . it smelled like oatmeal cookies and had a biscuity , bannana bread taste . this was so sickenly sweet it makes it hard to drink . this was a big disapointment since i so far have loved all the beers i 've tried by harpoon .  it 's cheap , surprisingly light-tasting ( for a 40 ) and packs a mighty whallop in terms of buzz . as a long fan of steel reserve 211 and st. ides , i admit that they do n't stand up to double malt in terms of taste and mouthfeel .

pours a true golden tone with a highly carbonated thick white head that could be compared to the billowing smoke clouds that that left the steel mills of pittsburgh 's past . the aroma is a very faint bitterness with some sweet tones hidden in there .  the taste was like a bad lambic - no bourbon hints , no real body , despite a nice dark pour that was visually enticing .  m - light bodied , overly acidic .

a wierd vegetable smell , a little like eggs . a good bitterness , though vegetable notes .  pours black with a touch of head .  it 's heavy and a little cloying . the mouthfeel is thick and unpleasant .

s : very grassy , skunky hops , with some sweet malt notes in the background . i am not impressed by the aroma of this brew at all , especially that of the hops - does it have anything to do with the fact that they 're organic ? however , the lifeless appearance and disagreeable aroma of this brew pull the score down a bit .  pours up nice ... .excellent color ... i was real excited to drink this .  mouthfeel : sharp at first , but the carbonation quickly fades away to a watery limpness .

smells like , uh , metal . thankfully the funky smell did not enter the taste , which was very sweet caramel-chocolate .  pours a copper/ amber-ish color with a small white head .  flavor was shallow , sweetness was hardly there at all , and mouthfeel was really thin .

aroma 2/5 nondescript aroma with some sweet malt character and an odd sharpness , like a pilsner . more malts and perhaps more hops will make this beer better , but the unoffensive character ( ? ) might get lost .  appearance- i do think this is a great looking beer .  ca n't get any metalic taste ( which is a good thing ) m- really high in carbonation to the point where it 's hard to pick out flavors . d- it is good just the high carbonation totally kills it .

aroma seemed a little off , some sour smell , and something else that just smelled bad .  a : pours a dark brown body . i want to check out the edges and see if it 's translucent , but the head -- 3 fingers of huge , fluffy bubbles -- lasts forever . i was told this is infected , so i was n't surprised to see this .  mouthfeel is watery and not that great .

smells of grainy corn , with a whisper of generic hops . rather weak .  appearance- this one looked pretty damn good . golden pour with a nice stream of bubbles coming from the bottom of my duvel glass . i guess that makes any beer look better than it actually is . good solid while creamy head and average lacing .  the taste is disappointing , just a german macro really . too thin , not much taste.barely average , but sub-par for the price .

the smell is faint , not good at all , musty almost , very grainy ... it may be a blessing that it is a faint smell .  pours a hazy sunshine gold with a genorous white foamy head .  mouthfeel watery + light .

overall : quite possibly the worst smelling beer i 've ever smelt , yet one of the best tasting .  the appearance is nice with a thick chocolate look and two fingers of tan head .  lots of carbonation and quite watery .

s : odd metallic smell ... maybe alcohol scents that overpower about anything else . almost like an artificial banana scent with marshmallow overtones .  a : black with a nice persistent dark tan head and lacing .  dissapointing mouthfeel , muted flavors .

nose is lots of vegetables , sweet corn , rahbarber , pepperspice and smooked .  looks pretty good .  the carbonation is ( too ) strong . the stronger old spelcked hen is an ok pale ale , but this one was watered down in every way .

it 's not great , tasty beer . there 's nothing in it to savor or appreciate . if it 's cold , and theres plenty of them , it 's a nice fun beer . just one mans opinion here .  it settled quite quickly leaving a very beautiful looking creamy head . a point off for appearance though because the very light amber colour and slight cloudy appearance is n't too appealing .  the beer is failed by its thin and bubbly mouthfeel , though .

s : malty ... corn ... not much recognizable hops , kinda metallic , and slightly skunky .  as for appearance , it is extremely dark in color with a thin foam .  mouthfeel is unremarkable , almost like water .

s : light biscuit smell . no overwhelming hop aroma . very faint lager yeast smell .  this is the palest triplet i 've ever seen , looks like a wit beer . good amount of white head on it as well .  t/m : the mouthfeel is thin and quite watery ; the taste is equally limp . mouthfeel and a general weakness of character ruins any chance at more than a passable brew .

s- kinda turns me off and almost taints the beer for me , its very light amounts of citrus and easy on pine . smells quite hay and straw with a certain funk that is not too appealing to me .  it looks and pours great .  the taste is o.k. , but the mouthfeel really drags this beer down for me .

the smell is a bit sickly sweet and fruity , not what i look for in a wheat .  appearance : surpisingly good . thick ( 2 finger width ) white head that diminished , but at least some head stayed on the beer the entire time .  the mouthfeel is severely lacking . water , with a very light carbonation the fails to liven this beer up .

well , there pretty much is no smell .  to reiterate - i dont get this beer or the brewery. & lt ; br & gt ; & lt ; br & gt ; dark chocolate brown with very small creamy heads that fades quickly .  thin , watery mouth , very little body .

appearance and smell are both pretty bad , typical for a common micro the taste has more going on than i would expect for this price .  pours a dark copper/amber color with a pretty good head on it . head does n't stick around very long , but overall pretty good lookin ' beer i reckon .  mouthfeel was a bit flat and watery , and the carbonation made this beer seem harsh and scratchy .

aroma is not great . slight sweet malt , and no real hop presence .  i do n't believe the hops in this beer come forth on their true bitter shovinism . when i reach for an ipa , i reach for true , crisp , bitter aftertaste that leaves all the feelings of a nice buzz at the end of a long day . this beer just falls a little short of a genuine ipa taste and feel . for a relatively novice beer drinker , this ipa definitely has promise , yet not entirely justifiable for this bitter-beer loving fool .  way too much malt presence . carbonation is weighed down .
