smell is just hoppy dingy sunky , whatever kind of nastyish cask ale - certain cask ales just smell like an old sponge , is this what the brits are talking about when they say some pubs dont keep their ales well ?  appearance is like any other quality brown ale - deep brown , thick light brown head .  a- light , golden , clear , no real head or lacing s- sweet , honey , cinnamon , hint of liquorice/mint t- very light , not much pumpkin m- very light and thin d- i could drink this for hours ( not in a good way ) it does n't have any of the weight or warmth that i want in a fall beer .

that being said , bud select is a pretty decent brew that i have no trouble drinking . the foamy head is actually pretty impressive , although it 's a 25 ouncer not a pint but still . the taste is a tolerable mix of corn , hops and carbonation but not an overpowering sharpness that i get from bud light . it seems to me that bud select is very unappreciated among the beer buyers because although this is n't top of the line , it certainly beats out bl and honestly i 'd rather have this than budweiser also .  right after the pour i picked up a sweet , yet sharp fruit and perfume aroma . i suppose it 's not bad for a sour beer , or if you 're into sour beer . it 's not a nasty infection that smells like vomit , but rather a lemon-lime juice sour tang that could use some sweetening .  m - pretty light bodied . surprising lack of carbonation given the beautiful head on this .

better than bud light in taste , but it does fall short of something great . cheap beer , 30 pack cans here are $ 10.99 .  poured a from a brown bottle into a pint glass dark muddy brown with a dark tan creamy inch of head .  likely one reason for the weakness of the taste is the watered down mouthfeel .
smells , strange frankly , quite a bit of hops .  starts good with a very nice head and a nice ambercolour beer .  just very watery and has an odd mouthfeel and finish to it .

smell : funny thing is , when i smell it i do n't find anything . no malt sweetness , no hop bitterness , nothing .  a : the beer has a nice orange/yellow color that is very cloudy . a good white foamy head forms with a bit of lace down the glass .  some sweetness at the start , but the palate gets watery and thin quite quickly ... so not much body to speak of .

a : golden yellow hue ; ample carbonation s : very little smell ; whiff of lemon t : light , sweet ; not much depth or breadth to the flavor , which dissipates quickly m : smooth , perhaps a bit too thin d : it comes close to lawnmower drinkability i disliked this beer the first time around ; the second time , it proved less distasteful .  appearance this beer is a light , very pretty yellow with tremendous carbonation and a good , rising head that showed some retention and left a lot of lacing . im impressed .  m - low carbonation , slick , flat finish .

on the nose , this beer is a complete mess . i know it 's billed as a smoked ale with junniper berries , but the combination is not attractive . however , the combination of smoke and gin gives this beer a sandlewood , dish soap aroma . is fairly low , it 's very difficult getting by the aroma on this beer .  pours a nice cloudy , golden color with a nice head .  m - this is where the beer is odd ... when cold , a really carbonated mouthfeel that is unappealing .

it smells like 7-up , which is not unpleasant , and the bottle says it is a 50:50 blend of beer and lemon soda , so no surprises . i can picture it as something you might have on a long bike ride or as a summer lawnmower beer .  pours a dark brown with a light brown head , leaving a thin lacing .  medium carbonation , no body , just water , spritzy bubbles .

there 's not much aroma at all , a slight smell of yeast , and some of skunkiness . probably the best danish beer i 've had , not that i 've had a lot , but usually they 're very skunky and very bitter .  glaring copper color with a soft yielding foam of yellowed puff about a finger high .  '' the mouthfeel is unfortunately thin , and the taste is pretty bland in general .

very faint , unexciting buttered citrus smell . flavor starts sweet but quite uncomplicated with some wheat malt , then dull uncoordinated hops that come off sour and confused .  poured a cloudy golden color with lots of fluffy white head on it .  feel is thin .

the smell is mild , not really inviting , not really foretelling . no noticeable yeast smells . t - the smell is mild which leaves you unprepared for the strong initial hop smack in the face you get on the first sip . there is no smell and a strong single hop flavor .  poured a typical darkish golden amber with decent head , which left nce lacing as the beer was drunk . the appearance was the high point with this beer , unfortunately .  thin feel .
do you think a super light macro lager is going to be some flavor explosion ?  nice looking light copper color body with a solid white head .  however water overrides any other flavor m - very thin .
nose is faint hops .  pours a medium black with a quickly dissipating tan head .  m- here is the downfall , it 's too thin for the style .

s : not much of a nose . t : it advertised a `` toasty ... malt '' taste ... sorry , very underwhelmed .  appearance : opaque reddish brown with an inch tall white head .  mouthfeel was too light for the style with a moderate amount of carbonation .

there was little to no lacing on the glass s - the first sniff of the beer was confusing , and i was n't able to tell if i liked the smell or not . i was able to able to pin down a lemon scent but there was an unappealing malty/sweet scent that was overwhelming .  i taste phenols like they tried belgian yeast in an imperial stout . i love avery beers but this one falls short for me .  lightly hopped and sparkling on the tongue , this brew is quite flavorful , and has a mouthfeel of carbonated water .

not much of any hops in the aroma but i do smell some corn .  poured into a pub glass , a clear , ruby red color , looks nice . the head was off-white nice and creamy with good retention .  m - there simply is n't enough texture here for a great dunkel . at first it seems almost medium but the brew quickly becomes far too thin for the style .
the aroma is very weak .  appearance is decent with good retention .  mouthfeel : pretty thin and watery for any beer , but especially so for a stout .

s- the aroma is very faint even for pale ale standards , let alone an ipa from california . there is some malt along with hints of citrusy hops . t- the taste has a little more flavor than i was expecting based on the weak aroma , but it still leaves a lot of flavor to be desired . '' overall , blue frog ipa is pretty decent brew , but there are many better ipas out there to buy this one again .  hmmmm , it lokks pretty nice with a deep amber color and small white head .  the mouthfeel is hot as hell . let a mouthful of this rest on your palate for 10-15 seconds , and it feels like the insides of your mouth are being dissolved . it 's very astringent and has a monster bite.the aftertaste is just ... boozy .

smell : smells a little skunky . ca n't smell much else .  a : at least this beer looks good , because that 's all it has going for it . a black pour with a nice fluffy mocha colored head on top .  mouthfeel is thin and flat .

smell : faint whiffs of cherries and not much else . some cooked veggie and skunky notes when agitated .  a : looks promising . rich copper color with thick head .  i was really looking forward to my first sip of this years bbcs on draft until the chap next to me said it was thin . my first sip tasted fantastic but yes it did indeed feel thin . as it warmed it should have gotten tastier but the thinness was more obvious than it was cold .

it looks a little better than it is , pale yellow , some white head , a lot less than you expect for the style . aroma is just not there , minimal , and i am not sure what it is . thin on the mouth , minor hints of clove and perhaps banana , but i am really looking hard to find something here .  pours a moderate copper color with a good white head and a nice amount of spotty lacing as the beer falls down into a nice cap and collar .  mouthfeel is where this beer falls apart . in all of that i can sense that the body is thin , could be more viscous .

nose has some faint fruity esters , nothing jumping out at you . nothing really jumps out about this guy , and likely wo n't seek it out again .  pours a clear , pale yellow with a big , fluffy white head that faded slowly with nice ring lacing .  mouthfeel : watery texture , medium body and low carbonation .

the smell was almost reminiscent of an american lager - not too appealing .  the beer arrived at the table a nice amber colour , with a small off-white head .  mouthfeel : the mouthfeel does n't carry the taste evenly - it 's too smooth and yet too coarse at the same time .

nice looking ale , a dark brown with a fully formed creamy white head . dull aromatics leave much to be desired and not much to describe .  this is kind of like a cross between a tulip and pint glass . the coloring was nice , and the lacing looks really good at the end .  m - moderate to low carbonation and almost watery .

smell was a bit stale and yeasty , but it tasted better .  the three finger head is off-white and compact . quite good retention . it leaves some lacing on the glass .  mouthfeel- thin , and light in body .

the smell is almost nonexistent , no real discernible scent ; however , there is a slight fruitiness and honey-esque aroma .  90 ibus . tan head with decent retention and decent to good stick .  the mouthfeel was weak bodied and highly carbonated .

heavy skunk aroma ... when will some of these breweries learn to quit bottling in clear bottles ? after some of the skunk faded , i could smell a mild malt aroma and some grassy hops . t & m - the taste followed the aroma ... mostly sweet malt with a tiny bit of a hop bite on the back end . they are n't all that sexy and any beer connoisseur usually steers clear because they know the effects light can have on beer .  pours a dark brown with some subtle deep orange around the edges , tons of soapy tan/coca cola-esque head and some solid retention . no lace left behind .  m - thin . very thin .
smelled like wet tin cans .  this beer pours with a slightly cloudy deep amber brown body topped by a medium thick head with some lacing .  light body and literally no carbonation .

definite aroma of cherry , not as much in the flavor . i do not enjoy the aroma , there is definitely a strong `` cherry flavored medicine '' smell going on for me .  very clear tan and to be honest looks pretty tasty .  mouthfeel is very thin and watery , and does nothing to enhance the thin flavors .

smells more like a pilsner . t : taste is much more like a whitbier .  a : average light brown , creamy head . lasts long and very sticky . very good lacing . the color was dark , dark brown and not quite black .  the mouthfeel is off , it is way to thin .

some mild pineapple citrus in the background . ( t ) - very similar to the smell . primarily has a malt profile of caramel with a touch of toffee .  the appearance was great , had nice thick head and stayed around for a little while as well .  the mouthfeel leaves a lot to be desired . thin , and too much carbonation .

cloudy , with a yellow gold color and a soft white head , it had almost no aroma on the initial greeting .  it is brilliantly clear , beautifully golden with peach accents , forming a large sea-foam white head atop medium-sized bubbles . carbonation is moderate , and retention and lacing are actually pretty good .  m/d - it is unbelievably thin .

very , very faint aroma of hop . flavor is primarily of hop , with just a tiny bit of malt dripping through .  nicey hazy golden color . lots of carbonation . fluffy , pillowy head with some rings of lace .  fairly thin with a lot of carbonation , watery , with some hop flavor . i am really enjoying all the craft beer i 've been drinking lately , but a bunch of miller lites iced down in a cooler on a hot summer day will work for me anytime .

the smell of this brew was a mixture of cheese , veggies , minerals and well poopy diaper . it is a bit yeasty and off in a bad way . a faint amount i citrus hops and fruity character is evident from the hops that quickly turn herbal and grassy . the taste is quite mineral filled with some flavoring of raw veggie hop matter mixed with dirty yeast flavors that bring forth a mineral aspect in the mouth just like the aroma led on .  the appearance is a nice golden colour . a white head quickly recedes into a film and leaves decent lacing .  mouthfeel - pretty thin .

s : could n't smell much of anything , it did n't have a distinct smell .  a- appealing looking bottle , cool lettering . light yellow color , poured into a pint glass .  m- thin and carbonated . probably the worst dimension to this so-so beer .

almost no nose at all ; just hints of wheat and a light honey sweetness .  very little character overall , with a light tart and sour nature , along with an unusually large head . this was a very fresh bottle , even for import standards , and i would imagine this will become much worse in the next few weeks/months .  the taste can only be described as `` extremely watery '' . as far as mouthfeel goes , once again the key words are `` extremely watery '' . flat and dull .

appearance - pale gold , lots of carbonation smell - slightly skunky taste - malty , very light hint of hops mouthfeel - light , airy overall - i was expecting a little more hop flavor from a `` pale ale '' and the skunky smell was a definite turn off but i did n't dislike the beer .  pours a golden orange with a soapy white head that retains well and leaves some lacing .  its certainly fine for the style , but would never wow anyone , unlike the carbonation , which made me think 'wow , this is fizzy ' .

smells ... like nothing just a hint of toasted malt ... .  pours a solid amber color with a sticky , white head that stays for a good long while .  m - very watery , light bodied and even undercarbonated .
nothing worth noting .  a - dark coffee with a white , slightly tanned , two finger head that stuck around .  the mouthfeel is light and watery .

smell : nothing special here . it 's smells very light and grassy ; underwhelming .  the appearance of this beer is great . it pours out to a very dark amber , almost black , with not much head and little carbonation .  it does leave a really nice lingering coffee flavor on your palate m : very thin . lacks carbonation .

skunk nose , it 's a damn shame too . even with the skunk , which dissapated quickly and did not ruin the experience for me at all , ( beyond the nose rating ) .  black pour with a nice khaki colored head .  my biggest disappointment was the mouthfeel with no lasting carbonation or creaminess .

the smell is faint grain combined with alcohol , basically the same aroma you get from other macros that are n't skunked .  a deep dark sludge of a brew , totally opaque , more like a imp stout than a bel dark .  it has an ok flavor , but it 's very thin .

s. slightly metallic and not very attractive t. light with very subtle hops . d. see taste and smell comments .  a - reddish brown color beer with a bit of a tan head that left behind some moderate lace .  t : watery mouthfeel overall is saved by light yeast , malty goodness and peanut shells in the finish .

vaguely sour aroma . overwhelming carbonation , especially for the style .  deep brown hue , changing to mahogany toward the bottom .  watery porter with good bittersweet chocolate malt . finish is dry and watery , with overwhelming carbonation .

*as an additional note , after reading many of the truly negative reviews for this beer , i have to wonder if there is a `` skunk '' factor popping up because of the clear glass bottles ? s : cooked corn , a medicinal note , and not much else .  fairly dark gold , it has a rather big , off-white head which shrinks slowly to a thin , creamy top and leaves decent lace .  mouthfeel is a bit thin and watery .

s : extremely mild , consisting mostly of carbon dioxide with a trace amount of milk chocolate .  dark caramel color . thin , off-white head quickly fades into thin skim retention but leaves nice surf splash lacing .  watery body .

nose is stale grains with some sulfur notes .  a : pours a black with a thin tan head . decent lacing on the glass s : chocolate aroma with a hint of hops .  it is thin bodied despite the nitro , with a masked , watery aroma . the beer may perhaps be too traditional to appreciate as it shows more modesty than american craft beers usually do . shannon 's core values are a dry grain and chaff taste with some show of dark lace . but the lack of body and flavor are obstacles to appreciation .

the aroma is rather nondescript . i read the ingredients and thought i was getting a pilsner , but this smells like a domestic macro-brew like bud/miller/coors . no hop nose worth mentioning with that kinda sweet corn smell of a macro .  poured a crystal clear medium copper hue with one and a half finger of loose foamy white head . there was good retention and lacing .  diluted watered down light to medium feel that washes back with a diluted overall feel , however lending to some drinkability , but lacking in carbonation . tacky cloying aftertaste .
i know that this beer 's scent is basically the kind i do n't like .  dark bronze color .  the mouthfeel is extraordinarily watery .
s - corn and adjuct , smells pretty sweet .  served in a tulip . pours a very dark brown with some crimson highlights .  some light but lasting carbonation . leaves mouth feeling bubbly and sudsy .

had one today after a scorching hot session of lawn mowing . definitely does the job as a lawnmower beer . taste is typical macro lager , perhaps a bit smoother with a richer mouthfeel . the only difference i noticed was a slight malty flavor that was not present in the frosted beer mug serving i had in vegas .  very , very dark brown in color with a thin khaki head .  just a touch of carbonation zing at the swallow . i just dont know what to think , and that slimey mouthfeel is really starting to irritate my gag reflex .

the aroma was really poor - corny and totally lacking in hop character , it had a little of the dishwater quality about it .  the colour is dark amber , almost brown . the finger thick head is pale beige with a tint of red . lots of fine lacing .  hops and barely . for a light beer it was actually pretty heavy . but other then that it was a light beer . in my mouth it was refeshinting , just like water which is what it tasted like . water .

really , rancid oil and soggy wet grain that has a bit a a spoiled smell .  nice looking ale , a dark brown with a fully formed creamy white head .  ) version of carlsberg 's elephant bock . this is one of my standard `` crap beers , '' the ones that you 're ashamed to admit you enjoy ( hey , we ca n't drink belgians all the time ) . it 's cheap , easy to stomach , tastes decent and has a cool elephant head on the label .

s- starchy and grainy , no smell of pumpkin or spices , no real malt or hops presence either . could use more aroma hops or spices . d- i would say this is an easy drinking beer at the least , would be a perfect introduction beer beyond bmc beers .  appearance is a very nice clear golden color with a nice white head .  mouthfeel is extremely thin for the style with no chewiness at all .

good carbonation and medium bodied . nose is not discernible , flavor is nutty , some hops with hints of caramel , finishes with a slight bitter aftertaste . $ 1.75 for a 12oz bottle from julio 's liquors westborough , ma .  330ml bottle sent to me my mulder , drank from a tulip ... a dark brown body , nothing of note . the head is medium tan , about two fingers rises and leave a full finger cap for several minutes .  this beer is able to skate by because it 's not cloying and the sourness distracts for the most part , but i can only imagine how good this would be if it were properly carbonated .

very typical in appearance and nose for a macro .  sweet cherry juice and crystal clear . i love the boont amber ( almost certainly my favorite amber ale ) .  m : very thin on the palate , incredibly light bodied with high carbonation .

the smell is odd , almost a sour milk aroma that is n't too enticing .  pours as a clear yellow honey color with massive carbonation and a nice full white head that 's about 2 inches tall .  mouthfeel - extremely watery overall - an uninteresting yet swilling pumpkin ale .

smell is almost non existent .  pours a hazy gold with a 4 finger head that peeks above the glass and is rocky when it starts to recede . kinda looks like a hefe .  very watery mouthfeel : very light body and i swear i can feel those floaties on my tongue , very disturbing .

12 oz bottle into into a snifter - best before 7/18/10 nice looking beer ... golden orange and slightly murky smell is a letdown . really working hard to pull out a hop presence and all i 'm coming up with is soapy perfume notes and malt . hmmmm . overall , a bummer .  a : black with a big beige head . scattered lacing .  carbonation is ridiculously high . the carbonation problem is a real worry .

however , the aroma put me off pretty quickly . something sort of like the smell of fresh asparagus .  this beer pours a solid brown with some decent off white head that fades very fast .  taste , amazingly thin , and keeps getting thinner . very creamy for the lack of thickness , a smooth , smoky , thin stout without any degree of bitterness of hops . but throughout , its just tough to get over the thin body for this beer . makes it more drinkable , but the difficulty in finding this stuff , as well as the price , makes it a little cost prohibitive for something this thin .

aroma is very unappealing to me , very earthy and musty , beets obviously , i do n't know ... dirt ?  beer pours a clear deep brown ; think a cola with a few ice cubes that have melted in it . plenty of active carbonation .  the real indicator was the body too thin and the general overall weakness will not make this a serious porter contender .
s - wine with some very faint fruit . i can hardly smell it , though .  v.07 clear dark copper , actively carbonated , but without any accumulation . bitter and thick .  m - watery . boring .

these macro reviews are killing my tastebuds , well not really giving them a workout would be more accurate ; ) well i guess yuengling is n't really a macro , but still a light lager so i went ahead and added them into my tasting . smell was full of grains and not really much else , slight hint at a caramel or sugar sweetness but very slight and only as it warmed .  pours a lighter brown with reddish hues throughout . a good pour leaving a soft white head with good retention and lacing through the whole tasting .  mouthfeel is absolutely awful and inconsistent .

it dissipated slower than other japanese beers , although there was no lacing to speak of . s : not much of one ... a tiny bit of nondescript fruitiness if you really breathed hard . t : there 's more flavor in the finish than the beer itself , but the finish is the same flowery , peachy hop flavor found in the `` frozen hop '' used to make kirin 's sparkling hop , my favorite dai-san .  a loose tan head with loud exploding bubbles .  the mouthfeel is far too thin .

s - slight hops , but more so a weird metallic odor . skunky .  whoa ! huge head overwhelms the glass . finally i pour the brew into the glass at a very slow rate . the brew is a hazy orange color with some sediment floating around .  mouthfeel is super thin and watery .

coors light 's twin . the color is yellow and clear with good carbonation that results in a white foam head that dissapates quickly . smell and taste are primarily grain with attempted balnace of hops , etc .  bright ruby red body slightly hazed when held toward the light , fine off white cream colored head leaves behind fine speckled lacing .  mouthfeel : thin and watery .

the aroma is faint , but has a slight yeast sent .  dark - yes head - no taste - at first not much , then a sour milk aftertaste the smell was ok , not bad but did not even hint to the bland then after swallow assault ahead .  drinks : warm , the obnoxious funk flavor , paired with the unsettling mouthfeel , makes this beer nigh undrinkable .

s- ca n't find much of anything on the nose . t- generic 'beer ' taste . better than some other macro lagers .  poured a large , fluffy , frothy , foamy , fine , white head that lasted a while and good lace . color is a pale , clear , bright yellow , with lots of small bubble trails .  mouthfeel was also very light and thin .

smell very light , fruity hop aroma with some out of place notes of grain . this smells like a bad macro .  appearance : dark orange . nice , off-white head .  dry as anything , with an unacceptable watery finish . the second bc stout lately to be really watery .

does not smell like much other than macro beer with a faint alcohol note . this is one of the better tasting macros .  beautiful rust color but the soapy , flat taste is unbearable .  m thin and really kind of boring .

i sampled this at the michigan brewers guild summer fest . no hop flavour ( as the style dictates ) .  but for now ... appearance : black , light tan head dissipates to a cap that sticks . decent lacings hangs out .  since it is so thin compared to other stouts , i do have to rate it accordingly . sorry but it could be thicker .

husky grain and a lot of veggies . quite metallic in taste with a sharp , almost astringent hop bite that lingers .  clear amber body with a thick white head that stayed there for a while.nice lacing.this is where the beer goes downhill for me .  unfortunately the lack of carbonation turns this into an overly sweet and cloying mess .

s ) touch funky , like rotting hay . light citrus note , but basically not very appealing .  the appearance is amber as advertised and the head is small but foamy .  mouthfeel was simply too thin for the style and for the abv .

s : really light on the nose . i 'm getting some light malts , some cereal grains , and that 's about it . good , no . better than bmc beers , but not a great beer by any stretch of the imagination .  nice enough looking brew .  m- watery and uneventful . no fizz or carbonation factor .

nose is uncommonly clean , save mabye a whiff of sulfur . corn and pale malt sweet upfront , with a curious blend of sulfur and ester , but nothing really offensive it and fades quickly .  poured from a 12 oz into a tulip , showed very nice head retention .  i really love the taste but the complete lack of carbonation is disappointing . i like this but even with some mild carbonation i would love this !

aroma is a partly unpleasant .  looked interesting . a- pours light brown becoming darker as the glass fills up .  too thin and the carbonation is too high given the taste . overall : the taste and smell of this beer are amazing , but the mouthfeel really took away from the beer .

this is different.. once you get past the initial skunky aroma this brew is actually pretty good . only linger here is the ( tail end of the ) skunk ...  poured a clear golden straw colored body with a good sized white head that quickly disappeared . lots of carbonation rising up , with pretty good lacing .  m - the one flaw . too wet and smooth .

s - the aroma starts with musty old dirty carpet and moves into low-presence roasted malts . i do n't get oak or vanilla beans in the scent but there is this lingering nose of old garbage can juice that 's bad but not as bad as it sounds .  it was being poured through a high pressure euro-faucet & was pushed by nitrogen ( instead off carbon dioxide ) , so , this in itself gave it a tight , wonderful head that sat about an inch over the rim of the `` stella '' glass . poured clean with a light amber hue .  mouthfeel is disturbingly thin and does n't have a lot of body at all .

it is very sweet and aptly named , especially as brown sugar is listed among the ingredients . there is little to no aroma .  this is way lighter than expected , my guess is it is a cream ale . some floral notes and cooked corn . appearance : pours with an inch white head , dissipates fairly slowly .  the middle is thin and sweetens some . when cold , the finish is slightly metallic with some obvious alcohol . this is n't bad compared to american macros and some other strong export lagers , but that 's about it .

a - pours a slightly cloudy amber with 1 finger of quickly dissipating head s - it smells kind of like someone waved some pumpkin at an ale .  the beer poured a deep amber , forming a 1/2 inch head , that quickly faded , leaving medium lacing on the glass .  m - very , very thin .

the aroma is very faint : a bit of burnt coffee , flowers , and a touch of cloves . oddly reminiscent of car exhaust . very much to style .  little to no head on this beer even with a moderately vigorous pour . the color is spot on amber to almost a garnet hue . deep and rich colored .  much too much carbonation .

skoal !  aromas of sweet caramel , coconut , vanilla , alcohol and some light dark fruit . the taste is way too syrupy sweet for my liking . this is a huge miss for me compared to the cuvee one . you do n't have to have a beer be so sweet and cloying and achieve a nice high abv , so i ca n't excuse it .  m - medium bodied with poor carbonation levels . the carbonation is just wrong for this style of beer .

i picked up a 6pk of pint cans at wal-mart for memories . s - no obvious smell here . hence my two since it 's mostly corn and water . t - very light and refreshing . d - very drinkable .  nice golden color in the glass ... nice head and lace ... in fact as i write this ( ten minutes after opening this guy ) there is still a thin head in my glass .  the first had carbonation while the second was still . flat beer is not enjoyable . if i want a no carbonation beverage i will drink one . the flavor is good but ... i wo n't buy it again unless i can be assured of carbonation .

pours clear yellow with a big white head . smell is truffles . this is one terrible beer -- or , rather , i ca n't tell what this beer is like , because of the damn truffle salt .  bottle : poured a clear golden color ale with a large foamy head with good retention and minimal lacing .  carbonation is too high , only further deteriorating that dry finish .

there 's a deep roasted malt background in there too , but the citrus is just too much for me and very distracting .  well , it looked good ... then it went downhill ... it poured a dark brown with a nice staying head and lacing .  highly carbonated to boot . thin finish , left me wondering a bit . still thin and contrived , but does n't seem as contrived as i remember , but seems like the same beer to me .

it smelled musty and unappealing . could n't place the scent , but i did n't like it . overall an excellent beer that i would definitely drink again , despite the fact that i really disliked the smell . recommend to just about everyone ; this beer has a unique enough taste that everyone should try it once .  appearance : pours a nice deep copper in to a pilsner glass . there is a sizable cream colored head with some decent retention but little lacing .  thin finish . ) the feel is watery and fizzy .

smell is weak but all-malt .  the pour was an impressive orange/light amber with a two finger head that quickly dissapated and left a thin white ring around the top of the beer .  2.5/5 m : thin and carbonated . unimpressive .
smells like almost nothing .  point : thick white head , tan body . first sip , very watery . good head retention . i 'd have pbr all day long over this .  m - hot and sticky . a loser .

the smell is something to be desired . i expect a pale ale to be full of hop aroma but with this beer i smell more of a caramel malt profile . there are some light citrus notes in the background , but they are barely identifiable .  pours a good two-finger , frothy head that leaves decent lacing . if all you drink is bud light and you 're looking for something a little more daring , you really ca n't go wrong with american ale as a stepping stone .  i 'm not a huge brown ale fan but i 've had some dang good ones lately so i 'm hoping this will be another winner ... pours a warm brown with a very thick creamy head of off white ... very warm and fall-like and makes me wish it was october ... very faint malty earthy aromas that seem rather muted ... toffee and caramel notes for sure but just not pronounced enough for my tastes ... very thin and watery , this one falls short in several categories ... definite caramel malt presence but there 's not enough substance to really enjoy it . almost get a little yeastiness here that mingles with the malts that give this a weird almost oxidized flavor.. sort of sweet and toffee-like but this could really use a little more thickness ... very average brown to me ... might do in a pinch but not one i 'd reach for by choice

smell seems off to me , though i cant identify why .  a : dark brown , thick and appears chocoately , decent head , lots of lacing . looks good . looks like more money went into the presentation ( ceramic bottle ) than the beer .  good slightly heavy feel , with a fresh , grassy/hops aftertaste , but in the middle the taste is sort of flat . sure , it has a nice head and a good , piney smell , but the feel is almost empty , like water , and all body is gone . it still has the obvious piney hops smell and taste , but the taste is quickly gone so all you 're left with is a pine-flavored water .
aroma is so weak it 's almost non-existant ; a hint of light , bready malt . a very bland lager .  orange-gold color with a thin white head .  m - watery and fizzy - kinda like ginger ale .

s : faint smells all around . touch of corn and saaz . smells a bit dusty , perhaps the faintest of lemons .  a - one finger of white foam on top of a crystal clear , amber body .  thin mouthfeel with a dry center and a rather silent finish .

s : sweet grain and cereal . a sulfur and metallic twang that i do n't like at all .  the aroma has me baffled ; funky peppery , yeast aroma . the flavor does n't get much better , spicy apple with a faint hint of chocolate , but unfortunately the peppery flavor overpowered everything else .  m - low marks again . thin and not up to snuff .

s - extremely mild . nothing worth note .  a : looks like a nice brown ale - dark brown , lighter highlights , tan head of a good size .  the mouthfeel just might be below the level of previous commented on mab , with the watery feel and the slight body .

not much aroma at all - just a little maltiness and some grainy character . the flavor is an amped up version of the aroma but a little citrusy tartness is added to the mix .  a : pours and orangeish red , touch lighter than a marzen . head is very nice ... fluffy and barely off white .  mouthfeel is thin and watery .

this beer is typical like its sister pabst . the smell and taste lean towards grainy . the mouthfeel is simple and quenches one 's thirst for standard american beer .  pours to a clear copper and is stacked tall and long with beige foam .  mouthfeel : thin and surprisingly flat .
the smell was very light , almost non-existent .  was a nice gold color with a bit of head .  m - thin with too much carbonation .

pretty typical macro aroma .  this clear dark yellow brew gives a healthy inch of dense foamy eggshell head .  probably too carbonated , almost prickly on the palate . this is a thin bodied beer , and other from the carbonation it goes down easily enough .

the aroma is sugar , lemon , and skunk . skunk is there , but not as bad as i thought from the aroma .  a - a deep red beer with a fairly large foamy head . the slightly pink head lingers for a few minutes and leaves thin sheats of lacing down the sides . looks good for a cherry lambic .  m : extremely thin , almost water like thickness .

there is practically no aroma that comes of this beer , which is a big disappointment .  medium yellow body , crystal clear with surprisingly decent head retention and lacing .  do n't like the mouthfeel in this - fizz seems a bit harsh and the body a bit watery .

dirty , shitty , smoky , fun ! s : slightly smoky dirty biscuit malt , light earthy dirty hops , and dirty adjunct . not much aroma at all out of the fridge , but more as the beer warmed . o : shitty , but not without its charm .  reviewed 7/22/2006 ( tap @ kelvin at arms , houston , tx ) : cloudy color , orange color , small head , white , good lacing .  this could have all been amplified with some carbonation . m : this is where cdt loses ... w/out the bubble , the tart and sourness are brought to a silent mumble .

bought at specs as a broken six pack single , no glass ... not much smell .. very health wise head , lacing too ... quite a smooth lager with no real offensive lyrics ..some corn ( cob ) in the taste department ( dmv ? ) a pretty easy going lager from america 's hat ... p-a-r-t - why ?  a- to my delight , it had a wonderful thick head , although quite airy , dark body , several dark brown tones . s- fruity , slightly sweet/spicy , reminds me of a sasafrass rootbeer .  sticky & flabby .

pours the darkest brown almost black with a 2 finger tan head that leaves spotted lacing smell - honestly i dont smell anything ? ? ? i wont give it a 1 since it does taste pretty good taste - is nice roasted and sweet carmel malts - small amount of cocoa and hop bitterness - tad watery mouthfeel while a bit thin it still is carbonated well and has a creamy finish drinkability is good - and easy drinking flavorful light porter that will not fill you up  appearance : pours a clear dark red/amber color with a layer of off white head .  thin and fizzy in the mouth .

my first japanese rice lager , let 's see if it 's much differnt from the american macro ricer . smell is right on though . almost nothing happening here , just a faint sweetness .  the body has a reddish color .  mouthfeel is very watery , like a light beer is born to be .

s : not much to note . some hops and corn . average for a mexican lager . i will grab one of these any time over corona or some of the other generic mexican lagers .  i 'm going to preface this review with `` i pray to god this is an infected bottle '' 22 oz bomber into sammy a glass . appearance and smell - good ambery clear color with a good head ... wait wait whats that smell . notes - it looks good before u put ur nose up to it and the mouthfeel is right for an ipa but something god awful happened to the flavor in this bottle and i really have no idea what it could be .  mouthfeel - very light , watery .

the smell was light and grassy with a bit of sour funkyness . overall not to bad , one of the better mass produced ab offerings .  appearance : black as night with a coffee-colored head .  with better carbonation , i think this beer has the elements to be phenomenal .

nothing to report in the smell department ( it 'smelled liked a beer ' to quote my g/f ) the flavor is also amiss , with no real malt sensations tho some honey style sweetness could be detected . thin bodied , but easy to drink but thoroughly lacking in character overall .  a - rich black color with a tan head that dissipates quickly .  very thin .

the aroma is pretty weak overall . earthy hops and a decent bitterness hits the palate , but nothing over the top .  nice foamy head that retains moderately , lapsing into a thin film on top of the brew .  mouthfeel is also tangibly lacking .

big oil can , just finished watching crocodile dundee in los angeles , so i had a hankering for this , a : pours a typical , pale yellow , but the head is really nice initially , and has pretty good retention , a nice , soapy white . s : very light , faint , some malt notes . t : light malt notes are backed up by a surprising amount of hops for this style of beer , definitely not an ipa or pilsner , but for an american macro lager , it 's got a bit of a crisp hop bite .  pours a clear golden color with an average off-white head that is quite creamy .  mouthfeel - thin and watery .

smell : aroma from this beer is very faint . smells of chocolate , toffee and coffee are present .  now this.. pours a nice golden color with a half finger white head that leaves some lacing .  mouthfeel - this is probably my biggest problem with this beer a very watery mouthfeel and it is very under-carbonated , almost flat .
really quite poor .  very nice looks , like foamy cristal ?  mouthfeel - a little thin and watery for me . also heavily carbonated , which adds an intense unpleasant tingling in the mouth .

the smell however is n't anything to call home about .  a-pours a nice clear amber color w/thick off-white head of mousse . a few small bits of sticky lacing , decent retention .  thin and watery mouthfeel with more carbonation then desired for the style . carbonation comeing through strong and man , i just cant get past this watery thin , frail mouthfeel .

the aroma was of apple juice , which is not a good thing because i hate apple juice .  looks like a champagne . nice head retention .  mouthfeel : watery in comparison to a pint drawn in a good pub with a nitrogen system . the watered down mouthfeel really detracts .

the smell does not leave me expecting much t- slightly fruity and still pretty grainy . m- smooth , little to no bitterness , watery mouthfeel .  steam beer you say , actually i like this one very much since i 've gone back more of it . i guess you can say the caramel tint is hidden in the flavor .  mouthfeel is very strange . then an odd meatiness and tannin-laden tongue coating descends upon the palate , rendering all flavors void and unable to be enjoyed .

corn is evident , taste is a tad more bold than the macrobrews of today . good looking bottle , though . one bottle out of the six was flat , skunky and undrinkable .  typical dark appearance with good head retention .  mouthfeel was a bit of a disaster , for the style anyway , as it was very thin and lifeless .

being that this is a mexican macro lager , i will allow the other reviews to speak for the appearance and smell of this beer . obviously corn beer but not offensive . the aftertaste leaves you wondering if there are hops are not . this beer does n't need a lime to cut the skunk . again , for the style , this is a good mexican macro . negro is excellent but i pour that beer ; this is right out of the bottle beer .  one finger white head with nice retention and some lacing .  m : thin . very dissapointing .

s-smells like it was imported , skunky , with a faint smell of hops .  appearance : clear copper color , huge head that volcanoes out of the glass .  thin mouthfeel . carbonation is overpowering from the rush at the start to the linger at the finish ; this one does n't settle with me all too well .

s- i honesty ca n't pick much smell here minus a very very small hint of sweetness . quite disappointing for an unplugged beer .  medium amber color with a medium sized head with decent looking lace .  woody creek white , flying dog 's 'new ' summer seasonal , pours as near white as one might imagine possible for a beer , which makes for an impressive look that is countered ( and unfortunately not enhanced ) by a fizzy , quick-to-dissipate head . across the tongue , this really just disappears , and the initial spice and malt flavors turn watery . this is not my favorite colorado wit nor my favorite flying dog brew .

the first characteristic i notice in the nose is wet cardboard and some sort of mineral smell . earthy , musty .  bright appearance with decent head retention when first poured from the can .  mouthfeel : way too thin for this type of beer .

the nose was very bland , with the most dominant aroma being yeast .  poured into a stemmed tulip : solid black with deep brown highlights around the edges . thin mocha covering with a thicker collar . some swabs of lacing .  taste/mouthfeel- watery feel to the beer , some grain and alcohol , hops and malt are present but do n't really make much of an impression . drinkability-refreshing on a hot summer day , other than that the thin feel dissapoints .
s - faint sweet smell is all i detected .  started with an mgd , now this one , and next , the ever present bud . maintains a good covering of white foam .  weak body and watery mouthfeel .

pours a semi-cloudy pale straw color with a decent lace of head . not much to smell here , a little dank though . taste is mediocre and not as bad as it could be . if someone offered it to me , i 'd probably drink it , but wo n't ever buy it again .  a- pours a murky reddish color with a nice off white head .  sweet maltiness in the front , but very thin . watery and plain .

smell starts out horribly . i dunno what is going on here but it smells of a pasture with fresh manure in the air . it becomes hugely malty/grainy with some citrus fruit and slight manure in the background , strange . no real off flavors but an off aroma for sure .  look : pours a clear yellow-straw color with a white head .  not much in malt or hop character , quite thin .

very mild and buttery in the aroma . a slight metallic character is present along with a bit of malty grain . i 'm not terribly familiar with the style , but i would consider the smell lacking regardless . i 'm usually a bit fan of flying dog brews but i ca n't help but be a little disappointed with this one .  arrived a pretty nice looking dark amber color . certainly looks the part . looks good !  very light body , coupled with carbonation and sweetness , this was closer to soda pop than banana bread . m=very loose ; no body whatsoever .

but there was n't much aroma at all , i 'm not sure if this was because of the nitro , but all i could get was a faint malt aroma .  ruby brown color .  mouthfeel : this is its weakness , no body , watery .

the smell is pretty faint and boring .  apperance : cinnamon . actually , more of reddish copper , and very clear . when i try to get `` past '' the cinnamon , there 's perhaps an evergreen smell . this is one of their four repeating seasonal beers .  carbonation is out of control and really distracts from truly enjoying this ale .

aroma and flavor are extremely light . grain and honey notes are barely perceptible . outstanding carbonation streams . very bland but completely non-repulsive .  its a hazy golden brew capped with a fluffy white head , which lasts for about half the beer .  thin may be a good description , but it was certainly not in line with what i would expect from an imperial stouts of this style .

the smell is not very exiting ; some white loaf , some sweet-sour malt and some anonymous bitter hints . the taste is mild and inoffensive : sweet malt , some bread-like flavours , low bitterness .  i have to zap this beer because i have been waiting so long to try it and when i finally get my hands on one ... the aroma is what gets me first , bananas . also their world wide stout had a banana problem as well , so right when i took a sniff of this i was immediately disappointed . the taste is mediocre at best and the banana is in there as well , so now we are in trouble . ginger , you get a hint of it behind the banana in the aroma . the over banana-ish taste and flavor of this and the world wide stout lead me to believe they are having a yeast problem .  but it 's got no carbonation .

the aroma is foul , it smells as if something has spoiled .  average size head . lots of lace left behind as the head rapidly diminishes .  very rich , sweet and no carbonation to balance it . what i like least : the lack of carbonation .

smells mildy grainy with a hint of hops .  i had a bottle with a someone a couple nights ago , hands down the worst tasting beer i have ever had . it looked fine , but it smelled and tasted like someone poured a glass of rum and a punch of rotten , fermented pumpkin in my ale .  mouthfeel ; really too fizzy , like carbonated water but sticky and not by any means crisp .

s- do n't really smell anything . for a double ipa i was hoping for a nice hop scent . very weak .  bomber into a stone tulip . golden-amber appearance , semi-hazy , with two fingers of pure white froth .  weak body , thin mouth feel..a let down after the looks and smell of this ale .

tire bite has a weak , slightly yeasty nose with hints of lemon and orange , as well as lightly toasted grains . some sugary esters float upwards as well , but overall the nose smells flat and slightly skunky ( as it did in the other bottles of tire bite ) .  a - poured from bottle , about a finger of head , perfect color and haziness for the style .  m - this beer was way too overcarbonated and it distracted from the taste .

a great thing about henry 's is that a six pack is generally cheaper than bud or any other of the major american beers . the smell is of hops with a hint of grain . sometimes i swear i smell a fruit flavor , but only sometimes but do n't quote me . ca n't stress this enough , average beer but much better than bud , coors , miller !  the beer pours an attractive gold color with very nice head retention and lacing .  a - appealing , very red color , but less than a half-finger of head and no lacing whatsover s - mostly malt scent , slight roasted , with a hint of coffee t - nice , roasted malt flavor , stronger than the smell but not too strong m - highly carbonated , to the detriment of the flavor d - a good red , but too carbonated in that it masks the flavor .

smells either slightly skunked , or possibly the hops they used ( i found no mention of the variety on their website , other than `` pacific northwest '' hops ) i sometimes mistake some of the czech/german hop aromas for light struck aromas . on the other hand , this is called `` 420 '' and the hibbidy-dibbidy jaboobly sometimes has the funky skunky aroma to it , if it 's good anyway .  a- rather shocking bright red color with a nice two inch head , that was pink .  taste was blah , watered down and unexceptional . very drinkable but why bother . ca n't say that i would give this beer another try , maybe if i was burning up at a disco and it was ice cold i could handle it .
